1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {[Introduction to the Author and the Course]Welcome to my Philidor Course and thank you so much for purchasing it! My name is Luke Calhoun and I'm a titled player, a USCF National Master. I have a lot of experience playing chess, from representing the Harvard University team in their match against Beijing University to competing in national tournaments for decades. I have played the Philidor Defense (which starts in the above position) for years as well. I first came upon the opening as a chess coach wanting something off the beaten path and good for my students, only to find I wanted it for my opening repertoire, too!   Beyond being a chess player, my main passion is actually in the teaching part. My primary job is as an educator: I am a state-certified high school English teacher (halfway through National Board Certification, the highest level of certification a teacher can earn here in the US), have taught full time for well over a decade, eventually leading schoolwide professional development sessions, and love researching new ways to teach. As a result, I am proud to say I have won several teaching awards thanks to student nominations, and one of my main passions within teaching is coaching chess, leading players to multiple regional championships. I just love the game and explaining things is ridiculously fun for me.    I have arranged this course with how I would setup lessons for one of my students--not a chess professional, but a chess fan that also has a day job or schoolwork. I have designed this course, therefore, for a Club Player. I'm going to capitalize that term and give it a specific meaning: a Club Player means the typical chess player who joins a club. The term means someone who is rated somewhere in the 1000-2200 range (my target audience), although truth be told, I play this same repertoire myself at the 2200+ level with great results and welcome all the titled players who have found their way here. However, this course is primarily designed for the regulars who just want to improve, enjoy the game, and potentially earn the title of Master.    If your rating is between 1000 and 2200 in classical, or between 1200 and 2300 on a site like Lichess or Chess.com, this course is primarily written with you in mind (though all are welcome). I hope that my trial and error in teaching over the years has led to a nice, polished delivery on not only an exciting opening but one that will teach you about chess generally. This is going to be a fun ride!} *

