1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {[Introduction to the Course]The teaching philosophy of this class differs from other chess books and even Chessable courses in fundamental ways. It's built on my philosophy as an educator and chess coach for over a decade, and here I'll try to justify why I chose to set it up differently than most other guides.   [The Mainlines of Most Opening Guides:] If you have read chess books, you will hear this word 'mainline.' What they mean is the line that proves to be the toughest, scariest line you can encounter and one of the leading lines in the highest echelons of Grandmaster chess. Playing against these mainlines often fills up most of these books. For example, Sam Shankland, in his Chessable course on the Classical Sicilian, dedicates four out of fourteen chapters (28%) of his course to the mainline Bg5 variation. In Grandmaster games, this is the leading variation. But if you use the Lichess database and filter the ratings selections to 1200-1800, you'll find the so-called 'Mainline' is played in 0.01 percent of games.   This means a titled player will find these 'Mainline' emphases a godsend against the GM players that crush them, but the average tournament player who doesn't play GM's every game (and frankly, would lose to a GM even if they survive the opening) , will find that 28% of the course focused on the 'main' line very rarely applies to their games and is more like a powerful scary sideline. It's a 1 in 100 chance of ever arising! So, I have chosen to respect this definition of Mainline for my master players but don't think this should be 99% of players' focus. This would be to misspend time on positions you don't actually get.  [The Mainlines for This Chessable Course] I provide two definitions of 'Mainline.'    The Grandmaster Mainline: the line hardest to get equality against.  This definition is not so original and is the regular meaning of the term for other opening guides. I refer to these lines as 'Grandmaster Mainlines,' as in what you will probably get in the event that you are paired against a Grandmaster.    It's worth noting that you will almost never encounter these lines in Club Level play except against a book-worm, well-prepared opponent. For example, most Grandmasters play what I call the 'Tension Variation' and stop b5 plans for Black. If you are playing a Lichess game and rated somewhere in the 1200-2000 range, the first move of the Philidor d6 in response to 1. e4 has occurred about 50 million times and after some normal moves that precludes the Pirc and reaches the position on the board now, we are at about 600,000 games. The 'Grandmaster Mainline' has occurred 3,600 times in those games and you have about a 0.6 percent chance of playing against it. In other words, if you play 100 games as Black--and White opens 1. e4 in every single one of them--you have about a 50-50 chance of ever seeing the 'Grandmaster Mainline' in those 100 games. So you should have a plan, but given you might lose to the Grandmaster in endgames or middlegames anyway, this should hardly be a focus (99 out of the 100 games, maybe all of them, won't be this line) . Look up these lines in this Chessable if playing a Grandmaster or to improve by 1%, but they shouldn't be the focus for most.    Club Player Mainline: the line you will probably see most against non-titled players. The main line you will see, if you will. The main thing you will play against a non-professional. My Club Player Mainline, for example, is trading the e-pawns in the position above and then trading the queens. If you are rated between 1200 and 2000, this has about a 50% chance of happening every Philidor game--compare that to the Grandmaster Mainline happening 50% of the time every 100 Philidor games! If you rule out the lower rating range there and only look at 2000-rated opponents, the chance of encountering this line increases to a 68% chance because the lower the rating the less consistently they play these intuitive-but-less-than-optimal moves.   Given that this course is for people trying to reach Master, this Chessable is not focused on beating on Grandmasters and earning a GM title, but instead, beating chess experts, 1900s and the masses that you encounter in coffee shops and regular tournaments. It's about playing the humans of the game instead of the superhumans. And winning. In fact, sometimes our 'Club Player Mainline' will just end with a completely won position for Black, and you will find yourself with a winning edge right out of the opening moves you encounter most often.    Organization Notes on these Mainlines: For the Queen trade line, the mainline for Club Players, I have combined Master, Grandmaster and Club Player play, labelling each accordingly. For the 'Grandmaster Mainline,' I had to have a separate section for the super scary Master Plus opponents, which most of you can skip until you start seeing this play over the board.    [Focus] The Focus of Most Opening Books: Moves! They focus on moves. So many moves to remember. Sometimes chess books are lauded for their thoroughness and exploration of every single option to the nth degree. Variation counts can stretch on and on in chapter after chapter. Many times, even the author has not memorized their work, as it's easier to pump out lines with an engine and a database than it is to commit it to memory.    The Focus of This Chessable  Ideas! Hence the title 'The Philosophical Philidor.' My goal is to limit the variations to a manageable number that I would feel comfortable asking a student of mine to memorize. Sometimes while creating this course, I would sit staring at my computer for half an hour debating whether to include a variation I had already written up, aware of the toll it takes on the memory to have each one. Instead of asking you to memorize sequences, I'll ask you to understand the underlying idea or philosophy of the position. I'll write paragraphs next to each move to help you understand its purpose and timing. You will learn the ideas at the heart of the Philidor, so that your moves don't feel merely memorized, but rather appear natural and according to the flow of the position. This way, when your opponent plays a new move, the reply will come, even if you've never studied it before. This is how I have played personally all my life. The memorized variations either illustrate the core concept or illustrate something that must be memorized because it is the exception rather than the rule and we must arm ourselves for the exceptions. Why do I prefer this method? Because as much as I love openings, I know people go out of book all the time. We must understand instead of merely memorize, so when we see a bad move, we go, 'Oh, White is supposed to play this to prevent this !' and then we play this and win.      [The Goal of Most Opening Guides:] The general strategy for Black opening guides since I was a kid has been to gain equality. The general strategy for White opening guides, conversely, has been to gain one of the following: a tricky sequence that tests Black's knowledge, a slight edge to press from (like the two bishops) , or an easy-to-play position.   Equality, however, is no easy business in chess from the Black perspective. For example, the Lifetime Philidor course by the fantastic, knowledgeable and charismatic grandmaster Pepe Cuenca involves one variation shy of 1,600 memorizable sequences and 43 hours of video. Unless you are a chess professional, these variations can be hard to memorize without detailed explaining and even then, 1,599 variations just to meet 1. e4 is a Herculean task to reach equality.   After all, White can play 1. d4 , among other moves, and also you're White half the time anyway. And is it worth it? After all, giving up and accepting a slight disadvantage of, say, 0.4 pawns, might lead you to the same point, especially when the average centipawn loss for most Club Players is around 0.4 pawns anyway--meaning you memorize it all and on the average move, you lose it all back to your opponent anyway, especially if the position is at all complicated.   Those courses have their target audiences--often me actually--and are great for encyclopedia-like tomes on pathways to equality or to look up a line you know you will face. There's nothing wrong with the main way of doing it, but I found as a teacher that it can be a bit overwhelming (even for myself) so adopted a new approach.  [The Goal of This Chessable Course:] In this course, we will aim for positions where our understanding is clear, minimizing middle-game centipawn loss: where you know the plans for both sides and positions resemble each other as much as possible so we're not learning hundreds of different setups and counterplans. There's a cost to this: I will accept a tiny, acceptable disadvantage as Black without batting an eye. But you will always get something for that 0.2-0.4 tiny slice of pawn. In addition to getting positions you know well and are tricky for your opponent, accepting this tiny pawn slice will allow us to cut down the variations as much as possible to make completing the Chessable practical for working professionals or students attending classes.   Also, we are going to assess other factors in terms of evaluating the resulting position. For example, if you're way more likely to remember the Chessable chapter notes in the critical moment, that will count in the variation's favor. If one variation involves 100 lines and crazy holds with only moves and another involves 4 lines and the difference between the end result is 0.2 pawns according to the computer, I will generally say '0.2 is worth the safety of knowing the position and not risking a memory lapse and instant loss.' In this course, I always factor in difficulty of play and memorization into the evaluation of the resulting position. But this isn't a surrender flag, it's actually much more devious....     I aim above all to find positions that offer practical high-win rates as Black against anyone under 2200 and satisfactory results against grandmasters--around what you'd expect of most Black openings. So before recommending, I check databases thoroughly to ensure Black is winning a lot at the Club Level and holding their own at the GM level. You will never play anything totally unsound to the point of refutation as judged by GM's with the White pieces being able to navigate the result and a Stockfish engine chiming in constantly. It will always hold up.   And I love lines where White just crumbles in game after game. Often, you will find your opponent has only memorized the way outlined in most opening manuals: the top engine move, and the second best move will push them out of their comfort zone. They may look it up later after a hard loss and find they have a 0.2 edge and so opt to play it against you again. But the 0.2 edge is based on them playing like a computer for fifty moves and you can play human moves and still hold so they lose again and again trying to find irrational move after irrational move when the position asks you to just play normal stuff. And if they miraculously do it, they will find their 0.2 peters out to equal in the end. Almost every line I recommend against Club Players has not an equal record for Black, but a very high win rate. These are practically downright treacherous for White.      Whenever possible, I recommended the path that would least hurt your brain, but I gave alternative lines to the perfectionist who insisted on the best even if it meant some serious study for microadvantages.   I hope you enjoy and that this path leads you to many glorious victories and exciting games!} *

