1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {[Course Guide based on Rating]Okay, so how should you complete this course? Well, of course, it's up to you and your learning style and needs, but my personal recommendation for most students would be to handle it differently depending on your rating. So, first question:   What is your over-the-board rating?   A. 500-1200 B. 1201-1600 C. 1600+  No over-the-board rating? Subtract about 200 points from your Lichess rating or 100 points from your Chess.com rating and use the metric above.   A: 500-1200 Rated Players   1. Read and reread the 'Pawns are the Soul of Chess' chapter .   2. Complete the 'Quickstarter (for Facing Club Players)' including the informationals mentioned in the opening .   3. Finally, thoroughly look over and analyze the 'Model Games (Club Players)' chapter:   Then start playing and having fun! After a few games, come back to the course and do the entire Queen Trade chapters. Use the rest of the book as a resource to look up what to do as you start to encounter it. Complete the rest of the course as it becomes relevant to your games.   B: 1201-1600 Rated Players   1. Do everything in the course in order, but focus on the lines deemed 'Club Player' lines.   2. Feel free to skip the lines labelled 'Master' or 'Grandmaster' and chapters on 'Master' play. Specifically, you can skip the following: the Quickstarter (Masters) , the Shirov Gambit (Master Sideline) , f3 lines, and Master Deviations. At least, until that type of play starts becoming likely in your games. One exception you might want to make is the Master Tension Variation as that's the mainline and may be good for you in terms of understanding the structure deeply.   This should make the course less overwhelming in terms of all the ideas yet highly practical and effective. Of course, if you don't feel overwhelmed, you can always study those chapters and lines for fun and improvement!    C: 1600+ Rated Players   Do the whole course in order but skip the alternative lines unless you really don't like the main recommendation. For those closer to 1600, consider doing path B first. Some good news there: I have agonized over reducing the lines to the most critical so it shouldn't be overly taxing.     For the highest rated of the bunch here, consider substituting any lines you don't like with a secondary source, like GM Pepe Cuenca's Lifetime Repertoire: Philidor Defense or through self research of the database. My lines should hold up against top level play but your preferences and ability to sort through the variations can augment the material even further if you so wish. Throughout the course, I will have suggestions for further study and give an overview of my assessment of alternatives if a move seems playable but not my preference. I hope this will help guide you in what you may want to add or switch up. For the highest rated, consider also learning the alternative lines I list to help you become more unpredictable--you will find an alternative line which is engine and database checked for accuracy and reliability in every major variation of the course and many minor ones.} *

