1. e4 d6 ({This is the first move of the Modern Philidor. The old school way to play it, and the way Philidor himself played it, was} 1... e5 2. Nf3 d6 {. However, as I will explain in the next informational, the move d6 is nowadays the preferred way to reach the Philidor by GM's and for good reason. Next, we plan to take out our knight and attack White's pawn to try to get Nc3 out of them. The reason why we play d6 first is to make sure White&#39;s pawn can&#39;t lunge at us. You see that e-pawn? It would love nothing more to start your knight on a romping adventure around the board. For example, Nf6 e5 Nd5} 3. c4 {would be called the Alekhine defense, named after the World Champion who didn&#39;t even regularly employ it himself.}) 2. d4 {Even beginners are taught to take the center when it's given and most white players will play this against you. We'll examine other ideas later.} Nf6 ({Black develops a knight and attacks the e-pawn. You'd be surprised at how many White players just drop the pawn at the below 1200 level. Above 1200, almost every white player will think they're playing against a Pirc. For the very new players reading this, you should just know that attacking your knight with the pawn basically loses for White. After all,} 2... e5 3. dxe5 dxe5 {Qxd1+ Kxd1 Ng4 and you're threatening the pawn on e5 and to fork White on f2 so you're winning.}) 3. Nc3 ({Of course, there are lots of ways to defend the pawn:} 3. Bd3 {, Qf3 , Qg4 ( We can dream!), etc. However, our plan will remain similar regardless. Nc3 makes the most sense, following Reuben Fine's 30 rules of chess, specifically 'knights before bishops.'}) 3... e5 ({This move defines the Philidor. However, Black can play the Modern Philidor with} 3... Nbd7 {delaying the pawn push till next move. Both Nbd7 and e5 have pros and cons but I think objectively, 3... e5 is the stronger move here and the course recommendation. Let's pause for a second and examine why it's recommended.   First, the main and practically only con of our move versus Nbd7 (3... e5 ) is that White can trade queens. Personally, I love a good queenless middlegame battle, but some people feel their queen is worth one and a half queens. Just try it out before you hate on it though. Others worry that this is a one-way train to draw-ville. That's actually incorrect, and in fact, GM Sergey Kasparov has called the queen trade line the 'Philidor Swamp' because White must tread carefully in a mucky tricky position to not lose. You will be armed and ready for this battle and your draw-seeking opponent will find themselves in a very lonely and dark place. We can only offer our condolences. Nbd7 is playable and sometimes called the Black Lion because even though it could transpose, it often marks the beginning of aggressive play with h6  g5 later. GM Simon Williams has a course here on Chessable involving this idea, and Alexander Alehkine said it was his preferred method to play the Philidor. The reason I didn't recommend it is because if White knows what they're doing, they can give us stressful moves like f4 or g4 , which offer very challenging issues compared to the queen trade lines in e5 , which is considered not very challenging. Almost all super GM's play e5 here as a result and it's also easier to play making it the course recommendation.}) *

