{Nf6 looks like it would work but then dxe5 Nxe4 , which is the mainline Qd5 which has a 57% win rate for White and a 15% win rate for Black, backed by a poor computer evaluation of Black. So, because both knight moves have issues, the safest option is to trade pawns. But hey, we often play this way in the mainline of this course! Sadly, the good news ends there.   A major con for rushing this central pawn trade is that White hasn't played a4 or kingside castled and so now White can castle queenside and launch deadly attacks against us. If we haven't done our homework here, their space advantage and highly mobile pieces will prevail. The dark-squared bishop even has a new option in f4 now as recommended in Wesley's So's Lifetime Repertoire: 1. e4 Chessable course. It's not the end of the world but the only way to equalize is to be incredibly exact and not-concept oriented but rather concrete--against the spirit of this course. Things get tactical with these opposite-wings castling and way easier to play with White. So I'm going to avoid recommending this move order but am listing it here so you know why and if you want to take it up, I wish you well. Cuenca's course includes this and all of its messiness, though he says in his introduction that after thoroughly analyzing it, he still prefers to play in the way outlined in this Chessable and finds gaining equality incredibly stressful with the move order shown above.} 1. e4 e5 {You can also get to the Philidor this way, and indeed, this was the old way and has had a recent minor surge in popularity among Super Grandmasters. The pros are that you get to avoid queen trade lines. I don't really mind those myself, and objectively, White isn't doing great in them. The cons are that when White plays d4 , you pretty much have to take on d4 immediately or be worse objectively and practically. You also have to have a plan against the King's Gambit and such.} 2. Nf3 ({Or} 2. f4 {or d4 or Nc3 or Bc4 but this is the main move you will face.}) 2... d6 3. d4 {[Why I Don't Recommend This Move Order]For the exceptionally curious, I will explain why this move order has real disadvantages practically speaking. So, I am not recommending this way of getting there, but for those who love my course but hate trading queens under even okay circumstances, this might be a path of self study. I'll explain the pro's and cons briefly here.    Again, the big pro is that the 1... e5 move order avoids the queen trade line so cuts down on how much you have to study queenless middlegames by a big chunk. For those who want a similar Black pawn structure position every time, this is a great way to go. You can pretty much just look at one pawn structure for Black as opposed to the three that are always possible when you keep the tension.  But there are some cons. Big ones. The first is not so bad: you have to have something against the King's Gambit and Center game and possibly the Vienna. That is very annoying but doable--none of those openings promise much for White against a well-studied opponent. The biggest con is that in this position, Black has to trade center pawns and cannot guard the e5 pawn and transpose to the Mainline Hanham Variation, the main line we see in the course and a very solid line for Black.} ({Why does Black have to take? Well, the obvious choice for Black here would be the following: Nd7} 3. Bc4 Nf6 {but after} 4. Ng5 {, we see the issue. Black is not in time to defend the f7 pawn. You might ask, well then why not 4... Be7 instead of 4... Ngf6 ?}) ({That loses this way: Nd7} 3. Bc4 Be7 {dxe5} 4. Nxe5 {forced as 5... dxe5 6. Qd5 decides the game because f7 is falling Nxe5} dxe5 5. Qh5 {and f7 and e5 are both attacked without a great response.}) *

