{Takeaways   The Philidor is not a reply to anything except White's most common, and arguably most dangerous, opening move: 1. e4 . But it pairs well with the Old Indian and King's Indian directly, though the latter has kingside, not queenside, play as its most common, but not obligatory, follow up plan. The Bogo Indian, Nimzo Indian and Queen's Indian are also good pairings as Black can often play d6 - e5 structures later in those. Finally, some find the Queen's Gambit Declined the best match because the goal is to put a pawn in the center in the same area that White did, much like the Philidor, even though we're on a different side of the board. So, I can recommend all of those openings as a complement to your repertoire against queen pawn openings. What you pair with it, whether it's an Old Indian or a cheese platter and a Merlot, is totally up to your tastes.} 1. d4 d6 {[Can I play the Philidor against 1. d4 ?] The short answer is 'no' but the medium answer is 'you can, but don't expect completely identical positions' and the long answer is as follows...   Why 1. d4 is different than 1. e4 :   The reason why 1. d4 is different than 1. e4 is because we don't have a pawn to attack when we play 2. ... Nf6 . You will see later that attacking White's e-pawn is a major strategy in the Philidor.} ({White can play Nf3 in the position on the board making e5 a bit trickier to get off than it is in the normal Philidor. For example, Nd7 Bf4 and we're in new territory. White can also play c4} 1... e5 {when a queen trade position is offered after} 2. dxe5 {dxe5 Qxd8 Kxd8 that is slightly different than the Philidor one. This endgame is good for Black, just like in the Philidor, but for different reasons and has a slightly different setup. Why 1. d4 and 1. e4 are similar:   You can play the same piece configuration as the Philidor generally and it would be called the Old Indian. You even have a luxurious option of fianchettoing your bishop because quick f7 attacks aren't an issue, which would be called the King's Indian.} ({In many games, White plays} 2. e4 {, which transposes directly to the Philidor. Even in games where White doesn't play that move here, they are often tempted to play it later.})) *

