{For this chapter, I want to talk about pawns. Philidor called them the 'souls of chess' and to be a great Philidor player, you have to understand the pawn structure well. From it, your plan will emerge. I don't want you to memorize anything here in terms of concrete moves as we will get to those later. Instead, I want to explore the three different types of pawn structures that Philidor players can get and what each one means.   Understand these and the concrete lines will be easier to remember and seem more natural. I considered just having a diagram of the end position but I wanted to give you a plausible sequence for arriving at it in case you wanted to see how we could arrive there. Feel free to just move to the end and treat it like a diagram.   Additionally, I'll mention a lot of squares using notation in my analysis. If this feels over your head, don't get overwhelmed and just take in the parts you can. Some players really prefer the concrete and others the theoretical. This chapter is very much about the theoretical.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {Black's e-pawn and white's d-pawn are tense here. They're both staring at each other awkwardly and eventually that awkward tension is going to need some resolution. One of three things will happen:    1. White will eat black and play dxe5 .   2. Black will eat white and play exd4 .   3. White will push their d-pawn so the two pawns aren't facing each other anymore.   Of course, neither side needs to resolve which one of these three outcomes we will reach right this second. White can (and probably should) defend the pawn and wait a little bit to find out more about Black's setup. And Black, likewise, should live flexibly. Knowing when to exchange and when to wait is key here. So let's talk about the three pawn formations in a simplified way.} 4. d5 {We start with White pushing. What could look more natural than a space grab? At the GM level, this will be played very carefully and not right away. But at the amateur level, I have found my students encounter this a lot right out of the gate. Again, it might not happen at this moment: often both sides make small improvement moves before the tension is resolved, but it could happen at some point. This structure is useful for other openings you might play in your lifetime like the King's Indian Defense, so let's dive right in:    Principles when White pushes   1. Note that the Black pawns form a chain that extend towards the kingside. This means that Black will generally aim to lengthen their pawn chain into the opponent's king. As a general rule in chess, if you can't move center pawns because they are locked, you want to move the wing pawn closest to the center in the direction your pawn is pointing. So here White will look to move their c-pawn and attack your queenside, while you will look to move your f-pawn and attack their kingside.    2. In these positions, it's best to hold off on moving your light-squared bishop.  Let it defend your queenside for now. After you have pushed your kingside pawns, this bishop will often find a way to finish your attack, whether it's by sacrificing itself on h3 , coming into g4 , or deploying to f5 after a trade of pawns. Please try to keep this piece around as many of White's fortresses can only be broken by this magical bishop.   3. The move c6 can be made but it comes with a cost. If you ever play c6 (or c5 ) White will be able to take and you will find yourself with a backward d-pawn on an open file. That can be quite scary though not bad. Since c6 opens the position, it's best not to combine it with f5 , and best to do it when White pushes too soon, before they've developed adequately.  c6 is a very concrete move and you have to be confident in the specifics (here, I think it's a good move). It will often transpose to the 'Battering Ram Plan' of the mainline if you play it. So look at those positions to better understand the back and forth there.} Be7 5. Bc4 O-O {A word of advice, don't rush to attack in the opening unless your opponent does something really wrong. Yes, I realize Bc4 wasn't great. But it's a perfect example of the non-book move approach you will see your opponents go for when playing against the Philidor. After all, this is a rarer line than e5 , the sicilian, and even the scandinavian! Expect a bit of confusion pre-2000 and even sometimes after that. We want f5 but we must do all our normal things: develop, castle, etc. etc. One exception is the development of our light-squared bishop. Generally, we can put it on e6 if white exchanges but against the push, the bishop will lurk back like a cobra and only come out to deliver the killing bite to break through White's kingside defenses. Don't worry about it. Its day will come.} 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Be3 Ne8 {We're in fresh territory and again, focus on the idea here. Black wants to play f5 and the knight is in the way. It must duck out by either going to e8 or h5 . h5 is often the more active choice but it can run into awkard discovered attacks by the White queen. So e8 will often be an easier place for it to duck to. Don't worry! It will be back. After you push your f-pawn, it can come back to f6 with even more pressure on White's e-pawn.} 8. O-O f5 {And this is our typical aim. Of course, concrete variations matter, but when we don't know what to do, this is often a good try. From here, we can play f4 , Kh8  g5  g4  Rg8  Nef6 and attack. If White captures the f-pawn, we'd ideally love to take back with a g-pawn (that's why g6 is a popular move before this one, but again, we're not thinking of this specific position but general planning) (if we've played g6 ) or a bishop, but if we have to take back with a rook, so be it. We will have great play on the f-file.} *

