1. e4 d6 {Feel free to skip quickly to the end comment of this as we are not trying to memorize specific moves yet, just looking at one possible end path in Philidor positions.} 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 ({Let's pause and examine White's optimal setup against taking right away:} 4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2 {followed by O-O-O and launching an attack. That position, generally speaking, is the one we want to avoid when we consider taking. It's playable for Black but it's worth avoiding because White wins way more than they lose in that position, White's position is easier to play, and play is very concrete and tactical--antithetical to the goals of the course. So, let's see what is gained by delaying the central capture...}) 5. Bc4 {exd4 Nxd4 is playable here and recommended in the New in Chess course, also available on Chessable, Play 1. ... d6 Against Everything.  The idea is by waiting one move, the c4 bishop is now easier to attack in starting a queenside attack. Still, play is more concrete and the win-loss rate for Black in Master level chess isn't terribly good so although it's solid enough objectively, I recommend waiting even longer. Plus, for those readers who already own the aforementioned course, I want to give something different.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 a5 8. Re1 c6 9. Ba2 Re8 10. Qe2 {This is a typical strategy in the mainline as played by highly skilled players. White tries to make the diagonal a bear. This is also a good example of when taking on d4 is helpful for Black.} exd4 {Now we come to a position where Black has initiated a trade in the center to reduce the tension.} 11. Nxd4 {[Principles of Black Taking White]After you trade pawns, generally speaking your next strategy is as follows:   1. Try to get the d-pawn to push in the long-term.   2. Try to eat anything that comes to f5 with your bishop.   3. Try to attack the e4 pawn (look at your knight and rook setup for optimizing this) 4. Retreat a bishop to f8 to enhance the e-file pressure.   5. Situate a piece on e6 to block the White light-squared bishop.   6. Consider attacking b2 if White moves the bishop When should we consider taking on d4 ?    Recall on the note to move 4 that White's optimal setup against an early exd4 involves putting a bishop on f4 and quickly castling queenside. This is, at least, the mainline version of the early takes idea and the proposal of Super GM Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire: 1. e4 Chessable. So, by waiting, we prevent White's best setup. So Black waited for the following:   1. White to castle kingside or play a4 , weakening the queenside safety.   2. White to move their queen, really any queen move helps Black take on d4 , a rule worth memorizing. Almost all available queen moves have downsides as the optimal square for it is often d2 , but to get there without blocking in the dark-squared bishop, White must move the bishop. See rule 3.  3. White moves the dark-squared bishop. Even here, there's not always a rush to take, but recall that the ideal square for the dark-squared bishop against taking is f4 , a square guarded by our e-pawn until we take. So, if White play Be3 or b3 or Bg5 , they will be a tempo down when compared to earlier taking.     There's no harm in waiting for one or more of these signs as White will rarely benefit from taking you.    What are the pro's and cons of taking White's pawn?   PRO:   1. Black gains an attack on e4 .   2. Black gains a bigger diagonal for their bishop if they can get it to the h8 - a1 diagonal.  3. Black stops d5 , so can put pieces on e6 more easily.    CON:   1. White gains more space and so has more available places for their pieces.   2. White gains an open d-file: If Black has played c6 , this open d-file will hit the backward d6 pawn. If Black does not play c6 , the open d-file will support a white knight in jumping to d5 --the only way to fully guard the square from Black's perspective is to play c6 , going back to the backward d-pawn con.   It may take some practice knowing when to release the tension and to a degree, it's subjective; however, looking over the pro and con list and the key plans should give you a head start in developing a feel for the right moment.} *

