1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. dxe5 {White captures Black here.} dxe5 6. Bc4 {Of course, doing this earlier and trading queens is also fine for Black, but let's just focus on the idea of this pawn move for now. Similar positions can be reached throughout the course as White can exchange on e5 at various times. So, let's examine what's going on here.   [Principles when White Takes Black:]1. The biggest difference between the two sides here is the placement of the knights. This might look like a very small difference but it actually matters a great deal. The knight on c3 will have trouble moving forward after the move c6 . Additionally, Black will find it natural to pawn storm the queenside first with c6 and a5 and later with possibly b5 and maybe b4 while White's knight will get in the way of their own queenside plans.    2. The white bishop will have to make a difficult developing decision. They had three places they could have put it: If White had played 6. Be2 , the bishop would have been somewhat inactive and e4 will be potentially vulnerable with the e-file blocked. So Black's defender-kicking idea of b5 - b4 will be powerful (if White guards e4 with f3 , the bishop on e2 would be even worse and the knight will be struggling emotionally on g1 and without a good move). If White had played 6. Bd3 , the bishop would be vulnerable to Nbd7 - Nc5 ideas, trying to win the bishop pair, and it would be passive. Finally, if the White bishop goes to c4 like in this position, it will allow b5 to be played with tempo. Then it will have to retreat back to one of the other options I mentioned or go to b3 , which sometimes fails to b4 ideas (kicking away the c3 knight) and then Nxe4 .  So play to restrict the awkward white light-squared bishop. 3. White's one advantage is that they have an easier time moving their kingside pawns (like playing f4 ). But this move is more dangerous than queenside play as it opens up a castled king to checks and if Black takes on f4 , White will have an isolated e-pawn to play against.    4. In this position, it is now safe to develop your light-squared bishop to e6 because d5 is no longer an option, booping it into oblivion. Be careful about Ng5 in response though.   Overall, White should only opt for this exchange if they are getting something very concrete. For example, we will see later that some White players will do this to exchange queens here (instead of Bg5 ) to prevent Black castling and potentially mess up Black's pawn structure. Even with both accomplished, the position is still equal and Black can play for a win. So, Black should be happy to see dxe5 .} *

