{White can trade queens by playing dxe5 dxe5 Qxd8 Kxd8 and the out-of-book moves in that position may seem tricky; however, I'll guide you in understanding what's going on so you are fully prepared here: Queen Trade informational chapter .} 1. e4 d6 {I hope you are excited about beginning your journey to becoming a Philidor all-star! It's worth noting that the following Quickstarter will cover the most common and most dangerous stuff played at the Club Player level, with two notes on the Master Level variations you might see and guidance on how to survive there. The Quickstarter (Masters) will cover the more sophisticated tries that you'll begin seeing at the 2200 level.  Nevertheless opponents do not always cooperate in playing the Quickstarter moves, so the purpose of this informational guide is to give you a guide towards the more philosophical aspects of these positions that, once understood, will help you find the right replies to weird moves by White. So without further ado...  [What to Do If Opponents Don't Play the Regular Moves]Deviations are the name of the game in Club Player chess. Memorizing all the different moves an opponent can make will quickly exhaust and confuse you. There are 9 million possible positions after three moves by both sides in chess and after four moves that number to around 318 billion. So trying to memorize your way through every variation in order to play perfectly for just three or four moves doesn't make sense. We memorize the scary stuff, the dangerous stuff, not the dry harmless stuff. We still prepare for the harmless but in a different way: by memorizing ideas in the position that will guide you through many possible deviations from an opponent.   I have placed blue arrows next to this move being clicked so that you can see the natural plan for our pieces at this point. Anything weird? Do a quick tactics check and if you have no way to punish and aren't going to lose material, just follow the path of moving your pieces according to those blue arrows. That's the safe reaction; however, we can often do even better than that.   Let's play a few moves and then talk about possible paths the position might take in the Modern Philidor and how to optimize your ability to form a great plan in those positions.} 2. d4 {The most common move. The next leading one is Nf3 but d4 has a hefty lead over the other options.} Nf6 {Black attacks the pawn and again, Black can follow the blue arrows diagrammed on this move if White does something weird.} 3. Nc3 {Again, most common, as it defends the pawn and develops a minor piece.} e5 {Okay, so White can do something unexpected at this point or earlier. Let's explore how to handle them.   Earlier Deviations   White can deviate from the moves I just played as early as move two! For positions where White refuses to take the center and play d4 , the first two parts of Guide to Deviations: Informational found in the Club Player Deviations chapter will guide you on how to proceed, and the most dangerous deviations mentioned there are covered in this Quickstarter as well. Generally, we will follow the blue arrows in setting up our pieces, as mentioned before, while ensuring we don't have something better and aren't in danger.    For deviations after White has grabbed the center with d4 , we can generally follow the 'Pawns are the Soul of Chess' chapter's guide to forming a plan and understanding the position, which will all depend on how the tension between the d4 pawn and the e5 pawn is resolved--this will be less relevant if they don't push d4 as there's no tension if there's no d4 pawn.   If White makes it to the position on the board here, they have played the best moves and so we have to be more careful than usual. Here, they have a big choice...   Queen Trade Plans Tension Variation Plans   White can also refuse the queen trade and play some kind of other line in this position. How to react to that can be found in the 'Pawns are the Soul of Chess' chapter, where you will come up with a plan based on how the central tension was or will be resolved: White trades center pawns , you trade center pawns , or White pushes the d-pawn .   So, as a recap: If you don't have time for the pleasure reading yet, follow the blue arrows I have put in the position. If you do have time, read five informationals --they will go by quick hopefully: one guide for deviations before White plays d4 , one guide for the queen trade line, and three guides based on how the e5 - d4 pawn tension is resolved.   If you are rated over 2000, you may want to check out a final sixth guide I wrote on understanding the most dangerous line of them all, played by most GM's. It's rare in Club Level play to encounter that position, but the higher rated players may want to dive in right away to the deep discussion of what's going on in the Grandmaster mainline here: The Master Tension Variation Informational .   So, if you're feeling lazy, just go with the blue arrows. But if you really want to get a feel for the position, reading those linked-to five core informationals will help you react well to all the oddities. You hopefully will find yourself and outpacing your friends who are trying to memorize a million reasonable three-move sideline sequences and constantly confusing which line they are in and what to do in the resulting positions they get. After all, many out-of-book moves require you to come up with a plan to guide you in finding not only a right move but also a right sequence and middle-game plan. So combine those four or five deep-dives into the plans for both sides with the relevant Quickstarter (s) and you will be a force to be reckoned with while playing the Philidor.} *

