1. e4 d6 {The reasoning behind the first three moves are described in 'The First Three Moves.'} 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 {Most Club Players take this pawn and trade queens. It's actually very hard for them to stay alive in this variation without understanding the complicated queenless middlegame that results.} dxe5 {Black has no other choice... we don't want to be down a pawn after all!} 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {It looks like Black hasn't castled and so is worse but actually White has a harder time unless they really know what they're doing, at which point the game is about equal. This is part of the trickiness of the Philidor: things that look good for White are a bit of an optical illusion. Here, the knight on c3 is going to be much easier to attack than Black's b8 knight, which is headed to d7 . Because Bb4 and c6  b5 - b4 can all hit the comparatively weaker c3 knight, White will struggle much more to defend e4 than Black will to defend e5 if White isn't precise. It takes a keen eye to spot this critical difference here, making many Club Players think they are better or, at least, like they have reached a drawish position.   Practically, White is in trouble unless they have studied the line. If they have studied the line, they can look forward to an equal and interesting game. White usually goes for Bg5 , trying to castle quickly, or Bc4 , attacking f7 here. We will pawn storm to activate our rooks and put our king on e7 or c7 depending on the scenario. The pawn storm is really quite a storm and White has to be careful of the inclement weather on the way as indicated by the excellent practical results in Black's favor here!} 6. Bg5 {White aims to castle queenside with check: the most popular move. We need to run to c8 , so let's clear that square.} Be6 {Our bishop always goes to e6 after the pawn trade--it's the best square and doesn't get in the way of the knight development. We will tuck our king in for the night and then attack with our pawns, taking advantage of the weak knight on c3 . White also has some issues with their light-squared bishop here... there's no great square for it.} 7. O-O-O+ Kc8 {The king is quite safe on c8 and it blocks White's rooks from infiltrating down the d-file. Attacks on f2 and pawn storming the queenside will be our main strategy, along with attempting Bb4 or Bc5 to create havoc. Our b8 knight can go to d7 and then Nb6 followed by Nc4 or just Nc5 right away. The purpose of the pawn storm is not to attack with pawns per se but more to unleash our a8 rook against the enemy king, so opening files will be the goal, and to gain space to constrict enemy movement   on that side of the board. If we need the other rook to join in on the fun, we can lift our king to c7 .} 8. Nf3 {Not a great move but a typical one. White attacks e4 . Without f4 though, White's play is very tame.} Nbd7 {We guard e5 and develop our pieces.} 9. Bxf6 {Again, not great, but a lot of White players don't understand how valuable that dark-squared bishop is and they over-value the doubling of Black's pawns.} gxf6 {The doubled pawns are not an issue at all. Here's why:  First, the doubled pawns open the g-file.  Rg8 later will leave White struggling to develop the light-squared bishop and if White plays g3 to free their bishop from babysitting that pawn, they will open themselves up to pieces travelling through the light squares and moves like Bg4 .   Second, Black now has an extra h6 square for their dark-squared bishop--doesn't go there often but I've seen Club Players accidentally play Rd2 to double and run into Bh6 winning the exchange.   Third, The f6 pawn stops all knight advancements to g5 and f5 looks like a nice square for the knight, but it doesn't threaten anything.   Fourth, it guards e5 , so now our pieces don't have to guard that themselves. So we can move our d7 knight to a more active square.} 10. Nd5 {The top White move here on Lichess. Not quite sure where it's going though.} c6 {1. attacking the knight and the d5 square perpetually to stop future invasions, 2. thinking about a pawn storm with b5 , and 3. clearing a square on c7 for our king to live so we can connect the rooks.} 11. Ne3 {White could also return, shame faced, to c3 but usually White aims to occupy f5 . We pawn storm against pretty much everything. To pawn storm, we just throw up the a and b pawns and open files for our rook.} b5 {White was looking at putting a piece on c4 so we stop it and start the pawn storm. It's going to be rainy!} 12. Kb1 {Bxa2 is often tactically possible for Black so White guards it.} Kc7 {Connecting the rooks and waiting on where to put the dark-squared bishop.} 13. Nh4 {White aims to control an outpost that doesn't help them much.} a5 {Continuing to pawn storm.} 14. Nhf5 {The knight looks scary but does nothing on this square. We can often ignore when it inhabits this ghost town.} a4 {Black has a slight edge--unless White doesn't find Be2 here, then it's a clear edge--and practically it's probably greater as it's way easier to play Black than White. The plan is simple: we develop our bishop to c5 and then play Rab8 and push our queenside pawns. Our goal is to clear files for our rooks and play against the enemy king and the kingside pawns.} *

