1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 {Most Club Players take this pawn and trade queens.} dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {It looks like Black hasn't castled and so is worse but actually White has a harder time unless they really know what they're doing, at which point the game is about equal. This is part of the trickiness of the Philidor: things that look good for White are a bit of an optical illusion. Here, the knight on c3 is going to be much easier to attack than Black's b8 knight, which is headed to d7 . Because Bb4 and c6  b5 - b4 can all hit the comparatively weaker c3 knight, White will struggle much more to defend e4 than Black will to defend e5 if White isn't precise. It takes a keen eye to spot this critical difference here, making many Club Players think they are better or, at least, like they have reached a drawish position. Practically, White is in trouble unless they have studied the line. If they have studied the line, they can look forward to an equal and interesting game. White usually goes for Bg5 , trying to castle quickly, or Bc4 , attacking f7 here. We will pawn storm to activate our rooks and put our king on e7 or c7 depending on the scenario. The pawn storm is really quite a storm and White has to be careful of the inclement weather on the way as indicated by the excellent practical results in Black's favor here!} 6. Bg5 {White aims to castle queenside with check. We need to run to c8 , so let's clear that square.} Be6 {Our bishop always goes to e6 after the pawn trade.} 7. O-O-O+ Kc8 {The king is quite safe on c8 . Attacks on f2 and pawn storming the queenside will be our main strategy, along with attempting Bb4 or Bc5 to create havoc. Our knight can go to d7 and then Nb6 - Nc4 or Nc5 . The purpose of the pawn storm is not to attack with pawns per se but more to unleash our a8 rook against the enemy king, so opening files will be the goal. If we need the other rook to join in on the fun, we can lift our king to c7 .} 8. Nf3 Nbd7 {We guard e5 .} 9. Bb5 {A relatable mistake. White is trying to develop but the queenside pawn storm makes this move backfire.} c6 10. Ba4 Bb4 {Threatening Bxc3 and Nxe4 .} ({Rhe1 won't work because of Bxc3 and then bxc3} 10... Bxa2 {. This position is a White nightmare.}) 11. Bxf6 {Desperate to reduce attacks on e4 , White gives up the bishop pair--the start of many concessions to Black.} gxf6 {We love the doubled f-pawns in the queen trade line! See previous line's commentary on why!} 12. Ne2 ({White tries to avoid doubled pawns. but the early bishop moves leave Black with a fork. Best is to play} 12. Bb3 {and allow} Bxc3 13. bxc3 Kc7 {. White isn't down a pawn but has horrible pawns and loses most of the time there. In that position just attack the copious isolated pawns on White's queenside and enjoy a pleasant game. The computer actually thinks White's position is so bad that even though they aren't technically down a pawn, they are in the eval bar.}) 12... Nc5 (12... Bxa2 {was also possible but this is simplest.}) 13. Bb3 Nxe4 {Black is a clear pawn up and has a great position. This has a high chance of occurring in your games, too!} *

