1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 {Most Club Players take this pawn and trade queens.} dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {It looks like Black hasn't castled and so is worse but actually White has a harder time unless they really know what they're doing, at which point the game is about equal. This is part of the trickiness of the Philidor: things that look good for White are a bit of an optical illusion. Here, the knight on c3 is going to be much easier to attack than Black's b8 knight, which is headed to d7 . Because Bb4 and c6  b5 - b4 can all hit the comparatively weaker c3 knight, White will struggle much more to defend e4 than Black will to defend e5 if White isn't precise. It takes a keen eye to spot this critical difference here, making many Club Players think they are better or, at least, like they have reached a drawish position. Practically, White is in trouble unless they have studied the line. If they have studied the line, they can look forward to an equal and interesting game. White usually goes for Bg5 , trying to castle quickly, or Bc4 , attacking f7 here. We will pawn storm to activate our rooks and put our king on e7 or c7 depending on the scenario. The pawn storm is really quite a storm and White has to be careful of the inclement weather on the way as indicated by the excellent practical results in Black's favor here!} 6. Bc4 {This is only the third most likely move at Club Level play but a good one, and the second most popular move-- Nf3 --often turns into this anyway. White attack's f7 and gives up the idea of castling queenside with ultra speed. Black's response may surprise you.} Be6 {Black boldly takes on doubled pawns, knowing the position has some secrets that make them okay here. Well, more than okay. Okay, if White really knows what they're doing and downright better if White doesn't. A very tricky variation.} 7. Bxe6 fxe6 {Accepting doubled isolated pawns. Now before you panic, let's look at some statistics. In Lichess games of Club Players, Black wins 48% to White's 42% after 6. Be6 . In Master level games only, White only has a tiny 3% edge over Black in the mainline and even in Master level play, White often doesn't play the right move here--the right move is literally the third choice of masters--and loses more than they win. Why? Because the e6 pawn stops all invading knights, is practically unattackable and allows the c-pawn to stay back and defend the bishop-- c6 is no longer necessary.} 8. Nf3 Bd6 {Unlike the Bg5 line where the king went to c8 and a pawn went to c6 , When we have doubled pawns, we want to put our king on e7 to guard the doubled pawns and move the bishop to d6 , keeping the c-pawn back. Why? Because e6 guards the knight outposts and we don't need c6 . If the c-pawn is staying back, then a bishop on d6 completely shuts down the d-file, leaving White struggling to find a plan.  The key move for White in this queenless middlegame is often f4 , which now undoubles our pawns. This leaves White to figure out how to proceed and it's not easy. Our king will be quite safe in the center as we have two pawns stacked up protecting us! While White is having an existential crisis on what to do with the position, we will pawn storm against the enemy king} 9. Bg5 Ke7 {We're coming for you White! Most White players castle queenside, but if they castled kingside, we'd do the same thing on the other side of the board. Open a file and attack!} 10. O-O-O a6 {We are pawn storming the queenside to activate our rook! It's going to be so much fun!} 11. h3 {I have no idea why most White players play this move, but they do.} Nbd7 {The d7 square is useful for our knight, it both defends f6 one more time and overprotects e5 .} 12. a3 b5 {Let's do this! Our rooks will slide behind our pawns and we will try to open a file.} 13. Rhe1 Rhb8 {14. Nd2 is the most popular move for White here but it has a horrible win rate. So here, let's prepare for the almost-as-played move, 14. Na2 , which does much better in practice.} 14. Na2 a5 {This position is technically almost equal--Black up -0.23 according to Stockfish 14--but easier to play with Black. We will just queenside pawn storm. In this position Black has a winning record despite the engine's equal evaluation. Opening up files and attacking with your rooks is just very easy to play practically. The best way to achieve that is to play b4 without allowing a4 and b3 . So moving our knight to guard a4 first seems in order via c5 or b6 .} *

