1. e4 d6 {See 'The First Three Moves' Chapter for explanations on the first three moves of the Philidor.} 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 {Most Club Players take this pawn and trade queens despite the fact that Black has better results than White in the resulting queenless middlegame.} dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {It looks like Black hasn't castled and so is worse but actually White has a harder time unless they really know what they're doing, at which point the game is about equal. This is part of the trickiness of the Philidor: things that look good for White are a bit of an optical illusion. Here, the knight on c3 is going to be much easier to attack than Black's b8 knight, which is headed to d7 . Because Bb4 and c6  b5 - b4 can all hit the comparatively weaker c3 knight, White will struggle much more to defend e4 than Black will to defend e5 if White isn't precise. It takes a keen eye to spot this critical difference here, making many Club Players think they are better or, at least, like they have reached a drawish position. Practically, White is in trouble unless they have studied the line. If they have studied the line, they can look forward to an equal and interesting game.} 6. Nf3 {A natural move. But f4 is White's key move in the Bg5 variation and f3 in the Bc4 variation, so ultimately probably a weak move.} Bd6 ({This line will usually just directly transpose with Bc4} 6... Be6 {or Bg5 Be6 and a similar Black strategic plan as the mainline Bg5 lines... albeit Black has committed the bishop to d6 which is odd, but in return, f4 , White's main plan of attack, is thwarted by their own knight. The f4 plan being thwarted is more of a plus for us than having our bishop on a non-ideal square for a move or two--the tempo shouldn't be so critical. The move Nf3 right away is common at club level even though I don't consider it as serious a try as the two bishop moves and usually it just converts into one of them. Just remember to defend the pawn with your bishop instead of your knight against it so that the c8 bishop isn't trapped in! Then pawn storm at the White king, regardless of which side of the board it lands on. Note that some White players on this move or in the future fall for Nb5 trying to win the bishop pair, which itself is not even very scary as the bishop on d6 isn't excellent and it will un-isolate our pawns. But in this case, it's just a blatant mistake for tactical as well as strategic reason: Nxe4 oops!}) *

