[PlyCount "24"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. d5 c6 {Again, early d5 pushes can be reacted to practically as in the 'Pawns are the Souls of Chess' chapter with decent results for Black. But if White pushes this pawn really early, c6 is almost always a good move.} 5. Bg5 {This is similar to other variations but White has held out on committing to dxc6 . It's not very good but very popular at the Club Player level.} Nbd7 {We want to recapture on f6 with a knight so we don't lose control of the d5 square.} 6. Nf3 {This position can also be reached with White playing Nf3 on move 4 and d5 later and hopefully illustrates that an early d5 push and a super early d5 push ultimately result in the same thing unless White is playing very bad moves. In the chapter, I list this early push in the Tension Variation part because most Masters play Nf3 entering the Tension variation before playing d5 . So, I decided to list it with d5 first in the Club Player Quickstarter, just to show you how this position can come up in multiple ways. Our moves remain the same: early d5 will be responded to with c6 by Black, Bg5 will be responded to by h6 eventually and Nf3  Nbd7 can be added at various moments.} h6 {We are trying to kick the bishop off the c1 - h6 diagonal.} 7. Bh4 {Not a terribly good move but a natural one if they're used to playing the Ruy Lopez. The only problem for White is that it's a different bishop and this isn't the Ruy Lopez.} cxd5 {We are ready to try to win this square, especially since we have g5 in our back pocket to allow all our knights to contest the square.} 8. exd5 ({As mentioned earlier, White really wants to recapture the pawn with a minor piece anytime that Black takes, but tactically the White knight can't jump into action right now as} 8. Nxd5 g5 9. Bg3 Nxe4 {is just winning a pawn. The computer recommends Bxf6} 10. Nf6+ {instead, giving Black a slight edge with the bishop pair. But realistically, most opponents will just take back the pawn.}) 8... Be7 {Unpinning our knight and preparing to castle.} 9. Bb5 {The top move on Lichess games here.} a6 {We are happy when White gives us the bishop pair, so we play a useful move and ask White what the plan is.} 10. Ba4 {Now both White's bishops are on diagonals that don't have many retreat squares. So it's time to have them do some jail time.} b5 {Sentence the light-squared bishop to many moves of hard time in a b3 prison where it cannot move.} 11. Bb3 {The bishop is in chess jail.} g5 {Bishop two is going to be convicted, too.} 12. Bg3 {And we sentence the bishop of many moves to no moves: another bishop tragically in jail. The threat of f5 looms large.} Nc5 {Black is much better-- By 2.4 according to Stockfish. White's bishops are totally stuck and Black dominates both sides of the board. Bg4 and e4 are next on the agenda or perhaps b4 and h5 with wing attacks. We can trade off White's bishop for our knight to win the bishop pair at our leisure, usually taking the b3 bishop so that we can attack d5 . For example, look at White's minor pieces and try to move one forward without immediately losing it... impossible. White is suffocated and Black has so many plans to choose from.} *

