1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 ({This is the mainline of grandmasters but not common among Club Players. What are your chances of facing it? Well, according to Lichess, I've done some analysis: Here, at 1000-1400 in Lichess games, White is likely to play} 4. dxe5 {of a rate of about 3 to 1 over anything else. Nf3 ,the mainline for grandmasters, is only the third most played move in 1000-1400 rated games and you only have a 20% chance of facing it there. At 1400-2000, your chances of facing the GM mainline knight move stays the same at 1 in 5 (oddly, as it's a good move, but many players at this level get more excited about queen trades and initiative). At 2200-2500, the GM line will be the main move you will face. Anecdotally, in coaching, I noticed these stats carry over well to over-the-board classical chess play. That said, we need to dedicate a hefty portion of the quickstarter to it as it's one of the more dangerous options by White, a bit more complicated to play against, and I want you fully prepared--or at least Quickstarter prepared.}) 4... Nbd7 5. d5 {White tries to squeeze us.} c6 {Playing more in the style recommended in 'Pawns are the Soul of Chess' also works and I list it as an alternative line in the relevant chapter. As I mentioned in the aforementioned chapter, c6 is sometimes a good reply and against a very early d5 , it works marvelously. The main thing to know on d5  c6 is that if Black ever plays cxd5 and White recaptures on d5 with a minor piece, White tends to be better. However, if after we take on d5 , White retakes with a pawn, Black tends to be better. White cannot make us take until we're ready though.  And if they try to guard the d5 pawn with Bc4 to help them take back with a minor piece, we can respond with Nbd7 and Nb6 , hitting the bishop and d5 . Finally, if White has to lose the light-squared bishop to secure the d5 hole with a minor piece, we are usually fine with that: those positions work well for Black as they have trouble holding that square in the long term.} 6. dxc6 {A common line.} bxc6 {We always want to take back with out pawn to guard the d5 and b5 entry points. Now with an extra center pawn, Black usually will have a space advantage in the long run. Although the open d-file looks scary, the d6 pawn is immune thanks to the dark-squared bishop.} 7. Bg5 {The dark-squared bishop is often a piece we want. It guards important diagonals and so when White puts it on g5 , we will almost always invite it to trade with us and play h6 . If it declines and play Bh4 , it won't guard many important diagonals and we will be able to play moves like Qb6 or even kingside attack with g5 , rendering it moveless.} h6 {Asking the bishop whether it wants to be banished to oblivion by moving back, give us the bishop pair or admit its mistake and go back to e3 where we can further harass it with Ng4 . Those options are bleak.} 8. Bxf6 {The main Club Player move.} Nxf6 {The knight helps us play d5 later with domination of the center--though don't hang e5 . The two bishops will offer a long-term advantage.} 9. Bc4 {Let's just assume White plays normal moves.} Be7 {We want to castle quickly before playing in the center.} 10. O-O O-O {We castle as well before embarking on central conquests. With the bishop pair, we want to open the position later.} 11. Qe2 Qb6 {And already, White is missing the dark-squared bishop.  b2 is threatened.} 12. b3 {The most common Club Player move--it defends b2 without making a rook passive.} Qa5 {Whenever White plays b3 , the c3 and a3 squares are weakened so we attack them. The queen also supports d5 later on this square.} 13. Na4 Bg4 {Black usually can't develop this bishop very easily in the Philidor, but here it works well as we are planning a center explosion with d5 and a later e4 possibly.} 14. h3 {White often feels annoyed with this bishop and asks us if we're willing to depart with the bishop pair.} Bh5 {We keep the bishop and maintain the pin. Black has a 1.3 point advantage according to the engine. d5 will happen soon with a center pawn advantage. The move g4 is possible but then e4 will be feeling some serious heat and White's kingside will be broken.} *

