1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 ({This is the mainline of grandmasters but not common among Club Players. What are your chances of facing it? Well, according to Lichess, I've done some analysis: Here, at 1000-1400 in Lichess games, White is likely to play} 4. dxe5 {of a rate of about 3 to 1 over anything else. Nf3 ,the mainline for grandmasters, is only the third most played move in 1000-1400 rated games and you only have a 20% chance of facing it there. At 1400-2000, your chances of facing the GM mainline knight move stays the same at 1 in 5 (oddly, as it's a good move, but many players at this level get more excited about queen trades and initiative). At 2200-2500, the GM line will be the main move you will face. Anecdotally, in coaching, I noticed these stats carry over well to over-the-board classical chess play. That said, we need to dedicate a hefty portion of the quickstarter to it as it's one of the more dangerous options by White, a bit more complicated to play against, and I want you fully prepared--or at least Quickstarter prepared.}) 4... Nbd7 5. d5 c6 {Playing more in the style recommended in 'Pawns are the Soul of Chess' also works and I list it as an alternative line in the relevant chapter. As I mentioned in the aforementioned chapter, c6 is sometimes a good reply and against a very early d5 , it works marvelously. The main thing to know on d5  c6 is that if Black ever plays cxd5 and White recaptures on d5 with a minor piece, White tends to be better. However, if after we take on d5 , White retakes with a pawn, Black tends to be better. White cannot make us take until we're ready though.  And if they try to guard the d5 pawn with Bc4 to help them take back with a minor piece, we can respond with Nbd7 and Nb6 , hitting the bishop and d5 . Finally, if White has to lose the light-squared bishop to secure the d5 hole with a minor piece, we are usually fine with that: those positions work well for Black as they have trouble holding that square in the long term.} 6. dxc6 bxc6 {Forced.} 7. Bc4 ({After this move, you should always fear} 7. Ng5 {. And to stop that nasty threat, you should prepare castling.}) 7... Be7 {We prepare to castle, as always, before embarking on central play.} 8. O-O h6 {Many moves are possible, and eventually Black will play for d5 , but there's no rush, hopefully you didn't click too many alternatives before finding your way here.  h6 cuts down on White's options--no analyzing Bg5 or Ng5 anymore--and prepares a safe place for the Black king for later to ensure no back rank checkmates happen. White's pride and joy is their bishop on c4 , and most of their other pieces are struggling. We will play against that bishop soon.} 9. Re1 O-O 10. h3 {h3 signals that White is thinking about playing Be3 . Generally, they might also want to prevent a bishop pin, but we don't often develop our light-squared bishop there anyway. So usually it's because they want to get out their dark-squared bishop but are worried that we can go bishop hunting with Ng4 . So that's a preparatory move. If the bishop is on e3 , it might be harder to play Nc5 without damaging our structure, so we should act fast.} Nc5 {Black has a miniscule advantage (essentially equal after White has played computer moves). We will play a5 to secure our knight, maybe even a4 afterwards, and then a bishop e6 next to eventually neutralize that white light-squared bishop. We have more center pawns and an open b-file with active pieces that are tying White up, who must defend e4 . Now Be3 will drop the e4 pawn and we also could play Nfd7 to guard our c5 knight if needed. The issue with developing the dark-squared bishop for White and the attacks on b2 make me enjoy playing Black over White here regardless of objectivity.} *

