1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 ({This is the mainline of grandmasters but not common among Club Players. What are your chances of facing it? Well, according to Lichess, I've done some analysis: Here, at 1000-1400 in Lichess games, White is likely to play} 4. dxe5 {of a rate of about 3 to 1 over anything else. Nf3 ,the mainline for grandmasters, is only the third most played move in 1000-1400 rated games and you only have a 20% chance of facing it there. At 1400-2000, your chances of facing the GM mainline knight move stays the same at 1 in 5 (oddly, as it's a good move, but many players at this level get more excited about queen trades and initiative). At 2200-2500, the GM line will be the main move you will face. Anecdotally, in coaching, I noticed these stats carry over well to over-the-board classical chess play. That said, we need to dedicate a hefty portion of the quickstarter to it as it's one of the more dangerous options by White, a bit more complicated to play against, and I want you fully prepared--or at least Quickstarter prepared.}) 4... Nbd7 5. d5 c6 {Playing more in the style recommended in 'Pawns are the Soul of Chess' also works and I list it as an alternative line in the relevant chapter. As I mentioned in the aforementioned chapter, c6 is sometimes a good reply and against a very early d5 , it works marvelously. The main thing to know on d5  c6 is that if Black ever plays cxd5 and White recaptures on d5 with a minor piece, White tends to be better. However, if after we take on d5 , White retakes with a pawn, Black tends to be better. White cannot make us take until we're ready though.  And if they try to guard the d5 pawn with Bc4 to help them take back with a minor piece, we can respond with Nbd7 and Nb6 , hitting the bishop and d5 . Finally, if White has to lose the light-squared bishop to secure the d5 hole with a minor piece, we are usually fine with that: those positions work well for Black as they have trouble holding that square in the long term.} 6. Bc4 Nb6 {A common maneuver for Black. The rule to guide you here is only take on d5 if White must take back with a pawn or give up the light-squared bishop. This knight move will achieve these possibilities. Generally, we are not afraid of trading pawns on c6 if White wishes and we will recapture with our pawn. We also want to avoid playing c5 most of the time as it pairs poorly with a5 and yields a lot of space. Here, we haven't played a5 yet so it may be okay but let's keep things consistent.} 7. Bb3 {White attempts to keep an eye on d5 .} cxd5 {Again, if you force White to put a pawn here or give you their bishop, you should be good. Why? Well a pawn taking back will give you a lot more center space and you can even attack the kingside. If they have to lose their bishop, then you will have an uncontested light-squared bishop and eventually get in some central burst.} 8. Nxd5 {White hopes you will not recapture their knight and allow a hole on d5 . But we don't have to give them this charity.} Nbxd5 9. exd5 {Or we would eat an enemy bishop there.} Be7 {Surprise, surprise, we prepare to castle before initiating action in the center.} 10. O-O O-O {Castling means we are prepared for central action. Always safeguard your king instead of rushing!} 11. c4 {White tries to start queenside play as they have very little breathing room on the kingside.} Bg4 {The pin is annoying as Black can push the pawn and threaten the knight and Qd3 doesn't help anything as 12... e4 still forks. And Qc2 Bxf3 cripples the White kingside with doubled pawns.} 12. h3 Bh5 {And Black has many of the same threats as before, forcing White to weaken their king substantially.} 13. g4 Bg6 {And Black has a clear advantage. White's kingside pawns are too extended and f5 will open everything up for an attack. We can just leave our queenside pawns where they are.} *

