1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 ({This is the mainline of grandmasters but not common among Club Players. What are your chances of facing it? Well, according to Lichess, I've done some analysis: Here, at 1000-1400 in Lichess games, White is likely to play} 4. dxe5 {of a rate of about 3 to 1 over anything else. Nf3 ,the mainline for grandmasters, is only the third most played move in 1000-1400 rated games and you only have a 20% chance of facing it there. At 1400-2000, your chances of facing the GM mainline knight move stays the same at 1 in 5 (oddly, as it's a good move, but many players at this level get more excited about queen trades and initiative). At 2200-2500, the GM line will be the main move you will face. Anecdotally, in coaching, I noticed these stats carry over well to over-the-board classical chess play. That said, we need to dedicate a hefty portion of the quickstarter to it as it's one of the more dangerous options by White, a bit more complicated to play against, and I want you fully prepared--or at least Quickstarter prepared.}) 4... Nbd7 {Guarding e5 .} 5. Bc4 {This natural move is common in both high-level and non-professional games at this point--though in non-professional games, White usually exchanges pawns on e5 and swaps queens so I really do mean 'after 5. Nf3 ' this is the most common follow up.} Be7 {As soon as we see 5. Bc4 , we always play 5... Be7 because Ng5 is scary. For example:} (5... a5 6. Ng5 {would have been a disaster.}) 6. O-O ({It's not a mainline, but Black should know that} 6. Bxf7+ Kxf7 7. Ng5+ {is a bit tricky... the idea is to play 8. Ne6 so} Kg8 8. Ne6 Qe8 9. Nxc7 Qg6 10. Nxa8 Qxg2 {and if you know this idea of counterattacking g2 , you should be able to play this out no matter what White does and find plenty of compensation... if we ever trap the knight, we are also winning as the rook is worth less than the white bishop and knight.}) 6... O-O {Safeguarding our king.} ({Sometimes a4} 6... c6 7. Re1 {Re8 is played which will just transpose.}) 7. Re1 ({Again, common for all rating ranges and the best move. After all, if White has made it this far, they probably know a little book. The idea of Re1 is to guard e4 , freeing up their knight and being flexible in terms of where they put their other pieces. It's worth mentioning why} 7. Re1 {is important in case you need to punish them for not playing it. Once Black takes on d4 , they will begin piling up on the e4 pawn and White will want to play f3 to just guard everything. But if they haven't moved their rook, then the bishop on e3 will suddenly be hanging in variation after variation because the f-pawn isn't guarding it.   So to punish an opponent going out of book and not playing Re1 , play Re8 and attack e4 . Once White plays f3 to guard it look for a d5 break to take advantage of a potentially vulnerable e3 bishop.}) 7... c6 {The ideas of c6 are as follows: We want to develop our queen to connect our rooks and c6 gives it many possible locations--it will usually go to c7 as that's a very safe square but who knows.  c6 also makes the c3 knight very neutralized as it has no path forward. Finally, c6 contains a bit of poison as if White isn't careful, we will play b5 and a5  b4 and attack the queenside--if we kick the c3 knight, e4 will we weaker, already showcasing the wisdom of White overguarding it. Usually White will stop us if they understand these subtleties of the position.} 8. a4 {White stops b5 . This is the best move and a sign of a well-studied opponent. But don't worry: these lines are fine for Black even against people who study ahead of time.} a5 {Black stops a5 and the resulting positional bind.} 9. h3 {A useful move that stops Ng4 . White is trying to play Be3 .} Re8 {Ng5 Rf8 is not very scary as the knight is misplaced and we'll just kick it anyway--we have a pleasant decision about taking on d4 first when the knight can't recapture or just playing h6 and Re8 again. In the meantime, we are hoping to save a tempo in delaying h6 .} 10. Be3 {The most common Club Player move here and a very normal looking one.} h6 {Stopping Ng5 so we can put pieces on f8 for the rest of the game.} 11. Qd2 Bf8 {Stopping h6 sacrifices for now and preparing to open up the rook.} 12. Rad1 exd4 {Now that Black has put a piece on f8 , we need a place for our d7 knight. How about c5 or e5 ? All we need to do to help it is take on d4 .} 13. Bxd4 Qc7 {The queen will almost always go here in these grandmaster variations.} 14. Nh4 {The knight heads to f5 to be a menace. Whenever we see this, we should try to stare at f5 with our c8 bishop.} Ne5 {Our bishop will take the knight on f5 when it arrives and we will play for d5 after we do so. Alternatively, if White never plays it there, we can play Be6 ourselves and trade the bishops to secure a very playable position.} *

