1. e4 d6 {See the First Three Moves for more information on why these moves.} 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 ({This is the mainline of grandmasters but not common among Club Players. What are your chances of facing it? Well, according to Lichess, I've done some analysis: Here, at 1000-1400 in Lichess games, White is likely to play} 4. dxe5 {of a rate of about 3 to 1 over anything else. Nf3 ,the mainline for grandmasters, is only the third most played move in 1000-1400 rated games and you only have a 20% chance of facing it there. At 1400-2000, your chances of facing the GM mainline knight move stays the same at 1 in 5 (oddly, as it's a good move, but many players at this level get more excited about queen trades and initiative). At 2200-2500, the GM line will be the main move you will face. Anecdotally, in coaching, I noticed these stats carry over well to over-the-board classical chess play. That said, we need to dedicate a hefty portion of the quickstarter to it as it's one of the more dangerous options by White, a bit more complicated to play against, and I want you fully prepared--or at least Quickstarter prepared.}) 4... Nbd7 {Guarding e5 .} 5. g4 g6 {For the quickstarter, just memorize playing g6 against g4 and not taking the seemingly free pawn. Fianchetto your bishop and play natural moves for a fun game! Why? Because g4 omits Bc4 so we have extra time to develop our bishop to an even better square! Also, practically speaking, this move is easiest to play with natural moves and you won't encounter this much until you get to higher-rated opponents. Please see the chapter if your opponent starts booking up against this sideline.} *

