1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 {Our preferred move order for reaching the Hanham variation of the Philidor.} 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 Be6 {This may look like just bad chess but the doubled pawns are actually great and White doesn't have much of an edge here. See the Club Player Quickstarter for a more detailed explanation.} 7. Bxe6 fxe6 {The e6 pawn can only be attacked by a knight and Ke7 will guard it. So we will prevent Nb5 and play Bd6  Ke7 with a good game. Next we will pawn storm the queenside.} 8. f3 {This is the Grandmaster move and a hard one to find over the board if you haven't studied this position. Most masters don't even find it! The idea is to attack e5 with a knight on d3 and possibly c4 . White will follow with Nh3 - Nf2 - Nd3 if they know what they are doing and try to attack the pawn. Very nuanced stuff!} a6 {8... c6 isn't necessary as the doubled pawn stops the c3 knight from making progress. But we do need to activate our rook by pawn storming. So far we proceed as if it's a Club Player line and see if White knows their stuff. If they don't know about the knight re-route, we'll continue as we did against 8. Nf3 in the Club Player Quickstarter with Bd6  Ke7 and a pawn storm.} 9. Nh3 {Probably the best move. White's moves are hard to find so expect only well prepared opponents here. It may look like Ng5 is a threat but the e6 pawn is secure. It's aiming for e5 via f2 and d3 .} Bd6 {Why Bd6 ? To neutralize the d-file. White's rooks aren't coming down that way with a bishop on d6 . Next, we want to play Ke7 against Ng5 . We don't want to play h6 just yet because then g4 - g5 might give White something later.} 10. Be3 ({A sensible move.} 10. Ng5 Ke7 {doesn't do much for White as we will get h6 in with tempo whenever we want, though honestly the knight doesn't do anything on g5 so no need to rush kicking it away.}) 10... Ke7 {When we have the doubled pawns, the king finds a nice safe haven on e7 , guarding a6 and practically immune from enemy attacks!} 11. Nf2 {White tries to relocate the knight to pressure e5 a little. But our bishop can hold it together.} c5 {This is a novelty but Black has many interesting tries here if you want to play it another way. The idea is to stop Nd3 and make White switch to a rook attack plan--not easy psychologically. The basics will be the same: pawn storm the queenside and take advantage of the bad c3 knight. The cons of c5 are that they weaken the d-file. The plusses are that White's knights will find it very hard to move, c4 and d3 will be covered by the advance. So it's a double-edged move, but let's try for a win! Don't panic because this is also computer checked and not only just as good as the other options but very different. When we have a very prepared opponents, novelties give even more practical advantage because it breaks their Stockfish lines and makes them think on their own!} 12. Nb1 {Even though the move c5 hasn't been played according to my classical chess database, I did find casual games played on Lichess with it. The move played by the most high-rated player on Lichess was a knight reroute: still going for those knights!} c4 {Stopping Nd3 and gaining space on the queenside.} 13. b3 {One attempt White might try to remove the c4 pawn though at this point, we're just playing chess.} Rc8 {With an interesting game ahead where we are pressing on the queenside. The doubled pawns look good for White but they're very hard to attack and help clog the file to protect our king. Since White should play on the kingside, it's difficult to figure out a plan that doesn't involve f4 , undoubling the pawns. So Black has great chances here as White must decide between counterplay that solves Black's problems or just taking the queenside beating. If White ever attacks down the d-file, Rc6 will guard the bishop while doubling.} *

