[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 {Our preferred move order for reaching the Hanham variation of the Philidor.} 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 {White aims to castle queenside quickly.} Be6 {Critically clearing the c8 square for our king should White castle queenside and ensuring the bishop is out so that we can develop our knight with Nbd7 without blocking it in. The c8 bishop is one of the trickiest to develop in the Philidor Queen trade line if you don't do it right away so it's always a high priority. As a final advantage, White's light-squared bishop finds a shortage of squares to go to once you play this move.} 7. O-O-O+ Kc8 {Let's get out of any pins! We will activate our a8 rook by playing a5 and moving the queenside pawns.} 8. f4 {A great and unobvious move. What's the idea for White? First, they want to crush you to death with f5 and have your bishop be banished to oblivion. Second, if you take, they want to play Bf4 at some point and stop your king lift to c7 --preventing you from using both your rooks. Very bold for someone who traded queens. But Black can equalize here, which is why most opening manuals avoid the queen trade line even if White knows the correct and most pressing follow up.} exf4 {We can't allow f5 with a crush-to-death plan. The tempo off our Be6 will be brutal and so we must take when we have a bishop there.} 9. Nge2 {9. Bxf4 is also possible and a line we will cover in depth in the later chapter along with 9. e5 . That said, those are sidelines. For the quick starter, let’s continue with the mainline of mainline and the most popular GM move. The idea of Nge2 is to recapture f4 with a knight and attack our e6 bishop. In White’s ideal world they win the bishop pair and gain dynamic play up the middle of the board.} Bd6 {The idea is when the knight takes on f4 , we attack whatever friend is guarding it. This forces White to make a big concession. I have an alternative with Nbd7 in the relevant chapter that has a very different character. I like the text because it’s relatively easy to understand and a bit off the beaten path while still equalizing.} 10. Nxf4 {The most popular and consistent move although other tries are examined in a later chapter. White threatens to win the bishop pair. But again, in all cases, whenever White takes back, we just look for the knight's friend and attack it...} h6 {The point of Bd6 : the idea is you will take the knight with check so Bxf6 isn’t possible. This is very forcing and so easier to remember than other lines. White only has one move that doesn't lose a piece!} 11. Nxe6 {The only move as we would have taken their knight if the bishop had moved.} hxg5 {We take off the delicious dark-squared bishop which will create long term issues for White on the dark squares. We are not interested in taking back the knight when White would have retained the bishop pair.} 12. Nxg7 ({If} 12. Nxg5 Bf4+ {will win the knight, so this is the only take-able pawn.}) 12... Bf4+ {We want to play c6  Kc7  Nbd7 and complete our development. Our compensation is long term... the white bishop will always be weaker than the dark-squared one and the e4 and h2 pawns will always be a bit of a liability. So there's no rush. Avoid Rxh2 before completing development, as then you develop their undeveloped rook and the attack on f7 will win back the pawn for them anyway.   So all that said, if we are going to play c6 to lift the king and connect the rooks, then we need to move the bishop so it doesn't get eaten by the d1 rook, and hence the check on f4 .} 13. Kb1 {The only move and a small plus for us as now White’s king is just a little further from the center and they may even have to waste a tempo later to avoid back rank checkmates.} Nbd7 {And a fairly even game has arisen where White cannot stop the c6  Kc7 plan. Black has lots of pressure on the files and good play. If you'd prefer to be up the pawn but have a dynamic disadvantage--opposite of this--I list an option in the alternatives in the relevant chapter.   Why do we have compensation? Well, the dark squares are just so weak for White. The h-pawn and e-pawn in particular are annoying to defend. Even Be5 - Bxc3 could be played at some point. More explanation is given in the chapter with theoretical moves extending past here but here's the last comment I'll make for the quickstarter: even if White somehow defends e4 , h2 and the dark-squares, the opposite color bishop ending make this a drawish position in the worst case scenario.   Not surprisingly, the engine is giving this as 0.0 equality and Black actually has things to attack and do while White has to miserably sit there and defend everything so I like Black practically speaking. In terms of play, just leap frog on the dark squares and attack pawns for the rest of the game and enjoy superior piece activity. White has no easy way of activating their pieces so it’s a long term compensation rather than requiring anything immediate.} *

