1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 {Our preferred move order for reaching the Hanham variation of the Philidor.} 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 {The move recommended in the Grandmaster Repertoire: 1. e4 series, and the top choice among high-level players. Of course, Bd3 and f3 are also possible as seen in the chapter. But you can, for now, just play normal moves against them and we will focus on the most popular top level plans.} Nbd7 5. g4 {The Shirov Gambit is always a nice scare at the high levels. Taking the pawn is the principled choice and objectively probably best but practically horrible. In both GM games and amateur games, accepting a teeny disadvantage in order to not play White's game has been incredibly effective. For example, White wins 49% to Black's 30% in Master games after Nxg4 (the computer move). After my recommendation of g6 (technically a teeny bit worse for Black), Black wins 31% to White's 28%. It's just much easier to play. For a full discussion of the strategy in this line and why g6 is great, click this link.} g6 {Why g6 ? Because Bc4  Ng5 is no longer threatened, so we can take a nicer diagonal than usual for our bishop. Plus, it stabilizes the h5 square so that on g5 , we can move there with our knight. That may seem like a passive square but it creates a nearly complete blockade against enemy assaults.} 6. g5 {White often lunges forward at some point or another. If they don’t, they have to worry about us capturing on g4 again and again.} Nh5 {The knight will always go here whenever White plays g5 . This stops the h-pawn from opening a file and eyes f4 , the other pawn break that would open a file. So it very much stunts White’s attack which psychologically gives us reasons to smile: Shirov Gambit players often hate being stymied like this.} 7. Be3 c6 {A multipurpose move, thinking about b5 one day, Qc7 or even Qa5 .} 8. Qd2 {White prepares queenside castling. It's hard to play a move like g4 and castle kingside after all.} Bg7 {Although Be7 is an option, if we had to play g6 , why not put the bishop on the long diagonal? Here it will help defend our king and even contribute to an attack sometimes.} 9. O-O-O Qc7 {Putting the queen on e7 is also an option but for complicated reasons is a bit more tactical, and I give it as an alternative in the relevant chapter. This move is easier to play. The queen guards e5 and gets off the awkward d-file in our usual way.} 10. Bh3 {Developing the bishop to c4 might run into pawn and piece attacks so often White tries to develop it actively on this diagonal.} Nb6 {This is our thematic move, eyeing c4 and offering a trade of bishops.} 11. Bxc8 Rxc8 {Technically White has a pull here in an engine versus engine battle. However, in human chess, I'd rather play Black. Why? Well, for example, the engine recommends the seemingly anti-positional b3 here to prevent knight moves. This weakens dark squares and allows Black eventual ways of opening files by pushing their a-pawn. Black has lots of moves to improve their position and the attack while White just looks all clogged up on the kingside making it difficult to play. Playing around in this position for awhile, there were often only moves by White and many options for Black. At some point, you can even consider sacrificing a pawn by playing Nf4 and nabbing that dark-squared bishop. This will open up your bishop and they won't be able to defend their dark-squares well. But for the pawn lovers, this is not required: feel free to just move your pieces over against the enemy king and enjoy your attack!} *

