1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 {Our preferred move order for reaching the Hanham variation of the Philidor.} 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 {The move recommended in the Grandmaster Repertoire 1. e4 and the top choice among high-level players. Of course, Bd3 and f3 are also possible as seen in the chapter. But you can, for now, just play normal moves against them and we will focus on the most popular top level plans.} Nbd7 5. Bc4 {White's Bc4 threatens Ng5 . So Black must play h6 or Be7 here to stop the threat. h6 would be the so-called Black Lion but the lack of development seems suspect.} Be7 6. Bxf7+ Kxf7 {Hold on to your seatbelts because we're in for a ride! The point is that White is sacrificing an entire bishop to weaken the e6 square and put a knight there with tempo.} 7. Ng5+ Kg8 ({Not} 7... Ke8 $4 8. Ne6 {and the queen is trapped or Kf8 Ne6 forking royalty. Just pretend you've castled and ignore the rook on h8 insisting you haven't. White must play extremely precisely because they are down a whole bishop. Even if they win the rook, the general rule is that two minor pieces beat out a rook even with some pawns thrown in early in the game. After all, there's a shortage of open files for the rooks and all of the minor pieces sacrificed had been developed.}) 8. Ne6 {Forking our queen and c7 pawn. Our next move should be easy to remember as the only possible way to not lose a queen.} Qe8 9. Nxc7 {White is happy that the material will be regained with interest. However, now it's our turn to have fun and counterattack!} Qg6 {This is a critical move to remember. White doesn't have time to defend g2 because we are one rook move away from just being up that bishop for two lousy pawns.} 10. Nxa8 ({Of course, White can get scared and play} 10. O-O Rb8 {but now they are down a piece so really must prove something quickly.  h6  Kh7 are ideas for Black in the future. Most Lichess players continue:} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. N3d5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bf8 {when the compensation isn't evident. Their most intense try is} 14. f4 {when multiple moves are winning for Black including Qxe4 , but simplest is just} h6 {to play Kh7 and White is losing momentum and the lost bishop will eventually be too much.}) 10... Qxg2 {Let's do a material count: White is up an exchange and a pawn in the short term. However, they have some not-so-small issues for their reckless aggression. Their pieces are out of gas: the knight on a8 will require some care and time to be a functional knight again, the rook on h1 is passive and on move 10 they have 'developed' really only one piece (the knight on c3 ). There's only one way for them to save the rook so their moves in this variation are very easy to predict.} 11. Rf1 exd4 {We must play aggressively in the short term to not allow White to consolidate their material advantage. How do we do that? By occupying those light squares: gaping holes in White's kingside. You can see the point of exd4 by noting that our knight on d7 had no move forward. So we clear e5 for it and once it gets to e5 , our bishop will come into the action to--either h3 or g4 depending on the tactics. Black wins 75% of the time in this position, we are not playing for perpetuals here.} 12. Qxd4 {White hopes to be able to play Qc4 + and fork your king and bishop. So there's really only one more move we have to remember to close out the game.} Ne5 {This is good for Black as Nfg4 and Nf3 are concrete threats that are hard to stop. To make matters worse, our bishops can come in the game. For example, Bh3 would make the f1 rook awkward. At the board you'll have to calculate after seeing whatever sad move White plays after this, but you have survived the scary part.} ({Here, the computer lists only f3 as giving Black a clear edge of -1.31, all other moves are nearly down a rook for White. And after} 12... Ng4 13. Qd5+ {not fxg4 because Bh4 + and you can block with your rook and allow Nf3 + or move away from the rook and watch it perish Nf7 Qc4 Yes, these are ridiculous defensive moves to find as White. Bh4+ Black is having all the fun with White's exposed king and lackluster development.}) *

