1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 {Our preferred move order for reaching the Hanham variation of the Philidor.} 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 {The move recommended in the Grandmaster Repertoire 1. e4 and the top choice among high-level players. Of course, Bd3 and f3 are also possible as seen in the chapter. But you can, for now, just play normal moves against them and we will focus on the most popular top level plans.} Nbd7 5. Bc4 {White's Bc4 threatens Ng5 . So Black must play h6 or Be7 here to stop the threat. h6 would be the so-called Black Lion but the lack of development seems suspect.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {a4 is sometimes played first but it transposes.} c6 8. a4 {White threatens a5 with a slow squeeze.} a5 {This is the mainline Philidor. White has essentially Five Plans here in GM play} {1. play b3 trying to play Ba3 and burst down the file with a later center push, 2. play Nh4 with the idea to play Nf5 combined with Qf3 and a kingside attack, 3. play Be3 with the idea of battering down the diagonal with Qd2 later and a natural aggressive setup, 4. play Ba2 and later adding a queen to the diagonal via Qe2 - c4 , hitting the f7 pawn when we move our rook, or 5. play d5 to open up the position a little. I really recommend the Tension Variation Master chapter to cover the five plans deeply. Given that this course is concise and philosophical whenever possible over variation heavy, it shouldn't be that much more work than most other Lifetime Course Quickstarters to do it the thorough way! But for the Quickstarter, I'll simplify and just advise that anytime White moves the queen, we should take on d4 (I actually make an exception in a few lines but for the Quickstarter, it's almost never wrong to deviate by following this rule and I'll try to show the lines where I do delay taking for a second here). For example, Qe2 exd4 will be a good path generally. We should then target the e4 pawn and aim to neutralize the bishop on c4 by sticking something on e6 . For waiting moves, Black can improve their position with the following moves:   h6   Re8    Qc7   Do those while you're waiting on the White queen. Finally, after b3 , we can also immediately take on d4 .} 9. h3 Re8 10. Be3 h6 11. Ba2 Qc7 {The queen is generally useful here, allowing the knight on d7 to transfer somewhere (either c5 or f8 ) without dropping the e5 pawn.} 12. Nh4 {Headed to f5 . When White threatens this, we can act with the following guidelines: if there is no bishop on the a2 - g8 diagonal, g6 is fine as long as it doesn't drop a pawn (here, there is both a bishop and it drops a pawn). If there is a bishop, we generally let the knight arrive on f5 and immediately eat it with our light squared bishop. Then we try to play d5 and block out the White bishop.} Nf8 {Preparing to eat a knight that lands on f5 .} 13. Qf3 exd4 {They moved the queen so we take on d4 .} 14. Bxd4 {Now plugging up the diagonal and getting a tempo on the bishop makes a lot of sense.} Ne6 15. Bxe6 {Best. White tries to preserve the bishop on d4 .} Bxe6 {The position is about equal. Black will aim to play d5 in the future. White has a nice center but the piece trades and bishop pair make this anyone's game. There have been four master games in this position with even results.} *

