1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 {Our preferred move order for reaching the Hanham variation of the Philidor.} 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 {The move recommended in the Grandmaster Repertoire 1. e4 and the top choice among high-level players. Of course, Bd3 and f3 are also possible as seen in the chapter. But you can, for now, just play normal moves against them and we will focus on the most popular top level plans.} Nbd7 5. Bc4 {White's Bc4 threatens Ng5 . So Black must play h6 or Be7 here to stop the threat. h6 would be the so-called Black Lion but the lack of development seems suspect.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {a4 is sometimes played first but it transposes.} c6 8. a4 {White threatens a5 with a slow squeeze.} a5 {This is the mainline Philidor. White has essentially Five Plans here in GM play} {1. play b3 trying to play Ba3 and burst down the file with a later center push, 2. play Nh4 idea to play Nf5 combined with Qf3 and a kingside attack, 3. play Be3 with the idea of battering down the diagonal with Qd2 later and a natural aggressive setup, 4. play Ba2 and later adding a queen to the diagonal via Qe2 - c4 , hitting f7 pawn when we move our rook, or 5. play d5 to open up the position a little. I really recommend the Tension Variation Master chapter to cover the five plans deeply. Given that this course is concise and philosophical whenever possible over variation heavy, it shouldn't be that much more work than most other Lifetime Course Quickstarters to do it the thorough way! But for the Quickstarter, I'll simplify and just advise that anytime White moves the queen, we should take on d4 (I actually make an exception in a few lines but for the Quickstarter, it's almost never wrong to deviate by following this rule and I'll try to show the lines where I do delay taking for a second here). For example, Qe2 exd4 will be a good path generally. We should then target the e4 pawn and aim to neutralize the bishop on c4 by sticking something on e6 . For waiting moves, Black can improve their position with the following moves:   h6   Re8    Qc7   Do those while you're waiting on the White queen. Finally, after b3 , we can also immediately take on d4 .} 9. b3 exd4 10. Nxd4 Ne5 {The bishop on c4 doesn't have a retreat square with b3 being played. The move Be2 will block the rook and allow d5 which is better for Black.} 11. Bf1 Re8 12. Ba3 Qb6 {Now that we know there's no Be3 , we get this ultra cool queen spot! Usually we have to put the queen on c7 , but whenever the dark-squared bishop can't go to e3 , this square opens up nicely!} 13. Qd2 {White prepares to put their pieces on the d-file.} Bg4 ({I call this the 'Magic Bishop' variation. The weird thing about this position is that White cannot kick the bishop as h3 loses to} 13... Bh3 14. gxh3 Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Nf3+ 16. Kh1 Nxd4) ({Also, f3 loses to Bxf3 and then gxf3} 13... Nf3+ {again we fork the queen and king with the pinned White knight powerless to stop us. So the bishop just hangs out in the middle of White's kingside. Black's next moves will be to activate their rooks and strive to play d5 or b5 one day.}) *

