[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "10"]

{1. White castles queenside quickly.   The white bishop in the way of queenside castling has only two active moves and since... Be3 Ng4 is awkward for White, who doesn't want to lose the bishop, most White players desiring to castle queenside have only one choice for the dark-squared bishop. Specifically, here, White often ends up playing Bg5 Be6 O-O-O Kc8 So let's call that plan the Bg5 variation.  When White checks us, we will often cower on c8 with our king. 2. White attacks the black f-pawn. Bc4 Be6 Bxe6 fxe6 Nf3 Bd6 Bg5 Ke7 O-O-O a6 . This gives Black useful doubled pawns: an open f-file, guarding knight outposts. Also, when we have doubled pawns, we want our king to go to e7 to defend them... that is to say after  Bd6 , don't block in your bishop. Let's call that White plan the Bc4 variation. There are, to be sure, other moves. For example, White can play Nf3 or f4 even. These are rare but we will cover them under the title 'Queen Exchange: Other Moves' as most of them are not so great and don't get their own chapter. 6. Nf3 , for example, will usually transpose to a bad version of one of the two plans above later, as White eventually has to get out a bishop. All this said, let's talk general plans in all these queenless middlegames. [Black's plan]1. Dark-square kingside play: Black wants to play on the dark squares on the kingside. Look for a timely Ng4 or even Nh5 in your games to initiate this kind of plan. Your dark squared bishop will look marvelous on c5 if you are going with this strategy and you will find that if White plays Nf3 before f4 , the f2 pawn is often lunch. If White plays f4 , generally we want to capture it before it shuts out our bishop and play Ng4 to Ne3 or Nf2 . White's dark squared bishop is valuable and we want it.   2.  Pawnstorm the queenside:  Black wants to activate the rook on a8 in many variations by pawn storming the queenside. This usually starts c6 and Kc7 if they need two rooks over there and then a5  b5  a4  b4 . Black attempts to open up a file or lodge in a piece against White's queenside. Unless you know what you're doing, generally do NOT play Nc6 as this stops your pawn storm. Instead, play Nbd7 and then either put it on c5 or c4 via b6 . Your light squared bishop almost always wants to go to e6 to contribute to your queenside expansion and it may need to be protected by 'h6' to keep out an intruding knight who seeks to capture it.   3. Wreck the pawns: Black sometimes takes advantage of the Nc3 's awkward placement and plays Bb4 and then Bxc3 to wreck up White's structure. The isolated c-pawns and isolated a pawn can be a headache for White at the expense of the bishop pair. If you ever encounter a White plan that you don't remember going over, choose one of the plans above based on the circumstances and just have some good old-fashioned Philidor fun. I promise you that this position packs a lot of punch and throughout the course, I'll be showing you how to punish White for common errors. I have used Lichess as a barometer for what people below Master will play. I have also included the hardest variations to go up against so that even if you play Magnus Carlsen, you will survive. The opening at least. So, what will White try to do to win here? Well, most of your losses will happen because of a kingside attack on your pawns. Let's get into it...  [White's plan] 1. Attack the kingside.  Usually f4 is White's main try because it helps get a bishop to f4 , delaying c6  Kc7 , and it allows for the occasional e5 push and attempt to force matters. After White has opened the f-file, expect some pressure down it.   2. Activate the knights. White has a pretty bad c3 knight. So White will often try to reroute the horse through d5 or even e5  Ne4 . If White can manage to trade one of their knights for your bishop, especially your light-squared one, and not take too many weaknesses in return, White will be very happy.    3. Keep the initiative. White's edge grows smaller with every quiet move as Black unwinds. Therefore, it's critical that White attack you and play actively or they could end up worse.   As we go through these lines, remember our goal is to accomplish our plan and foil our opponent's. That's what chess is all about.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {This is the queen trade line. White believes that it's worth it to go into the non-optimal 'White takes Black's pawn' line because they deny Black castling rights. It's worth pointing out the plans for both sides in the abstract here before we get into the concrete. So, White has two main tries that you're most likely to face: What do they have in common?  In both, we will pawn storm wherever the enemy king decides to castle: leading the way with a supported b5 if White castles queenside, and h6  g5 if White castles kingside. In both our knight will probably go to d7 and if White castles queenside, we will play for a5  b5  Rab8  a4  b4  b3 or if they castle kingside we will play h6  g5 and go on that wing.   What's the key thing to differentiate the Bg5 and Bc4 variations? Remember that when you have doubled e-pawns, your king needs to defend them with Ke7 in the Bc4 version. In the Bg5 version, you don't have doubled e-pawns so your king goes to c8 and later to c7 . That is very important. The other important difference is when you have doubled e-pawns, your doubled e-pawn defends d5 so you can keep your c-pawn back. If you don't have doubled e-pawns, you'll need to play c6 to keep the White knight out of your kingdom.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Queen Trade (6. Bg5)"]
[Black "The Club Player Mainline: (6."]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 {They might be playing this to trade queens and go for a draw or to play for a win by depriving you of your castling rights, but it's not scary and it's not a draw.} dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {See the introduction for information on what's happening here generally. For now, we'll dive into the specifics of a popular way to play as White that just doesn't work well for them.} 6. Bg5 {White develops the bishop and prepares to castle queenside following a 'when in doubt, go for check' mantra. This is popular because many players think if you haven't castled, it's time to go for mate and the lack of queens doesn't discourage them. Sometimes, there's something to that way of thinking but here, we will have plenty of defensive resources and are not getting mated.} Be6 {Black's main plan here is to play his king to c8 and later c7 and storm the queenside. Additionally, attacking the f2 pawn can be an amazing tactical resource.} 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 {Getting off the long file and preparing for a queen pawn storm! It's going to be fun!} 8. Nf3 {I'm not wild about this move for White. It blocks f4 which is a main trump for White in this structure (see Pawns are the Soul of Chess) . Nonetheless, this is very natural. It gets out a knight, attacks a pawn. Also, in practice, the Queen trade players fall into two categories: 1. Those who love this endgame and know it, 2. Those who want a draw and regard it as 'safe.' 'Safe' players tend to be afraid of a move like f4 which invites an isolated pawn and doesn't develop a piece. To be clear, f4 is definitely best. But your average draw-mongering lower-rated opponent is scared of it. So they will play Nf3 . And probably lose. The stats? Black wins 51%, they draw 36%, and White wins 13%. It may shock you to see this position and discover that Black wins more than White victories and draws put together. And this psychological disbelief is largely responsible for so many White demises. The position is tricky. Please refer to the pawn structure section on why this isn't symmetrical.} Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. Bb5 {The most popular move on Lichess in this position by players sub-2000. This move doesn't make sense positionally. Black wants to pawn storm (see chapter on Pawns are the Soul of Chess) and White just encourages c6 . However, most White players at the pre-Master level don't understand this structure very well. They do want to follow general chess wisdom of developing pieces actively and, well, Be2 and Bd3 didn't look very active. Their knight had no useful moves, so by process of elimination, they arrive here. Black wins 61% of games to White's 32% according to the Lichess database here in lower level games. This way of playing has never been played by White in Master games and we are about to see why.} c6 10. Ba4 {10. Be2 is better conceding that they allowed Black c6 for free. But White players don't like to admit mistakes so will often retreat the bishop. Here, Black can play many moves for a positional edge. Bc5 , Kc7 (with the idea of connecting the rooks and playing b5  a5 ), Ng4 (attacking the weak f2 pawn), a5 , Be7 . All are black edges. So I'll just choose one move here that looks incredibly good among many.} Bb4 ({Threatening the pawn, e.g., a3? Bxc3 bxc3} 10... Nxe4 {.}) 11. Bxf6 {Trying to relieve the pressure on the e-pawn to avoid doubled c-pawns. But like the early trade of these pieces, this one smells.} gxf6 12. Ne2 {White should admit defeat here and just play the retreat Bb3 , accepting horrible pawns after Bxc3 . But it's hard practically and Black's next double attack is easy to miss. For those wanting something very easy to play, you can play the text here and Black is much better with an easy-to-play pawn storm and a free e4 pawn. But the a2 pawn is hanging and for those wanting the objectively best, most ruthless line possible (or for those just interested in learning how Black can keep gobbling a2 and live to tell about it) . I have my 2200+ alternative waiting for you...} Nc5 {Attacking e4 and the bishop and showing why we delayed b5 .} 13. Bb3 Nxe4 {Black is up a pawn and his queenside play is still going on. White will have to passively guard the f2 pawn before even dreaming of counterplay.} *

