1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {7... Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. Nf3 {I'm not wild about this move for White. It blocks f4 which is a main trump for White in this structure (see Pawns are the Soul of Chess) . Nonetheless, this is very natural. It gets out a knight, attacks a pawn. Also, in practice, the Queen trade players fall into two categories: 1. Those who love this endgame and know it, 2. Those who want a draw and regard it as 'safe.' 'Safe' players tend to be afraid of a move like f4 which invites an isolated pawn and doesn't develop a piece. To be clear, f4 is definitely best. But your average draw-mongering lower-rated opponent is scared of it. So they will play Nf3 . And probably lose. The stats? Black wins 51%, they draw 36%, and White wins 13%. It may shock you to see this position and discover that Black wins more than White victories and draws put together. And this psychological disbelief is largely responsible for so many White demises. The position is tricky. Please refer to the pawn structure section on why this isn't symmetrical.} Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. Bb5 {The most popular move on Lichess in this position by players sub-2000. This move doesn't make sense positionally. Black wants to pawn storm (see chapter on Pawns are the Soul of Chess) and White just encourages c6 . However, most White players at the pre-Master level don't understand this structure very well. They do want to follow general chess wisdom of developing pieces actively and, well, Be2 and Bd3 didn't look very active. Their knight had no useful moves, so by process of elimination, they arrive here. Black wins 61% of games to White's 32% according to the Lichess database here in lower level games. This way of playing has never been played by White in Master games and we are about to see why.} c6 10. Ba4 {Be2 is better conceding that they allowed Black c6 for free. But White players don't like to admit mistakes so will often retreat the bishop. Here, Black can play many moves for a positional edge. Bc5 , Kc7 (with the idea of connecting the rooks and playing b5  a5 ), Ng4 (attacking the weak f2 pawn), a5 , Be7 . All are black edges. So I'll just choose one move here that looks incredibly good among many.} Bb4 ({Threatening the pawn, e.g., a3? Bxc3 bxc3} 10... Nxe4 {.}) 11. Bxf6 {Trying to relieve the pressure on the e-pawn to avoid doubled c-pawns.} gxf6 12. Ne2 {White should admit defeat here and just play Bb3 , accepting horrible pawns. But it's hard practically. For those wanting something very easy to play, you can go Nc5 here and Black is much better with an easy-to-play pawn storm and a free e4 pawn. But the a2 pawn is hanging and for those wanting the best, most ruthless line possible...} Bxa2 {I give this as an alternative. It's even better than Nc5 - Nxe4 , but harder to learn slightly and a bit crazier. It is useful for getting a feel for these Philidor positions though even if you choose not to go this route.} 13. b3 {Probably White will play here to trap your bishop. Fine in theory, but the issue is that White's bishop is trapped too after b5 !} Ba3+ 14. Kd2 Nc5 {The knight hits e4 and the rook comes to d8 and life is hard for White.} 15. Ng3 {I think most players will guard the e4 pawn but everything loses.} b5 16. Ra1 Rd8+ ({It's useful to throw this move in. White's king doesn't have a good square: Ke2} 16... Nxa4 {and if} 17. Rxa2 Nc3 {forks the rook, or bxa4 Bc4+ clears the bishops so it's no longer trapped and we're up material.}) ({Ke1} 16... Bb4+ {Kf1 Nxa4 Rxa2 Rd1+} 17. Ke2 {Nc3+ Ke3 Bc5 Nd4 Bxd4 is a fun way to be ahead.}) ({Kc3} 16... Nxa4 17. bxa4 b4 {is a pretty finish.}) {Ke3 is probably the best of many bad options but you can calculate over the board the inferior moves without having to memorize every possibility.} 17. Ke3 Nxa4 {Shockingly, we don't need to take the bishop with the pawn if we have a bishop check.} 18. bxa4 Bc5+ 19. Ke2 Bc4+ 20. Ke1 Bb4+ {White has not only failed to get the bishop but they are losing everything here.} *

