1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. Nf3 {I'm not wild about this move for White. It blocks f4 which is a main trump for White in this structure (see Pawns are the Soul of Chess) . Nonetheless, this is very natural. It gets out a knight, attacks a pawn. Also, in practice, the Queen trade players fall into two categories: 1. Those who love this endgame and know it, 2. Those who want a draw and regard it as 'safe.' 'Safe' players tend to be afraid of a move like f4 which invites an isolated pawn and doesn't develop a piece. To be clear, f4 is definitely best. But your average draw-mongering lower-rated opponent is scared of it. So they will play Nf3 . And probably lose. The stats? Black wins 51%, they draw 36%, and White wins 13%. It may shock you to see this position and discover that Black wins more than White victories and draws put together. And this psychological disbelief is largely responsible for so many White demises. The position is tricky. Please refer to the pawn structure section on why this isn't symmetrical.} Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. Bb5 {The most popular move on Lichess in this position by players sub-2000. This move doesn't make sense positionally. Black wants to pawn storm (see chapter on Pawns are the Soul of Chess) and White just encourages c6 . However, most White players at the pre-Master level don't understand this structure very well. They do want to follow general chess wisdom of developing pieces actively and, well, Be2 and Bd3 didn't look very active. Their knight had no useful moves, so by process of elimination, they arrive here. Black wins 61% of games to White's 32% according to the Lichess database here in lower level games. This way of playing has never been played by White in Master games and we are about to see why.} c6 10. Ba4 {Be2 is better conceding that they allowed Black c6 for free. But White players don't like to admit mistakes so will often retreat the bishop. Here, Black can play many moves for a positional edge. Bc5 , Kc7 (with the idea of connecting the rooks and playing b5  a5 ), Ng4 (attacking the weak f2 pawn), a5 , Be7 . All are black edges. So I'll just choose one move here that looks incredibly good among many.} Bb4 {Threatening Bxc3 and Nxe4} 11. Rhe1 {Defending the e-pawn the natural way.} Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bxa2 {And Black is up in a decisive way. I usually reserve these pawn grabs for the 2200+ and big memorizer crowds. But here, the bishop can't even be trapped, so you don't even need to know a deep concrete line. If it gets attacked, just retreat it to e6 .} *

