1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 {Bg5 makes a lot of sense. White wants to castle queenside and check Black, trying to play against the uncastled king.} Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. Nf3 {I'm not wild about this move for White. It blocks f4 which is a main trump for White in this structure (see Pawns are the Soul of Chess) . Nonetheless, this is very natural. It gets out a knight, attacks a pawn. Also, in practice, the Queen trade players fall into two categories: 1. Those who love this endgame and know it, 2. Those who want a draw and regard it as 'safe.' 'Safe' players tend to be afraid of a move like f4 which invites an isolated pawn and doesn't develop a piece. To be clear, f4 is definitely best. But your average draw-mongering lower-rated opponent is scared of it. So they will play Nf3 . And probably lose. The stats? Black wins 51%, they draw 36%, and White wins 13%. It may shock you to see this position and discover that Black wins more than White victories and draws put together. And this psychological disbelief is largely responsible for so many White demises. The position is tricky. Please refer to the pawn structure section on why this isn't symmetrical.} Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. Bxf6 {The second most popular move at the club level and a mistake. Generally, we should always take this bishop back with the pawn. Note: White may play this at many points, so this study will be about principles as well as the specific variation of taking it now.} gxf6 {Black's pawn structure may look damaged but doubled pawns always have an upside: an extra open file. Here, the g-file is quite valuable. Additionally, Black now has three great places for their bishop to go: h6 , c5 , and b4 ! Finally, the f6 pawn prevents the knight from attacking our e6 bishop, stabilizing that scary gaze at White's kingside. In the endgame, we can always play f5 if we don't want the doubled pawns anymore, but for now, keep them back and tally ho on the kingside. I'll continue playing the most common club player moves.} 10. Nd5 {White could have played a litany of other moves, but typically club players like this move because it looks aggressive. Also, they want to play Nf5 later because it's consistent with Bxf6 doubling our pawns. Against other moves just do the usual c6  b5  a5  a4  b4 stuff and enjoy life.} c6 11. Ne3 {Again, White should not provoke c6 for free but White often has this vision on living on f5 with a knight. Black is winning in practically every line here though as the knight on f5 won't attack anything and we can just continue storming the gates.} b5 {This is my suggestion for the 99%. What's the best move?  Bxa2 . For sure. It just wins. Why don't I have it as my main suggestion? Well, it's a lot of memorization and you have to play precisely. For some, this is worth it: if not for the specifics, for the general ideas that the variation contains--and indeed, you may want to look through it even if you follow my suggested b5 . The issue is that it's a lot of precision play for a thematic position that you may encounter with slight variances in practice.  b5 is in the spirit of what you should usually play against this and almost all similar positions so it will ground you in the basic plan for Black.   Yes, it's not objectively as good as eating the a2 pawn and high-tailing it, but it will save you a ton of memorization for those with day jobs and some stress (this is far easier to play) . And Black wins close to 70% playing the move b5 here with a computer edge, so practically, Black just has a very nice easy-breezy game at the expense of a slight edge instead of a clear one. For Masters and those who don't mind some extra homework (or for those returning to this chapter after already completing the course), I give the alternative win line as separate. As I believe Shakespeare once said, 'How do I refute thee? Let me count the ways.'} 12. Kb1 {White really should defend this pawn as Bxa2 and then a5  a4 freeing it was looking good. Note even after you take on a2 , the other bishop can come to a3 to shy away the enemy king and combined with Nc5 , the attack is often deadly.} Kc7 {To connect the rooks so that our h8 rook can go to g8 or b8 .} 13. Nh4 a5 14. Nhf5 {White takes f5 ! Congratulations to them, they are now attacking air.} a4 {Black has played naturally and has an advantage with a plan of activating the other rook after a bishop move and trying to open files towards White's king. Black's knight can be deployed to either c5 or b6 and then c4 .} *

