1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. Nf3 {I'm not wild about this move for White. It blocks f4 which is a main trump for White in this structure (see Pawns are the Soul of Chess) . Nonetheless, this is very natural. It gets out a knight, attacks a pawn. Also, in practice, the Queen trade players fall into two categories: 1. Those who love this endgame and know it, 2. Those who want a draw and regard it as 'safe.' 'Safe' players tend to be afraid of a move like f4 which invites an isolated pawn and doesn't develop a piece. To be clear, f4 is definitely best. But your average draw-mongering lower-rated opponent is scared of it. So they will play Nf3 . And probably lose. The stats? Black wins 51%, they draw 36%, and White wins 13%. It may shock you to see this position and discover that Black wins more than White victories and draws put together. And this psychological disbelief is largely responsible for so many White demises. The position is tricky. Please refer to the pawn structure section on why this isn't symmetrical.} Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. Bxf6 {The second most popular move at the club level. Generally, we should always take this bishop back with the pawn.} gxf6 {Black's pawn structure may look damaged but doubled pawns always have an upside: an extra open file. Here, the g-file is quite valuable. Additionally, Black now has three great places for their bishop to go: h6 , c5 , and b4 ! Finally, the f6 pawn prevents the knight from attacking our e6 bishop, stabilizing that scary gaze at white's kingside. In the endgame, we can always play f5 if we don't want the doubled pawns anymore, but for now, keep them back and tally ho on the kingside. I'll continue playing the most common club player moves.} 10. Nd5 c6 11. Ne3 {Again, White should not provoke c6 for free but White often has this vision on living on f5 with a knight. Black is winning in practically every line here though as the knight on f5 won't attack anything and we can just continue storming the gates.} Bxa2 {White probably thought this bishop would be trapped, but Black is just winning the pawn and the game.} 12. b3 Ba3+ 13. Kd2 {Those excellent at calculating, can just trust that Black will have enough. Attack the king. That's the plan. For those that struggle tactically, memorizing the next sequence will help you secure the point. It's not as easy as b5 , but Black is nearly up a piece at the end of it.} Nc5 {Attacking e4 and clearing the way for Rd8 +. White can defend the pawn or go bishop hunting. Let's look at both.} 14. Ra1 {White goes bishop hunting.} Nxe4+ {Hitting some critical squares: the weak f2 pawn, the king, and the c3 square where it can protect the bishop and start operation rescue bishop with a5 - a4 and prying the b3 pawn out of the way.  Also, from c3 it will hit White's king if they go to e2 , which is the otherwise ideal location for the monarch.} 15. Ke2 (15. Kd3 Nxf2+ {gives Black a rook. Ke1 Bb4+} 16. Ke2 {Nc3+ and with the knight firmly on c3 , operation rescue bishop with a5 - a4 can commence. There's just no great place for the white king here and Black is going to be massively winning with accurate play.}) 15... Bb2 ({Bishop hunting is not going well for White. Now Rxa2 runs into} 15... Nc3+ {followed by capturing the rook.}) 16. Re1 {They can't even go to d1 because of the knight fork on c3 . Life is hard for White right now.} Nc3+ 17. Kd2 {Almost any move wins from here on out. Ne4 is good as is b5 . What follows is my opinion of the simplest way to close out the game though some may want to just stop here and rely on their intuition to guide them the rest of the way. The MoveTrainer will continue until five more moves to achieve a simplicity in the win.} Rd8+ {I like this move because it's easier to predict White's next move and so cuts down on memory.} 18. Bd3 b5 {Black is preventing Nc4 , trapping our bishop on b2 , and maybe even Bc4 later, guarding b3 and making our bishop on a2 stuck. Without the Nc4 resource for White, the move ... e4  next will fork White, so they have to act fast or they will be down a piece and again play is forcing.} 19. Nd1 {Guarding e4 and White's best.} Nxd1 20. Kxd1 {Forced or we play e4 : the rook must guard the pawn advance.} Rxd3+ {And now we can simplify, sacrificing the exchange to free our bishop and make the position easy to play.} 21. cxd3 Bxb3+ {Simplest. Now the bishop has escaped. Black has three pawns and a bishop for a rook, with the bishop pair and outside connected passed pawns. It's over.} 22. Ke2 Be6 {Black stops White's last gasp attempt: Rb1 , which would have won a bishop. Now the game should be easy for Black to play: go make a queen! Computer gives Black an edge the equivalent of being an entire minor piece up, -3.10, or, in other words, completely winning.} *

