1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. Nf3 {I'm not wild about this move for White. It blocks f4 which is a main trump for White in this structure (see Pawns are the Soul of Chess) . Nonetheless, this is very natural. It gets out a knight, attacks a pawn. Also, in practice, the Queen trade players fall into two categories: 1. Those who love this endgame and know it, 2. Those who want a draw and regard it as 'safe.' 'Safe' players tend to be afraid of a move like f4 which invites an isolated pawn and doesn't develop a piece. To be clear, f4 is definitely best. But your average draw-mongering lower-rated opponent is scared of it. So they will play Nf3 . And probably lose. The stats? Black wins 51%, they draw 36%, and White wins 13%. It may shock you to see this position and discover that Black wins more than White victories and draws put together. And this psychological disbelief is largely responsible for so many White demises. The position is tricky. Please refer to the pawn structure section on why this isn't symmetrical.} Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. Bxf6 {The second most popular move at the club level. Generally, we should always take this bishop back with the pawn.} gxf6 {Black's pawn structure may look damaged but doubled pawns always have an upside: an extra open file. Here, the g-file is quite valuable. Additionally, Black now has three great places for their bishop to go: h6 , c5 , and b4 ! Finally, the f6 pawn prevents the knight from attacking our e6 bishop, stabilizing that scary gaze at white's kingside. In the endgame, we can always play f5 if we don't want the doubled pawns anymore, but for now, keep them back and tally ho on the kingside. I'll continue playing the most common club player moves.} 10. Nd5 c6 11. Ne3 {Again, White