[PlyCount "38"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. Nf3 {I'm not wild about this move for White. It blocks f4 which is a main trump for White in this structure (see Pawns are the Soul of Chess) . Nonetheless, this is very natural. It gets out a knight, attacks a pawn. Also, in practice, the Queen trade players fall into two categories: 1. Those who love this endgame and know it, 2. Those who want a draw and regard it as 'safe.' 'Safe' players tend to be afraid of a move like f4 which invites an isolated pawn and doesn't develop a piece. To be clear, f4 is definitely best. But your average draw-mongering lower-rated opponent is scared of it. So they will play Nf3 . And probably lose. The stats? Black wins 51%, they draw 36%, and White wins 13%. It may shock you to see this position and discover that Black wins more than White victories and draws put together. And this psychological disbelief is largely responsible for so many White demises. The position is tricky. Please refer to the pawn structure section on why this isn't symmetrical.} Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. Bxf6 {The second most popular move at the club level. Generally, we should always take this bishop back with the pawn.} gxf6 {Black's pawn structure may look damaged but doubled pawns always have an upside: an extra open file. Here, the g-file is quite valuable. Additionally, Black now has three great places for their bishop to go: h6 , c5 , and b4 ! Finally, the f6 pawn prevents the knight from attacking our e6 bishop, stabilizing that scary gaze at white's kingside. In the endgame, we can always play f5 if we don't want the doubled pawns anymore, but for now, keep them back and tally ho on the kingside. I'll continue playing the most common club player moves.} 10. Nd5 c6 11. Ne3 {Again, White should not provoke c6 for free but White often has this vision on living on f5 with a knight. Black is winning in practically every line here though as the knight on f5 won't attack anything and we can just continue storming the gates.} Bxa2 {White probably thought this bishop would be trapped, but Black is just winning the pawn and the game.} 12. b3 Ba3+ 13. Kd2 {Those excellent at calculating, can just trust that Black will have enough. Attack the king. That's the plan. For those that struggle tactically, memorizing the next sequence will help you secure the point. It's not as easy as b5 , but Black is nearly up a piece at the end of it.} Nc5 {Attacking e4 and clearing the way for Rd8 +. White can defend the pawn or go bishop hunting. Let's look at both.} 14. Bd3 Bb4+ 15. c3 {This blocks Bc3 and maybe White is thinking they can do something useful with the extra tempo on the bishop.   But they cannot.} Ba5 16. b4 {The fork is just an illusion as we can move our knight away while trading. But White had to play b4 because it was a move it or lose it situation.} Nxd3 {The knight threatens Nxf2 so it must be taken.} 17. Kxd3 Bb6 {The Black bishop on a2 is free and Black also has the bishop pair and a safer king. Just one more try by White...} 18. c4 {Not the best move, but I have to show you the bishop is not trapped.} a5 {And if White plays Ra1 , axb4 guards the bishop and prepares b3 . If White pushes the pawn with b5 then on cxb5 cxb5 your bishop is free and you're still up in material and positionally due to the bishop pair.} 19. b5 cxb5 {Black's bishop is free and Black is winning.} *

