1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. Nf3 {I'm not wild about this move for White. It blocks f4 which is a main trump for White in this structure (see Pawns are the Soul of Chess) . Nonetheless, this is very natural. It gets out a knight, attacks a pawn. Also, in practice, the Queen trade players fall into two categories: 1. Those who love this endgame and know it, 2. Those who want a draw and regard it as 'safe.' 'Safe' players tend to be afraid of a move like f4 which invites an isolated pawn and doesn't develop a piece. To be clear, f4 is definitely best. But your average draw-mongering lower-rated opponent is scared of it. So they will play Nf3 . And probably lose. The stats? Black wins 51%, they draw 36%, and White wins 13%. It may shock you to see this position and discover that Black wins more than White victories and draws put together. And this psychological disbelief is largely responsible for so many White demises. The position is tricky. Please refer to the pawn structure section on why this isn't symmetrical.} Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. a3 {This move stops Bb4 , which was our course of attack in countless lines. But it seems to me a mistake. After all, Bb4 was a great place for the bishop but so is c5 ! Is it really worth a whole tempo to make Black go to a teensy weensy worse square?} Bc5 10. Rd2 ({Here, Ng4} 10. Bh4 {transposes to a line we will see next for those wanting to simplify the work. But it's worth noting that Black has an even better option that provides an illustrative maneuver.}) 10... h6 {A good maneuver by Black to know about. Of course, many moves are playable here (e.g., c6 )} 11. Bh4 {The f2 pawn is defended now but the bishop is vulnerable to attack.} Nh5 {With the idea of winning the bishop pair with g5 and leaving White with no good way to take back. For example, White has many moves here but one way to lose quickly and illustrate Black's threat is to play...} 12. Be2 g5 13. Bg3 (13. Ne1 {was probably better when Black is still slightly ahead. Anytime you have to put a knight on e1 to hold, you know things are a struggle.}) 13... Nxg3 ({And a lot of White players will see hxg3} 13... Bxf2 {and miss....}) 14. fxg3 Be3 {Winning.} *

