1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. Nf3 {I'm not wild about this move for White. It blocks f4 which is a main trump for White in this structure (see Pawns are the Soul of Chess) . Nonetheless, this is very natural. It gets out a knight, attacks a pawn. Also, in practice, the Queen trade players fall into two categories: 1. Those who love this endgame and know it, 2. Those who want a draw and regard it as 'safe.' 'Safe' players tend to be afraid of a move like f4 which invites an isolated pawn and doesn't develop a piece. To be clear, f4 is definitely best. But your average draw-mongering lower-rated opponent is scared of it. So they will play Nf3 . And probably lose. The stats? Black wins 51%, they draw 36%, and White wins 13%. It may shock you to see this position and discover that Black wins more than White victories and draws put together. And this psychological disbelief is largely responsible for so many White demises. The position is tricky. Please refer to the pawn structure section on why this isn't symmetrical.} Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. a3 {This move stops Bb4 , which was our course of attack in countless lines. But it seems to me a mistake. After all, Bb4 was a great place for the bishop but so is c5 ! Is it really worth a whole tempo to make black go to a teensy weensy worse square?} Bc5 10. Bh4 {The bishop defense of f2 makes sense. No more h6 with a gain of tempo, no more bishop pinning the White rook. White will keep the rook off d2 to be safe.} Ng4 {'White?' 'Yes.' 'I'm going to have to ask you to put your rook on d2 .' 'NOoooooooo!'   Okay, granted without h6  g5  Nh5 there's not the same tactics as in the poorly played line. But Black will still have a good game here.} 11. Rd2 f6 {This serves many purposes. First, it guards e5 . Second, it prepares g5 which banishes the white bishop and forbids f4 . If White lets us play h5  h4 we may even win f2 . But mostly, we are playing to block the kingside up so we can do our normal queenside pawn storm. The one downside is that our knight has to do an awkward walk when kicked.} 12. h3 Nh6 13. Be2 Nf7 {Black stands better here. White just has problems activating their bishop and Black is ready to proceed on the queenside, using the a3 pawn as a bait to open files after c6  Kc7  a5 and b5 . Black will play g5 next and put an end to White's kingside f4 counterplay hopes. See the pawn structure section and imagine we eliminate White's f4 bonus.} *

