1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. Nf3 {I'm not wild about this move for White. It blocks f4 which is a main trump for White in this structure (see Pawns are the Soul of Chess) . Nonetheless, this is very natural. It gets out a knight, attacks a pawn. Also, in practice, the Queen trade players fall into two categories: 1. Those who love this endgame and know it, 2. Those who want a draw and regard it as 'safe.' 'Safe' players tend to be afraid of a move like f4 which invites an isolated pawn and doesn't develop a piece. To be clear, f4 is definitely best. But your average draw-mongering lower-rated opponent is scared of it. So they will play Nf3 . And probably lose. The stats? Black wins 51%, they draw 36%, and White wins 13%. It may shock you to see this position and discover that Black wins more than White victories and draws put together. And this psychological disbelief is largely responsible for so many White demises. The position is tricky. Please refer to the pawn structure section on why this isn't symmetrical.} Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. Bh4 {Warning:  Bh4 is a mark of a smart opponent.    This move won't be seen at lower levels. It just looks downright weird and is the best way to play the Bg5  Nf3 system. The move makes sense when you think about things deeply. We will see, from White's perspective, how powerful Black's threat of Ng4 and Bc5 can be, how annoying defending f2 is, and how terrifying the Black bishop on e6 is. So, now White responds to these issues: overprotects f2 to stop Ng4  Bc5 ideas, and threatens Ng5 , seizing not only the bishop pair generally but also that delicious e6 bishop specifically.} {Luckily, we have nothing to fear. Before moving to my recommendation it is worth mentioning that h6 is both the most popular and arguably simplest-to-understand move by Black. The idea is to stop Ng5 and maybe one day play g5 . It's totally playable, but ultimately, I didn't recommend it because it creates a kingside weakness for White to play against and wastes a valuable tempo in this fast-paced position. Nothing devastating but the move does demand some accurate and slightly complex play ahead for Black. Nevertheless, those wanting an alternative to my proposal can study it on their own and will find it works alright if given the right amount of study. The easiest route to equality in my opinion is to counterattack instead and play....} Bb4 {Okay, okay, it's a bit caveman to threaten Bxc3  Nxe4 , but hey, the cavemen invented fire and fought saber-toothed tigers, so let's not disparage their approach.} 10. Ng5 ({Let's look at what happens if White ignores Black's threat and goes ahead with the plan. This is really the only scary option that involves memorization as other options just entail playing intuitively. For example, In my database, White has slightly preferred} 10. Nd5 {when} Nxd5 11. exd5 Bg4 {along with Bc5 both equalize and in fact, White has never won. The trickiest move is Ng5 which earned White a win in a game and involves some fireworks worth memorizing.}) 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 (11. Nxe6 {was also possible but then} Bxb2+ {and we would have an extra pawn. White's argument, if they have one at all, in this position is that it looks like White will net the bishop pair here in exchange for bad doubled c-pawns. After all, if you take on a2 , c4 traps the bishop with Kb2 coming next. Right?}) 11... Bxa2 {Wrong! And the a2 pawn is once again takeable as in so many Philidor positions, defying the laws of logic. Just when you think it's trapped, it lives on.} 12. c4 {Otherwise, Black will just return to e6 up a pawn. It may be doubled, but it's still an extra pawn. White is now threatening to take on f7 and win the bishop with Kb2 , so we must be accurate.} b5 {White can take on f7 or take on b5 . I don't think anything is really good for White here. The computer recommends the least human move for White which we will explore now...} 13. f4 {The computer move, but hard to believe it will be played. The idea is Nxf7 and then Nxe5 .} Ng4 {We guard e5 to stop the Nxf7 - Nxe5 gain of two pawns.  Ne3 is possible in some lines.} 14. Nxf7 {White shouldn't sit around and wait for f6 or Ne3 .} Re8 {Over guarding e5 to free our Ng4 for other tasks like landing on e3 .} 15. Kb2 Bxc4 {And White has many moves here so we can stop. Black's outside passer makes them better yet again as White didn't manage to gain back the a2 pawn despite their best efforts. Additionally, White will soon be losing the bishop pair and the e4 pawn can come under attack.} *

