1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. Nf3 Nbd7 {We must defend our e5 pawn from the poorly placed knight and not vindicate our opponent's strategic error.} 9. Bh4 {Warning:  Bh4 is a mark of a smart opponent.    This move won't be seen at lower levels. It just looks downright weird and is the best way to play the Bg5  Nf3 system. The move makes sense when you think about things deeply. We will see, from White's perspective, how powerful Black's threat of Ng4 and Bc5 can be, how annoying defending f2 is, and how terrifying the Black bishop on e6 is. So, now White responds to these issues: overprotects f2 to stop Ng4  Bc5 ideas, and threatens Ng5 , seizing not only the bishop pair generally but also that delicious e6 bishop specifically.} {Luckily, we have nothing to fear. Before moving to my recommendation it is worth mentioning that h6 is both the most popular and arguably simplest-to-understand move by Black. The idea is to stop Ng5 and maybe one day play g5 . It's totally playable, but ultimately, I didn't recommend it because it creates a kingside weakness for White to play against and wastes a valuable tempo in this fast-paced position. Nothing devastating but the move does demand some accurate and slightly complex play ahead for Black. Nevertheless, those wanting an alternative to my proposal can study it on their own and will find it works alright if given the right amount of study. The easiest route to equality in my opinion is to counterattack instead and play....} Bb4 {Okay, okay, it's a bit caveman to threaten Bxc3  Nxe4 , but hey, the cavemen invented fire and fought saber-toothed tigers, so let's not disparage their approach.} 10. Ng5 {Let's look at what happens if White ignores Black's threat and goes ahead with the plan.} Bxc3 11. bxc3 {It looks like White will net the bishop pair here in exchange for bad pawns.} Bxa2 {And the a2 pawn is once again takeable as in so many Philidor positions, defying the laws of logic. Just when you think it's trapped, it lives on.} 12. c4 {Otherwise, Black will just return to e6 up a pawn. It may be doubled, but it's still an extra pawn.} b5 13. Nxf7 {Not best but White has given up on trapping the bishop and is trying to win back the pawn. Unfortunately for them, they don't because c4 will be hanging.} Rf8 {The tricky part in your memorization is to remember the rook goes to e8 in the f4 variation and f8 here. Why? Well in the f4 variation, there was pressure on e5 and we didn't need to win a tempo to take the c4 pawn. Here, we have to act fast to just be ahead.} 14. Ng5 Bxc4 {And Black is up a pawn and better. White can saddle Black with doubled c-pawns but they are tricky to attack and White has their own weak pawns on the kingside.} *

