1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Nge2 {This I would call the mainline of this variation as it's the most played by Masters and above. White's plan is to take back with a knight, accepting the isolated pawn in order to keep the position open. In an open position, Black's kingside attack is harder to pull off as there's not as much cover in the middle of the board. That said, White incurs some risks by taking on the worse pawn structure. The better player should win and if both are capable, it should be a draw. Indeed, this position after Black's next move has been reached only seven times and has a 71% draw rate with the decisive results being evenly split among the two camps.} Bd6 {This wasn't preferred by the Masters but it's the easiest path to achieving equality. I give the Master's most popular move, 6. Nbd7 , as an alternative. Against best play, Nbd7 will lead to a position where you are a pawn up but positionally worse and Bd6 will lead to the opposite: you'll be a pawn down but positionally better. Generally I find it's easier to have the active pieces for the pawn than a pawn for active pieces in terms of both the fun you're having and easiness to play, but I know there are the materialists out there who will greatly prefer their pawn and Nbd7 will be the way. Both are solid even if the computer prefers 6. Bd6 in the end slightly. Finally, Nbd7 is more technical and concrete--knowing your moves matters and I noticed many Masters played it to positions that were worse for Black because it's a bit tricky--while Bd6 is more concept oriented and knowing the ideas matter, which are also a little tricky. Practically, both have fine results especially if you look at results where Black plays it correctly and knows the follow ups.   Unlike other alternatives, I really think 6. Nbd7 one is in many ways as much in the spirit of the course as my main recommendation and there is a strong case to be made for it being the primary recommendation. So, with them so close, choose based on your own preference. That said, ultimately, I recommended 6. Bd6 because I found it more idea-based and less concrete, and so figured it would be easier to memorize for club players that don't get this position a lot and is fitting within the philosophical spirit of the course.} 10. Nxf4 h6 ({The point. White can't play Bxf6 because of} 10... Bxf4+ 11. Kb1 {gxf6 winning a piece.}) 11. Nxe6 hxg5 ({Nxg5?} 11... Bf4+ 12. Kb1 Bxg5 {would be winning, so White has to take the other g-pawn.}) 12. Nxg7 Bf4+ 13. Kb1 {The White h-pawn will eventually be threatened but hold off on taking it for now. For example, there's a concrete and idea-based reason for why it wouldn't work. The concrete issue is that after Rxh2 Rxh2 Bxh2 Bc4 you are losing the f7 pawn and have to deal with Rh1 threats that both attack your bishop and threaten to invade into the last rank. And if you capture it with the bishop, you will be pinned there for awhile. The idea-based reason is that Black and White both have development issues: White has an undeveloped bishop and rook and Black has an undeveloped knight and rook. By trading on h2 , you are giving up your active developed rook for the undeveloped one and so will feel the pain of being behind in a somewhat open position. The concrete line above is just a manifestation of those principles. Once we have gotten out a few more pieces, we may be ready to threaten it once again.} Nbd7 ({Developing a piece and planning to move towards the center to guard the f-pawn if it ever is harassed by the white bishop.} 13... Ng4 14. g3 {is an alternative that is highly tactical. It also probably settles on equal and you're welcome to explore it on your own if you wish. It looks aggressive and White may not find g3 , but Black really forgoes developing when they play in this way and so it is dicey in terms of executing it right. Everything we threaten to win here--the h2 pawn, the h1 rook--helps to develop White's pieces!   The text move is simpler to understand and play. We don't need to panic about taking on h2 as I mentioned in my note to the last move. We have opposite colored bishops to make the pawn down not matter quite as much in the endgame and enhance attacks. The h-file is a pain in the neck for White, as are all the dark squares. The computer hovers around equal and 0.3 edge for White, giving us more than enough compensation, and practically speaking, it's easier to be the one active in these types of positions. Not a bad end result for Black when White is playing all the mainline moves. We will continue by developing our last rook via a king lift and play actively against White's pawns.   I'll end the MoveTrainer here but go a few more moves deep in my commentary to just show you the computer lines from here on out in case you play an incredibly well prepared opponent.}) 14. Bd3 c6 {Our usual move to lift the king on c7 so it never experiences a check again. Also, we don't want creatures living on d5 .} 15. h3 Kc7 16. Ne2 Be5 17. Nf5 Nc5 {And at this point, lots of moves can be played. Black has great knights and enough compensation for the pawn. The white bishop looks so miserable stuck there on d3 and White's extra pawn on the queenside has too many enemies in the way to ever hope for queenship. Interestingly, in the other line with 9. Nbd7 instead of 9. Bd6 , it is Black who ends up a pawn up with White having the compensation. So if you don't like active pieces for a pawn, try the other side of it in the Alternative Line. For most club players, the active pieces will be easier to do something with than the extra pawn, so I stand by my recommendation. Both are considered essentially equal by the engine.} *

