1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Nge2 {This I would call the mainline of this variation as it's the most played by Masters and above. White's plan is to take back with a knight, accepting the isolated pawn in order to keep the position open. In an open position, Black's kingside attack is harder to pull off as there's not as much cover in the middle of the board. That said, White incurs some risks by taking on the worse pawn structure. The better player should win and if both are capable, it should be a draw. Indeed, this position after Black's next move has been reached only seven times and has a 71% draw rate with the decisive results being evenly split among the two camps.} Bd6 {This wasn't preferred by the Masters but it's the easiest path to achieving equality. I give the Master's most popular move, 6. Nbd7 , as an alternative. Against best play, Nbd7 will lead to a position where you are a pawn up but positionally worse and Bd6 will lead to the opposite: you'll be a pawn down but positionally better. Generally I find it's easier to have the active pieces for the pawn than a pawn for active pieces in terms of both the fun you're having and easiness to play, but I know there are the materialists out there who will greatly prefer their pawn and Nbd7 will be the way. Both are solid even if the computer prefers 6. Bd6 in the end slightly. Finally, Nbd7 is more technical and concrete--knowing your moves matters and I noticed many Masters played it to positions that were worse for Black because it's a bit tricky--while Bd6 is more concept oriented and knowing the ideas matter, which are also a little tricky. Practically, both have fine results especially if you look at results where Black plays it correctly and knows the follow ups.   Unlike other alternatives, I really think 6. Nbd7 one is in many ways as much in the spirit of the course as my main recommendation and there is a strong case to be made for it being the primary recommendation. So, with them so close, choose based on your own preference. That said, ultimately, I recommended 6. Bd6 because I found it more idea-based and less concrete, and so figured it would be easier to memorize for club players that don't get this position a lot and is fitting within the philosophical spirit of the course. Also, in the Nbd7 line, you don't play Bg4 at a critical point while in another line I'm recommending, you do. So 6. Bd6 eliminates mixing those two lines up.} 10. Bxf6 {I imagine that a lot of players don't like Bd6 because they fear the tripling of their pawns. But remember, we are up a pawn, so it is really just doubling the pawns. These structures are nothing to be feared. Let me demonstrate.} gxf6 11. Nd5 {White tries to recapture on f4} Nd7 12. Nexf4 {This move was played in the game Dzhumaev vs. Khismatullin. It is weaker than the other knight capturing the pawn though White is worse in both cases. I can understand the instinct though: the bishop was dying to come out!} c6 13. Nxe6 {Forced as the other defending knight was being attacked.} fxe6 14. Nc3 {Or Ne3  Bf4 when the e-file is blocked from protecting e4 and White is tangled up.} Kc7 15. g3 {Stopping Bf4 check ideas so that White can double their rooks--you'd be surprised how often Rd2  Be3 ends the game--and also thinking about Bg2 for passive defense or Bh3 for active counterattacking. And now Black played} {Be5 in Dzhumaev vs. Khismatullin but many moves are possible ( h5 , a5 , etc.). Black's bishop is better and the knight will be stationed on c5 probably to eye e4 (or e5 if the season fits). White's knight is stuck and their bishop has no good squares because it will be stuck babysitting e4 in the end--or a rook will, which is even worse for White. Black has an advantage here. I would have proceeded a little differently as Black from the previously mentioned game and gone for...} Nc5 {In the aforementioned game, Black played Be5 and was also better. I don't know if the bishop is that much better on e5 though and Ne2 is kind of what White wants anyway, to reroute towards f4 . After playing around with an engine in this position for awhile, I think anchoring White's pieces onto e4 is the better course. White can kick the knight with b4 , but not without creating weaknesses.} 16. Bh3 Rae8 {Black's king is closer to the center. Black can play b5 or h5 , on either wing, and has good play against White's pawns. Black will have an easy time defending f6 with his powerful dark squared bishop but e4 will be a perennial problem for White. Computer gives Black about a pawn edge and I think a human would too.} *

