1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Nge2 {This I would call the mainline of this variation as it's the most played by Masters and above. White's plan is to take back with a knight, accepting the isolated pawn in order to keep the position open. In an open position, Black's kingside attack is harder to pull off as there's not as much cover in the middle of the board. That said, White incurs some risks by taking on the worse pawn structure. The better player should win and if both are capable, it should be a draw. Indeed, this position after Black's next move has been reached only seven times and has a 71% draw rate with the decisive results being evenly split among the two camps.} Bd6 {This wasn't preferred by the Masters but it's the easiest path to achieving equality. I give the Master's most popular move, 6. Nbd7 , as an alternative. Against best play, Nbd7 will lead to a position where you are a pawn up but positionally worse and Bd6 will lead to the opposite: you'll be a pawn down but positionally better. Generally I find it's easier to have the active pieces for the pawn than a pawn for active pieces in terms of both the fun you're having and easiness to play, but I know there are the materialists out there who will greatly prefer their pawn and Nbd7 will be the way. Both are solid even if the computer prefers 6. Bd6 in the end slightly. Finally, Nbd7 is more technical and concrete--knowing your moves matters and I noticed many Masters played it to positions that were worse for Black because it's a bit tricky--while Bd6 is more concept oriented and knowing the ideas matter, which are also a little tricky. Practically, both have fine results especially if you look at results where Black plays it correctly and knows the follow ups.   Unlike other alternatives, I really think 6. Nbd7 one is in many ways as much in the spirit of the course as my main recommendation and there is a strong case to be made for it being the primary recommendation. So, with them so close, choose based on your own preference. That said, ultimately, I recommended 6. Bd6 because I found it more idea-based and less concrete, and so figured it would be easier to memorize for club players that don't get this position a lot and is fitting within the philosophical spirit of the course. Also, in the Nbd7 line, you don't play Bg4 at a critical point while in another line I'm recommending, you do. So 6. Bd6 eliminates mixing those two lines up.} 10. Bxf6 {I imagine that a lot of players don't like Bd6 because they fear the tripling of their pawns. But remember, we are up a pawn, so it is really just doubling the pawns. These structures are nothing to be feared. Let me demonstrate.} gxf6 11. Nd5 Nd7 12. Ndxf4 {This situation might come about via many different moves. Generally what you should know is that this is fine for Black. The bishop pair are centralized and powerful. White still has an awkward isolated e4 pawn that makes their light-squared bishop bad. And if White ever takes out one of the bishops, it will undouble Black's pawns. Here, Nc5 wins the pawn and White is in for a struggle to hold. But even if that weren't the case, putting your bishops on e5 and e6 should hold these TYPES of positions whenever they arise in the Bd6 line.} Nc5 {The knight can't defend e4 because the other knight will be hanging. They can try...} 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Nc3 {But Black is doing very well here. Black has a much better bishop and a much better knight and easy play against the white king.} a5 {Stopping b4 ... our knight is feeling very steed-like in its glorious position on c5 . I'll end the MoveTrainer on this move, but I'll also show the best moves by both sides according to a computer accompanied by explanations so you get a feel for the position. The evaluation is clear edge for Black.} 15. Bc4 Bf4+ {Pushing the king away from the center. In the event of an arising endgame, this will be nice.} 16. Kb1 Be5 {Threatening Bxc3 .} 17. Nb5 {Black is not interested in trading e4 for e6 as e4 is much weaker and the trade would relieve White of a weakness while creating an isolated f6 pawn for Black. That's probably fine for equality but Black can play for more.} c6 {With the goal of trading bishop for knight to avoid an opposite-colored bishop ending where White has more drawing chances.} 18. Nd4 ({Or} 18. Nd6+ Bxd6 19. Rxd6 Kc7 {where we also achieve the bishop trade and get a similar position.}) 18... Bxd4 {I don't normally trade bishops for knights but we don't want the opposite color bishop ending when we have the edge. We are now playing to win.} 19. Rxd4 Kc7 {And we have a good knight versus bad bishop scenario. Defending the e4 pawn will be a pain-- e5 is threatened, for example, right this moment--and Black's king is much faster at joining the game than White's. Plus, Black has play on both wings. I'll leave it here with the computer evaluation of around -0.7} *

