1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Nge2 {This I would call the mainline of this variation as it's the most played by Masters and above. White's plan is to take back with a knight, accepting the isolated pawn in order to keep the position open. In an open position, Black's kingside attack is harder to pull off as there's not as much cover in the middle of the board. That said, White incurs some risks by taking on the worse pawn structure. The better player should win and if both are capable, it should be a draw. Indeed, this position after Black's next move has been reached only seven times and has a 71% draw rate with the decisive results being evenly split among the two camps.} Nbd7 {This move is preferred by most Masters. I give it as my alternative for the reasons stated in the Bd6 line.} 10. Nxf4 Bg4 {I don't like this move as much even though it's what is most popular in high level play. I tried to make it work because it's popular and logical, but I couldn't justify it. Playing around with the engine in this position for an hour or two, I concluded White just wins the bishop pair if they play it right without much compensation for Black. It's still probably a draw, and losing the bishop pair isn't world ending, but I'm not a fan. Nonetheless, let's cover this in an informational for two reasons: 1. I think it's useful to see how Black can react to the bishop being attacked by the knight in similar positions. 2. Some players might be okay with the resulting position and interested in self studying this move.} 11. Re1 {Threatening h3 winning the bishop pair after all of Black's work.} Ne5 12. h3 {And sadly, the computer would rather part with the bishop after all that than play Bd7 . The computer line continues...} Be6 13. Rd1 Bc5 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bf4 Nfd7 {This position is playable for Black. The knight is well stationed and cannot be easily dislodged. Nonetheless, with White's bishop pair and Black's misplaced rook, I would like something better.} *

