1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Nge2 {This I would call the mainline of this variation as it's the most played by Masters and above. White's plan is to take back with a knight, accepting the isolated pawn in order to keep the position open. In an open position, Black's kingside attack is harder to pull off as there's not as much cover in the middle of the board. That said, White incurs some risks by taking on the worse pawn structure. The better player should win and if both are capable, it should be a draw. Indeed, this position after Black's next move has been reached only seven times and has a 71% draw rate with the decisive results being evenly split among the two camps.} Nbd7 {This move is preferred by most Masters. I give it as my alternative for the reasons stated in the Bd6 line.} 10. Nxf4 Bb4 {This has only been played once and Black lost. But not because of this move. The bishop is consistent with playing against White's isolated pawn and Bg4 didn't save the light-squared bishop anyway.} 11. Ncd5 {This seems like the natural move.} Bxd5 {Black does this for concrete reasons. The basic strategic point is to close the d-file down for business and capturing with the bishop first gives White less options of taking on e6 with their knight as an intermezzo. Is this tricky to learn? Yes. It's a bit unintuitive, but we have 6. Bd6 for those who want more idea-chess over concrete lines and the line by White is rare. Both Nxd5 and Nxe4 are similar in terms of their evaluation, though the computer gives a tiny, tiny preference for this move so why not play the best one to settle the tie? None of the other options are simple either. However, I will analyze them in this note for people wanting options:} (11... Nxe4 12. Nxe6 fxe6 {or 12. Nxb4 or 12. Bd3 , White's plentiful options is why I prefer the text} 13. Nxb4 Nxg5 {where the computer says equal and the practical results are good for Black, though optically the bishop looks better than the knight and White's pawn structure and rooks are better, so personally I'd prefer White, though only very slightly.}) (11... Nxd5 {and again White has an irritating amount of solid choices in 12. Nxd5 , 12. Nxe6 and} 12. exd5 Bg4 {the computer gives this move a plus over the option Bf5 as Black needs to threaten things to compensate for their lower development} 13. Be2 {White can block the threat while developing at least somewhat. Again, computer says close to equal, but Black has a series of issues here that are harder to solve in human play like how to activate the rook with a pawn on d5 guarding c6 and what to do about White's lead in development. Already, when I play around in this position, practically anything for White is fine and retains the evaluation, while Black often has to find a single move to retain equality again and again because of the development issues. It is technically equal but not practically. This is probably fine in the end but I prefer the text.}) 12. exd5 (12. Bxf6 Nxf6 {is another option but either way, the file will be closed or White will lose all their knights in the process of keeping it open, making the position less dangerous for Black.}) ({Another option for them is} 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 {and if White still insists on keeping the d-file open with} 13. Rxd5 {then} c6 {hits the rook and ensures we will be extra fast in playing Kc7 and activating our a8 rook.}) 12... Bd6 {And White has won the bishop pair but d4 is weak. The threat is h6 , winning the bishop pair back. So White must move the knight. Only where to go? The computer recommends Nd3 , parting with the pawn and counting on the bishop pair to equalize in the open position. But most humans aren't so brazen. So let's look at Ne2 , the ugly materialistic move, as well.} 13. Ne2 Ng4 {With a double attack on h2 and the f2 square, which would fork the rooks.} 14. Bh4 Nxh2 {And despite White's best intentions, Black still takes a pawn for the bishop pair. Of course, h5 and even Ne3 were also possible. Black is fine in this position. Their pieces are just very active. Long term we will try to take advantage of our kingside majority by pushing those pawns.} *

