he e4 threat by counterattacking the b4 bishop} Bxd5 {Black does this for concrete reasons. The basic strategic point is to close the d-file down for business and capturing with the bishop first gives White less options of taking on e6 with their knight as an intermezzo. Is this tricky to learn? Yes. It's a bit unintuitive, but we have 6. Bd6 for those who want more idea-chess over concrete lines and the line by White is rare. Both Nxd5 and Nxe4 are similar in terms of their evaluation, though the computer gives a tiny, tiny preference for this move so why not play the best one to settle the tie? None of the other options are simple either. However, I will analyze them in this note for people wanting options:} (11... Nxe4 12. Nxe6 fxe6 {or 12. Nxb4 or 12. Bd3 , White's plentiful options is why I prefer the text} 13. Nxb4 Nxg5 {where the computer says equal and the practical results are good for Black, though optically the bishop looks better than the knight and White's pawn structure and rooks are better, so personally I'd prefer White, though only very slightly.}) (11... Nxd5 {and again White has an irritating amount of solid choices in 12. Nxd5 , 12. Nxe6 and} 12. exd5 Bg4 {the computer gives this move a plus over the option Bf5 as Black needs to threaten things to compensate for their lower development} 13. Be2 {White can block the threat while developing at least somewhat. Again, computer says close to equal, but Black has a series of issues here that are harder to solve in human play like how to activate the rook with a pawn on d5 guarding c6 and what to do about White's lead in development. Already, when I play around in this position, practically anything for White is fine and retains the evaluation, while Black often has to find a single move to retain equality again and again because of the development issues. It is technically equal but not practically. This is probably fine in the end but I prefer the text.}) 12. exd5 (12. Bxf6 Nxf6 {is another option but either way, the file will be closed or White will lose all their knights in the process of keeping it open, making the position less dangerous for Black.}) ({Another option for them is} 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 {and if White still insists on keeping the d-file open with} 13. Rxd5 {then (c6 hits the rook and ensures we will be extra fast in playing Kc7 and activating our a8 rook.)}) 12... Bd6 {And White has won the bishop pair but the concrete matters decide: d4 is weak. The threat is h6 , winning the bishop pair back. So White must move the knight. Only where to go? The computer recommends Nd3 , parting with the pawn and counting on the bishop pair to equalize in the open position. But most humans aren't so brazen. So let's look at Ne2 , the ugly materialistic move, as well.} 13. Nd3 {The computer move. And a move I don't think you'll ever face. But still as the most dangerous move, it deserves coverage for its worst-case-scenario factor.} Nxd5 14. g3 N7b6 15. Bh3+ {This is the engine-inspired White's idea. Ultimate king banishment in exchange for the pawn.} Kb8 {And here, we are beyond the opening as both sides had a lot of options even up until this point. Black has an extra pawn but a bad rook and White has the bishop pair. The computer concludes dramatic equality. If you'd rather try the active pieces and be down the pawn, try the Bd6 line instead! The choice is yours!} *

