1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Nge2 {This I would call the mainline of this variation as it's the most played by Masters and above. White's plan is to take back with a knight, accepting the isolated pawn in order to keep the position open. In an open position, Black's kingside attack is harder to pull off as there's not as much cover in the middle of the board. That said, White incurs some risks by taking on the worse pawn structure. The better player should win and if both are capable, it should be a draw. Indeed, this position after Black's next move has been reached only seven times and has a 71% draw rate with the decisive results being evenly split among the two camps.} Nbd7 {This move is preferred by most Masters. I give it as my alternative for the reasons stated in the Bd6 line.} 10. Nxf4 Bb4 {This has only been played once and Black lost. But not because of this move. The bishop is consistent with playing against White's isolated pawn and Bg4 didn't save the light-squared bishop anyway.} 11. Nfd5 {The other knight jump, as we saw in the last variation, was far from convincing so some players try this one. One advantage of our antidote in the other line is that it's the same as in this one: close the d-file.} Bxd5 {And now the issue for White is that they want to avoid Bxc3 , ruining their structure. But if they take back with the knight hitting your bishop, Nxe4 hits their bishop, tactically giving Black a pawn. So they must part with the bishop pair in order to not be worse.} 12. Bxf6 {White tries to remove Black's defensive resources and even though it's an engine-concocted try for an edge it fizzles out quickly.} Nxf6 13. Nxd5 {Now Nxe4 doesn't hit the white bishop and so loses a piece. But the game is so liquidated that White has achieved very little. We have an isolated pawn for White and a bad rook for Black. They probably even each other out and the computer reads 0.0 after a few more exchanges. After all, we also have opposite colored bishops.} Nxd5 14. Rxd5 ({White has played good moves and so has Black. On} 14. exd5 {Black could have played Bd6 and Kd7 and there's no more White attack.}) 14... c6 {With equality. I'm sorry. I know you wanted more here. But when White plays the top line and wants a draw, it's very hard to resist. A very high rated player could still outplay a lower rated player here (after all, there are still imbalances and the opposite colored bishops heighten attacks) , but chess is a draw at core. You can consider not taking the knight on d5 if you are in a desperate situation, but you will be worse. I can't formally recommend it as its 'desperate measures' only.} *

