1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Nge2 {This I would call the mainline of this variation as it's the most played by Masters and above. White's plan is to take back with a knight, accepting the isolated pawn in order to keep the position open. In an open position, Black's kingside attack is harder to pull off as there's not as much cover in the middle of the board. That said, White incurs some risks by taking on the worse pawn structure. The better player should win and if both are capable, it should be a draw. Indeed, this position after Black's next move has been reached only seven times and has a 71% draw rate with the decisive results being evenly split among the two camps.} Nbd7 {This move is preferred by most Masters. I give it as my alternative for the reasons stated in the Bd6 line.} 10. Nxf4 Bb4 {This has only been played once and Black lost. But not because of this move. The bishop is consistent with playing against White's isolated pawn and Bg4 didn't save the light-squared bishop anyway.} 11. Nxe6 {Vladimir Nevostrujev's choice in the one game in which this position occurred. This is exceedingly rare stuff but White has been playing well so it would be remiss not to have a Black plan here.} fxe6 12. Bc4 Re8 13. Rhf1 Bxc3 14. bxc3 ({We have been following Nevostrujev vs. Ivanov up until this point. Black felt stressed about the pressure on the e-pawn and so played} 14. e5 $2 {However, that opened up play on the light squares, took away a valuable place for the d7 knight to go and was a bit committal. Much better is the recommended move, 14... a5 , with the idea of a4 and activating the a8 rook. A complicated position has arisen where White can claim the bishop pair and Black can be excited about four isolated pawns to play against. It should be even.}) 14... a5 {This position is about level with plenty of play. White has the bishop pair, and Black has the better pawn structure and some nice knight outposts. White has foreseen that if Black takes on e4 , there's enough counterplay with a rook to the seventh. But that requires nerves of steel and every move they have to think about the e4 pawn falling. It's telling that the engine recommends White take the f6 knight and give up the bishop pair immediately. Again, that will be a hard pill for White to swallow here. Once Black activates the rook on a8 , they can slide it to the c-file and Nc5 ideas are always possible, hitting e4 again. The position is fluid so make sure you don't cruise control here, but with care, you should find the position fine and this is again to illustrate that even with engine like play, Black survives just fine in the Philidor and even has a lot to play on for.} *

