1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Bxf4 Nbd7 {We are already in a rare place with White playing solid moves. Two games have been played here with Black winning one and drawing one, even if the engine says White has a slight edge. The most natural move ( Nf3 ) transposes to a good position for Black. h3 could be played to stop Ng4 but it's hard to imagine that not developing is the ideal setup.} 10. Nf3 {After the next move, in practice Black wins 36% of the time, White 11% and they draw 52%.} Bc5 {Theoretically speaking, White has a good position. Their pieces are developed and their king is safe. Practically speaking, it is hard to play as White here for a few reasons. First, Black has a natural plan of playing into the dark squares on the kingside (e.g., Ng4 - e3 ) or playing on the queenside with a6 - b5 and against the isolated e-pawn. White's moves are just hard to play. For example, let's look at a few of White's ideas:   1. Stop kingside play with h3   2. Develop and don't panic   3. Chase the e6 bishop} 11. h3 {White tries to stop kingside play with h3 . This is reasonable at first glance, as we've seen Ng4 in action. But Black has two good moves here. They can just play Bb4 , arguing the wasted tempo is fine because White wasted a tempo with h3 . Or they can attack the dark squares in another way....} Nh5 12. Bh2 Be3+ 13. Kb1 Bf4 {And in a high rated game between Kravtsiv vs. Khismatullin, Black went on to win in this equal and double edged position. And Black will still invade with the knight on the dark squares.} *

