1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Bxf4 Nbd7 {We are already in a rare place with White playing solid moves. Two games have been played here with Black winning one and drawing one, even if the engine says White has a slight edge. The most natural move (Nf3) transposes to a good position for Black. h3 could be played to stop Ng4 but it's hard to imagine that not developing is the ideal setup.} 10. Nf3 {After the next move, in practice Black wins 36% of the time, White 11% and they draw 52%.} Bc5 {Theoretically speaking, White has a good position. Their pieces are developed and their king is safe. Practically speaking, it is hard to play as White here for a few reasons. First, Black has a natural plan of playing into the dark squares on the kingside (e.g., Ng4 - e3 ) or playing on the queenside with a6 - b5 and against the isolated e-pawn. White's moves are just hard to play. For example, let's look at a few of White's ideas:   1. Stop kingside play with h3   2. Develop and don't panic   3. Chase the e6 bishop} 11. Bd3 ({White tries to follow the mantra 'Develop and don't panic.' The make-basic-moves approach allows Black the kingside dark squared play for now. I should note for those wondering why I'm not immediately going with the very natural Phildor move c6 followed by b5 that with f4 trading for e5 the c7 square is covered and the king could feel a bit more drafty than those lines where White played passively. So with an open center, piece play over pawn play takes over for a bit. After we trade some pieces, our king should feel safe with the pawn storm. Black can play several attacking ideas here like Bb4 or Ng4 . I'm not sure they're justified though when White hasn't wasted any moves so I prefer to just secure our bishop by stopping} 11. Ng5 {.}) 11... h6 {Preventing Ng5 and sometimes we will consider g5 . For example, if White would weirdly play Rd2 then g5  Bg3  Be3 wins. This makes doubling against us annoying.} 12. Kb1 {So that White can double. Here, it's a game but I'll show a few moves to give you a feel for the position.} g5 13. Bg3 Nh5 14. Be1 Nf4 15. Bf1 c6 {And with the dark-squared bishop no longer guarding c7 , we do the normal plan. Note that actual play may vary from this computer versus computer stuff but the takeaway should be this: when the f4 plan is in place and Black has had to play e5xf4 , use your knight and pawns to bully the dark-squared bishop and play actively on the kingside. When the diagonals are controlled, we can do our normal pawn storm.} *

