1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Bxf4 Nbd7 {We are already in a rare place with White playing solid moves. Two games have been played here with Black winning one and drawing one, even if the engine says White has a slight edge. The most natural move (Nf3) transposes to a good position for Black. h3 could be played to stop Ng4 but it's hard to imagine that not developing is the ideal setup.} 10. Nf3 {After the next move, in practice Black wins 36% of the time, White 11% and they draw 52%.} Bc5 {Theoretically speaking, White has a good position. Their pieces are developed and their king is safe. Practically speaking, it is hard to play as White here for a few reasons. First, Black has a natural plan of playing into the dark squares on the kingside (e.g., Ng4 - e3 ) or playing on the queenside with a6 - b5 and against the isolated e-pawn. White's moves are just hard to play. For example, let's look at a few of White's ideas:  1. Stop kingside play with h3   2. Develop and don't panic  3. Chase the e6 bishop} 11. Bd3 {The make basic moves approach allows Black the kingside dark squared play for now. I should note for those wondering why I'm not immediately going c6  b5 that with f4 trading for e5 the c7 square is covered and the king could feel a bit more drafty than those lines where White played passively. So with an open center, piece play over pawn play takes over for a bit. After we trade some pieces, our king should feel safe with the pawn storm. Black can play several attacking ideas here like Bb4 or Ng4 . I'm not sure they're justified though when White hasn't wasted any moves so I prefer to just secure our bishop.} Ng4 {This has been the choice of some GM's over the course recommendation of h6 . I'm not sure Black achieves equality here but will note it for those who don't like h6 and it's certainly double edged. I'm ending the Move Trainer here as based on a reader comment I want to give two responses to White's next move. Be sure to check out the notes to it for more information.} 12. Rhe1 Bb4 {Black has nice counterplay but White has hopes of securing the bishop pair and active rooks. Objectively, White is a bit better but in practice, Black has done well and is having a lot of fun.} ({UPDATE NOTE: A reader pointed out that Stockfish 16 gives the following line: Nb5 Ba5 guarding c7 ... Stockfish 14 and Deep Fritz recommend taking the rook at first but it looks bad when I run it deeply Re2 Nc5 with an eval of 0.7 but hovering into 0.8 every so often. I'm not sure most humans will play in such a way and in Kiuttu vs. Kilik here--2303 FIDE vs. 2406,--White instead opted for 13. e5 and lost, but I will list a note here for another way to play this alternative that is Stockfish 16 slightly better on the end evaluation...} 12... h6 {with the goal of playing g5 and installing a knight on e5 if the bishop moves off the diagonal or going into e3 if they don't. Play may continue...} 13. h3 g5 $1 14. Bg3 Be3+ 15. Kb1 Bf2 {with a complicated game that the computer evaluates around 0.4 to 0.5. This evaluation is better objectively than the Bb4 line if White finds Nb5 but then again h3 and Bg3 are much simpler moves for White to find than Nb5 where they stay down the exchange for a long time. So, I'm ending the Move Trainer at Ng4 and letting you choose between 12... h6 and 12... Bb4 or go back to my recommended line.}) *

