1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Bxf4 Nbd7 {We are already in a rare place with White playing solid moves. Two games have been played here with Black winning one and drawing one, even if the engine says White has a slight edge. The most natural move (Nf3) transposes to a good position for Black. h3 could be played to stop Ng4 but it's hard to imagine that not developing is the ideal setup.} 10. Nf3 {After the next move, in practice Black wins 36% of the time, White 11% and they draw 52%.} Bc5 {Theoretically speaking, White has a good position. Their pieces are developed and their king is safe. Practically speaking, it is hard to play as White here for a few reasons. First, Black has a natural plan of playing into the dark squares on the kingside (e.g., Ng4 - e3 ) or playing on the queenside with a6 - b5 and against the isolated e-pawn. White's moves are just hard to play. For example, let's look at a few of White's ideas:   1. Stop kingside play with h3   2. Develop and don't panic   3. Chase the e6 bishop} 11. Ng5 {It's reasonable for White to go for the plan 'Chase the e6 bishop.' If so, White must act now to attack the e6 bishop before Black can play h6 .} Bg4 {Black keeps the bishop. This will be tricky for the 9. Nge2  Nbd7 Alternative line players as I had to have an informational on why not to play this move in that line. All the 9. ... Bd6 players following my main recommendation are safe from mixing things up, they can just always move the bishop here if it is attacked. For the 9. ... Nbd7 alternative players, a mnemonic you could use to tell the difference is this: 'In the GM variation, if White immediately moves a bishop after you take on f4 , you get to move your bishop later too!'  But use whatever works best for you, even if it's drilling the two lines side by side so you can keep them straight. Here, concretely, this move works much better than it did in the Nge2 Alternative variation, which I covered in the informational in this chapter. In fact, the engine recommends the ridiculous looking 12. Nf3 for White, apologizing for the knight chase and accepting Black can play Be6 and repeat if they so choose.   Instead of the inhuman 11. Nf3 mentioned above, White can play a lot of moves here, so let's talk about things more conceptually to allow for good reactions to them all. The f7 pawn and d1 rook are immediate concrete considerations. Once they are resolved, Black will aim to get rid of the dark-squared bishop so that they can play c6 and Kc7 and connect their rooks. There are several ways to go about this, but the easiest might be to either play h6  g5 (risky because then the f-pawn is backwards) and something like Nh5 , or Ng4 (after the bishop has moved) and then potentially f6  Ne5 , creating a blockade on the diagonal or Ng4  Be3 + trading the bishops. If Black unwinds, the isolated e-pawn will be a natural target. Let's follow a high level game that reached this position...} 12. Be2 Bxe2 13. Nxe2 Ng4 {This is Axel Smith vs. Angela Borsuk where the lower-rated Black player won. The f7 pawn is defended in a tactical way as Rf8 and then Nf2 would be a powerful response. Black can play Re8 next (assuming White stops Nf2 ) and attack the e4 pawn and threaten f6 . Black's king will emerge and the e-pawn will possibly fall.} *

