1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Bxf4 Ng4 {This alternative move has been played by strong players though. It is principled and looks a lot like other lines we've played. The fork threat is annoying to guard because on Bg3 Ne3 is winning the important bishop pair. So White must guard f2 awkwardly with a rook or a knight. As a downside, it violates the opening rule about not moving a piece twice and releases some of the pressure on e4 . 9. Nbd7 is my main recommendation.} 10. Nh3 {Black's results have been terrific here even if the computer gives White an edge. I think it's just easier to play Black without losing anything while White's pieces are clumsy even if an engine can somehow coordinate them in a funky way. If this were the only move White had, Ng4 wouldn't be an alternative but, rather, the recommendation!} Nd7 11. Nb5 {Attacking c7 but we are in time to defend.} Nde5 {This is the idea for Black of this line: clog up the e5 square. The knight on h3 stops White from dislodging the enemy knight.  Nh3 has been played in all games with this variation, but the reason it's only an alternative for Black in my course is because White's Nh3 isn't forced as we saw in the previous Rd2 line.} *

