1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. Bxf4 Ng4 {9. Nbd7 is my main recommendation. This alternative move has been played by strong players though. It is principled and looks a lot like other lines we've played. f2 is an annoying square to guard because on...} {Bg3 Ne3 is winning the important bishop pair. So White must guard f2 awkwardly with a rook or a knight. As a downside, it violates the opening rule about not moving a piece twice and releases some of the pressure on e4 .} 10. Rd2 {This has never been played by White... all games went Nh3 in high level play, which we will cover next. But let's start with the scariest move to face for this alternative that makes me worry about the immediate Ng4 . The rook move has a strong downside: it allows an annoying pin. Perhaps that's why White players have avoided it. But the good news for White is that their knight can develop more actively than the square h3 allowed.} Bb4 {Is probably what White is fearing so that they played Nh3 instead. But after Nf3 , White has a lot of active play for the bad structure and I couldn't find equality for Black.} 11. Nf3 Bxc3 12. bxc3 {This line might be playable for White but their structure is awful.} Nf6 13. Nd4 ({Most players, I should note, won't play this engine-concocted knight move against you. They will play} 13. Bd3 {guarding the pawn and when you develop your knight with} Nbd7 {, you'll get a similar, but slightly less scary, version of the same position.}) ({The move here is based on a ridiculously complicated tactic: Nxe4 Nxe6 fxe6 because taking the rook results in White taking on c7 and snagging your rook while still up a piece} 13. Re2 {and if Nc5 guarding e6 and trying to prevent the infiltration of a very active enemy rook, White has g3 followed by Bg2 and making it almost impossible for you to lift your king and activate your final rook. This pawn-sacrifice variation is a bit ridiculous in terms of calculation and strategic understanding, but let's just assume for a second that you have either an incredibly strong tactical opponent or someone who looked up your lines on a computer before the game: we want to be prepared. So as tempting as pawns are, we must complete our development first with this position still fairly open. In fact, that's a good rule in general: grabbing pawns in the Philidor is usually a bad idea if it leads you far behind in development, especially in the Queen Trade lines with f4 . So develop first, then go pawn hunting.}) 13... Nbd7 {The computer likes White but practically, Black may be easier to play here. White's two bishops in the hands of an engine are wonderful but the doubled c-pawns and isolated a and e pawns would be tricky for any human player, which is why no human has ever gone into this wasteland as White. I can't speak to this variation objectively, but practically, Black has an edge in most games and Rd2 is a rare move compared to Nh3 . There's a solid enough second option to avoid this type of debate in my main recommendation but Ng4 has great practical chances, seems essentially sound, and I can recommend it enthusiastically as an alternative as a result.} *

