1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. e5 {A not terribly popular move but threatening checkmate is always exciting. Please DO NOT move the knight or Rd8 is game over. I lost this way once in blitz and I had to cry myself to sleep that night.} h6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. exf6 Bc5 {See the Bd6 line of Nge2 for a similar principle of the two bishops for doubled f-pawns. The long and short of this is that Black is doing great. f6 is a hard pawn for white to fully protect and the doubled pawns are trickier than they look to capture while the two bishops dominate the landscape. In the meantime, the open g-file means pressure on g2 , which can't move unless White undoubles Black's pawns. I'm not claiming an edge for Black here with best play by both sides but in Delgado vs. Oratovsky, the almost 200 points lower-rated Black player had no issues drawing this. And the 2600 White player immediately played g3 here and undoubled Black's pawn rather than playing against all that pressure.} *

