1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. e5 {A not terribly popular move but threatening checkmate is always exciting. Please DO NOT move the knight or Rd8 is game over. I lost this way once in blitz and I had to cry myself to sleep in the fetal position.} h6 10. Bxf4 (10. Bh4 g5 11. exf6 gxh4 {was played against me once, but it will be very similar to Bxf6 except White will have one less pawn.}) 10... Ng4 {White has succeeded in stopping Black's slow crush squeeze on the queenside. But at a price. Their dark squares are weak and the immediate threat is Nf2 . On Bg3 (the most natural block), Black wins the bishop pair with Ne3 . Nh3 leaves the knight without moves and the Black knight without a fear of h3 . So...} 11. Ne4 {This is the active looking move, threatening h3 , which would trap the black knight. But White cannot move twice and has no time: Black will threaten things for the next few moves and unwind with a tiny advantage.} Nd7 {Attacking e5 .} 12. Nf3 {The only move that would protect the e-pawn from a capture by Black's knights. h3 is threatened again.} Nc5 {Luring the knight away from the f2 square and trying to develop the black bishop on recapture. White should probably not allow that and play...} 13. Nfd2 {But with the d2 square occupied by the knight, there's now no retreat square for the bishop that guards e3 . C'est la vie....} g5 {With the idea of Ne3 on Bg3 again. g5 is an important idea in these lines because the dark-squared bishop is often overworked guarding e4 and the e3 entry point. White's best continuation is...} 14. h3 gxf4 15. hxg4 Bxg4 {Black has a tiny edge here. I'm not sure they get to keep the pawn, but they will probably hold on to the bishop pair awhile and can press. The rook will be activated either by a5 - a4 or c6  Kc7 .} *

