1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ {Nbd7 can be played here by Black but I will recommend the approach taken by the top players.} Kc8 8. f4 {This is what White should do. In my database, literally every top Super GM has pushed f4 here as White, and non-Super-GM titled players still prefer f4 by an overwhelming margin in this position. It was even chosen by Super GM Wesley So when he was paired against a Philidor expert, GM Melik Khachiyan. I'm not saying the higher-rated players will all know about this move though, 8. Nf3 was chosen about 33% of the time in Master games despite being an inferior move. The Philidor is rare and people can be expected to misplay against it even into the 2300 levels. With this move, White is threatening to take our pawn or dislodge our beautiful e6 bishop with f5 . So we need to take on f4 .} exf4 9. e5 {A not terribly popular move but threatening checkmate is always exciting. Please DO NOT move the knight or Rd8 is game over. I lost this way once in blitz and I had to cry myself to sleep in the fetal position.} h6 10. Bxf4 (10. Bh4 g5 11. exf6 gxh4 {was played against me once, but it will be very similar to Bxf6 except White will have one less pawn.}) 10... Ng4 {White has succeeded in stopping Black's slow crush squeeze on the queenside. But at a price. Their dark squares are weak and the immediate threat is Nf2 . On Bg3 (the most natural block), Black wins the bishop pair with Ne3 . Nh3 leaves the knight without moves and the Black knight without a fear of h3 . So...} 11. Rd2 g5 12. Bg3 Ne3 13. Bd3 Nc6 14. Nf3 Nf5 {The knight's job on e3 complete, it now heads to harass the g3 bishop and assist the other knight in travelling to d4 so we can trade and play c6  Kc7 . With a pawn threatening to go to g4 and a knight threatening to remove the bishop defender, white might find the e5 pawn hard to hold.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
