[Black "Club Player Mainline"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "28"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 {In addition to our recommendation, Ke8 and Bb4 are interesting choices. Of those, I think the former has the best standing and it has been played by Vachier Lagrave, Jobava, and Rapport (quite the endorsement). Let me give you some information on those two options in case you want to self study them and also explain why I like the purposeful doubling of our pawns here instead.   Ke8 is a very difficult move to make work. Our normal plans are just harder to initiate and Black has to know several ways to untie a Gordian knot in order to get their pieces to work together. It's often more concrete than philosophical. I've experimented with it myself and find it atrociously hard and moves are situational and it's nothing like the Bg5 systems. So, if you're playing for a win against a 2700 rated GM, Ke8 might be a good pet project. If you're trying to beat someone rated a mere 2200 or below, our normal line should give you enough chances and will be a lot easier to master in a short time.   Bb4 was what I wanted to make work because it has two advantages that I typically love: it's kind of obscure and the win rates are good. That said, there's a reason it's obscure: it's slightly suspect. I don't think it loses, but it looks like Black will be playing with an isolated pawn if White responds correctly and White will have a nagging all-game push. Given that the mainline is so so strong, it seems like a pity to allow White this. Especially since surprise value may work on a 2700 with Bb4 but for most of my readers, their opponents will be surprised by the Philidor in the first place, without us having to do anything weird. Cuenca, in his Lifetime Philidor, recommends Bb4 and for the purposes of appealing to readers who own both courses, in addition to the other reasons, I'll go a different route.} Be6 {This move is hard to play as on first glance, it looks absolutely awful. But it is a diamond in the rough and you will see that White has to tread carefully. It has tremendous stats: White only wins 25% against it to Black's 18% with the rest draws in Master-level chess. It has been played by super grandmasters Gulko and Jobava, so it is legit. In Lichess battles, Black actually wins more than loses with a 47% win rate and a 43% loss rate. This second stat shows you of the effectiveness of this pre 2200: the game is rarely drawn. If White doesn't know the path, it will be very exciting for Black, and if they do, you should hold the position into a draw.} 7. Bxe6 {I mean, what else?} fxe6 {So, let's talk about plans here and those ugly doubled pawns.   Okay, the CON : they look ugly and like they're always on the verge of death. I see that too. But it's a mirage. A clever one. And they secretly not only aren't as bad as they seem but they're also actually... good!   Let's look closer: I want you to note something: where would one of White's knights or bishop or rooks have to be to attack the e6 pawn? You might notice that practically every square is either blocked from entry or can be blocked from entry. That e6 pawn is not easily attacked at all! For example, Black could play h6 and b6 and then no knight could ever come to attack it, which I will later call the Fort Knox setup. Okay, okay, so you say it's not as bad as it looks, but that doesn't mean it's not bad...   Well, it's not just that the doubled pawns are hard to attack, it's that Black's pawn structure also comes in handy in three ways. So here's the PRO :   1. The e6 pawn prevents knights from landing into d5 or f5 , two outposts they strove to arrive at in the Bg5 variation.   2. The doubled pawn opens the f-file for Black. This means that Black can get to f4 with a knight later and support it with a rook, harassing the White kingside. If White ever plays g3 to kick your knight in response to this, their f2 pawn will be backwards on the open f-file.   3. The pawn on e6 indirectly stops a major White plan in this position: f4 . We saw in the Bg5 line how important f4 was for White to pressure Black. But now f4 undoubles Black's pawns and you don't even lose your e-pawn presence!   The major decision Black must make is whether to pursue a queenside pawn storm and play for a win with some risk or to just lock down with the b6  h6 strategy. I think whenever possible, it's best to play with some flare, so I'm recommending the queenside pawn storm strategy but as an alternative for those who feel very cautious, I will give you the Fort Knox setup.} {Here, if you are 2200 and above, you may want to pay very close attention to f3 lines and possibly Be3 as those are White's two main tries for an advantage with complex follow ups. But if you're anywhere below the professional title level, I'll be honest: White's unlikely to play either of the best moves. The main moves for White here according to the Lichess database among mere mortals are Nf3 and Bg5 , two natural and bad moves. If I cap it off at 1600 on Lichess, White has only played f3 or Be3 in 600 out of 6,500 games. That's only a one in ten chance. So I'd say study Nf3 and Bg5 first here as you'll see a big advantage in most of your games. Then go back and be able to play against the others if you start randomly encountering Philidor experts who for some reason don't play the better mainline tension variations.} 8. Nf3 Bd6 {One big difference between the Queen Trade Bc4 and Queen Trade Bg5 variation is where you put your dark-squared bishop.  Often in the Queen Trade Bc4 variation, the dark-squared bishop wants to go to d6 to guard the e5 pawn.    We can leave it at that for those who live and breathe principles but for those who only remember rules when those rules have a reason, let's dive into the 'why?'   Well, first, we want it on d6 to guard e5 ; it was attacked. Well and good but Nbd7 could have also defended so we need more reasons. So second, we want the bishop on d6 because it helps prevent White's f4 break. Third, it's just safe there: Black can protect the bishop there with the c7 -pawn all game. Note that this is different from the other line and so needs to be emphasized. Recall that the c-pawn couldn't stay back in the 'Queen Trade Bg5 ' variation because Black had to use it to block enemy knight jumps. But here, we have doubled pawns. Those doubled pawns prevent enemy knight jumps and, as a result, give the c-pawn the flexibility of staying back and defending our bishop, creating an awesome blockade and force field around our king. No rooks are coming down the d-file with the bishop secure on d6 .   Also, remember a huge pro of the doubled pawns was that it opened up the f-file, which will help us get a knight to f4 . From d6 , the bishop will x-ray protect that knight on f4 and contribute to that vision.   Finally, our king often steps forth to defend e6 here, so unless we want that bishop blocked in by a monarch, it has to move now. So this move, Bd6 , guarded by the c7 pawn just makes a lot of sense as our preferred blockade-White's-plans setup in the Queen Trade Bc4 line.} 9. Bg5 {Not the best move, but the most likely. Moves here matter less than understanding. We are essentially doing the same setup every time. Bd6 - Ke7 - a6 - Nbd7 .} ({Sometimes, in Club Level play, White plays} 9. Ng5 {here when} Ke7 {strongly resembles a position and pawn structure mentioned at the end of one of the Queen Trade Sidelines chapter notes that you can check out here.}) 9... Ke7 10. O-O-O a6 {To be honest, Nc6 looks fantastic here and has a great win rate in practice. Defending e5 so you can play Bb4 makes a lot of sense. That said, playing a6 in one variation and Nc6 in another is liable to be confusing. Given that a6 works, let's just play the same way against the club players as we do against the grandmasters.} 11. h3 {This is the most popular move but looking at the database it just appears that White has no idea what they're doing. Random moves pop up and it all reeks of confusion and disarray. No wonder stat wise, Black is winning a whopping 61% of the games.} Nbd7 {Stage one of Black's plan is complete. Now for the pawn storm. White tends to play a3 , Rhe1 and Nd2 in that order here in non-master games. I don't think you need to memorize a variation against all of them, just tally ho on the queenside.} 12. a3 b5 13. Rhe1 Rhb8 14. Na2 a5 {Black plans to open up files on the queenside while neutralizing the kingside. With the queenside files, you can play for checkmate or try to win material over on that side of the board with your superior piece count. When we play b5 , White will want to play a4  b3 and close things up, declining the open file offers. So we can use the knight to discourage such avoidances and look at that side of the board to force White's hand. Also, e4 is always a possible attack spot.} *

