ou will see that White has to tread carefully. It has tremendous stats: White only wins 25% against it to Black's 18% with the rest draws in Master-level chess. It has been played by super grandmasters Gulko and Jobava, so it is legit. In Lichess battles, Black actually wins more than loses with a 47% win rate and a 43% loss rate. This second stat shows you of the effectiveness of this pre 2200: the game is rarely drawn. If White doesn't know the path, it will be very exciting for Black, and if they do, you should hold the position into a draw.} 7. Bxe6 {I mean, what else?} fxe6 {So, let's talk about plans here and those ugly doubled pawns.   Okay, the CON : they look ugly and like they're always on the verge of death. I see that too. But it's a mirage. A clever one. And they secretly not only aren't as bad as they seem but they're also actually... good!   Let's look closer: I want you to note something: where would one of White's knights or bishop or rooks have to be to attack the e6 pawn? You might notice that practically every square is either blocked from entry or can be blocked from entry. That e6 pawn is not easily attacked at all! For example, Black could play h6 and b6 and then no knight could ever come to attack it, which I will later call the Fort Knox setup. Okay, okay, so you say it's not as bad as it looks, but that doesn't mean it's not bad...   Well, it's not just that the doubled pawns are hard to attack, it's that Black's pawn structure also comes in handy in three ways. So here's the PRO :   1. The e6 pawn prevents knights from landing into d5 or f5 , two outposts they strove to arrive at in the Bg5 variation.   2. The doubled pawn opens the f-file for Black. This means that Black can get to f4 with a knight later and support it with a rook, harassing the White kingside. If White ever plays g3 to kick your knight in response to this, their f2 pawn will be backwards on the open f-file.   3. The pawn on e6 indirectly stops a major White plan in this position: f4 . We saw in the Bg5 line how important f4 was for White to pressure Black. But now f4 undoubles Black's pawns and you don't even lose your e-pawn presence!   The major decision Black must make is whether to pursue a queenside pawn storm and play for a win with some risk or to just lock down with the b6  h6 strategy. I think whenever possible, it's best to play with some flare, so I'm recommending the queenside pawn storm strategy but as an alternative for those who feel very cautious, I will give you the Fort Knox setup.} {Here, if you are 2200 and above, you may want to pay very close attention to f3 lines and possibly Be3 as those are White's two main tries for an advantage with complex follow ups. But if you're anywhere below the professional title level, I'll be honest: White's unlikely to play either of the best moves. The main moves for White here according to the Lichess database are 8. Nf3 and 8. Bg5 , two natural and bad moves. If I cap it off at 1600 on Lichess, White has only played f3 or Be3 in 600 out of 6,500 games. That's only a one in ten chance. So I'd say study Nf3 and Bg5 first here as you'll see a big advantage in most of your games. Then go back and be able to play against the others if you start randomly encountering Philidor experts who for some reason don't play the better mainline tension variations.} 8. Nf3 Nc6 {Of course, as an alternative, we can just do the fianchetto the king strategy. In that case, we will play on the other side of the board and try to make that open f-file matter.} 9. Bg5 h6 10. O-O-O+ Bd6 11. Bh4 Kc8 {You'll catch a few people with Nb5  Nxe4 . You'd be surprised how many forget the e-pawn is hanging once they go bishop hunting.} 12. Nd2 {We're out of any forced theory and more just looking at the Black setup.} b6 {Look at all the knight moves that would hit the e6 pawn: totally neutralized.} 13. Nc4 Bb4 {It's approximately level and we are Fort Knoxing it with play on the kingside. If White plays f3 , it will be cousin to the end position of a variation that will be covered later . Just make sure to watch for White's attempts to put a rook on the seventh.} *

