ou will see that White has to tread carefully. It has tremendous stats: White only wins 25% against it to Black's 18% with the rest draws in Master-level chess. It has been played by super grandmasters Gulko and Jobava, so it is legit. In Lichess battles, Black actually wins more than loses with a 47% win rate and a 43% loss rate. This second stat shows you of the effectiveness of this pre 2200: the game is rarely drawn. If White doesn't know the path, it will be very exciting for Black, and if they do, you should hold the position into a draw.} 7. Bxe6 {I mean, what else?} fxe6 {So, let's talk about plans here and those ugly doubled pawns.   Okay, the CON : they look ugly and like they're always on the verge of death. I see that too. But it's a mirage. A clever one. And they secretly not only aren't as bad as they seem but they're also actually... good!   Let's look closer: I want you to note something: where would one of White's knights or bishop or rooks have to be to attack the e6 pawn? You might notice that practically every square is either blocked from entry or can be blocked from entry. That e6 pawn is not easily attacked at all! For example, Black could play h6 and b6 and then no knight could ever come to attack it, which I will later call the Fort Knox setup. Okay, okay, so you say it's not as bad as it looks, but that doesn't mean it's not bad...   Well, it's not just that the doubled pawns are hard to attack, it's that Black's pawn structure also comes in handy in three ways. So here's the PRO :   1. The e6 pawn prevents knights from landing into d5 or f5 , two outposts they strove to arrive at in the Bg5 variation.   2. The doubled pawn opens the f-file for Black. This means that Black can get to f4 with a knight later and support it with a rook, harassing the White kingside. If White ever plays g3 to kick your knight in response to this, their f2 pawn will be backwards on the open f-file.   3. The pawn on e6 indirectly stops a major White plan in this position: f4 . We saw in the Bg5 line how important f4 was for White to pressure Black. But now f4 undoubles Black's pawns and you don't even lose your e-pawn presence!   The major decision Black must make is whether to pursue a queenside pawn storm and play for a win with some risk or to just lock down with the b6  h6 strategy. I think whenever possible, it's best to play with some flare, so I'm recommending the queenside pawn storm strategy but as an alternative for those who feel very cautious, I will give you the Fort Knox setup.} {Here, if you are 2200 and above, you may want to pay very close attention to f3 lines and possibly Be3 as those are White's two main tries for an advantage with complex follow ups. But if you're anywhere below the professional title level, I'll be honest: White's unlikely to play either of the best moves. The main moves for White here according to the Lichess database are 8. Nf3 and 8. Bg5 , two natural and bad moves. If I cap it off at 1600 on Lichess, White has only played f3 or Be3 in 600 out of 6,500 games. That's only a one in ten chance. So I'd say study Nf3 and Bg5 first here as you'll see a big advantage in most of your games. Then go back and be able to play against the others if you start randomly encountering Philidor experts who for some reason don't play the better mainline tension variations.} 8. Bg5 {This move isn't very good but it's played a lot. The reason it's not great is that White will never want to take the Black knight: that would just un-isolate Black's pawn and it wouldn't double anything. Additionally, with the open f-file, the h6  g5 plans are usually good for Black and White just gives them this expansion for free. Better is to play f3  Be3 and restrict Black's bishop. One good plan here is to do the usual setup, Bd6  Ke7  a6 and keep it simple. Since that is self explanatory and since White really is asking for kingside assaults with Bg5 I give this line as an additional way of playing} h6 ({Some players will play O-O-O} 8... Bd6 {but this will just transpose. Attacking the bishop is good because it invites White to give you the bishop pair for nothing or redirect it to a worse diagonal. 9. Bxf6 is even worse here than usual because it un-isolates our doubled pawns.}) 9. Bh4 g5 {This is a novelty that looks great. The bishop will be out of play and Black can attack on the kingside.} 10. Bg3 Bd6 {See previous notes on why the bishop wants to go to d6 in the Queen Trade Bc4 variation. I'd recommend the fianchetto the king strategy a la Fort Knox setups here because that setup likes kingside play and we already have dividends. But Ke7  a6  b5 stuff is also playable. Personal preference and Black is fine.} *

