ou will see that White has to tread carefully. It has tremendous stats: White only wins 25% against it to Black's 18% with the rest draws in Master-level chess. It has been played by super grandmasters Gulko and Jobava, so it is legit. In Lichess battles, Black actually wins more than loses with a 47% win rate and a 43% loss rate. This second stat shows you of the effectiveness of this pre 2200: the game is rarely drawn. If White doesn't know the path, it will be very exciting for Black, and if they do, you should hold the position into a draw.} 7. Bxe6 {I mean, what else?} fxe6 {So, let's talk about plans here and those ugly doubled pawns.   Okay, the CON : they look ugly and like they're always on the verge of death. I see that too. But it's a mirage. A clever one. And they secretly not only aren't as bad as they seem but they're also actually... good!   Let's look closer: I want you to note something: where would one of White's knights or bishop or rooks have to be to attack the e6 pawn? You might notice that practically every square is either blocked from entry or can be blocked from entry. That e6 pawn is not easily attacked at all! For example, Black could play h6 and b6 and then no knight could ever come to attack it, which I will later call the Fort Knox setup. Okay, okay, so you say it's not as bad as it looks, but that doesn't mean it's not bad...   Well, it's not just that the doubled pawns are hard to attack, it's that Black's pawn structure also comes in handy in three ways. So here's the PRO :   1. The e6 pawn prevents knights from landing into d5 or f5 , two outposts they strove to arrive at in the Bg5 variation.   2. The doubled pawn opens the f-file for Black. This means that Black can get to f4 with a knight later and support it with a rook, harassing the White kingside. If White ever plays g3 to kick your knight in response to this, their f2 pawn will be backwards on the open f-file.   3. The pawn on e6 indirectly stops a major White plan in this position: f4 . We saw in the Bg5 line how important f4 was for White to pressure Black. But now f4 undoubles Black's pawns and you don't even lose your e-pawn presence!   The major decision Black must make is whether to pursue a queenside pawn storm and play for a win with some risk or to just lock down with the b6  h6 strategy. I think whenever possible, it's best to play with some flare, so I'm recommending the queenside pawn storm strategy but as an alternative for those who feel very cautious, I will give you the Fort Knox setup.} {Here, if you are 2200 and above, you may want to pay very close attention to f3 lines and possibly Be3 as those are White's two main tries for an advantage with complex follow ups. But if you're anywhere below the professional title level, I'll be honest: White's unlikely to play either of the best moves. The main moves for White here according to the Lichess database are 8. Nf3 and 8. Bg5 , two natural and bad moves. If I cap it off at 1600 on Lichess, White has only played f3 or Be3 in 600 out of 6,500 games. That's only a one in ten chance. So I'd say study Nf3 and Bg5 first here as you'll see a big advantage in most of your games. Then go back and be able to play against the others if you start randomly encountering Philidor experts who for some reason don't play the better mainline tension variations.} 8. f3 {f3 introduces the best way to play the Queen Trade Bc4 line. The move prepares possible kingside play, stops Ng4 (thereby preparing Be3 ), guards e4 to free up the White knight. It's the top Grandmaster choice. The nice thing about this position is practically any reasonable move in response is okay and has been played. In the seven moves Black has played in Master level games ( So if you're just studying the non-GM games for now, just play with the principles below and you should survive Club Player attacks.   [Black's setup:] 1. Black wants to play the king to e7 . This guards e6 and is hard for White to attack because the e6 pawn guards all useful knight checking squares.   2. We want to put our bishop on d6 .  If we are playing Ke7 at some point, then we need to play Bd6 first so we don't block the bishop in, and so we have extra protection against White's f4 break (White will want to open up things against our centralized king).   3. We want to play a6  b5 eventually, leaving the c-pawn back for now. When we play our bishop to d6 , we need some protection against Nb5 later. c6 would be the normal prevention move but don't do that. The doubled pawns are already guarding central knight jumps so we can hang back with the c-pawn to guard our bishop on d6 .  That said there's some good news: Nb5 winning our bishop is usually not so bad for Black anyway if we can recapture with the c-pawn. So a6 prevents a reasonable option for White, but not a deadly one, and starts the queenside pawn storm to activate our rooks.   The Bd6 , Ke7 , a6 setup will clog the d-file which is White's main counterplay when Black doesn't have a light-squared bishop.  We will use this setup for a central fortress and then pawn storm the queenside. We must pawn storm because otherwise our rooks will be bad: they need pawn trades to access good files. We can also pawn storm the kingside if White castles over there with h6  g5 . For the sake of something new and exciting, in some variations here I'm going to recommend going for it by pushing the c-pawn, which will unclog the d-file but accelerate the queenside storm. It's all computer checked but more cautious players can keep leaving that c-pawn behind.} {Bd6 , Bc5 , Nc6 , a6 , Nbd7 , Bb4 , c6 ), White hasn't mustered above a 40% win rate against any of them.} a6 {This will be the mainline but it entails some risk. Probably safer and more drawish would be the b6  h6 strategy (I'm giving it as an alternative ) or Bb4 .} 9. Nh3 {White is eyeing Ng5 . With our King heading to e7 we don't want to play h6 in this variation (that's the Fort Knox one). We need to make sure we don't block our bishop when we come to the pawn's rescue, so now is the time to play Bd6 .} Bd6 {Recall that we always want the bishop here as was explained in the opening Club Player chapter.} 10. Be3 Ke7 (10... Nc6 {is very good. I'm going to avoid it mainly because I want to try to keep things consistent between this variation and the Bg5 one and aim for a queenside pawn storm in both. That way the main thing to remember is king goes to e7 when you have doubled pawns.}) 11. Nf2 {Up until this point we have been following Spasov vs. Gelashvili, 2008. Black has played h6 and Nc6 here with good results (drawn) but I'd like to surprise our opponent here and play something never before played.} c5 {A novelty. If our opponent is this booked up, we might as well take them out of their comfort zone in a sensible way. The idea is to hinder the White knight from going to d3 and provide a retreat location for our bishop if it so desires. The queenside space is also part of the usual plan here. Usually this isn't playable because of Nd5 but the e6 pawn nicely covers the d5 hole. We have no Master games in this line, so I have to use blitz chess to guess White's potential reaction here.} 12. Nb1 c4 {And this sensible move now has no blitz chess games, so we really are in the unexplored. But it is very logical, preventing Nd3 and taking the c4 square that the White knight wanted to reroute through. We will proceed on the queenside most likely but are ready to play on either wing. White is a bit cramped for space but Black still has those pawns long term so it's about level. From here on out I'll follow three computer lines in the alternatives for higher depth and give analysis on the most natural White human plans along the way and our response to them. I end the MoveTrainer here as the position is now unlikely for Club Level players, and even unlikely for the Master ones. But I give more depth here and as alternatives for those at the highest rating ranges wishing to maximize the follow ups.} *

