1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 {In addition to our recommendation, Ke8 and Bb4 are interesting choices. Of those, I think the former has the best standing and it has been played by Vachier Lagrave, Jobava, and Rapport (quite the endorsement). Let me give you some information on those two options in case you want to self study them and also explain why I like the purposeful doubling of our pawns here instead.   Ke8 is a very difficult move to make work. Our normal plans are just harder to initiate and Black has to know several ways to untie a Gordian knot in order to get their pieces to work together. It's often more concrete than philosophical. I've experimented with it myself and find it atrociously hard and moves are situational and it's nothing like the Bg5 systems. So, if you're playing for a win against a 2700 rated GM, Ke8 might be a good pet project. If you're trying to beat someone rated a mere 2200 or below, our normal line should give you enough chances and will be a lot easier to master in a short time.   Bb4 was what I wanted to make work because it has two advantages that I typically love: it's kind of obscure and the win rates are good. That said, there's a reason it's obscure: it's slightly suspect. I don't think it loses, but it looks like Black will be playing with an isolated pawn if White responds correctly and White will have a nagging all-game push. Given that the mainline is so so strong, it seems like a pity to allow White this. Especially since surprise value may work on a 2700 with Bb4 but for most of my readers, their opponents will be surprised by the Philidor in the first place, without us having to do anything weird. Cuenca, in his Lifetime Philidor, recommends Bb4 and for the purposes of appealing to readers who own both courses, in addition to the other reasons, I'll go a different route.} Be6 {This move is hard to play as on first glance, it looks absolutely awful. But it is a diamond in the rough and you will see that White has to tread carefully. It has tremendous stats: White only wins 25% against it to Black's 18% with the rest draws in Master-level chess. It has been played by super grandmasters Gulko and Jobava, so it is legit. In Lichess battles, Black actually wins more than loses with a 47% win rate and a 43% loss rate. This second stat shows you of the effectiveness of this pre 2200: the game is rarely drawn. If White doesn't know the path, it will be very exciting for Black, and if they do, you should hold the position into a draw.} 7. Bxe6 {I mean, what else?} fxe6 {So, let's talk about plans here and those ugly doubled pawns.   Okay, the CON : they look ugly and like they're always on the verge of death. I see that too. But it's a mirage. A clever one. And they secretly not only aren't as bad as they seem but they're also actually... good!   Let's look closer: I want you to note something: where would one of White's knights or bishop or rooks have to be to attack the e6 pawn? You might notice that practically every square is either blocked from entry or can be blocked from entry. That e6 pawn is not easily attacked at all! For example, Black could play h6 and b6 and then no knight could ever come to attack it, which I will later call the Fort Knox setup. Okay, okay, so you say it's not as bad as it looks, but that doesn't mean it's not bad...   Well, it's not just that the doubled pawns are hard to attack, it's that Black's pawn structure also comes in handy in three ways. So here's the PRO :   1. The e6 pawn prevents knights from landing into d5 or f5 , two outposts they strove to arrive at in the Bg5 variation.   2. The doubled pawn opens the f-file for Black. This means that Black can get to f4 with a knight later and support it with a rook, harassing the White kingside. If White ever plays g3 to kick your knight in response to this, their f2 pawn will be backwards on the open f-file.   3. The pawn on e6 indirectly stops a major White plan in this position: f4 . We saw in the Bg5 line how important f4 was for White to pressure Black. But now f4 undoubles Black's pawns and you don't even lose your e-pawn presence!   The major decision Black must make is whether to pursue a queenside pawn storm and play for a win with some risk or to just lock down with the b6  h6 strategy. I think whenever possible, it's best to play with some flare, so I'm recommending the queenside pawn storm strategy but as an alternative for those who feel very cautious, I will give you the Fort Knox setup.} {Here, if you are 2200 and above, you may want to pay very close attention to f3 lines and possibly Be3 as those are White's two main tries for an advantage with complex follow ups. But if you're anywhere below the professional title level, I'll be honest: White's unlikely to play either of the best moves. The main moves for White here according to the Lichess database are 8. Nf3 and 8. Bg5 , two natural and bad moves. If I cap it off at 1600 on Lichess, White has only played f3 or Be3 in 600 out of 6,500 games. That's only a one in ten chance. So I'd say study Nf3 and Bg5 first here as you'll see a big advantage in most of your games. Then go back and be able to play against the others if you start randomly encountering Philidor experts who for some reason don't play the better mainline tension variations.} 8. f3 {f3 introduces the best way to play the Queen Trade Bc4 line. The move prepares possible kingside play, stops Ng4 (thereby preparing Be3 ), guards e4 to free up the White knight. It's the top Grandmaster choice. The nice thing about this position is practically any reasonable move in response is okay and has been played. In the seven moves Black has played in Master level games ( So if you're just studying the non-GM games for now, just play with the principles below and you should survive Club Player attacks.   [Black's setup:] 1. Black wants to play the king to e7 . This guards e6 and is hard for White to attack because the