e we don't block our bishop when we come to the pawn's rescue, so now is the time to play Bd6 .} Bd6 {Recall that we always want the bishop here as was explained in the opening Club Player chapter.} 10. Be3 Ke7 {Nc6 is very good. I'm going to avoid it mainly because I want to try to keep things consistent between this variation and the Bg5 one and aim for a queenside pawn storm in both. That way the main thing to remember is king goes to e7 when you have doubled pawns.} 11. Nf2 {Up until this point we have been following Spasov vs. Gelashvili, 2008. Black has played h6 and Nc6 here with good results (drawn) but I'd like to surprise our opponent here and play something never before played.} c5 {A novelty. If our opponent is this booked up, we might as well take them out of their comfort zone in a sensible way. The idea is to hinder the White knight from going to d3 and provide a retreat location for our bishop if it so desires. The queenside space is also part of the usual plan here. Usually this isn't playable because of Nd5 but the e6 pawn nicely covers the d5 hole. We have no Master games in this line, so I have to use blitz chess to guess White's potential reaction here.} 12. Nb1 {This is what a 2650 blitz player did in this position. It makes sense: trying to relocate the bad knight and go to b6 via Nd2 - c4 .} c4 {And this sensible move now has no blitz chess games, so we really are in the unexplored. But it is very logical, preventing Nd3 and taking the c4 square that the White knight wanted to reroute through. We will proceed on the queenside most likely but are ready to play on either wing. White is a bit cramped for space but Black still has those pawns long term so it's about level. From here on out I'll follow three computer lines in the alternatives for higher depth and give analysis on the most natural White human plans along the way and our response to them. I end the MoveTrainer here as the position is now unlikely for Club Level players, and even unlikely for the Master ones. But I give more depth here and as alternatives for those at the highest rating ranges wishing to maximize the follow ups.} 13. b3 {b3 could be played to challenge Black. But White isn't ahead in development, so I'm not sure it's right on principle.} Rc8 14. Nd2 ({White doesn't want to take Black and isolate the c-pawn on the open file. So perhaps White thinks a knight attack will force the issue? The problem with that idea is that Black can now just activate their pieces by clearing the c-file and getting to the seventh rank. It's so strong for Black on the queenside that I even entertained recommending b5 here when} 14. bxc4 Bb4+ {is interesting. The pawn sacrifice b5 worked out to a probable draw but it was more complicated than the simple cxb3 , so I guess I just have to sigh and recommend the simple path to equality instead of making it harder on ourselves.}) 14... cxb3 {With movement on the queenside ahead of us: b5 , Rc2 , Nc6 , etc.} 15. cxb3 b5 {The position is fairly level. White is going to try to make the argument that the doubled pawns matter. It's a tricky argument to make because they are very easy to defend, not attackable by a rook and hard to attack with knights while Black can guard them with almost every piece they have. Black is going to argue that they have nice outposts for the knights on d4 and f4 and have gotten to the c-file first, so have a certain amount of queenside pressure. Probably both downsides can be defended with accurate play and there are enough pieces on the board that the better player should win. The black bishop is a great defender; however, if you wanted to switch to offense, it would love to go to a3 . If the bishop gets to a3 , White will have trouble fighting back on the c-file, so it's something to think about depending on the situation and how much White is tying the bishop to the defense of the e5 pawn.   Infiltrating the c-file with rooks and advancing knights is slightly easier to plan than somehow trying to pick on the doubled pawns so I'd rather play Black. Stockfish says totally equal.} *

