ure we don't block our bishop when we come to the pawn's rescue, so now is the time to play Bd6 .} Bd6 {Recall that we always want the bishop here as was explained in the opening Club Player chapter.} 10. Be3 Ke7 {Nc6 is very good. I'm going to avoid it mainly because I want to try to keep things consistent between this variation and the Bg5 one and aim for a queenside pawn storm in both. That way the main thing to remember is king goes to e7 when you have doubled pawns.} 11. Nf2 {Up until this point we have been following Spasov vs. Gelashvili, 2008. Black has played h6 and Nc6 here with good results (drawn) but I'd like to surprise our opponent here and play something never before played.} c5 {A novelty. If our opponent is this booked up, we might as well take them out of their comfort zone in a sensible way. The idea is to hinder the White knight from going to d3 and provide a retreat location for our bishop if it so desires. The queenside space is also part of the usual plan here. Usually this isn't playable because of Nd5 but the e6 pawn nicely covers the d5 hole. We have no Master games in this line, so I have to use blitz chess to guess White's potential reaction here.} 12. Nb1 {This is what a 2650 blitz player did in this position. It makes sense: trying to relocate the bad knight and go to b6 via Nd2 - c4 .} c4 {And this sensible move now has no blitz chess games, so we really are in the unexplored. But it is very logical, preventing Nd3 and taking the c4 square that the White knight wanted to reroute through. We will proceed on the queenside most likely but are ready to play on either wing. White is a bit cramped for space but Black still has those pawns long term so it's about level. From here on out I'll follow three computer lines in the alternatives for higher depth and give analysis on the most natural White human plans along the way and our response to them. I end the MoveTrainer here as the position is now unlikely for Club Level players, and even unlikely for the Master ones. But I give more depth here and as alternatives for those at the highest rating ranges wishing to maximize the follow ups.} 13. a4 {a4 seemed reasonable, stopping b5 and trying to pick off c4 . But without White's light-squared bishop, I had my doubts and the biggest issue is that it weakens the b4 square so Black can continue...} Nc6 14. c3 b5 {And with our rooks connected, we play it anyway.} 15. Nd2 Rhc8 ({Many Black moves were possible. This one, prophylactically stopping b3 by being on the file, preparing to double by lifting, and potentially supporting pieces into c5 is a nice option along with} 15... Nd7 {. Again, perhaps White has a slight edge on paper, but Black's position is so much easier to play. Black can reroute the f6 knight to f4 via h5 or to c5 via d7 . I prefer the latter in most cases. I have trouble finding a great White plan here.}) *

