ure we don't block our bishop when we come to the pawn's rescue, so now is the time to play Bd6 .} Bd6 10. Be3 Ke7 {Nc6 is very good. I'm going to avoid it mainly because I want to try to keep things consistent between this variation and the Bg5 one and aim for a queenside pawn storm in both. That way the main thing to remember is king goes to e7 when you have doubled pawns.} 11. Nf2 {Up until this point we have been following Spasov vs. Gelashvili, 2008. Black has played h6 and Nc6 here with good results (drawn) but I'd like to surprise our opponent here and play something never before played.} c5 {A novelty. If our opponent is this booked up, we might as well take them out of their comfort zone in a sensible way. The idea is to hinder the White knight from going to d3 and provide a retreat location for our bishop if it so desires. The queenside space is also part of the usual plan here. Usually this isn't playable because of Nd5 but the e6 pawn nicely covers the d5 hole. We have no Master games in this line, so I have to use blitz chess to guess White's potential reaction here.} 12. O-O-O (12. Nb1 {might be what a 2600 played but O-O-O is for the normal chess player.}) 12... Nbd7 (12... Nc6 {looks like the ideal way to go but} 13. Na4 {exposes some dark squared problems in Black's camp and we need to keep an eye on those.}) 13. Rd2 {Doubling seems natural.} Rac8 {This is a multi-functional move. First, we are going to help our dark-squared bishop relocate if necessary to either b8 , where it won't disconnect our rooks, or c5 , where it may need some extra defending. Second, we are protecting a pawn push to c4 to obstruct the enemy White knight from going to d3 . Third, we are planning Rc6 to make sure the d6 bishop gets to relocate leisurely instead of reactively to Rhd1 . We move this rook instead of the other one because we want to allow options of Rhd8 and because we don't want Bb8 to cut them off from each other.} 14. Rhd1 Rc6 ({One positional trap to watch out for is} 14... Bb8 $2 15. Ng4 {when our f6 knight can't move for fear of Rxd7 . White can remove defenders of the d7 knight and our seventh is weaker than normal without our bishop, so we want to make sure it's guarded before we reroute our bishop. At this point, we can stop memorizing unless we are above a certain level--those who want more can look at the optional DEPTH line. Play up to this point has been very directed with deviations likely and the further we go, the more deviations we get potentially. No move hangs in the balance here. Black will continue expanding on both wings and controlling White's d-file pressure. Pushing the c-pawn in these lines is a double-edged sword: the queenside pressure Black generates grows but the d-file is going to be harder to blockade. A couple of plans to leave you with if you won't be joining us for the alternative DEPTH lines...  1. Black can relocate the bishop later, and almost anywhere is an option based on the position. Once the bishop is moved, Black can play Rd6 to reduce some of that d-file double-rook pressure.    2. Black can play on the kingside too with h6  g5 and even Nh5 ideas. Just be a little careful of moving your f6 knight too soon as then the d7 knight will have no defense and the bishop on d6 will be pinned into blocking for it.   3. Black can play b5 and c4 .  c4 especially is nice for prevention against the white knight on f2 getting into the game via d3 . If White tries to play b3 to remove that pawn, they will open the c-file to potentially doubled rooks. Sometimes it might be better to play b5 first so that on a3 , Black can push and threaten to open the c-file by recapturing with the c-pawn.}) *

