he e6 pawn guards all useful knight checking squares.   2. We want to put our bishop on d6 .  If we are playing Ke7 at some point, then we need to play Bd6 first so we don't block the bishop in, and so we have extra protection against White's f4 break (White will want to open up things against our centralized king).   3. We want to play a6  b5 eventually, leaving the c-pawn back for now. When we play our bishop to d6 , we need some protection against Nb5 later. c6 would be the normal prevention move but don't do that. The doubled pawns are already guarding central knight jumps so we can hang back with the c-pawn to guard our bishop on d6 .  That said there's some good news: Nb5 winning our bishop is usually not so bad for Black anyway if we can recapture with the c-pawn. So a6 prevents a reasonable option for White, but not a deadly one, and starts the queenside pawn storm to activate our rooks.   The Bd6 , Ke7 , a6 setup will clog the d-file which is White's main counterplay when Black doesn't have a light-squared bishop.  We will use this setup for a central fortress and then pawn storm the queenside. We must pawn storm because otherwise our rooks will be bad: they need pawn trades to access good files. We can also pawn storm the kingside if White castles over there with h6  g5 . For the sake of something new and exciting, in some variations here I'm going to recommend going for it by pushing the c-pawn, which will unclog the d-file but accelerate the queenside storm. It's all computer checked but more cautious players can keep leaving that c-pawn behind.} {Bd6 , Bc5 , Nc6 , a6 , Nbd7 , Bb4 , c6 ), White hasn't mustered above a 40% win rate against any of them.} a6 {This will be the mainline but it entails some risk. Probably safer and more drawish would be the b6  h6 strategy (I'm giving it as an alternative) or Bb4 .} 9. Nh3 {White is eyeing Ng5 . With our King heading to e7 we don't want to play h6 in this variation (that's the Fort Knox one). We need to make sure we don't block our bishop when we come to the pawn's rescue, so now is the time to play Bd6 .} Bd6 10. Be3 Ke7 {Nc6 is very good. I'm going to avoid it mainly because I want to try to keep things consistent between this variation and the Bg5 one and aim for a queenside pawn storm in both. That way the main thing to remember is king goes to e7 when you have doubled pawns.} 11. Nf2 {Up until this point we have been following Spasov vs. Gelashvili, 2008. Black has played h6 and Nc6 here with good results (drawn) but I'd like to surprise our opponent here and play something never before played.} c5 {A novelty. If our opponent is this booked up, we might as well take them out of their comfort zone in a sensible way. The idea is to hinder the White knight from going to d3 and provide a retreat location for our bishop if it so desires. The queenside space is also part of the usual plan here. Usually this isn't playable because of Nd5 but the e6 pawn nicely covers the d5 hole. We have no Master games in this line, so I have to use blitz chess to guess White's potential reaction here.} 12. O-O-O {Nb1 might be what a 2600 played but O-O-O is for the normal chess player.} Nbd7 {Nc6 looks like the ideal way to go but Na4 exposes some dark squared problems in Black's camp and we need to keep an eye on those.} 13. Rd2 {Doubling seems natural.} Rac8 {We are going to defend the bishop with this rook.} 14. Rhd1 Rc6 ({One positional trap to watch out for is} 14... Bb8 $2 15. Ng4 {when our f6 knight can't move for fear of Rxd7 . White can remove defenders of the d7 knight and our seventh is weaker than normal without our bishop, so we want to make sure it's guarded before we reroute our bishop. For the die-hard chess players, I will give this optional-to-memorize line. If your rating is below 2000, you can avoid.}) 15. h3 {The computer move and a testament to how hard it is to find moves for White. Black's pieces may look in need of shuffling but Black has an abundance of small improvement moves that reveal themselves readily while White has to be very precise in their stalling. The plan is to play Ng4 and try to open up the h file. It's clever and we are playing a harder opponent in this variation than most will ever meet over the board. Luckily, our plan is simple.} b5 16. Ng4 Rhc8 {We ignore the knight parading around on the kingside, no need to give them the file by playing Nxg4  hxg4 . Our plan here is to play c4  b4  c3 and possibly Nh5 . If carried out, Black boasts a clear edge. So White must play preventatively.} 17. a3 b4 18. axb4 cxb4 19. Na4 {A double-edged position has arisen. At this point, we've guessed at way too many moves for this to be considered still the opening. If you put this on a computer, they will duke it out to equality. For the purposes of closure, I'll show a computer line here that reflects its estimation of best play by both sides. Of course, if you want solidity, go with the Fort Knox. This queenside pawn storm is all about trying to outplay the lower rated draw mongerer and it's more risky as a result.} b3 20. c3 {The b3 pawn is both a weakness and a strength.} R8c7 {Guarding this knight is typically helpful in these positions so that your f6 knight can go Nh5 - f4 without tactics on the file.} 21. Rd3 {Even White's computer moves show a pointlessness. So hard to play.} Nh5 22. Bf2 Nf4 23. Bh4+ Nf6 24. R3d2 a5 {I'll stop here, props if you checked this all the way through. Stockfish 14 gives this a 0.3 edge for White but of course, it's just plain unclear. It's very hard for White to find concrete threats and Black too. Both have played well. I don't think you'll ever get this position--hence the advice to stop on Rc6 for the non die-hards--but it's nice to know that not even Stockfish can crack Black's plan.} *

