[White "3) Queen Trade (6. Bc4)"]
[Black "Grandmaster Variation: Altern"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "24"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 {In addition to our recommendation, Ke8 and Bb4 are interesting choices. Of those, I think the former has the best standing and it has been played by Vachier Lagrave, Jobava, and Rapport (quite the endorsement). Let me give you some information on those two options in case you want to self study them and also explain why I like the purposeful doubling of our pawns here instead.   Ke8 is a very difficult move to make work. Our normal plans are just harder to initiate and Black has to know several ways to untie a Gordian knot in order to get their pieces to work together. It's often more concrete than philosophical. I've experimented with it myself and find it atrociously hard and moves are situational and it's nothing like the Bg5 systems. So, if you're playing for a win against a 2700 rated GM, Ke8 might be a good pet project. If you're trying to beat someone rated a mere 2200 or below, our normal line should give you enough chances and will be a lot easier to master in a short time.   Bb4 was what I wanted to make work because it has two advantages that I typically love: it's kind of obscure and the win rates are good. That said, there's a reason it's obscure: it's slightly suspect. I don't think it loses, but it looks like Black will be playing with an isolated pawn if White responds correctly and White will have a nagging all-game push. Given that the mainline is so so strong, it seems like a pity to allow White this. Especially since surprise value may work on a 2700 with Bb4 but for most of my readers, their opponents will be surprised by the Philidor in the first place, without us having to do anything weird. Cuenca, in his Lifetime Philidor, recommends Bb4 and for the purposes of appealing to readers who own both courses, in addition to the other reasons, I'll go a different route.} Be6 {This move is hard to play as on first glance, it looks absolutely awful. But it is a diamond in the rough and you will see that White has to tread carefully. It has tremendous stats: White only wins 25% against it to Black's 18% with the rest draws in Master-level chess. It has been played by super grandmasters Gulko and Jobava, so it is legit. In Lichess battles, Black actually wins more than loses with a 47% win rate and a 43% loss rate. This second stat shows you of the effectiveness of this pre 2200: the game is rarely drawn. If White doesn't know the path, it will be very exciting for Black, and if they do, you should hold the position into a draw.} 7. Bxe6 {I mean, what else?} fxe6 {So, let's talk about plans here and those ugly doubled pawns.   Okay, the CON : they look ugly and like they're always on the verge of death. I see that too. But it's a mirage. A clever one. And they secretly not only aren't as bad as they seem but they're also actually... good!   Let's look closer: I want you to note something: where would one of White's knights or bishop or rooks have to be to attack the e6 pawn? You might notice that practically every square is either blocked from entry or can be blocked from entry. That e6 pawn is not easily attacked at all! For example, Black could play h6 and b6 and then no knight could ever come to attack it, which I will later call the Fort Knox setup. Okay, okay, so you say it's not as bad as it looks, but that doesn't mean it's not bad...   Well, it's not just that the doubled pawns are hard to attack, it's that Black's pawn structure also comes in handy in three ways. So here's the PRO :   1. The e6 pawn prevents knights from landing into d5 or f5 , two outposts they strove to arrive at in the Bg5 variation.   2. The doubled pawn opens the f-file for Black. This means that Black can get to f4 with a knight later and support it with a rook, harassing the White kingside. If White ever plays g3 to kick your knight in response to this, their f2 pawn will be backwards on the open f-file.   3. The pawn on e6 indirectly stops a major White plan in this position: f4 . We saw in the Bg5 line how important f4 was for White to pressure Black. But now f4 undoubles Black's pawns and you don't even lose your e-pawn presence!   The major decision Black must make is whether to pursue a queenside pawn storm and play for a win with some risk or to just lock down with the b6  h6 strategy. I think whenever possible, it's best to play with some flare, so I'm recommending the queenside pawn storm strategy but as an alternative for those who feel very cautious, I will give you the Fort Knox setup.} {Here, if you are 2200 and above, you may want to pay very close attention to f3 lines and possibly Be3 as those are White's two main tries for an advantage with complex follow ups. But if you're anywhere below the professional title level, I'll be honest: White's unlikely to play either of the best moves. The main moves for White here according to the Lichess database are 8. Nf3 and 8. Bg5 , two natural and bad moves. If I cap it off at 1600 on Lichess, White has only played f3 or Be3 in 600 out of 6,500 games. That's only a one in ten chance. So I'd say study Nf3 and Bg5 first here as you'll see a big advantage in most of your games. Then go back and be able to play against the others if you start randomly encountering Philidor experts who for some reason don't play the better mainline tension variations.} 8. f3 {If you want something new and solid, I would like to point out a more Fort Knox setup against f3 . I didn't recommend it as the mainline because I had trouble playing for a win against an expert or above, but against a high-rated opponent, a draw might be ideal. And low-rated opponents below expert can make mistakes against these defensive setups so maybe you want it as a backup line against the overly aggressive. Essentially, we're going to fianchetto our king here combined with h6 and a6 . And then just sit back and let White come to us.} Nc6 {This is a very safe alternative. With the pawns going to b6 and h6 to stop attacks on the e6 pawn, it makes sense to play Nc6 . After all, we no longer need to stay out of the way of a brazen c-pawn or maneuver to c4 . It's a defense knight now and on c6 , it's basically unable to be attacked. Our king will also connect our rooks so in this variation, we can contest the d-file.} 9. Be3 Kc8 {This is technically a novelty but the idea is not. We are fianchettoing our king. Bb4 is an interesting try to spice up this line a bit and was played by a strong GM once. That said, we are Fort Knoxing in this alternative line. To my knowledge the idea of fianchettoing the king here and playing h6 and on the kingside was first played by GM Melik Khachiyan. At first, the computer protests against Black's position, aghast at the e6 pawn. But if you play moves to see how White will break through, the computer just adjusts to equal. The concept is more important than the moves here, so let me play a few more moves and then we will chat about what's going on in this alternative line.} 10. O-O-O b6 11. Nh3 h6 {All knight squares that would attack e6 are under control. Black can now commence kingside play.} 12. Nf2 Kb7 {Note that practically every knight move that could attack e6 has been protected by a pawn, establishing a Fort Knox type defense. The computer likes White a bit more but in a nebulous, intangible, hard-to-make-moves for White kind of way. The pawns certainly don't look pretty but practically, there's not much to be done about them. Black has a series of natural moves: centralizing their rooks, trying to move a knight to a d4 or f4 outpost, and even thinking about h6 and g5 kingside expansion--this is one of the few variations where the storm is on the kingside instead of the queenside.    GM Melik has played setups like this as Black in a few games and I'd recommend checking out his games to see how he handles these middle game structures if this intrigues you. In practice, Black is holding these positions well and I'd evaluate the position as close to equal on a human level.} *

