1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 {In addition to our recommendation, Ke8 and Bb4 are interesting choices. Of those, I think the former has the best standing and it has been played by Vachier Lagrave, Jobava, and Rapport (quite the endorsement). Let me give you some information on those two options in case you want to self study them and also explain why I like the purposeful doubling of our pawns here instead.  6... Ke8 is a very difficult move to make work. Our normal plans are just harder to initiate and Black has to know several ways to untie a Gordian knot in order to get their pieces to work together. It's often more concrete than philosophical. I've experimented with it myself and find it atrociously hard and moves are situational and it's nothing like the Bg5 systems. So, if you're playing for a win against a 2700 rated GM, Ke8 might be a good pet project. If you're trying to beat someone rated a mere 2200 or below, our normal line should give you enough chances and will be a lot easier to master in a short time.   6... Bb4 was what I wanted to make work because it has two advantages that I typically love: it's kind of obscure and the win rates are good. That said, there's a reason it's obscure: it's slightly suspect. I don't think it loses, but it looks like Black will be playing with an isolated pawn if White responds correctly and White will have a nagging all-game push. Given that the mainline is so so strong, it seems like a pity to allow White this. Especially since surprise value may work on a 2700 with 6... Bb4 but for most of my readers, their opponents will be surprised by the Philidor in the first place, without us having to do anything weird. Cuenca, in his Lifetime Philidor, recommends 6... Bb4 and for the purposes of appealing to readers who own both courses, in addition to the other reasons, I'll go a different route.} Bb4 {Some readers might want more information on their other options, though I hope by now I will have convinced them that 6... Be6 is a good response to 6. Bc4 with two setups possible in the Fort Knox and the recommendation. Three recommendations would be a bit overkill for this line, but I'll quickly get you started on 6... Bb4 and a sample position. If you love it, you can practice playing it. 6... Ke8 is going to be concrete and complicated so, again, that is for when you hit GM. A Cunning Chess Opening for Black by Sergey Kasparov explores that in a chapter if you're interested. But for most readers, 6... Bb4 will be the closest alternative in style to our recommended move. You'd have to plunge into Cuenca's Lifetime Repertoire: Philidor Defense course for a full on repertoire there and he will be very detailed and very concrete. If you don't know, I provide this informational to give you a feel for how that would possibly go so you can see at the end whether it's the position you want to end up in.} ({Here, the point of} 6... Bb4 {is that if White defends the e-pawn with say} 7. f3 {then we can play} Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Be6 {transposing to our line while doubling White's pawns at the expense of our good bishop... very double edged but both players get the doubled pawns here. I quite liked this idea if f3 was forced, but didn't like...}) 7. Bxf7 Nxe4 8. Nge2 Rf8 9. Bb3 {Black has a nice initiative here for the isolated pawn but their king is in the way of the other rook coming into the game, and very intuitive moves like 9... Nxf2 are bad. This makes it a concrete nightmare in terms of memory and if you mis-remember, you could be in a lot of trouble. It continues...} Nc5 {Threatening to capture the bishop pair and opening up a path for the c8 bishop to develop.} 10. Bc4 Be6 {Trading the bishops and giving us our normal c8 hiding spot should we need it.} 11. Bxe6 Nxe6 12. O-O Nd7 {Our last minor piece is joining the game.  c6  Kc7 is on the agenda.} 13. Be3 c6 {Again, playable and for those who don't like 6... Be6 , this is a great self-study line. Black has the isolated pawn and no queenside storm so it's a unique position. And if you play this 6... Bb4 option, you still have to know the Be6 plans outlined in the course. After all, against 7. f3 , you're playing 7... Be6 and going into that doubled pawn position anyway. Learning multiple different setups and having some be very concrete and on a thin line wouldn't fit our vision for the course, but I wanted to give it here so you could see how it comes out and choose it if you wanted to make an extra effort. It has great practical results for those who burn the midnight hours on it.} *

