1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. f4 {The goal here by White is to enter the Master and Grandmaster variations of the Queen Trade line while saving a tempo. After all, usually, in those, White had to play the f-pawn push after moving the dark-squared bishop, and then later take on f4 with the same bishop. If Black takes the pawn, White will achieve a hyped up version of the top line by saving a tempo not moving their bishop first! Nice idea! However, there's a reason this is a sideline: without Black having moved their pieces, there is no f5 threat attacking an e6 bishop, so we can counterattack quickly!} ({The main other option White has here is played by Club players and it goes} 6. Nf3 Bd6 {which we will examine for the rest of the chapter after dealing with this f4 try.}) 6... Bb4 ({Rather than defending e5 , we attack e4! Now Bd2} 6... exf4 {is awkward. White didn't win the tempo after all! fxe5 Nxe4 is playable but Black has a slight edge there with the better pawn structure.}) 7. Bd3 {This defends the pawn on e4 but gives up on attacking f7 with Bc4 .} exf4 (7... Re8 {was also fine but White has put their bishop passively on d3 so we don't need to be afraid opening up the position. Additionally, by taking, we give White an isolated pawn and have a fresh file for the rook in the d-file that may be even better than the e-file.}) 8. Bxf4 Be6 {Play will resemble the mainlines. The position is about equal and Black will try to remove the dark-squared bishops gaze on c7 as usual before playing c6  Kc7 .  Bxc3 was also an idea, playing against the bad pawns (but giving up this bishop will make it harder for you to stop the bishop on f4 . Clogging the diagonal by getting a knight there is one option for Black's gameplay.)} *

