1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Nf3 ({This is a very common Club Player move. White isn't trying to beat you, they're just getting out their knights and bishops. Now, we have to be a little careful here as Nbd7 , our usual move, blocks in our light-squared c8 bishop. So,} 6. Bc4 {would create an awkward moment where we can't play our usual move inviting doubled pawns.}) 6... Bd6 ({Now Bc4} 6... Be6 {is just a transposition to the Queen Trade Bc4 variation, covered earlier.}) 7. Be3 {This is the only really independent move. Now there's lots of Black tries here that lead to equality like Ke7 . But it would require us learning a newer position so I propose a new try...} Ng4 {Attacking e3 .} 8. Bg5+ f6 {Setting a tiny positional trap as Bd2 now falls into Bc5 when White is still alive after Nd1 but horribly passive. Most White players will retreat the bishop to h4 instead. One thing to note is that if you ever have to retreat your knight in this position, the bishop pair will make up for the doubled pawns. So, even if you decided to randomly retreat the knight... Nh6 Bxh6 gxh6 is not a horrible position for Black with the open g-file and bishop pair. There's no reason to randomly retreat it here, I recommend you wait until White makes you move there. The point of that variation is just that I don't want you to worry about that knight's retreat... you don't need to move your f-pawn or anything crazy here.} 9. Bh4 Be6 10. O-O-O Kc8 {And we get a position close to our usual one. We will move our knight to f7 to support our bishop and the e5 pawn.} 11. h3 Nh6 12. Kb1 Nd7 13. Be2 Nf7 {The position is equal and should be intuitive to play if you're used to the Bg5 variation.} *

