{Even without a check, let's just play the usual plan. Importantly, Nb5 Nxe4 is a common theme and surprisingly, a lot of White players forget to guard the e-pawn. We will continue with all the normal Bg5 variation moves. Just remember to move your bishop before playing c6 in this position!} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Nf3 ({This is a very common Club Player move. White isn't trying to beat you, they're just getting out their knights and bishops. Now, we have to be a little careful here as Nbd7 , our usual move, blocks in our light-squared c8 bishop. So,} 6. Bc4 {would create an awkward moment where we can't play our usual move inviting doubled pawns.}) 6... Bd6 ({Now Bc4} 6... Be6 {is just a transposition to the Queen Trade Bc4 variation, covered earlier.}) 7. Bg5 {This is almost the Queen Trade Bg5 version but we wasted a move with our bishop and White committed to go with Nf3 instead of an f4 plan. Ultimately, the f4 plan is the only good one though, so we're happy to have wasted a tempo here if it means White can't do the scariest option against us!} Be6 8. O-O-O Kc8 *

