1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Nf3 ({This is a very common Club Player move. White isn't trying to beat you, they're just getting out their knights and bishops. Now, we have to be a little careful here as Nbd7 , our usual move, blocks in our light-squared c8 bishop. So,} 6. Bc4 {would create an awkward moment where we can't play our usual move inviting doubled pawns.}) 6... Bd6 7. Bg5 Be6 8. Bd3 {I've seen this in quite a few club games. The idea is just to castle. Now that the e4 pawn is guarded, Nb5 is threatened, so let's stop it. There's also a variant to just castle after Bc4 or even Be2 , but our plan of storming in the direction of the enemy king stays the same in all variations so don't sweat the details of the bishop placement.} c6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rad1 {White continues according to principles: rooks belong on open files.} Kc7 11. Rfe1 h6 12. Bh4 {Bc1 is the best move but most White players playing in this fashion are just trying to do 'normal things' to their own detriment.} Nh5 {And now we start our pawn storm on the other wing! They castle kingside? We can attack kingside! Rg8  g5  Bg3  Nxg3  h5 is coming with a scary attack on the white king. Black has a clear edge.} *

