[PlyCount "8"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 {This is what I call the 'Tension Variation' as White and Black are both waiting to decide what happens with the tension between the d4 and e5 pawns. This is the mainline in Master level chess and what you will probably encounter if you play a grandmaster. It's the third most popular move in the Club Player Lichess database, both in blitz and classical. Most Club Players will play the queen trade line. They also like pushing their d-pawn at you, which I have put in the tension line--even though it breaks the tension immediately--because it fits structurally here.    Against Master level play, our goal is to develop according to the arrows, with the moves Be7  c6  a5  O-O  Re8  h6  Qc7 .  Once White develops a plan, often signaled by a queen move, and starts to put it into action, we will break the tension and take on d4 --this stops most of White’s plans.  After trading pawns in the center, we will try to attack the e4 pawn with our rook and knights. Luckily, this idea isn't even mentioned in the '1. e4 Chess Dojo Chessable' and or Wesley So's 'Lifetime Repertoire 1. e4 Chessable,' which only considers immediate center exchanges or none at all. We are doing a delayed exd4 so we should be surprising our opponents, eliminating their best setups, and all lines are computer checked and database checked--in fact, they are often the leading GM choice.    Against Club level play, we will play the same waiting moves, but sometimes they will make a mistake allowing us an advantage. For example, Club Players often forget to play a4 and let us play a queenside pawn storm.} ({Other Club Players might play an early} 4... d5 {. Against this, sometimes we will be able to play a quick c6 and take the center or, instead, play calmly and later attack the kingside with f5 . For these ideas, revisit the 'Pawns are the Soul of Chess' chapter.}) ({Finally, against the Club Player move Bg5 'threatening'--is it a threat?--to trade their good bishop for our knight, we will kick the bishop with} 4... h6 {Bh4 and then play a quick c6 taking advantage of the fact that the bishop cannot stop Qb6 all the way over on h4 . All of these ideas are responses to White's play whenever it may occur and should help you find your way.}) *

