les for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. h3 {White prepares Be3 and guards the knight hop to exchange it. White usually plays this (which fits many different plans), b3 , or Ba2 in high-level chess. In low level chess, the top two are the same, but they also play the positionally weak Bg5 , which looks natural but reflects a lack of understanding of what's going on. In this course, I won't handle every time White can play a move like Ba2 . Instead, I'll just label that the Sling Shot Plan and show you some variations of it and the general tug and pull. You should be able to figure it out at the board just fine if you understand the concepts. Here, Ba2 would be weaker than later because if you're going to attack f7 , you might as well wait until we've moved our rook!} Re8 {This was Jobava's choice. Essentially, Black has to decide where to put the knight on d7 (which must be moved to activate the light-squared bishop).   There are options for your knight:   1. It can go to the queenside via Nb6 . This has a lot of fans and the idea is clever: to tempo on the White bishop and play exd4  c5  c4 at some point, restricting the bishop play. Nonetheless, it has some downsides: the knight leaves the kingside and sometimes you can be attacked and the plan is based on a very tricky pawn structure switch that can saddle Black with a backwards d-pawn.   2. It can go to c5 after exd4 . This tends to be very solid and is the antidote to many of White's tries as it stops d5 plans.   3. It can go to f8 , which will be my general preference when we don't have to red alert to c5 as it leads to a safe king and straightforward play on the kingside.  Re8 toys with the idea of taking on d4 and targeting f4 while clearing a path for the knight.   h6 is slightly more popular and it's a great move. But I don't think we need to waste the tempo just yet as on Ng5  Rf8 we will play h6 or exd4 next with White not able to recapture with a knight. So White will have forced a good h6 move or a good open Philidor (yes you moved your rook twice but they moved their knight twice). In some lines, the attack on e4 could use a tempo up.} 10. Be3 {Be3 fits all plans. d5 could still be in the cards as could Ba2 . b3 is off the table, but otherwise White is flexible. White will eventually have to reveal though as their queen moves tells us a lot. So we keep making our natural moves.} h6 {This move h6 is a clever move and when we don't know what to do, it should follow Re8 . The idea is twofold. The simple one is to stop Ng5 so we can put stuff on f8 . A more complex idea that Magnus Carlsen tried once is trade off some minor pieces to relieve some of the space issues Black is dealing with. In some lines, you can play Nfh7  Ng5 and if we have to take back with the h-pawn, then the f4 square will be primed for our Nf8 - g6 - f4 maneuver. Remember, though, we have to guard e5 with Qc7 before we can move the d7 knight!} 11. Qd2 {Sacrificial Lamb Plan Key Signs:  Be3  h3  Qd2 (sometimes Bg5  Qd2 if lower rated), Rad1 and even g4 . White's goal: White is preparing for two things: a potential sacrifice on h6 and an assault down the d-file, using dxe5 or more likely d5 as the opener. Sometimes, White even throws in g4 for a kingside rush. So given that they may sacrifice on h6 , let's bring in some reinforcements.   Counter : Bf8 seems appropriate to overguard h6 . This does means that our d7 knight will lack a square, so we will play exd4 so it can go to c5 instead. This will be more effective than usual because the bishop on e3 is blocked in by the queen and so White's rook has a little less of a grip over protecting e4 .} Bf8 12. Rad1 {Most to players have continued to slow play with Qc7 . This is fine, but I want to show you how we're going to relieve the tension, whether you want to do it now or later is up to you, just look out for d5 pushes if you delay.} exd4 13. Bxd4 Qc7 {Technically Nb6 might be even better here, but we might get this position in a different way, so key is just looking at the setup. With the bishop on d4 , Nc5 allows Bxf6 , doubling our pawns. So we improvise a bit.} 14. Nh4 {This is the old Nf5 plan. Remember the rule: if they can stay on f5 , you soon won't be alive. So we have to move a knight to make sure our bishop can eat that incoming f5 knight.} Ne5 {This so happens to come with tempo.} 15. Bf1 ({And we're just playing chess. If they had taken the knight, we would have taken back with the pawn, entering the pawn structure we like. If} 15. Ba2 Be6 {we would have tried to trade the bishops. Now, Black has a creative try with the white bishop off the long diagonal and can play...}) 15... g5 ({And the point is that} 15... Nf3+ {allows} 16. Nxf3 {doubling the pawns so...}) 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. exf5 Bg7 {White has a tiny pull with the bishop pair but Black is solid and hard to crack. Eventually Black wants to push d5 and take advantage of their increased center presence.} *

