do. There are of course other plans for Black. For people wanting another plan involving self-study, a6 can be played here. There will already be alternatives within the c6 line and covering a6 as well as c6 would be a bit too much for this course.} c6 {This move ( c6 ) has been played by Radjabov, Firouzja, Beliavsky, Azmaiparashvili, Ivanchuk, Svidler, Morozevich, etc. etc. etc. It's a Who's Who of Super Grandmasters. Why is it so popular? Well, the idea is to activate the queen (usually to c7 ). Once the queen is on c7 , e5 will be defended so the knight on d7 can frolic as knights are wont to do. That's one idea. The second is to stop Nd5 . Especially if White opts for a dxe5 line, this is useful. A third idea is to play b5 and expand on the queenside. This comes with tempo. I've seen countless games where my students won a pawn with b5  Bb3  b4  Ne2  Nxe4 . It's amazing how you forget e4 is hanging! Even if there was no pawn win: b5  Bb7  a6  c5 is a natural plan for Black. White's next move is pretty important in stopping this.} 8. a4 a5 (8... Qc7 {is more popular and h6 was recommended by GM Cuenca in his Lifetime Philidor course here on Chessable. but} 9. a5 {has among the best win rates here and leads to less variance in structure. A high practical win rate and easier to remember than leading alternatives? Sounds like our repertoire! The point of the a-pawn move is to stop White from playing a5 themselves and enacting a python-like squeeze. I've personally been suffocated when White gets that plan off and I want to avoid it without having to memorize 42 variations on prevention and reaction. a5 flatly stops White from controlling the queenside and also helps the Black knight occupy c5 without a b-pawn boop later in the game. Also, for people below Master, it makes the resulting positions more similar so helps a lot with memory. There are downsides, but the simplicity and easiness to play make this a straightforward decision for us. There's two basic principles for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. h3 {White prepares Be3 and guards the knight hop to exchange it. White usually plays this (which fits many different plans), b3 , or Ba2 in high-level chess. In low level chess, the top two are the same, but they also play the positionally weak Bg5 , which looks natural but reflects a lack of understanding of what's going on. In this course, I won't handle every time White can play a move like Ba2 . Instead, I'll just label that the Sling Shot Plan and show you some variations of it and the general tug and pull. You should be able to figure it out at the board just fine if you understand the concepts. Here, Ba2 would be weaker than later because if you're going to attack f7 , you might as well wait until we've moved our rook!} Re8 {This was Jobava's choice. Essentially, Black has to decide where to put the knight on d7 (which must be moved to activate the light-squared bishop).   There are three options for your knight:   1. It can go to the queenside via Nb6 . This has a lot of fans and the idea is clever: to tempo on the White bishop and play exd4  c5  c4 at some point, restricting the bishop play. Nonetheless, it has some downsides: the knight leaves the kingside and sometimes you can be attacked and the plan is based on a very tricky pawn structure switch that can saddle Black with a backwards d-pawn.   2. It can go to c5 after exd4 . This tends to be very solid and is the antidote to many of White's tries as it stops d5 plans.   3. It can go to f8 , which will be my general preference when we don't have to red alert to c5 as it leads to a safe king and straightforward play on the kingside.  Re8 toys with the idea of taking on d4 and targeting f4 while clearing a path for the knight.   h6 is slightly more popular and it's a great move. But I don't think we need to waste the tempo just yet as on Ng5  Rf8 we will play h6 or exd4 next with White not able to recapture with a knight. So White will have forced a good h6 move or a good open Philidor (yes you moved your rook twice but they moved their knight twice). In some lines, the attack on e4 could use a tempo up.} 10. Be3 {Be3 fits all plans. d5 could still be in the cards as could Ba2 . b3 is off the table, but otherwise White is flexible. White will eventually have to reveal though as their queen moves tells us a lot. So we keep making our natural moves.} h6 {h6 is a clever move and when we don't know what to do, it should follow Re8 . The idea is twofold. The simple one is to stop Ng5 so we can put stuff on f8 . A more complex idea that Magnus Carlsen tried once is trade off some minor pieces to relieve some of the space issues Black is dealing with. In some lines, you can play Nfh7  Ng5 and if we have to take back with the h-pawn, then the f4 square will be primed for our Nf8 - g6 - f4 maneuver. Remember, though, we have to guard e5 with Qc7 before we can move the d7 knight!} 11. Qd2 {Sacrificial Lamb Plan Key Signs:  Be3  h3  Qd2 (sometimes Bg5  Qd2 if lower rated), Rad1 and even g4 . White's goal: White is preparing for two things: a potential sacrifice on h6 and an assault down the d-file, using dxe5 or more likely d5 as the opener. Sometimes, White even throws in g4 for a kingside rush. So given that they may sacrifice on h6 , let's bring in some reinforcements.   Counter : Bf8 seems appropriate to overguard h6 . This does means that our d7 knight will lack a square, so we will play exd4 so it can go to c5 instead. This will be more effective than usual because the bishop on e3 is blocked in by the queen and so White's rook has a little less of a grip over protecting e4 .} Bf8 12. g4 {It's good to know how to deal with this. Usually when they go h3  g4 , we break in the center. Here, the fork is one way to open it up.} Nxe4 13. Nxe4 d5 {Black is regaining the piece and the open board makes h3  g4 look weird.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Tension Variation (Master "]
[Black "The Battering Ram Plan (d5) I"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4 a5 9. d5 {[The Battering Ram]The d-pawn push at some point I dub 'the Battery Ram Plan.' I will often have an irresistible urge to quote the Three Little Pigs when talking about it: 'Little Pigs! Little Pigs! Let me come in! Or I'll huff and I'll push d5 by the hair of my chinny chin chin.' It's a critical test for Black, and so many Black players react wrong that it inspires beginner players to do it again and again. Masters do it too, of course, but they have better timing with the push.   So what's the point? Well, White wants you to take their d-pawn with your c-pawn. If accomplished, their knight on c3 , which couldn't move forward at all, will be able to go to b5 or even d5 ! And Black will have a backwards d-pawn and b-pawn! White is also thinking about trading pawns later to open up the d-file one day.    Here's how we should counter:   1. When a wolf knocks on your door, do NOT open the door.  cxd5, opening the door to the d5 square, is not wise unless you know for a sure that d5 will be occupied by a White pawn or you'll win the light-squared bishop.  As long as you can close the d-file down for business, you're okay trading pawns.} ({Here, White has a knight, bishop and queen guarding the square so cxd5} 9. Nd5 {and you are not going to be able to force them to take back with a pawn.  9... c5 (opening the door to the b5 square) is also not advisable against a d5 push.  Why make their knight great? Although not as bad as cxd5 , it's a positional mistake and White will just chill on b5 all game.}) {2. Follow the Daoist principle of Wu Wei: the action of inaction.  Just don't worry about it and don't be opening any doors. White can't MAKE you get rid of your c6 pawn. Sure they can take it, but you will take back with your b-pawn and it will reappear.  Play your normal moves -- Qc7 , h6 , etc.--and just make sure you don't drop a pawn. Keeping the pawn on d5 makes White's bishop look silly so eventually they will want to trade on c6 , frustrated that you passed the test and didn't open a door. If they ever take your c6 pawn, try to recapture with your b-pawn. This will keep d5 out of their knight's hands.  3. Against the Battering Ram, Nb6 is a clever tactic to know about.  Often it hits the c4 bishop and the d5 pawn, increasing your piece count to a level where you can trade and prevent White from living there. For example, in the position on the board, Black can play Nb6 as I will show.  4. If you can force White to take back with a pawn, Black will have central and kingside play ideas.  White will get an outpost on b5 to brag about in return but Black's center space and kingside play will be great for us. Look for moves like f5 or deploying your bishop to g4 to bring on the pressure. Also, their light-squared bishop will be cut off from anything useful with the diagonal blocked.} 9... Nb6 10. Bb3 cxd5 11. Nxd5 Nfxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Be6 {Now technically, Be6 isn't forced (even though it's good) and Qxb7 would have to be calculated (it gives Black ample compensation after Rb8 and f5 and such) , but this is an informational, not a variation, so even though other moves were possible, I want to show the idea that with all those trades Be6 will gain at least equality if not more.   The point is that here, all the White minor pieces that would live on d5 are gone in an effort to not take back with a pawn. And with Black having a light-squared bishop, d5 will come and the whole will be fixed (even f5 can fix it as there's no light-squared White bishop to keep the f7 pawn at bay) . This is the Nb6 idea in action.} *

