1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 {This is the so called Hanham variation of the Philidor. White is keeping the tension in the center and quickly developing their pieces. This makes a lot of sense and it was the recommendation in the Grandmaster Repertoire 1. e4 books. Here, White has the exciting g4 or the very normal Bc4 . This chapter is about Bc4 and other normal developing moves. Bg5 is a bad move here as it inspires trading pieces when White has a small space edge so reflects a misunderstanding of the position. Nonetheless, we will look at it and other ideas by White here.} 5. Bc4 Be7 {h6 is the so called Black Lion, which Simon Williams tried to make work and which Alexander Alekhine recommended for Black to play actively. It's a fun idea, but a bit anti-positional (or maybe the nice phrase is 'strategically risky')--it involves a lot of pawn moves in the opening and delayed castling. One thing to note is that whenever you see White play a bishop to c4 and knight to f3 , you must immediately respond Be7 in the Philidor. If you hesitate for an instant (for example, you play g6 ) Ng5 will unleash a carnage that is not child appropriate. Again, for emphasis: We always put the bishop on e7 when we see Nf3 and Bc4 so we can meet Ng5 with castles.} 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {Sometimes White plays a4 first, but it doesn't change anything. We've reached something of a tabiya. White has made a bunch of reasonable moves that are well suited for whichever pawn structure we get later. They are ready to push d5 if we play something like b6 and make it stronger, they are ready to take on e5 if they find a way to put pressure there, and they are ready to allow us to take if we so choose. A waiting game has commenced. Just so you are aware, here are the waiting moves that usually will not hurt and will often help Black in the usual order I recommend them: c6 , a5 , Re8 , h6 , Qc7 , Nf8 - Ng6 - potentially f4 So we have essentially things to improve when we don't know what to do. There are of course other plans for Black. For people wanting another plan involving self-study, a6 can be played here. There will already be alternatives within the c6 line and covering a6 as well as c6 would be a bit too much for this course.} c6 {This move ( c6 ) has been played by Radjabov, Firouzja, Beliavsky, Azmaiparashvili, Ivanchuk, Svidler, Morozevich, etc. etc. etc. It's a Who's Who of Super Grandmasters. Why is it so popular? Well, the idea is to activate the queen (usually to c7 ). Once the queen is on c7 , e5 will be defended so the knight on d7 can frolic as knights are wont to do. That's one idea. The second is to stop Nd5 . Especially if White opts for a dxe5 line, this is useful. A third idea is to play b5 and expand on the queenside. This comes with tempo. I've seen countless games where my students won a pawn with b5  Bb3  b4  Ne2  Nxe4 . It's amazing how you forget e4 is hanging! Even if there was no pawn win: b5  Bb7  a6  c5 is a natural plan for Black. White's next move is pretty important in stopping this.} 8. a4 a5 (8... Qc7 {is more popular and h6 was recommended by GM Cuenca in his Lifetime Philidor course here on Chessable. but} 9. a5 {has among the best win rates here and leads to less variance in structure. A high practical win rate and easier to remember than leading alternatives? Sounds like our repertoire! The point of the a-pawn move is to stop White from playing a5 themselves and enacting a python-like squeeze. I've personally been suffocated when White gets that plan off and I want to avoid it without having to memorize 42 variations on prevention and reaction. a5 flatly stops White from controlling the queenside and also helps the Black knight occupy c5 without a b-pawn boop later in the game. Also, for people below Master, it makes the resulting positions more similar so helps a lot with memory. There are downsides, but the simplicity and easiness to play make this a straightforward decision for us. There's two basic principles for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. h3 {White prepares Be3 and guards the knight hop to exchange it. White usually plays this (which fits many different plans), b3 , or Ba2 in high-level chess. In low level chess, the top two are the same, but they also play the positionally weak Bg5 , which looks natural but reflects a lack of understanding of what's going on. In this course, I won't handle every time White can play a move like Ba2 . Instead, I'll just label that the Sling Shot Plan and show you some variations of it and the general tug and pull. You should be able to figure it out at the board just fine if you understand the concepts. Here, Ba2 would be weaker than later because if you're going to attack f7 , you might as well wait until we've moved our rook!} Re8 {This was Jobava's choice. Essentially, Black has to decide where to put the knight on d7 (which must be moved to activate the light-squared bishop).   There are three options for your knight:   1. It can go to the queenside via Nb6 . This has a lot of fans and the idea is clever: to tempo on the White bishop and play exd4  c5  c4 at some point, restricting the bishop play. Nonetheless, it has some downsides: the knight leaves the kingside and sometimes you can be attacked and the plan is based on a very tricky pawn structure switch that can saddle Black with a backwards d-pawn.   2. It can go to c5 after exd4 . This tends to be very solid and is the antidote to many of White's tries as it stops d5 plans.   3. It can go to f8 , which will be my general preference when we don't have to red alert to c5 as it leads to a safe king and straightforward play on the kingside.  Re8 toys with the idea of taking on d4 and targeting f4 while clearing a path for the knight.   h6 is slightly more popular and it's a great move. But I don't think we need to waste the tempo just yet as on Ng5  Rf8 we will play h6 or exd4 next with White not able to recapture with a knight. So White will have forced a good h6 move or a good open Philidor (yes you moved your rook twice but they moved their knight twice). In some lines, the attack on e4 could use a tempo up.} 10. Be3 {Be3 fits all plans. d5 could still be in the cards as could Ba2 . b3 is off the table, but otherwise White is flexible. White will eventually have to reveal though as their queen moves tells us a lot. So we keep making our natural moves.} h6 {h6 is a clever move and when we don't know what to do, it should follow Re8 . The idea is twofold. The simple one is to stop Ng5 so we can put stuff on f8 . A more complex idea that Magnus Carlsen tried once is trade off some minor pieces to relieve some of the space issues Black is dealing with. In some lines, you can play Nfh7  Ng5 and if we have to take back with the h-pawn, then the f4 square will be primed for our Nf8 - g6 - f4 maneuver. Remember, though, we have to guard e5 with Qc7 before we can move the d7 knight!} 11. d5 {The Battering Ram Plan! White tries to use their pawn to break down our castle door. Little Pigs! Little Pigs! Let Me Come in! Holy mixed metaphor, we will NOT let you in!   Key Signs of a Battering Ram Plan: White plays d5 or starts doubling on the d file. White's Goal: White wants Black to make some kind of concession. They waited for c6 before pushing d5 to avoid the pawn push lines. Next they will think about taking on c6 and trying to win the d-pawn, or if we push, they will come into our camp via d5 . If we take their pawn, they want to take back with a piece and play against our backward d-pawn and with a hole on b5 . How do we respond?   Counter : Almost always, we want to keep the tension and just play Qc7 (or even Nf8 , just ignore White's Big Bad Wolf Attack: our house is made of brick here). If you're playing bullet, play Qc7 . But if you have more time to think, let me offer a more complicated response. c5 is almost always bad. Don't do that. Taking the pawn if a piece can recapture and stay on d5 is also almost always a disaster. But playing xd5 is usually okay if White must recapture with a pawn. In these positions, if you haven't already committed the knight to f8 , you might find you have a tactic where you play Nb6 and attack d5 and the Bc4 . When you do this, sometimes you can get White to take back with a pawn. Let me show you here...} Nb6 12. Ba2 cxd5 13. Bxb6 Qxb6 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Be6 {This hopefully is a good illustration of the nuance: Black wasn't able to accomplish their objective but White had to lose a very powerful bishop to stop them and so things even out. Nb6 will often allow some tricks that allow you to take and get something for your trouble. If you don't like to calculate though, the safest bet is usually to just keep the tension and ignore them.} *

