1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4 a5 9. h3 Re8 10. Be3 h6 11. Ba2 Qc7 12. Qe2 {[The Slingshot]At some point, maybe not at this moment (perhaps earlier or later) , White might execute what I call 'the Slingshot Plan,' where they pull back their bishop like a rubber band and then put the queen on c4 and slingshot it into your king. If they can play Ng5 , even better for them!    Why does White do this in high level chess?    White plays the Slingshot plan for two good reasons:   First, even if you don't lose to it, it is preventative. After all, it makes it dangerous for you to transfer pieces via f8 because then you can't play Rf8 to block an f7 pawn attack. And f8 was a key transit location.   Second, it helps support d5 because if you play Qc7 like in the current position then Qc4 will pin your c6 pawn.    So here is our counter:   1. Luckily, as with all these plans, they almost always make exd4 more tempting (it's literally an antidote to pretty much anything and so it's just about letting White poorly set up their pieces for it) . We will play exd4 right before they play Qc4 as a rule.    Why? Well, first Qe2 and Qd3 , the two ways to get to c4 , are both bad moves against exd4 . The queen on e2 will leave the e4 pawn pinned as we have a rook on e8 . The queen on d3 will allow Ne5 with tempo. And when the queen gets to c4 , Ne5 will also be great! Second, we can block the diagonal by putting pieces on e6 (like a knight or bishop) . White's counter to that is to push d5 and kick our e6 minor piece. But if we take their d4 pawn, there's no kick! We're there to stay.   2. After 12. ... exd4 against this plan, White will recapture with a knight or a bishop.   If White recaptures with the knight, look for a quick d5 push and a knight to go to e6 , usually via c5 . If White recaptures with the bishop, you should avoid Nc5 and instead play Nf8 , to support Be6 , or Ne5 . I'll write more about this on the next move but Nf8  Be6 is easiest to remember of these two options and so my usual recommendation, but you have to know some downsides and tactics.   The downside is that the dark-squared bishop will have to wait on falling back to f8 and unleashing the rook behind it. The tactical consideration is that once Black trades pawns in the center, White can often look for an e5 push to open things up and exploit their lead in development. Sometimes that tactical danger rules out Nf8 altogether, which moves a piece backward and is sometimes ill-suited for sudden openings of this position.  Ne5 , therefore, is sometimes best if we see this pawn push working for White because it just shuts down the e5 counter. Also, sometimes it just works brilliantly for tactical reasons, so always compare and contrast the two. The downside of Ne5 as a response to Bxd4 is that it will be harder to trade bishops, and you also have to watch out for the sudden f4 later, kicking the knight, and setting up Qc4 with pressure on the diagonal. If you want a general rule, Ne5 works great when it forces a knight trade or is needed to stop e5 .   Here's how I remember what to do after exd4 : 'If the White knight recaptures, put a Black knight on e6 , if the White bishop recaptures, consider putting a Black bishop on e6 .'    3. If you haven't played h6 yet, play h6 !  Ng5 is scary!} {For example, after exd4 Nxd4 , the white bishop can't eat your knight on c5 , so it's safe to transfer via that square with Nc5 and then Ne6 . Later your dark-squared bishop will fall back to f8 to unleash your rook.} exd4 13. Nxd4 {And before we get into the variations and slight differences, let's look at the position conceptually. With the White knight on d4 , we typically want a Black knight on e6 to trade it off. If they play Nf5 , you will take it with your bishop and play d5 . The e4 pawn looks very vulnerable here after Bf8 and after Bf8 and something like Nc5 , your queen will guard f7 until you are ready to play a minor piece to e6 .} ({Finally, if} 13. Bxd4 {things are different. When the bishop takes, you can play Be6 because there's now no knight attacking that square. That said, Nc5 is almost always a worse move against bishop takes because on many occasions they can take your knight and press e5 with a kingside attack. So in that case, you always want to go to f8 to help reinforce Be6 or play Ne5 . In this specific position,} Ne5 {is the better move because on Nf8 , White has e5 ideas which makes our Nf8 here specifically too slow... though other positions are different and so always look for that maneuver while watching for White e5 counter pushes.}) *

