1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 {This is the so called Hanham variation of the Philidor. White is keeping the tension in the center and quickly developing their pieces. This makes a lot of sense and it was the recommendation in the Grandmaster Repertoire 1. e4 books. Here, White has the exciting g4 or the very normal Bc4 . This chapter is about Bc4 and other normal developing moves. Bg5 is a bad move here as it inspires trading pieces when White has a small space edge so reflects a misunderstanding of the position. Nonetheless, we will look at it and other ideas by White here.} 5. Bc4 Be7 {h6 is the so called Black Lion, which Simon Williams tried to make work and which Alexander Alekhine recommended for Black to play actively. It's a fun idea, but a bit anti-positional (or maybe the nice phrase is 'strategically risky')--it involves a lot of pawn moves in the opening and delayed castling. One thing to note is that whenever you see White play a bishop to c4 and knight to f3 , you must immediately respond Be7 in the Philidor. If you hesitate for an instant (for example, you play g6 ) Ng5 will unleash a carnage that is not child appropriate. Again, for emphasis: We always put the bishop on e7 when we see Nf3 and Bc4 so we can meet Ng5 with castles.} 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {Sometimes White plays a4 first, but it doesn't change anything. We've reached something of a tabiya. White has made a bunch of reasonable moves that are well suited for whichever pawn structure we get later. They are ready to push d5 if we play something like b6 and make it stronger, they are ready to take on e5 if they find a way to put pressure there, and they are ready to allow us to take if we so choose. A waiting game has commenced. Just so you are aware, here are the waiting moves that usually will not hurt and will often help Black in the usual order I recommend them: c6 , a5 , Re8 , h6 , Qc7 , Nf8 - Ng6 - potentially f4 So we have essentially things to improve when we don't know what to do. There are of course other plans for Black. For people wanting another plan involving self-study, a6 can be played here. There will already be alternatives within the c6 line and covering a6 as well as c6 would be a bit too much for this course.} c6 {This move ( c6 ) has been played by Radjabov, Firouzja, Beliavsky, Azmaiparashvili, Ivanchuk, Svidler, Morozevich, etc. etc. etc. It's a Who's Who of Super Grandmasters. Why is it so popular? Well, the idea is to activate the queen (usually to c7 ). Once the queen is on c7 , e5 will be defended so the knight on d7 can frolic as knights are wont to do. That's one idea. The second is to stop Nd5 . Especially if White opts for a dxe5 line, this is useful. A third idea is to play b5 and expand on the queenside. This comes with tempo. I've seen countless games where my students won a pawn with b5  Bb3  b4  Ne2  Nxe4 . It's amazing how you forget e4 is hanging! Even if there was no pawn win: b5  Bb7  a6  c5 is a natural plan for Black. White's next move is pretty important in stopping this.} 8. a4 a5 (8... Qc7 {is more popular and h6 was recommended by GM Cuenca in his Lifetime Philidor course here on Chessable. but} 9. a5 {has among the best win rates here and leads to less variance in structure. A high practical win rate and easier to remember than leading alternatives? Sounds like our repertoire! The point of the a-pawn move is to stop White from playing a5 themselves and enacting a python-like squeeze. I've personally been suffocated when White gets that plan off and I want to avoid it without having to memorize 42 variations on prevention and reaction. a5 flatly stops White from controlling the queenside and also helps the Black knight occupy c5 without a b-pawn boop later in the game. Also, for people below Master, it makes the resulting positions more similar so helps a lot with memory. There are downsides, but the simplicity and easiness to play make this a straightforward decision for us. There's two basic principles for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. h3 {White prepares Be3 and guards the knight hop to exchange it. White usually plays this (which fits many different plans), b3 , or Ba2 in high-level chess. In low level chess, the top two are the same, but they also play the positionally weak Bg5 , which looks natural but reflects a lack of understanding of what's going on. In this course, I won't handle every time White can play a move like Ba2 . Instead, I'll just label that the Sling Shot Plan and show you some variations of it and the general tug and pull. You should be able to figure it out at the board just fine if you understand the concepts. Here, Ba2 would be weaker than later because if you're going to attack f7 , you might as well wait until we've moved our rook!} Re8 {This was Jobava's choice. Essentially, Black has to decide where to put the knight on d7 (which must be moved to activate the light-squared bishop). There are three options: 1. It can go to the queenside via Nb6 . This has a lot of fans and the idea is clever: to tempo on the White bishop and play exd4  c5  c4 at some point, restricting the bishop play. Nonetheless, it has some downsides: the knight leaves the kingside and sometimes you can be attacked and the plan is based on a very tricky pawn structure switch that can saddle black with a backwards d-pawn. 2. It can go to c5 after exd4 . This tends to be very solid and is the antidote to many of White's tries as it stops d5 plans. 3. It can go to f8 , which will be my general preference when we don't have to red alert to c5 as it leads to a safe king and straightforward play on the kingside. Re8 toys with the idea of taking on d4 and targeting f4 while clearing a path for the knight. h6 is slightly more popular and it's a great move. But I don't think we need to waste the tempo just yet as on Ng5  Rf8 we will play h6 next and White will have forced a good h6 move (yes you moved your rook twice but they moved their knight twice). In some lines, the attack on e4 could use a tempo up.} 10. Be3 {Be3 fits all plans. d5 could still be in the cards as could Ba2 . b3 is off the table, but otherwise White is flexible. White will eventually have to reveal though as their queen moves tells us a lot. So we keep making our natural moves.} h6 {h6 is a clever move and when we don't know what to do, it should follow Re8 . The idea is twofold. The simple one is to stop Ng5 so we can put stuff on f8 . A more complex idea that Magnus Carlsen tried once is trade off some minor pieces to relieve some of the space issues Black is dealing with. In some lines, you can play Nfh7  Ng5 and if we have to take back with the h-pawn, then the f4 square will be primed for our Nf8 - g6 - f4 maneuver. Remember, though, we have to guard e5 with Qc7 before we can move the d7 knight!} 11. Ba2 {White Goal 2: Key signs: White plays Ba2 , Qe2 , Qd3 or Qc4 . Sometimes even the sneaky Qb1 - a2 , though in that case, White has to very carefully look at the Nb6 tactics as the bishop doesn't have a lot of retreat squares. White's Goal: White wants to assault the f7 square and play against Re8 and the f8 square being a transit location. They're hoping that by tying the rook to f8 , you will not be able to better your pieces. When White does this, it usually looks like a gigantic slingshot being deployed against you so I'm calling this the Slingshot Plan. The bishop on c4 pulls its rock-solid self back to a2 . The Queen goes to e2 or d3 and then moves to where the bishop used to be on c4 , ready to be sling-shotted into f7 . Combine it with Ng5 and you have a menacing plan. It also works well to combine this with d5 as if we've played Qc7 then after Qc4 the c6 pawn will be pinned and Nb5 tactics will come up as well as d5 against any piece that dares get in our way of f7 . When you see the signs, it's time to play proactively. The counter will be to play h6 (to stop Ng5 ) Re8  Nf8 (to deploy a piece on e6 to block up the diagonal). Now a word about tactics in this plan. White will often let you block with something on e6 only to play d5 and when you move away, pxc6 discovered attack. Black has already played h6 and White Ba2 . Let's see Black and White each execute the rest of their plans...} Qc7 12. Qe2 {The idea of this move is to play Qc4 at some point and take advantage of our weak f7 pawn. So we have to do one of two things: 1. remove all minor pieces in the way of our queen guarding that square, 2. play xd4 . Why the second option? Well even though I'll show you both, I think the easiest conceptual plan is to always take on d4 right before Qc4 . Why? Well, for a few reasons. First, the queen has to get to c4 via e2 or d3 . A queen on e2 means opening the e-file is stronger for Black and a Queen on d3 can be hit with Nc5 after we take. Second, after Qc4 we would love to neutralize the slingshot by putting some minor piece on e6 --clogging the entire diagonal. Generally, we will put a bishop there if it cannot be eaten by a knight and a knight there if we can't put a bishop there because of the other rule. But after Nf8  Qc4  Be6 White has d5 ! The pawn is untakeable due to the pin on the c7 queen and the bishop must move, setting up a discovered attack once White takes on c6 . This is very sad for out optimal setup. So how do you stop d5 as an antidote to Be6 or Ne6 ? You take out the d4 pawn, that's how. And we have to do it now because if we wait for Qc4 then they'll be on f7 with their queen before you can count to three. This is a very clear conceptual rule that should replace the need to memorize a ton of variations. But in order to show you there are always options, I will provide this alternative, not meant for memorizing as much as to show you that chess is always about the specific position.} Nf8 {So I recommend exd4 against the Slingshot Plan. But I wanted to show you one alternative that was played by GM Vorobiov to beat none other than World Champion Contender Fabiano Caruana.} 13. Qc4 Bd8 {This key move is just in time, defending f7 with the queen and still eyeing the e4 pawn should White lose sight of it. This alternative is also a good time to talk about the downside. The Slingshot Variation allows d5 to carry a punch because as you can see, there's more pressure on c6 . Vorobiov's brilliant idea to guard his queen with Bd8 so that c6 isn't being pinned by the White queen is very elegant. That said, this variation is less conceptual as Black achieves this by a single move. So when going for this setup all the time, be careful to calculate and be flexible if you can't arrive here in time. I'd recommend this for anyone who wants a more offbeat way of playing or something that liquidates a little less and so may provide more winning chances.} 14. Rad1 Ng6 {White's moves prepare for an opening of the d-file via dxe5 or more likely d5 .} 15. d5 {Generally, we should not react when we see d5 . c5 would allow Nb5 . We can't play cxb5 without losing our queen but it should be of note that even if that wasn't true, we generally don't want to take White as we get a big hole and the backward d-pawn is harder to push without the c6 support.} Ra6 {Black has dreams of activating the rook to b6 and is waiting for White to do something. Things hang by a thread. An exciting game is ahead of us. Black is very solid and is preparing for the files to open. They want to position their knights into the f4 square if at all possible (e.g., Nh5 - f4 ). Caruana played Qd3 here, which is probably best, but we should probably address the one game White won in this position, playing...} 16. Qd3 {This was Caruana's choice....} Be7 {We don't want to lose d6 after dxc6 and we are not interested in taking back with our rook.} 17. Nd2 Nh5 18. Ne2 Rf8 {A weird thing about the Philidor is that you will find your rook travelling to e8 only to go back to f8 . Why? Well because the rook is ideally placed on f8 after d5 because we want to push f5 . Before d5 , e8 threatens to open the game up and attack e4 . So every move had its purpose and its time. Technically the computer wants Nhf4 allowing a position where Black plays with a precarious pawn that it has calculated is holdable and equalish. But that move seems less intuitive to play even if objectively it is better, so let's play a more natural move and keep our e5 pawn where it is. Those feeling confident about Nhf4 can by all means play it though!} 19. dxc6 bxc6 {Caruana relieved the tension too early and lost a complicated game. Black's pawns look attackable but it's actually quite tricky. Then again, it was hard to see how White should have made progress in a constant state of tension. Maybe a computer can guess the exact right time to act, but humans might find this is a bit lofty for expectations.} *

