[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Tension Variation (Master "]
[Black "The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4) Info"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "23"]

1. e4 {For this and future informationals, we will discuss plans and counters in the main Grandmaster position that arises out of most top-level Philidor games. As you go through the trainables, we'll practice reaching those mainline positions and give explanations for Black's moves leading up to them, but for now, let's focus on the move 10 and beyond plans and the major ideas behind them.} d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4 a5 9. h3 h6 10. Be3 Re8 11. Ba2 Qc7 12. Nh4 {[The Knight f5 Attack]The goal of White's last move, which can be played at various points in the game, to play Nf5  Qf3 and either Qg3 or g4 - g5 . I dub this the 'Knight f5 Plan' which is aimed at attacking play. It works best for White after Black has moved their queen away from the kingside and has committed to h6 , which allows the Nf5 to eye the h6 pawn for sacrifices or for the g-pawn pushes to open the position. Here are the six rules to remember as this type of plan can occur at any moment:   1. Usually Nxe4 doesn't work.  Don't try it.    2. If you can trade your bishop for the knight on f5 , always do it.  If they recapture with the e-pawn, look to follow up with d5 .    3. Often, exd4 is a good move against it because they can't recapture with a knight. But you don't have to rush and can play some normal moves first and wait for Qf3 before playing exd4 , when the knight cannot retreat. That's usually my preference because it's even better with the queen misplaced, and the main recommendation for the course.   4. After exd4 , your knights will find e5 is a great spot if the bishop retakes and e5 or c5 if the queen retakes.  If the knight is already on f8 , Ne6 or Be6 is almost always good.    5. g6 to stop Nf5 isn't good in most cases where the light-squared white bishop is alive.  First, here it loses the h6 pawn, but even if it didn't, knight captures g6 would reveal that the f7 pawn is pinned quite nicely. And even if you avoided h6 (not advisable) (g6 would create dark square issues. You can play g6 as soon as you trade your light-squared bishop for theirs with Be6 . This is because you won't have a pinned f7 pawn and the pressure down the f-file will be weaker for White.    6. If your light-squared bishop can either trade for their light-squared bishop or take their knight, both work so don't sweat over the decision.  Generally if you trade light squared bishops you can play g6 to kick the knight anyway, so pick your preference with peace of mind.)} *

