[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "23"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 a5 8. Re1 c6 9. h3 h6 10. Nh4 {[Why We Don't Play Nxe4 Here]So, I'd like to talk about why Nxe4 is rarely a good move against Nh4 . After all, it looks like a very simple tactic to win a pawn because if you move the knight, your bishop will attack their knight. This is an illusion that has led to many a tragedy for the Black player. The reason why I advise you pretty much not waste your brain space calculating it is that White almost always gets something when you go pawn hunting while down in development. And in this case, the compensation is always scary. Let's see why...} Nxe4 ({Now White usually can capture the knight back and get compensation. For example, here,} 10... Nxe4 {Bxh4 Nxd6 is almost winning on the spot except Black has Bxf2 Kxf2 Qf6+ followed by queen takes knight. But even that position is no cakewalk as White has fully developed with the bishop pair and lots of open files. If the white bishop had been on e3 when this happened, you wouldn't have had the saving Bxf2 move. For example, if we put a white bishop on e3 and move your rook to e8 (the mainline) , the knight on d6 would be forking your Re8 and f7 pawn. When you move your rook back to guard f7 , they can just take and after all the trades on f7 , finish you with Qh5 + forking your king and bishop: game over. So, if White has a certain setup, you will just lose on the spot with this trick. And worse, when they don't have the right setup, they get a great game with declining the sacrifice and playing...}) 11. Nf5 {Your knight is threatened and so natural is...} Nxc3 12. bxc3 ({The computer gives this line as about equal with White having the bishop pair and a great knight in exchange for the pawn. Even seemingly harmless moves like} 12. d5 {lose on the spot to Nxe7+ Qxe7 Ba3} c5 {Bxd5 . So, you can do one of two things: 1. Study exactly when you can sacrifice the knight and the resulting complicated middle games, at best achieving equal and weird.   2. My recommendation: Don't play this tactic of Nxe4 discovered attack on early Nh4 moves. And never worry about losing on the spot while attempting it. After all, White will always have the option of Nf5 or Nxe4 and Nxd6 . I prefer less work so let's save some relaxation by not thinking of doing this.}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Tension Variation (Master "]
[Black "The Knight f5 Plan I (12. Nh4, with 15. Bxe6)"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "36"]

{Black will have counterplay against White's pawns after the bishops trade--or White will get a wrecked pawn structure upon refusing: Be3 Bxc3 bxc3 , Black will be able to play the rooks onto the dark squares. Either Re5  Re8 for your standard attack on e4 pawn followed by d5 or if the situation warrants it Ra6 - b6 and on b3 or Rb1  Rb4 , eyeing the e pawn and also creating queenside counterplay with possible b5 ideas. Black should be happy here.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 {This is the so called Hanham variation of the Philidor. White is keeping the tension in the center and quickly developing their pieces. This makes a lot of sense and it was the recommendation in the Grandmaster Repertoire 1. e4 books. Here, White has the exciting g4 or the very normal Bc4 . This chapter is about Bc4 and other normal developing moves. Bg5 is a bad move here as it inspires trading pieces when White has a small space edge so reflects a misunderstanding of the position. Nonetheless, we will look at it and other ideas by White here.} 5. Bc4 Be7 {h6 is the so called Black Lion, which Simon Williams tried to make work and which Alexander Alekhine recommended for Black to play actively. It's a fun idea, but a bit anti-positional (or maybe the nice phrase is 'strategically risky')--it involves a lot of pawn moves in the opening and delayed castling. One thing to note is that whenever you see White play a bishop to c4 and knight to f3 , you must immediately respond Be7 in the Philidor. If you hesitate for an instant (for example, you play g6 ) Ng5 will unleash a carnage that is not child appropriate. Again, for emphasis: We always put the bishop on e7 when we see Nf3 and Bc4 so we can meet Ng5 with castles.} 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {Sometimes White plays a4 first, but it doesn't change anything. We've reached something of a tabiya. White has made a bunch of reasonable moves that are well suited for whichever pawn structure we get later. They are ready to push d5 if we play something like b6 and make it stronger, they are ready to take on e5 if they find a way to put pressure there, and they are ready to allow us to take if we so choose. A waiting game has commenced. Just so you are aware, here are the waiting moves that usually will not hurt and will often help Black in the usual order I recommend them: c6 , a5 , Re8 , h6 , Qc7 , Nf8 - Ng6 - potentially f4 So we have essentially things to improve when we don't know what to do. There are of course other plans for Black. For people wanting another plan involving self-study, a6 can be played here. There will already be alternatives within the c6 line and covering a6 as well as c6 would be a bit too much for this course.} c6 {This move ( c6 ) has been played by Radjabov, Firouzja, Beliavsky, Azmaiparashvili, Ivanchuk, Svidler, Morozevich, etc. etc. etc. It's a Who's Who of Super Grandmasters. Why is it so popular? Well, the idea is to activate the queen (usually to c7 ). Once the queen is on c7 , e5 will be defended so the knight on d7 can frolic as knights are wont to do. That's one idea. The second is to stop Nd5 . Especially if White opts for a dxe5 line, this is useful. A third idea is to play b5 and expand on the queenside. This comes with tempo. I've seen countless games where my students won a pawn with b5  Bb3  b4  Ne2  Nxe4 . It's amazing how you forget e4 is hanging! Even if there was no pawn win: b5  Bb7  a6  c5 is a natural plan for Black. White's next move is pretty important in stopping this.} 8. a4 a5 (8... Qc7 {is more popular and h6 was recommended by GM Cuenca in his Lifetime Philidor course here on Chessable. but} 9. a5 {has among the best win rates here and leads to less variance in structure. A high practical win rate and easier to remember than leading alternatives? Sounds like our repertoire! The point of the a-pawn move is to stop White from playing a5 themselves and enacting a python-like squeeze. I've personally been suffocated when White gets that plan off and I want to avoid it without having to memorize 42 variations on prevention and reaction. a5 flatly stops White from controlling the queenside and also helps the Black knight occupy c5 without a b-pawn boop later in the game. Also, for people below Master, it makes the resulting positions more similar so helps a lot with memory. There are downsides, but the simplicity and easiness to play make this a straightforward decision for us. There's two basic principles for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. h3 {White prepares Be3 and guards the knight hop to exchange it. White usually plays this (which fits many different plans), b3 , or Ba2 in high-level chess. In low level chess, the top two are the same, but they also play the positionally weak Bg5 , which looks natural but reflects a lack of understanding of what's going on. In this course, I won't handle every time White can play a move like Ba2 . Instead, I'll just label that the Sling Shot Plan and show you some variations of it and the general tug and pull. You should be able to figure it out at the board just fine if you understand the concepts. Here, Ba2 would be weaker than later because if you're going to attack f7 , you might as well wait until we've moved our rook!} Re8 {This was Jobava's choice. Essentially, Black has to decide where to put the knight on d7 (which must be moved to activate the light-squared bishop).   There are three options for your knight:   1. It can go to the queenside via Nb6 . This has a lot of fans and the idea is clever: to tempo on the White bishop and play exd4  c5  c4 at some point, restricting the bishop play. Nonetheless, it has some downsides: the knight leaves the kingside and sometimes you can be attacked and the plan is based on a very tricky pawn structure switch that can saddle Black with a backwards d-pawn.   2. It can go to c5 after exd4 . This tends to be very solid and is the antidote to many of White's tries as it stops d5 plans.   3. It can go to f8 , which will be my general preference when we don't have to red alert to c5 as it leads to a safe king and straightforward play on the kingside.  Re8 toys with the idea of taking on d4 and targeting f4 while clearing a path for the knight.   h6 is slightly more popular and it's a great move. But I don't think we need to waste the tempo just yet as on Ng5  Rf8 we will play h6 or exd4 next with White not able to recapture with a knight. So White will have forced a good h6 move or a good open Philidor (yes you moved your rook twice but they moved their knight twice). In some lines, the attack on e4 could use a tempo up.} 10. Be3 {Be3 fits all plans. d5 could still be in the cards as could Ba2 . b3 is off the table, but otherwise White is flexible. White will eventually have to reveal though as their queen moves tells us a lot. So we keep making our natural moves.} h6 {h6 is a clever move and when we don't know what to do, it should follow Re8 . The idea is twofold. The simple one is to stop Ng5 so we can put stuff on f8 . A more complex idea that Magnus Carlsen tried once is trade off some minor pieces to relieve some of the space issues Black is dealing with. In some lines, you can play Nfh7  Ng5 and if we have to take back with the h-pawn, then the f4 square will be primed for our Nf8 - g6 - f4 maneuver. Remember, though, we have to guard e5 with Qc7 before we can move the d7 knight!} 11. Ba2 {Key Signs of a Possible Slingshot Plan: White plays Ba2 , Qe2 , Qd3 or Qc4 . Sometimes even the sneaky Qb1 - a2 , though in that case, White has to very carefully look at the Nb6 tactics as the bishop doesn't have a lot of retreat squares.   All of that said, you have to be careful about red herrings as Ba2 is the preferred waiting move by many a GM. Generally speaking, Qe2 will signal the full on commitment. After all, it's useful for the bishop to be hidden away; in many variations, our knight would gain a tempo off of it when moving to b6 or e5 . So, don't panic yet, but narrow your eyes in suspicion.   Recap of White's Possible Goal: When you see Ba2 , suspect that White wants to assault the f7 square and play against Re8 and the f8 square being a Black transit location. They're hoping that by tying your rook to f8 , you will not be able to better your pieces. When White does this, it usually looks like a gigantic slingshot being deployed against you, hence 'Slingshot Plan.' The bishop on c4 pulls its elastic self back to a2 . The rock-solid Queen goes to e2 or d3 and then moves to where the bishop used to be on c4 , ready to be sling-shotted into f7 . Combine it with Ng5 and you have a menacing plan. It also works well for White to combine this plan with d5 . Sometimes, after the Black queen arrives on c7 and the White one on c4 , the c6 pawn will be pinned and Nb5 tactics will come up.   Now a word about the tactical considerations in this plan. White will often let you block with something on e6 only to play d5 and when you move away, play dxc6 discovered attack.   The Counter: The counter will be to play h6 (to stop Ng5 ) Re8  Nf8 (to deploy a piece on e6 to block up the diagonal). It will also often involve taking in the center when we see a queen move so that they lose their d5 move that combos so well with this setup and prevents us from clogging the diagonal with pieces into e6 .   The reason I am pointing this out is to show that you have to be thinking about multiple White possibilities simultaneously and playing moves that aid you in either. So, if they play Ba2 , h6 is a great waiting move because it will block that plan while being useful against other plans. The only plan h6 doesn't need to be played against is the d6 Assault Plan, which is no longer great as b3 will block the bishop. Next, I will show White both taking the normal path with Ba2 but also calling audibles this way and that.    Returning to the position on the board, Black has already played h6 , a counter, and White Ba2 , a waiting move that considers the Sling Shot idea. But the position is filled with subtlety. White's last move took away the d6 Assault Plan as b3 doesn't make sense but that leaves three audibles possible: White can switch to Nf5 Attacks, The Battering Ram or The Sacrificial Lamb... they are waiting to see how we react. So we need to move against the Slingshot Plan and be ready while at the same time prepared for the audibles.} Qc7 12. Nh4 {This is the mainline: White attempts to commandeer the f5 square for a knight. That said, Black is fine if they know what to do. You can always take on d4 here but waiting a move is also good. I will list both options as recommended because conceptually I want to show you that allowing Qf3 is fine.} Nf8 {We are ready to start relocating things. The black bishop now eyes f5 . If White's knight jumps in, take it and then play exd4 so as to play d5 , with a great center and the better game.} 13. Qf3 ({These moves are clearly for the high rated players on here or those pitted against them. White's plan is to again control f5 . Black has two responses and in addition to my recommendation also has} 13. Be6 {here. This is also logical, just trying to restrict f5 movement by putting a pawn on e6 . Both this and the recommended move looked good but I had to choose and I chose the one with the higher win rate in Master level games. And it wasn't even close on that count....}) 13... exd4 {This is justified because the queen will be attacked when things start landing on e5 and the e4 pawn is a pain to defend without the option of f3 (the misplaced knight and queen make f3 a tricky move to play. Also h3 means that on f3 , Black may have Nh5 ideas and playing into dark squares.} 14. Bxd4 Ne6 ({In return for this pawn structure, Black gains a ton of speed. White should probably give up the bishop pair here with the idea of playing actively} 14... Be6 15. Bxe6 {. The computer likes this though Be3 is the more popular move in actual play and what you'd likely get. It's also a bit trickier than the computer move because getting their light-squared bishop is more self evidently nice for us than having to play with the tension.}) 15. Bxe6 {The better and hard to make move.} Bxe6 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Nd7 18. Rad1 {And things are equal. Black will play Bf6 and the backward d-pawn will be easy to defend, one day pushing d5 perhaps. Diagonal attacks on d6 by the queen can be easily parried by putting a piece (like the rook) on e5 after the bishops trade off. Qb6 can be played sometimes as well to target the b2 pawn.} Bf6 *

