loy a piece on e6 to block up the diagonal). It will also often involve taking in the center when we see a queen move so that they lose their d5 move that combos so well with this setup and prevents us from clogging the diagonal with pieces into e6 .   The reason I am pointing this out is to show that you have to be thinking about multiple White possibilities simultaneously and playing moves that aid you in either. So, if they play Ba2 , h6 is a great waiting move because it will block that plan while being useful against other plans. The only plan h6 doesn't need to be played against is the d6 Assault Plan, which is no longer great as b3 will block the bishop. Next, I will show White both taking the normal path with Ba2 but also calling audibles this way and that.    Returning to the position on the board, Black has already played h6 , a counter, and White Ba2 , a waiting move that considers the Sling Shot idea. But the position is filled with subtlety. White's last move took away the d6 Assault Plan as b3 doesn't make sense but that leaves three audibles possible: White can switch to Nf5 Attacks, The Battering Ram or The Sacrificial Lamb... they are waiting to see how we react. So we need to move against the Slingshot Plan and be ready while at the same time prepared for the audibles.} Qc7 12. Nh4 {This is the mainline: White attempts to commandeer the f5 square for a knight. That said, Black is fine if they know what to do.} Nf8 {We are ready to start relocating things. The black bishop now eyes f5 . If White's knight jumps in, take it and then play exd4 so as to play d5 , with a great center and the better game.} 13. Qf3 ({These moves are clearly for the high rated players on here or those pitted against them. White's plan is to again control f5 . Black has two responses and in addition to my recommendation also has} 13. Be6 {here. This is also logical, just trying to restrict f5 movement by putting a pawn on e6 . Both this and the recommended move looked good but I had to choose and I chose the one with the higher win rate in Master level games. And it wasn't even close on that count....}) 13... exd4 {This is justified because the queen will be attacked when things start landing on e5 and the e4 pawn is a pain to defend without the option of f3 (the misplaced knight and queen make f3 a tricky move to play. Also h3 means that on f3 , Black may have Nh5 ideas and playing into dark squares.} 14. Bxd4 Ne6 ({In return for this pawn structure, Black gains a ton of speed. White should probably give up the bishop pair here with the idea of playing actively} 14... Be6 15. Bxe6 {. The computer likes this though Be3 is the more popular move in actual play and what you'd likely get. It's also a bit trickier than the computer move because getting their light-squared bishop is more self evidently nice for us than having to play with the tension.}) 15. Be3 {The computer wants White to just give up on the dark-squared bishop but almost every human won't willy nilly give up the bishop pair and will play Be3 instead.} Ng5 ({I generally am a little scared of playing} 15... Nc5 {when they have a dark-squared bishop eyeing it as} 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. e5 {can lead to weird hard-to-defend positions. If you could play Nc5  and  Nfd7 , before they took, it would be alright, but that's impossible. So Nf5 is threatened when according to principle, we want to take. Nf8 and Nd8 look passive so by process of elimination, we have this move that takes advantage of h6 . This position has been reached five times and each time, White played the same reply....}) 16. Bxg5 hxg5 17. Nf5 Bf8 (17... Bxf5 {is always our instinct but} 18. Qxf5 {makes the pawn on g5 an annoying thing to defend, so we have to think a little here. 17... Bf8 , the move recommended, now prepares Bxf5 next because Qxf5 will be met with Re5 , guarding everything.    You can stop here as both sides have many moves. That said, Black should be able to get d5 in here eventually and can take white's knight soon (like maybe after Re5 if they want to force a pawn to recapture or quicker if they feel like it). A pawn recapture of the knight on bishop takes will allow Black to play d5 (basically this is what we always do after taking on f5 and having White recapture with a pawn). Then their Ba2 will be in a dark dungeon. The d6 pawn is well covered without White's dark-squared bishop and Black even has a slight edge.}) *

