1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 {This is the so called Hanham variation of the Philidor. White is keeping the tension in the center and quickly developing their pieces. This makes a lot of sense and it was the recommendation in the Grandmaster Repertoire 1. e4 books. Here, White has the exciting g4 or the very normal Bc4 . This chapter is about Bc4 and other normal developing moves. Bg5 is a bad move here as it inspires trading pieces when White has a small space edge so reflects a misunderstanding of the position. Nonetheless, we will look at it and other ideas by White here.} 5. Bc4 Be7 {h6 is the so called Black Lion, which Simon Williams tried to make work and which Alexander Alekhine recommended for Black to play actively. It's a fun idea, but a bit anti-positional (or maybe the nice phrase is 'strategically risky')--it involves a lot of pawn moves in the opening and delayed castling. One thing to note is that whenever you see White play a bishop to c4 and knight to f3 , you must immediately respond Be7 in the Philidor. If you hesitate for an instant (for example, you play g6 ) Ng5 will unleash a carnage that is not child appropriate. Again, for emphasis: We always put the bishop on e7 when we see Nf3 and Bc4 so we can meet Ng5 with castles.} 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {Sometimes White plays a4 first, but it doesn't change anything. We've reached something of a tabiya. White has made a bunch of reasonable moves that are well suited for whichever pawn structure we get later. They are ready to push d5 if we play something like b6 and make it stronger, they are ready to take on e5 if they find a way to put pressure there, and they are ready to allow us to take if we so choose. A waiting game has commenced. Just so you are aware, here are the waiting moves that usually will not hurt and will often help Black in the usual order I recommend them: c6 , a5 , Re8 , h6 , Qc7 , Nf8 - Ng6 - potentially f4 So we have essentially things to improve when we don't know what to do. There are of course other plans for Black. For people wanting another plan involving self-study, a6 can be played here. There will already be alternatives within the c6 line and covering a6 as well as c6 would be a bit too much for this course.} c6 {This move ( c6 ) has been played by Radjabov, Firouzja, Beliavsky, Azmaiparashvili, Ivanchuk, Svidler, Morozevich, etc. etc. etc. It's a Who's Who of Super Grandmasters. Why is it so popular? Well, the idea is to activate the queen (usually to c7 ). Once the queen is on c7 , e5 will be defended so the knight on d7 can frolic as knights are wont to do. That's one idea. The second is to stop Nd5 . Especially if White opts for a dxe5 line, this is useful. A third idea is to play b5 and expand on the queenside. This comes with tempo. I've seen countless games where my students won a pawn with b5  Bb3  b4  Ne2  Nxe4 . It's amazing how you forget e4 is hanging! Even if there was no pawn win: b5  Bb7  a6  c5 is a natural plan for Black. White's next move is pretty important in stopping this.} 8. a4 a5 (8... Qc7 {is more popular and h6 was recommended by GM Cuenca in his Lifetime Philidor course here on Chessable. but} 9. a5 {has among the best win rates here and leads to less variance in structure. A high practical win rate and easier to remember than leading alternatives? Sounds like our repertoire! The point of the a-pawn move is to stop White from playing a5 themselves and enacting a python-like squeeze. I've personally been suffocated when White gets that plan off and I want to avoid it without having to memorize 42 variations on prevention and reaction. a5 flatly stops White from controlling the queenside and also helps the Black knight occupy c5 without a b-pawn boop later in the game. Also, for people below Master, it makes the resulting positions more similar so helps a lot with memory. There are downsides, but the simplicity and easiness to play make this a straightforward decision for us. There's two basic principles for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. h3 {White prepares Be3 and guards the knight hop to exchange it. White usually plays this (which fits many different plans), b3 , or Ba2 in high-level chess. In low level chess, the top two are the same, but they also play the positionally weak Bg5 , which looks natural but reflects a lack of understanding of what's going on. In this course, I won't handle every time White can play a move like Ba2 . Instead, I'll just label that the Sling Shot Plan and show you some variations of it and the general tug and pull. You should be able to figure it out at the board just fine if you understand the concepts. Here, Ba2 would be weaker than later because if you're going to attack f7 , you might as well wait until we've moved our rook!} Re8 {This was Jobava's choice. Essentially, Black has to decide where to put the knight on d7 (which must be moved to activate the light-squared bishop). There are three options: 1. It can go to the queenside via Nb6 . This has a lot of fans and the idea is clever: to tempo on the White bishop and play exd4  c5  c4 at some point, restricting the bishop play. Nonetheless, it has some downsides: the knight leaves the kingside and sometimes you can be attacked and the plan is based on a very tricky pawn structure switch that can saddle black with a backwards d-pawn. 2. It can go to c5 after exd4 . This tends to be very solid and is the antidote to many of White's tries as it stops d5 plans. 3. It can go to f8 , which will be my general preference when we don't have to red alert to c5 as it leads to a safe king and straightforward play on the kingside. Re8 toys with the idea of taking on d4 and targeting f4 while clearing a path for the knight. h6 is slightly more popular and it's a great move. But I don't think we need to waste the tempo just yet as on Ng5  Rf8 we will play h6 next and White will have forced a good h6 move (yes you moved your rook twice but they moved their knight twice). In some lines, the attack on e4 could use a tempo up.} 10. Be3 {Be3 fits all plans. d5 could still be in the cards as could Ba2 . b3 is off the table, but otherwise White is flexible. White will eventually have to reveal though as their queen moves tells us a lot. So we keep making our natural moves.} h6 {h6 is a clever move and when we don't know what to do, it should follow Re8 . The idea is twofold. The simple one is to stop Ng5 so we can put stuff on f8 . A more complex idea that Magnus Carlsen tried once is trade off some minor pieces to relieve some of the space issues Black is dealing with. In some lines, you can play Nfh7  Ng5 and if we have to take back with the h-pawn, then the f4 square will be primed for our Nf8 - g6 - f4 maneuver. Remember, though, we have to guard e5 with Qc7 before we can move the d7 knight!} 11. Ba2 {Key Signs of a Possible Slingshot Plan: White plays Ba2 , Qe2 , Qd3 or Qc4 . Sometimes even the sneaky Qb1 - a2 , though in that case, White has to very carefully look at the Nb6 tactics as the bishop doesn't have a lot of retreat squares.   All of that said, you have to be careful about red herrings as Ba2 is the preferred waiting move by many a GM. Generally speaking, Qe2 will signal the full on commitment. After all, it's useful for the bishop to be hidden away; in many variations, our knight would gain a tempo off of it when moving to b6 or e5 . So, don't panic yet, but narrow your eyes in suspicion.   Recap of White's Possible Goal: When you see Ba2 , suspect that White wants to assault the f7 square and play against Re8 and the f8 square being a Black transit location. They're hoping that by tying your rook to f8 , you will not be able to better your pieces. When White does this, it usually looks like a gigantic slingshot being deployed against you, hence 'Slingshot Plan.' The bishop on c4 pulls its elastic self back to a2 . The rock-solid Queen goes to e2 or d3 and then moves to where the bishop used to be on c4 , ready to be sling-shotted into f7 . Combine it with Ng5 and you have a menacing plan. It also works well for White to combine this plan with d5 . Sometimes, after the Black queen arrives on c7 and the White one on c4 , the c6 pawn will be pinned and Nb5 tactics will come up.   Now a word about the tactical considerations in this plan. White will often let you block with something on e6 only to play d5 and when you move away, play dxc6 discovered attack.   The Counter: The counter will be to play h6 (to stop Ng5 ) Re8  Nf8 (to deploy a piece on e6 to block up the diagonal). It will also often involve taking in the center when we see a queen move so that they lose their d5 move that combos so well with this setup and prevents us from clogging the diagonal with pieces into e6 .   The reason I am pointing this out is to show that you have to be thinking about multiple White possibilities simultaneously and playing moves that aid you in either. So, if they play Ba2 , h6 is a great waiting move because it will block that plan while being useful against other plans. The only plan h6 doesn't need to be played against is the d6 Assault Plan, which is no longer great as b3 will block the bishop. Next, I will show White both taking the normal path with Ba2 but also calling audibles this way and that.    Returning to the position on the board, Black has already played h6 , a counter, and White Ba2 , a waiting move that considers the Sling Shot idea. But the position is filled with subtlety. White's last move took away the d6 Assault Plan as b3 doesn't make sense but that leaves three audibles possible: White can switch to Nf5 Attacks, The Battering Ram or The Sacrificial Lamb... they are waiting to see how we react. So we need to move against the Slingshot Plan and be ready while at the same time prepared for the audibles.} Qc7 12. Nh4 {This is the mainline: White attempts to commandeer the f5 square for a knight. That said, Black is fine if they know what to do. Why now? Well a few reasons.  Nf5 is better after Black has played h6 because then g6 can be met with winning a pawn and sacrifice ideas come up along with g4 - g5 tricks.  Nf5 is also better when Black has played Qc7 .  Ba2 was a waiting move because it's generally useful without committing--queen moves would have also worked, but White wants to play Qf3 in the Nf5 setup to move it to the kingside. Why is it better when Black has played Qc7 ? Because it sets a devilish trap.} ({It looks like Nxe4 just wins a pawn with a discovered attack on the} 12. h4 {knight. Before reading more, see if you can spot why that doesn't work.  So, against this, White can take the knight} Nxe4 {and on Bxh4 White has the stunning} 13. Bxf7+ {, regaining the pawn because if you take it,} Kxf7 {Qh4+ wins the Black bishop. So it's a pawn for a pawn but trust me when I say that's no even trade: your f-pawn was critical for king safety and the missing e-pawn actually opens up White's rook. So no shenanigans here.   This is an alternative line for Black if you don't want to immediately relieve the tension.}) 12... Nf8 {We are ready to start relocating things. The black bishop now eyes f5 . If White's knight jumps in, take it and then play exd4 so as to play d5 , with a great center and the better game.} 13. Qf3 {These moves are clearly for the high rated players on here or those pitted against them. White's plan is to again control f5 . Black has three responses: 13... exd4 is always good and is justified because the queen will be attacked when things start landing on e5 and the e4 pawn is a pain to defend without the option of f3 (the misplaced knight and queen make f3 a tricky move to play to guard e4 (plus, they've played h3 making f3 a holy move, and by that I mean it creates a lot of holes) and, to make matters worse for White, the queen is standing in the White knight's retreat square (if they chicken out of f5 ). No wonder 13... exd4 has the highest win rate in Master level chess for Black. Okay, okay, I'll stop swooning over my main recommendation again and get back to it...  13... Be6 is also logical, just trying to restrict f5 movement by putting a pawn on e6 and trading the light-squared bishops. 13... Ne6 makes sense because the idea is to transpose to the 13... exd4 lines and threaten to win the bishop or force a capture with the White knight. The downside is that it blocks our ability to take on f5 immediately and also wouldn't be in the spirit of the alternative (we're just playing a glorified 13... exd4 strategy). Both looked good and even though 13... Ne6 drew more in Master level games 13... Be6 was the overwhelming favorites of most GM's who had decided to not take on d4 already (it wasn't even close on that count), so let's look at Be6 ....} Be6 {White has three lines here. They can play 14. Nf5 (consistent) and argue you wasted a tempo moving your bishop, 14. dxe5 --either now or after trading bishops, or play 14. Bxe6 right away without a dxe5 follow up. Let's look at each and then I'll cover the most pressing option:} (13... Be6 {gives Black an interesting choice. Nxe6 back is the safe and recommended call because you can stop the immediate} 14. Nf5 {with Nxd4 Bxd4} exd4 15. Nxd4 g6 {and again, without the light-squared bishops, g6 isn't a positional issue here and the knight will never return to f5 . The riskier choice is to recapture the bishop with your pawn and play with a structure similar to the Queen Trade Bc4 lines. I'm not a huge fan of this as we don't have any pawn storms or a firm grip on c5 later. The b6 square is often positionally weak in these c6  a5 structures. Still, two 2400's played in this way and no one played 14... Nxe6 , probably because 14... Nxe6 looks a lot like an exd4 line and these players were trying to do something different. One drew and one lost. So different didn't really pay off for them. Therefore, I recommend 14... Nxe6 because I can't see doing something weird like recapturing with the pawn to win when Black has never won.}) ({dxe5 dxe5 allows White to keep a knight on f5 . For example,} 13... Be6 {, asking the same question from the previous line, and if Nxe6} 14. Nf5 {. Recall that previously when the pawns weren't exchanged here, I recommended Nxd4 here and then g6 . But now, you have no way to stop the knight on f5 . So key is to stop the kingside pawn storm that begins g4 . Black has the option to allow it, but why? Instead,} h5 {is very strong, stopping g4 . Black decides to try to trade off the white knight later and makes g6 possible without losing a pawn on h6 . GM Khachiyan played in this way against an expert and prevailed, though it wasn't the opening but rather the complicated arising position. In that game, Black ended up a tiny bit worse later actually before eventually winning. There, White tempted Black to play g6 with Qg3 and then took out the dark squared bishop, but converting that small edge to a win is very hard as so many pieces have been traded and the kingside is hard to access. Additionally, Black could have met Qg3 ideas with Bb4 before committing to g6 as the Knight on e6 already blocked checkmate. This would have led to equality according to the engine.}) ({Nf5 right away without trading bishops or pawns is the final idea and the subject of the move trainer. This move makes Black spoiled for choice (although sometimes that's a burden). Does Black want to trade the bishop for the knight with} 13... Bf5 {or trade the bishops with Bxa2? Both are reasonable and good moves. The final Black option is to play} 14. Ng6 {with the idea of keeping the tension, eyeing f4 and (if White exchanges pawns in the center) recapturing Nxe5 to avoid doubled pawns in the event of a bishop trade on e6 . This is a bit better here than usual because the pawn will tempo on the knight f5 . I'll make it my mainline alternative MoveTrainer as the other options have fairly obvious play and this one would most benefit from memorization.}) 14. Nf5 Ng6 {The game continues with the tension preserved. Let's examine White's most forcing option which might also be their best try here.} 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Nxe7+ {Now Black took with the rook in Schneder vs. Osmondoja but Qxe7 makes sense as we want to bring things to the kingside in order to attack and get rid of Bxh6  gxh6  Qxf6 ideas.} Qxe7 17. dxe5 Nxe5 {The point. Black is now in a position to take back with the knight.} 18. Qe2 {18. Qd1 was the computer move, but most of your opponents will not want to allow Nc4 later. 18. Qg3 looks awkward because of 18... Nh5 and it's banished to h2 .} d5 {Black is in time for a central break and a double-edged game is ahead of us. The White bishop is slightly stronger than either Black knight giving White a tiny edge on that count-- Bb6 to try to attack a5 is this looming threat that keeps the a8 rook at bay. On the other hand, Black's knights are nothing to laugh at and with the extra center pawns, they will have outposts to move forward into the White position. This position has never been reached before, but for those not wanting to give up the center: it may not be quite as equal (tiny edge White) but look at your center and this is anyone's game!} *

