rade off some minor pieces to relieve some of the space issues Black is dealing with. In some lines, you can play Nfh7  Ng5 and if we have to take back with the h-pawn, then the f4 square will be primed for our Nf8 - g6 - f4 maneuver. Remember, though, we have to guard e5 with Qc7 before we can move the d7 knight!} 11. Ba2 {Key Signs of a Possible Slingshot Plan: White plays Ba2 , Qe2 , Qd3 or Qc4 . Sometimes even the sneaky Qb1 - a2 , though in that case, White has to very carefully look at the Nb6 tactics as the bishop doesn't have a lot of retreat squares.   All of that said, you have to be careful about red herrings as Ba2 is the preferred waiting move by many a GM. Generally speaking, Qe2 will signal the full on commitment. After all, it's useful for the bishop to be hidden away; in many variations, our knight would gain a tempo off of it when moving to b6 or e5 . So, don't panic yet, but narrow your eyes in suspicion.   Recap of White's Possible Goal: When you see Ba2 , suspect that White wants to assault the f7 square and play against Re8 and the f8 square being a Black transit location. They're hoping that by tying your rook to f8 , you will not be able to better your pieces. When White does this, it usually looks like a gigantic slingshot being deployed against you, hence 'Slingshot Plan.' The bishop on c4 pulls its elastic self back to a2 . The rock-solid Queen goes to e2 or d3 and then moves to where the bishop used to be on c4 , ready to be sling-shotted into f7 . Combine it with Ng5 and you have a menacing plan. It also works well for White to combine this plan with d5 . Sometimes, after the Black queen arrives on c7 and the White one on c4 , the c6 pawn will be pinned and Nb5 tactics will come up.   Now a word about the tactical considerations in this plan. White will often let you block with something on e6 only to play d5 and when you move away, play dxc6 discovered attack.   The Counter: The counter will be to play h6 (to stop Ng5 ) Re8  Nf8 (to deploy a piece on e6 to block up the diagonal). It will also often involve taking in the center when we see a queen move so that they lose their d5 move that combos so well with this setup and prevents us from clogging the diagonal with pieces into e6 .   The reason I am pointing this out is to show that you have to be thinking about multiple White possibilities simultaneously and playing moves that aid you in either. So, if they play Ba2 , h6 is a great waiting move because it will block that plan while being useful against other plans. The only plan h6 doesn't need to be played against is the d6 Assault Plan, which is no longer great as b3 will block the bishop. Next, I will show White both taking the normal path with Ba2 but also calling audibles this way and that.    Returning to the position on the board, Black has already played h6 , a counter, and White Ba2 , a waiting move that considers the Sling Shot idea. But the position is filled with subtlety. White's last move took away the d6 Assault Plan as b3 doesn't make sense but that leaves three audibles possible: White can switch to Nf5 Attacks, The Battering Ram or The Sacrificial Lamb... they are waiting to see how we react. So we need to move against the Slingshot Plan and be ready while at the same time prepared for the audibles.} Qc7 12. dxe5 {White prevents us from taking on d4 , but loses the right to play d5 so now we can occupy the e6 square with pieces, not worried about being harassed by the White central pawn.} dxe5 13. Nh4 {Audible! Knight f5 Attack! White is always trying this idea at various times! Recall the goals of our play from the informational: eat the f5 knight with our bishop when it arrives.} Nf8 14. Nf5 Bxf5 {Thematic, see informational on the Nf5 Plan.} 15. exf5 {This was Gawain Jones-Jobava. Jobava played Bb4 here, instead of my recommendation, which was good but we can take a small edge with a different move. Regardless, Black should feel good already. After all, Black has done well: when White tries this Nf5 stuff, we want to play Nf8 so as to let the bishop take the f5 knight quickly. Once we do that, we can feel good about ourselves even if we don't play the exact computer follow up.} e4 {Improving on Jones-Jobava by making it difficult for White to defend f5 and also blocking solid White formations involving f3 and Ne4 . This is the last sort of weird move. Black's play should be fairly natural from this point forth.} *

