les for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. h3 {White prepares Be3 and guards the knight hop to exchange it. White usually plays this (which fits many different plans), b3 , or Ba2 in high-level chess. In low level chess, the top two are the same, but they also play the positionally weak Bg5 , which looks natural but reflects a lack of understanding of what's going on. In this course, I won't handle every time White can play a move like Ba2 . Instead, I'll just label that the Sling Shot Plan and show you some variations of it and the general tug and pull. You should be able to figure it out at the board just fine if you understand the concepts. Here, Ba2 would be weaker than later because if you're going to attack f7 , you might as well wait until we've moved our rook!} Re8 {This was Jobava's choice. Essentially, Black has to decide where to put the knight on d7 (which must be moved to activate the light-squared bishop).   There are three options for your knight:   1. It can go to the queenside via Nb6 . This has a lot of fans and the idea is clever: to tempo on the White bishop and play exd4  c5  c4 at some point, restricting the bishop play. Nonetheless, it has some downsides: the knight leaves the kingside and sometimes you can be attacked and the plan is based on a very tricky pawn structure switch that can saddle black with a backwards d-pawn.   2. It can go to c5 after exd4 . This tends to be very solid and is the antidote to many of White's tries as it stops d5 plans.   3. It can go to f8 , which will be my general preference when we don't have to red alert to c5 as it leads to a safe king and straightforward play on the kingside.  Re8 toys with the idea of taking on d4 and targeting f4 while clearing a path for the knight.   h6 is slightly more popular and it's a great move. But I don't think we need to waste the tempo just yet as on Ng5  Rf8 we will play h6 or exd4 next with White not able to recapture with a knight. So White will have forced a good h6 move or a good open Philidor (yes you moved your rook twice but they moved their knight twice). In some lines, the attack on e4 could use a tempo up.} 10. Nh4 {The Knight f5 attack!    Signs of a Nf5 attack: 1. Nh4 .   Okay, that's pretty much the only sign. Sometimes they get really into their knight and put a queen on f3 to cheer it on.   White's plan: They want to put a knight on f5 . They are very simple.    Why? Because it's near your king and they love the warm feeling of checkmate in the morning. If you play g6 after it arrives, they will move the knight to h6 in response. If you play g6 before the knight arrives, they will play against your dark-squares and may even play f4 to open up the f-file.   Black's Counter: Well, generally speaking, we clear our knight on d7 so we can take the knight on f5 . Nf8 is an option if you want to keep the position closed but if we're playing by simple rules, the easiest path is to always take on d4 when you see Nh4 .   Why? Because White usually has to take back with the queen or bishop (neither ideal) and after Nc5 or Ne5 , your bishop will guard f5 and on Ne5 , you'll block the h4 knight from retreating without doubling pawns (or playing f4 , which weakens e4 ), and on Nc5 you'll get Ne6 hitting the queen later and an enhanced e-pawn attack. So in short, take the d-pawn, move your knight and eat whatever lands on f5 . If you have already traded light-squared bishop then usually White's attack isn't that great anyway and you can even play g6 because there's not so much pressure down the f-file without that c4 bishop.} exd4 {A common retort. Even d5 was possible here but I prefer to keep things thematic.} 11. Qxd4 {Here, the move d5 along with... Nc5 are both reasonable but d5 is often unplayable, so let's keep it conceptual with moves that at least almost always can be played in response. Black's next move is more thematic so my recommendation for your memorization purposes.} Ne5 12. Be2 Nxe4 ({And technically after} 12... Nxe4 {Black should play d5 here for an edge, but let's not obsess over the intermezzo tactics as for most readers the simple Bxh4 in reply will be more than fine. Even though knight sacrifices on e4 early are bad, by move twelve with the center opened up we're back to considering them and in this case it works very well. Just make sure to calculate it out!}) *

