se other plans for Black. For people wanting another plan involving self-study, a6 can be played here. There will already be alternatives within the c6 line and covering a6 as well as c6 would be a bit too much for this course. Generally, we will take on d4 after White moves the queen or plays b3 for reasons I will explain in each variation} 7... c6 {This move ( c6 ) has been played by Radjabov, Firouzja, Beliavsky, Azmaiparashvili, Ivanchuk, Svidler, Morozevich, etc. etc. etc. It's a Who's Who of Super Grandmasters. Why is it so popular? Well, the idea is to activate the queen (usually to c7 ). Once the queen is on c7 , e5 will be defended so the knight on d7 can frolic as knights are wont to do. That's one idea. The second is to stop Nd5 . Especially if White opts for a dxe5 line, this is useful. A third idea is to play b5 and expand on the queenside. This comes with tempo. I've seen countless games where my students won a pawn with b5  Bb3  b4  Ne2  Nxe4 . It's amazing how you forget e4 is hanging! Even if there was no pawn win: b5  Bb7  a6  c5 is a natural plan for Black. White's next move is pretty important in stopping this.} 8. a4 a5 (8... Qc7 {is more popular and h6 was recommended by GM Cuenca in his Lifetime Philidor course here on Chessable. but} 9. a5 {has among the best win rates here and leads to less variance in structure. A high practical win rate and easier to remember than leading alternatives? Sounds like our repertoire! The point of the a-pawn move is to stop White from playing a5 themselves and enacting a python-like squeeze. I've personally been suffocated when White gets that plan off and I want to avoid it without having to memorize 42 variations on prevention and reaction. a5 flatly stops White from controlling the queenside and also helps the Black knight occupy c5 without a b-pawn boop later in the game. Also, for people below Master, it makes the resulting positions more similar so helps a lot with memory. There are downsides, but the simplicity and easiness to play make this a straightforward decision for us. There's two basic principles for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. h3 {White prepares Be3 and guards the knight hop to exchange it. White usually plays this (which fits many different plans), b3 , or Ba2 in high-level chess. In low level chess, the top two are the same, but they also play the positionally weak Bg5 , which looks natural but reflects a lack of understanding of what's going on. In this course, I won't handle every time White can play a move like Ba2 . Instead, I'll just label that the Sling Shot Plan and show you some variations of it and the general tug and pull. You should be able to figure it out at the board just fine if you understand the concepts.} ({Here,} 9. Ba2 {would be weaker than later because if you're going to attack f7 , you might as well wait until we've moved our rook!}) 9... Re8 {This was Jobava's choice. Essentially, Black has to decide where to put the knight on d7 (which must be moved to activate the light-squared bishop).   There are three options for your knight:   1. It can go to the queenside via Nb6 . This has a lot of fans and the idea is clever: to tempo on the White bishop and play exd4  c5  c4 at some point, restricting the bishop play. Nonetheless, it has some downsides: the knight leaves the kingside and sometimes you can be attacked and the plan is based on a very tricky pawn structure switch that can saddle black with a backwards d-pawn.   2. It can go to c5 after exd4 . This tends to be very solid and is the antidote to many of White's tries as it stops d5 plans.   3. It can go to f8 , which will be my general preference when we don't have to red alert to c5 as it leads to a safe king and straightforward play on the kingside.  Re8 toys with the idea of taking on d4 and targeting f4 while clearing a path for the knight.   h6 is slightly more popular and it's a great move. But I don't think we need to waste the tempo just yet as on Ng5  Rf8 we will play h6 or exd4 next with White not able to recapture with a knight. So White will have forced a good h6 move or a good open Philidor (yes you moved your rook twice but they moved their knight twice). In some lines, the attack on e4 could use a tempo up.} 10. Ba2 {White's last move signals the 'Sling Shot Plan,' but remember White can combine plans and a bishop retreat isn't a commitment yet, just an innuendo. Many White players like to play it as a waiting move to see what you are up to. Be ready for Qe2 - Qc4 and when you see Ba2 , make sure you have h6 on the board to stop Ng5 . Be3 is the main move here which often transposes.} ({It would be a big mistake to play Nf8} 10. Ng5 {when the f7 pawn isn't easy to defend without wrecking your pawn structure. Black must block this threat with 10... h6 as a result.}) 10... h6 ({Now Be3} 10... Qc7 {would be back to the mainline Slingshot Plan. Let's look at an attempt to avoid the bishop development and accelerate the knight f5 attack by a tempo.}) 11. dxe5 (11. Nh4 {is also possible but generally, Black can just respond to Nh4 with} exd4 {immediately or on the next move. Personally, I prefer to try to wait for the queen to go to f3 but that's small potatoes, both are fine. So because White wants to prevent exd4 as a response, they exchange in the center.}) 11... dxe5 12. Nh4 {The Sling Shot Plan has switched into the Knight f5 Plan and White has tried trading pawns so we can't do our normal thing: wait for the queen to move and play exd4 . This is normal. Plans are fluid and when you stop one, your opponent will often switch gears. Remember the quote: 'If White keeps a knight on f5 , you soon won't be alive.' So Care Bear bishop, it's time for a Care Bear STAAAARE!} Nf8 13. Qf3 {White adds Qf3 to the Nf5 plan a lot so that they don't have awkward pawns after the exchange.} Be6 {The only thing that light-squared bishop loves to eat more than a knight f5 is the opposing light-squared bishop. Generally, you'll even allow a knight on f5 , if you know White doesn't have one of their most essential attacking pieces: that bishop. I guess we have to add to the rhyme: 'If a knight can stay on f5 , you soon won't be alive, unless their light-squared bishop has taken a dive.' Okay, I tried, but sometimes rules are complicated.} 14. Bxe6 Nxe6 15. Nf5 Nd4 {And simplest is to just eliminate the f5 knight this way. But anything was fine. The position is totally equal and you may now proceed to try to win and play against the misplaced c3 knight.} *

