[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "32"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4 a5 9. b3 {[The d6 Assault]White's last move, b3 , initiates the d6 Assault Plan. White wants to play Ba3 and hardcore attack your center pawns without their bishop blocking a central file--so better rooks. They will open things up with dxe5 or d5 at a choice moment, usually the latter.   Here's a conceptual analysis to guide you in principled play:  1. b3 blocks the light-squared bishop retreat path, so against b3 , I recommend exd4 and on Nxd4  Ne5 to expose the bishop and to banish it.    2. Without the bishop on e3 , the black queen is best deployed on b6 , that's where we wanted it anyway but usually the bishop on e3 would tactic us. Now it's a great queen! You may want to wait for Ba3 or Bb2 before playing it.   3. It is a bad move for White to play h3 here. There's no need. White could switch to Be3 after playing b3 , but then why did they have to block in their light-squared bishop from retreating?  To take advantage of the mistake h3 ? by White, you can often sacrifice your bishop on h3 and then fork them on f3 .  I'll show you in this informational later how that would work.   4. Black no longer needs to play h6 here as the f7 attack is off limits when White can't maintain their bishop on the diagonal.  5. Black can sometimes play Qc7  b5 in the middle game and launch a queenside attack, cutting off the Ba3 in the process.   6. If White ever takes d6 with the bishop, often you can pin it to their queen or trade and then get a rook on the seventh at the end of it.  So don't overstress about your d6 pawn.} exd4 10. Nxd4 Ne5 {Thematic and the issue with b3 : the bishop has to move off the scary diagonal. Since the whole point of playing b3 was to not have a bishop in the way of the rooks, Bf1 seems called for.} 11. Bf1 Re8 12. Ba3 Qb6 {Remember, against b3 the queen can come here without a Be3 tactic.  Qc7 is fine if you forget but just think about the downsides to b3 long enough and it might come to you.} 13. h3 {This doesn't go with b3 . Here's a tactic to remember...} Bxh3 14. gxh3 Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Nf3+ 16. Kg2 Nxd4 {This comes up a lot in this b3  Ba3 variation. Without the bishop being able to recapture on d4 , Black can force this combo whenever White plays h3 . This also means that as soon as you see h3 , your queen can go to c7 because they probably won't be playing the b3 system.} *

