les for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. b3 {White Goal 3: b3  Bb2 aims to target e5 , and Ba3 aims to target d6 , so let's remove the e5 target. Also, against xd4 the bishop often belongs on f4 but now b3 will just look weird.} exd4 10. Nxd4 {Black has many ways to proceed here, but I like....} Ne5 {Black gains a valuable tempo on the c4 bishop and pre-emptively stops Bf4 ideas by blocking the diagonal.} 11. Bf1 {The best square so that the e1 rook can still help defend Black's sudden e4 attack.} Re8 12. Ba3 {The most played move. White eyes d5 . If you don't play this, why play b3 ?} Qb6 {It's important to clear the d file for rooks. Sometimes when White takes d6 , Black will have enough compensation because they will be able to attack whatever took it with Rd8 and pin it to the enemy queen or if the enemy queen took it, play rook to the seventh to counter and win back the material. Notice how well Qb6 fits in with this as the queen spies f2 when the knight moves and if you get a rook on the seventh, that queen spy will come in handy.} 13. Qd2 {I am following Weiqi Zhou vs. Yangyi Yu (2603 vs. 2760). Yu won the game and provided a roadmap on how to play these positions. That said, they played Bd7 here and I am proposing an interesting novelty that also contains a trap that should be sure to snare an expert or two.} Bg4 {The idea is to stop White from putting a rook on the d-file. At first, this move looks suspect. e6 was out of the question because of our rule 'Don't put a bishop on e6 if it can be eaten by a knight' but d7 looks easier. After all, it looks like White can just play h3 (a useful move) and if Bd7 , Black reached an inferior version of Bd7 right away (because h3 was helpful). And if Bh4 then Nf5 and we can't take the knight! This has never been played before in Masters games or on Lichess. So I will have to guess as to the mainline. Black's plan is straightforward: bring the a-rook to d8 , start calculating central pawn breaks (namely d5 but even sometimes Nfd7  f5 ), try not to lose the d6 pawn without getting something out of it like a rook on the seventh.} 14. h3 {White foolishly thinks they can threaten a Magic Bishop!} Bxh3 15. gxh3 Qxd4 16. Qxd4 Nf3+ 17. Kg2 Nxd4 {Black is up a pawn and threatening c2 . Life is good.} *

