tant to clear the d file for rooks. Sometimes when White takes d6 , Black will have enough compensation because they will be able to attack whatever took it with Rd8 and pin it to the enemy queen or if the enemy queen took it, play rook to the seventh to counter and win back the material. Notice how well Qb6 fits in with this as the queen spies f2 when the knight moves and if you get a rook on the seventh, that queen spy will come in handy.} 13. Qd2 {I am following Weiqi Zhou vs. Yangyi Yu (2603 vs. 2760). Yu won the game and provided a roadmap on how to play these positions. That said, they played Bd7 here and I am proposing an interesting novelty that also contains a trap that should be sure to snare an expert or two.} Bg4 {The idea is to stop White from putting a rook on the d-file. At first, this move looks suspect. e6 was out of the question because of our rule 'Don't put a bishop on e6 if it can be eaten by a knight' but d7 looks easier. After all, it looks like White can just play h3 (a useful move) and if Bd7 , Black reached an inferior version of Bd7 right away (because h3 was helpful). And if Bh4 then Nf5 and we can't take the knight! This has never been played before in Masters games or on Lichess. So I will have to guess as to the mainline. Black's plan is straightforward: bring the a-rook to d8 , start calculating central pawn breaks (namely d5 but even sometimes Nfd7  f5 ), try not to lose the d6 pawn without getting something out of it like a rook on the seventh.} 14. Qe3 {This is probably most logical, getting the queen off the d-file so they can take on d6 with a bishop without a rook pin to their queen. Also, h3 and f3 resulted in instant death because of that queen on d2 ! So White has to waste a tempo and put their queen on an awkward square (note Qf4 wasn't possible as their knight would hang). That said, now they have e-file issues and we can open the rook a little more with Bf8 (our knight wasn't going there anyway. If our bishop goes back now