t to clear the d file for rooks. Sometimes when White takes d6 , Black will have enough compensation because they will be able to attack whatever took it with Rd8 and pin it to the enemy queen or if the enemy queen took it, play rook to the seventh to counter and win back the material. Notice how well Qb6 fits in with this as the queen spies f2 when the knight moves and if you get a rook on the seventh, that queen spy will come in handy.} 13. Qd2 {I am following Weiqi Zhou vs. Yangyi Yu (2603 vs. 2760). Yu won the game and provided a roadmap on how to play these positions. That said, they played Bd7 here and I am proposing an interesting novelty that also contains a trap that should be sure to snare an expert or two.} Bg4 {The idea is to stop White from putting a rook on the d-file. At first, this move looks suspect. e6 was out of the question because of our rule 'Don't put a bishop on e6 if it can be eaten by a knight' but d7 looks easier. After all, it looks like White can just play h3 (a useful move) and if Bd7 , Black reached an inferior version of Bd7 right away (because h3 was helpful). And if Bh4 then Nf5 and we can't take the knight! This has never been played before in Masters games or on Lichess. So I will have to guess as to the mainline. Black's plan is straightforward: bring the a-rook to d8 , start calculating central pawn breaks (namely d5 but even sometimes Nfd7  f5 ), try not to lose the d6 pawn without getting something out of it like a rook on the seventh.} 14. Qe3 {This is probably most logical, getting the queen off the d-file so they can take on d6 with a bishop without a rook pin to their queen. Also, h3 and f3 resulted in instant death because of that queen on d2 ! So White has to waste a tempo and put their queen on an awkward square (note Qf4 wasn't possible as their knight would hang). That said, now they have e-file issues and we can open the rook a little more with Bf8 (our knight wasn't going there anyway. If our bishop goes back now, it can claim it made White put the queen on an awkward square and be happy.} Bf8 15. f3 {White has unpinned the knight from the Queen's gaze so finally tries to kick the annoying g4 bishop that was stopping rooks from going to d1 . Okay, so my official recommendation is to bring the bishop back here. It's just the practical choice and pretty good, backed by a GM game where a similar idea was employed and containing some poison that's easy to remember. But I can't resist putting down an even better alternative that is truly magical: just leaving the bishop there, which is not just trickery, it's the best move! I would recommend it as my main move if this course was catered to titled players who wanted to burn the midnight oil studying. But let's be reasonable for a second: this position has NEVER occurred and when you do play Bg4 for the first time ever, there's no guarantee your befuddled opponent will play Qe3  f3 . So it seems like a lot of memorization work when Bd7 works without the brain fatigue. For those who demand the best of the best, I give Rad8 as an incredibly cool alternative and the best line here.} Rad8 {This alternative line is just shocking. This is all new stuff. The bishop just stays there like it doesn't even care about pawn threats. White has to unwind in a weird way. The general rule is when they take it, take back with the e knight and play d5 to open the d-file against the d4 knight. Just enjoy the fireworks as the Magical Pawn Defying Bishop Variation is truly a beautiful sight.} 16. Qf2 h6 {The computer recommends retreating the bishop to c8 and going for the central pawn breaks, but although that may be good, we are in no rush. This move is evaluated just as high and in the spirit of the Magical Pawn Defying Bishop Variation.} 17. fxg4 {There's nothing left to do but take the thing! Otherwise Bd7 or Bc8 with a normal position when Black feels like it. h3 incidentally loses. This leads to a long line that ends in a fantastic bind against White.} Nexg4 18. Qd2 d5 19. Bxf8 dxe4 {A powerful intermezzo move: Black's threat of taking the knight with their rook is so powerful that White must respond and doesn't have time to rescue their bishop. After all, Ba3 Rxd4 will set up an attack on the White queen and a potential discovered attack on the a7 - g1 diagonal.} 20. Nce2 Kxf8 21. Qc3 c5 22. Nb5 ({White is up the piece still but the e-pawn is terrifying and the White pieces are tripping over each other. It's important for White to meet c4+ with Nd4 or else White will get mated. For example,} 22. Kh1 $4 Nf2+ 23. Kg1 Nh3+ 24. Kh1 {Qg1+} Ng1 {Nf2 .}) ({This comes up with the move} 22. Nf5 {as well because after} Re5 {, White can't move the knight anywhere useful because of c4 as a threat and White won't be able to block the diagonal.}) 22... e3 {This is a key move and unintuitive. Black blocks the c4 threats, accepting White is ready for Nd4 in response. The new plan involves attacking the dark squares with the queens and knights, eventually planting a knight on f2 to stop White from playing with any rooks at all and trying to checkmate White. In addition to guarding the dark squares, e3 clears up a space for Ne4 , an important way of increasing the pressure. Black's pawn asks loudly 'Guess who's coming to dinner?' to the White army. I'll play a few more moves to show you. Ensuring play on the dark squares and giving the f6 knight a path into the White position.} 23. h3 {This will be my 'White doesn't play perfectly' line to show you how Black proceeds. The key move is Ne4 in almost all variations. I have marked the last move as the end of the study-able line as we're now in unexplored territory.} Ne4 24. Qb2 Qg6 {This line should illustrate how powerful the knights are, especially when White doesn't clear e1 for the queen. Black will simply play the queen to the h file and play Nf2 to threaten mate on h1 , using a rook lift for any finishing touches.} 25. hxg4 Qxg4 26. Red1 Rxd1 27. Rxd1 Qh4 28. Nbc3 Nf2 {And it's going to be over for White soon as mate is coming and White needs to go into sacrifice all my pieces to stop it mode (even then, this is mate in twelve for those who like a puzzle challenge).} *

