les for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. b3 {White Goal 3: b3  Bb2 aims to target e5 , and Ba3 aims to target d6 , so let's remove the e5 target. Also, against xd4 the bishop often belongs on f4 but now b3 will just look weird.} exd4 10. Nxd4 {Black has many ways to proceed here, but I like....} Ne5 {Black gains a valuable tempo on the c4 bishop and pre-emptively stops Bf4 ideas by blocking the diagonal.} 11. Bf1 {The best square so that the e1 rook can still help defend Black's sudden e4 attack.} Re8 12. Ba3 {The most played move. White eyes d5 . If you don't play this, why play b3 ?} Qb6 {It's important to clear the d file for rooks. Sometimes when White takes d6 , Black will have enough compensation because they will be able to attack whatever took it with Rd8 and pin it to the enemy queen or if the enemy queen took it, play rook to the seventh to counter and win back the material. Notice how well Qb6 fits in with this as the queen spies f2 when the knight moves and if you get a rook on the seventh, that queen spy will come in handy.} 13. Qd2 {I am following Weiqi Zhou vs. Yangyi Yu (2603 vs. 2760). Yu won the game and provided a roadmap on how to play these positions. That said, they played Bd7 here and I am proposing an interesting novelty that also contains a trap that should be sure to snare an expert or two.} Bg4 {The idea is to stop White from putting a rook on the d-file. At first, this move looks suspect. e6 was out of the question because of our rule 'Don't put a bishop on e6 if it can be eaten by a knight' but d7 looks easier. After all, it looks like White can just play h3 (a useful move) and if Bd7 , Black reached an inferior version of Bd7 right away (because h3 was helpful). And if Bh4 then Nf5 and we can't take the knight! This has never been played before in Masters games or on Lichess. So I will have to guess as to the mainline. Black's plan is straightforward: bring the a-rook to d8 , start calculating central pawn breaks (namely d5 but even sometimes Nfd7  f5 ), try not to lose the d6 pawn without getting something out of it like a rook on the seventh.} 14. Qe3 {This is probably most logical, getting the queen off the d-file so they can take on d6 with a bishop without a rook pin to their queen. Also, h3 and f3 resulted in instant death because of that queen on d2 ! So White has to waste a tempo and put their queen on an awkward square (note Qf4 wasn't possible as their knight would hang). That said, now they have e-file issues and we can open the rook a little more with Bf8 (our knight wasn't going there anyway. If our bishop goes back now, it can claim it made White put the queen on an awkward square and be happy.} Bf8 15. f3 {White has unpinned the knight from the Queen's gaze so finally tries to kick the annoying g4 bishop that was stopping rooks from going to d1 . Okay, so my official recommendation is to bring the bishop back here. It's just the practical choice and pretty good, backed by a GM game where a similar idea was employed and containing some poison that's easy to remember. But I can't resist putting down an even better alternative that is truly magical: just leaving the bishop there, which is not just trickery, it's the best move! I would recommend it as my main move if this course was catered to titled players who wanted to burn the midnight oil studying. But let's be reasonable for a second: this position has NEVER occurred and when you do play Bg4 for the first time ever, there's no guarantee your befuddled opponent will play Qe3  f3 . So it seems like a lot of memorization work when Bd7 works without the brain fatigue. For those who demand the best of the best, I give Rad8 as an incredibly cool alternative and the best line here.} Rad8 {This alternative line is just shocking. This is all new stuff. The bishop just stays there like it doesn't even care about pawn threats. White has to unwind in a weird way. The general rule is when they take it, take back with the e knight and play d5 to open the d-file against the d4 knight. Just enjoy the fireworks as the Magical Pawn Defying Bishop Variation is truly a beautiful sight.} 16. Qf2 h6 {The computer recommends retreating the bishop to c8 and going for the central pawn breaks, but although that may be good, we are in no rush. This move is evaluated just as high and in the spirit of the Magical Pawn Defying Bishop Variation.} 17. fxg4 {There's nothing left to do but take the thing! Otherwise Bd7 or Bc8 with a normal position when Black feels like it. h3 incidentally loses. This leads to a long line that ends in a fantastic bind against White.} Nexg4 18. Qd2 d5 19. Bxf8 dxe4 {A powerful intermezzo move: RxN is so powerful that White must respond and doesn't have time to rescue their bishop. After all, RxN will set up an attack on the White queen and a potential discovered attack on the a7 - g1 diagonal.} 20. Nce2 Kxf8 21. Qc3 c5 22. Nb5 {White is up the piece still but the e-pawn is terrifying and the White pieces are tripping over each other. It's important to meet c4 + with Nd4 or else White will get mated. For example, c4 + Kh1 ?? Nf2 + Kg1  Nh3 + Kh1  Qg1 ++. This comes up with Nf5 because after Re5 , White can't move the knight anywhere useful because of c4 as a threat.} e3 {This is a key move and unintuitive. Black blocks the c4 threats, accepting White is ready for Nd4 in response. The new plan involves attacking the dark squares with the queens and knights, eventually planting a knight on f2 to stop White from playing with any rooks at all and trying to checkmate White. In addition to guarding the dark squares, e3 clears up a space for Ne4 , an important way of increasing the pressure. Black's pawn asks loudly 'Guess who's coming to dinner?' to the White army. I'll play a few more moves to show you. Ensuring play on the dark squares and giving the f6 knight a path into the White position.} 23. Red1 {Best and already White's play isn't easy.} Ne4 24. Qe1 {Let's see how a computer finishes White off here (except I substituted a few White computer moves for what most humans would feel in my opinion--some of them were strange and even with best play, the computer evaluates this as -1.7). Black has many moves here (for example Qf6 is also amazing, eyeing f2 and in some variations h4 - h2 )} Nef2 25. Rxd8 Qxd8 {Rxd8 is also winning. Black's compensation is a positional bind and as such, there's} 26. g3 Qd5 27. Bg2 Qh5 28. h4 Ne5 29. Qf1 Nf3+ 30. Bxf3 Qxf3 31. Kh2 g5 32. Nbc3 gxh4 33. Qg2 Qh5 34. Kg1 hxg3 {And I think I can stop here. White has played the very best defense according to a strong engine and is down about a rook in evaluation. Humans can probably sense the compensation here too: push the pawns, keep the pieces on and watch the white rook struggle to activate. If the g3 pawn ever falls, Re6 - g6 will be brutal.} *

