[White "6) Tension Variation (Master "]
[Black "The d6 Assault Plan (9. b3) 9"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 {This is the so called Hanham variation of the Philidor. White is keeping the tension in the center and quickly developing their pieces. This makes a lot of sense and it was the recommendation in the Grandmaster Repertoire 1. e4 books. Here, White has the exciting g4 or the very normal Bc4 . This chapter is about Bc4 and other normal developing moves. Bg5 is a bad move here as it inspires trading pieces when White has a small space edge so reflects a misunderstanding of the position. Nonetheless, we will look at it and other ideas by White here.} 5. Bc4 Be7 {h6 is the so called Black Lion, which Simon Williams tried to make work and which Alexander Alekhine recommended for Black to play actively. It's a fun idea, but a bit anti-positional (or maybe the nice phrase is 'strategically risky')--it involves a lot of pawn moves in the opening and delayed castling. One thing to note is that whenever you see White play a bishop to c4 and knight to f3 , you must immediately respond Be7 in the Philidor. If you hesitate for an instant (for example, you play g6 ) Ng5 will unleash a carnage that is not child appropriate. Again, for emphasis: We always put the bishop on e7 when we see Nf3 and Bc4 so we can meet Ng5 with castles.} 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 {Sometimes White plays a4 first, but it doesn't change anything. We've reached something of a tabiya. White has made a bunch of reasonable moves that are well suited for whichever pawn structure we get later. They are ready to push d5 if we play something like b6 and make it stronger, they are ready to take on e5 if they find a way to put pressure there, and they are ready to allow us to take if we so choose. A waiting game has commenced. Just so you are aware, here are the waiting moves that usually will not hurt and will often help Black in the usual order I recommend them: c6 , a5 , Re8 , h6 , Qc7 , Nf8 - Ng6 - potentially f4 So we have essentially things to improve when we don't know what to do. There are of course other plans for Black. For people wanting another plan involving self-study, a6 can be played here. There will already be alternatives within the c6 line and covering a6 as well as c6 would be a bit too much for this course.} c6 {This move ( c6 ) has been played by Radjabov, Firouzja, Beliavsky, Azmaiparashvili, Ivanchuk, Svidler, Morozevich, etc. etc. etc. It's a Who's Who of Super Grandmasters. Why is it so popular? Well, the idea is to activate the queen (usually to c7 ). Once the queen is on c7 , e5 will be defended so the knight on d7 can frolic as knights are wont to do. That's one idea. The second is to stop Nd5 . Especially if White opts for a dxe5 line, this is useful. A third idea is to play b5 and expand on the queenside. This comes with tempo. I've seen countless games where my students won a pawn with b5  Bb3  b4  Ne2  Nxe4 . It's amazing how you forget e4 is hanging! Even if there was no pawn win: b5  Bb7  a6  c5 is a natural plan for Black. White's next move is pretty important in stopping this.} 8. a4 a5 (8... Qc7 {is more popular and h6 was recommended by GM Cuenca in his Lifetime Philidor course here on Chessable. but} 9. a5 {has among the best win rates here and leads to less variance in structure. A high practical win rate and easier to remember than leading alternatives? Sounds like our repertoire! The point of the a-pawn move is to stop White from playing a5 themselves and enacting a python-like squeeze. I've personally been suffocated when White gets that plan off and I want to avoid it without having to memorize 42 variations on prevention and reaction. a5 flatly stops White from controlling the queenside and also helps the Black knight occupy c5 without a b-pawn boop later in the game. Also, for people below Master, it makes the resulting positions more similar so helps a lot with memory. There are downsides, but the simplicity and easiness to play make this a straightforward decision for us. There's two basic principles for this pawn structure:   When we have this pawn structure, we should avoid the move b6 . It may look like it helps get out a bishop but it creates all kinds of unpleasant drama from a structure standpoint. For example, if Black had another move and played b6 here then d5 would immediately force a hole on b5 for White's knight to jump into. So not being able to play b6 means our bishop is going to have to try a little harder than normal to activate. Totally worth stopping White from python squeezing us in my opinion. The move b5 might be playable later--for now, White is preventing that--but one day it could be reasonable. Just play with caution.    The second thing to know is that Black is always looking for ways to play d5 . That could change if White trades in the center but generally, central breaks are hard to achieve but immediately equalizing.      White's plans can be broken down into the following labels:   1. The Battering Ram Plan (d5)   2. The Sacrificial Lamb Plan (Be3 Qd2 )    3. The Slingshot Plan (Ba2 Qe2 - c4 )    4. The Knight f5 Plan (Nh4)    5. The d6 Assault Plan (b3 Ba3 )   They can also do things like have no plan, play Bg5 and dxe5 mindlessly. I won't call those 'plans' but they do come up and they will be covered in the Club Player Tension Variation chapter. Please make sure you read through the informational on each of the five plans before proceeding with memorizing moves.}) 9. dxe5 dxe5 {White will often take the pawn at some point. This is almost never a problem for us. We can now play Nc5 without having to give up the center! Woohoo! So just play Qc7 and play Nc5 and enjoy moves like Be6 without having to fear d5 . I'll illustrate one line to show you that if White commits to this before playing b3 (which allowed exd4 ) then they run into all kinds of pragmatic problems from normal Black moves.} 10. b3 {This is usually a player that has seen GM's play b3 but didn't fully understand why. So they are thinking the goal is to fianchetto.} Qc7 {Guarding e5 to play Nc5 or Nb6 if the bishop can't run.} 11. Bb2 Bb4 {Might as well pin the knight and just annoy them.} 12. Re3 Bc5 13. Rd3 {It looks like White has made progress but....} Nb6 {Actually they're just tumbled up in a knot. The bishop can't run away and there's nowhere to go on the d-file because our queen left it long ago. Black is winning here with the bishop pair coming.} *

