1. e4 {Nbd7 against d5 is a strong alternative because probably your opponent will play Nf3 when you are in the 4. Nf3 variation after c6 . I call it Lazy because you're basically wanting to halve your work by playing something and hoping for a transposition instead of the objectively stronger move. But I'm with you: this is uncommon anyway so I can see wanting to lower the memorization. The only strong popular alternative in Club Player games is Bg5 . But you can memorize this chapter instead of the forcing c6 move if you want.} d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. d5 Nbd7 {I can't think of any great move against this except Nf3 which just transposes and makes the prep simple. That said, c6 gives White more opportunities to fall on their face and given that d5 is so popular at the Club Player level, it's worth doing the extra homework to really succeed here. So I give c6 as my main recommendation, Nbd7 for the exceptionally busy.} *

