1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. d5 {I am of mixed opinion in terms of what to recommend here for Black. On the one hand, c6 just equalizes pretty easily. If you've read the Master Mainlines, you know that the position is a very good variation for Black of the Battering Ram Plan. On the other hand, Be7 wins more in actual practice, with the idea of either playing c6 later or playing the f5 kingside attack idea. For now, for those wanting a simpler repertoire, I advise Nbd7 and decide next move. Why? Because after Nf3 , we transpose to Nf3  Nbd7  d5 , where I already have both a c6 and f5 alternative plan. This will reduce your memorization. But for those who want the absolute best, c6 has to win out and is the official recommendation.} c6 {The c6 move is very good as White can't hold d5 very easily this early on. That said, Nbd7 , even though it's listed as an alternative, seems just as good as this move so it's really a 'you choose' option. Nbd7 is a bit less memorization so for those encountering this line rarely, it may be a good choice.  c6 feels best objectively though for those encountering this line often.} 5. Bg5 Nbd7 {Again, c6 and Nbd7 also lead to the same types of positions. I'm listing this as a variation for both and just showing how we can also get here with c6 first. White has combined d5 and Bg5 and the big issue will be after h6 , the bishop will be confined to a tiny diagonal and not helpful towards participating in the center fight.} 6. Nf3 h6 {Correct is probably Bxf6 here giving up the bishop pair for a sake of some light-square pressure and time. However, most Club Players respond to h6 incorrectly with...} 7. Bh4 {The issue for White in these positions is the bishop is too removed from the central action. If it arrives on g3 , it will see a pawn chain staring at it and immobilizing it. In other positions, White could try to play d4 to batter at Black's pawn chain but as has often been said 'pawns do not move back' and d4 is no longer an option due to White's early push.} cxd5 {And for tactical reasons, White is in trouble. The issue is that when the knight takes, the e4 pawn hangs after g5 .} 8. exd5 Be7 {This move gives Black an advantage as well and is a bit easier to remember as we play it so often.} 9. Bb5 a6 10. Ba4 {The main move by White but now we take the space....} b5 11. Bb3 g5 {And now to the other bishop!} 12. Bg3 Nc5 {Black's pieces have great squares and Black has a queenside and kingside advantage. White is squished and their bishops can barely move. Next up is Bg4 or b4 . Eventually we will take White's b3 bishop with out knight and attack d5 and down the open c-file. The engine has Black up by about 2.5 points.} *

