st objectively though for those encountering this line often.} 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. Nf3 h6 {Correct is probably Bxf6 here giving up the bishop pair for a sake of some light-square pressure and time. However, most Club Players respond to h6 incorrectly with...} 7. Bh4 {The issue for White in these positions is the bishop is too removed from the central action.} cxd5 {And for tactical reasons, White is in trouble. The issue is that when the knight takes, the e4 pawn hangs after g5 .} 8. Nxd5 g5 9. Bg3 Nxe4 {Black stands better. The only remaining challenge is how to move out your dark-squared bishop ( g7 leaves d6 weak and e7 allows White to take it) . So we will play a6  b5 and attack the d5 knight to dislodge it before continuing. Black has an edge.} *

