1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. d5 {I am of mixed opinion in terms of what to recommend here for Black. On the one hand, c6 just equalizes pretty easily. If you've read the Master Mainlines, you know that the position is a very good variation for Black of the Battering Ram Plan. On the other hand, Be7 wins more in actual practice, with the idea of either playing c6 later or playing the f5 kingside attack idea. For now, for those wanting a simpler repertoire, I advise Nbd7 and decide next move. Why? Because after Nf3 , we transpose to Nf3  Nbd7  d5 , where I already have both a c6 and f5 alternative plan. This will reduce your memorization. But for those who want the absolute best, c6 has to win out and is the official recommendation.} c6 {The c6 move is very good as White can't hold d5 very easily this early on. That said, Nbd7 , even though it's listed as an alternative, seems just as good as this move so it's really a 'you choose' option. Nbd7 is a bit less memorization so for those encountering this line rarely, it may be a good choice.  c6 feels best objectively though for those encountering this line often.} 5. Nf3 Nbd7 {Transposes to the 4. Nf3  Nbd7  d5 line . Playing d5 first before Nf3 doesn't change anything against our setup.} *

