1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 ({A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess) is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592, 500 play dxe5 , 186,223 play Nf3 , 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {, and 33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. d5 {Black has two great options here: 1. c6 , transposing to the Battering Ram Plan where White can't hold it together and 2. Be7 going for a kingside pawn storm. Objectively speaking, c6 is better in this specific position (and indeed it wins 53% of the time) but the kingside plan wins even more at 55%, probably because even though it's not as high on the evaluation, it's easy to find the moves (and fun!). I give both: you choose! For the sake of reducing your study, c6 will be the mainline.} c6 6. dxc6 {Some White players will just take.} bxc6 {It's hard to go on concretely because White has so many moves: Be3  Bg5  Be2  Bd3  Bc4  g3  h3  b3 . And all of them are slightly worse for White. So rather than memorizing a specific retort against so many moves and have things spiral out of control quickly, let me just say that the way to play such positions are to understand them. Why is Black doing fine here? Well, because of a few reasons:  1. The Nc3 has no advancing squares.   2. The b-file makes developing White's dark-squared bishop difficult.  3. Black's moves are easy to play.   This doesn't mean Black's necessarily better, as Black has some issues too (backwards d-pawn for example) but I would prefer to take Black here any day. I'll give you White's probably best move to show you what will inevitably happen (lots of moves by both sides can be played and the one who gains an edge is the one who understands the position) , and more to show you one possible sequence that will resemble others. Most Club Players prefer Bg5 here as White.} 7. Bc4 {This move is logical, trying to stop d5 and threatening a possible Ng5 jump as usual.} Be7 {We prepare to castle so that Ng5 O-O Nxf7 Rxf7 Bxf7 Kxf7 and we will happily trade our rook and pawn for the knight and bishop if White goes for that! The trade is almost always better for Black.} 8. O-O h6 {Stopping Ng5 and Bg5 . Next we castle.} 9. Re1 O-O 10. h3 Nc5 {Black has played very normal moves and the computer gives them a -0.42 advantage.  Be6 may come next. It's still hard for White to improve their position or get out their bishop without having a b2 assault.} *

