1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. d5 {Black has two great options here: 1. c6 , transposing to the Battering Ram Plan where White can't hold it together and 2. Be7 going for a kingside pawn storm. Objectively speaking, c6 is better in this specific position (and indeed it wins 53% of the time) but the kingside plan wins even more at 55%, probably because even though it's not as high on the evaluation, it's easy to find the moves (and fun!). I give both: you choose! For the sake of reducing your study, c6 will be the mainline.} c6 {This move is just plain logical. White just doesn't have enough pieces defending the d5 square. Again, the rule is we take on d5 as long as White has to recapture with a pawn or give up their light-squared bishop.} 6. Bc4 {White's move is logical: try to guard d5 so that a piece can retake. But there's often the following tactic...} Nb6 {This is thematic. You can play it against Bc4 guarding the d5 pawn in all kinds of scenarios.} 7. Bb3 cxd5 {And we take because White will have to recapture with a pawn or give up their light-squared bishop.} 8. Nxd5 {Against any pawn retake, we will have f5 as our long term plan with monster pawns in the center. So White fights. Don't take the e4 pawn here, that gets scary fast with the open position and us behind on development. Instead play...} Nbxd5 {Why the b-knight? Well it would be less useful in a position where they took back with a pawn. White shouldn't give away the bishop pair for free and so should play...} 9. exd5 Be7 {We have normal development and will castle before playing in the center.} 10. O-O O-O 11. c4 {White tries to undermine Black with a clever idea of c5 and Nxe5 . The other option was wait around for us to play for f5 and a center attack.} Bg4 {Let's just put that knight on hold for a second. Now e4 is threatened.} 12. h3 Bh5 13. g4 (13. Be3 {was the only game White won here--in speed chess--but} e4 {just wins against it so not much studying is involved. Therefore, let's see what happens after the computer's favorite move here, and not assume our opponent will blunder.}) 13... Bg6 {Black has a pretty good edge in the resulting position with easy kingside play after f5 and good pieces.} *

