1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. d5 {Black has two great options here: c6 , transposing to the Battering Ram Plan where White can't hold it together and Be7 going for a kingside pawn storm. Objectively speaking, c6 is better in this specific position (and indeed it wins 53% of the time) but the kingside plan wins even more at 55%, probably because even though it's not as high on the evaluation, it's easy to find the moves (and fun!). I give both: you choose! For the sake of reducing your study, c6 will be the mainline.} Be7 6. Bd3 O-O {It seems ridiculous to have an alternative to an alternative but I want to say that if you are in love with the f5 pawn storm, it's almost always a viable option against these early pushes if you haven't moved your c-pawn yet. As I will illustrate against a move, Bd3 , that's main purpose is to stop f5 --and in vain.} 7. O-O Ne8 8. h3 {Here, with the bishop eyeing f5 indirectly, reinforcements need to be called in. All White's moves will be the most popular one according to Lichess.} g6 9. Bh6 Ng7 10. Qd2 f5 11. exf5 gxf5 {The computer gives this as equal, but I find Black much easier to play here. The e6 hole is open to a knight, so most White players play...} 12. Ng5 {Setting up an evil threat of Bxg7 and then Ne6 forking everything. But it's easy to stop.} Nf6 {Now White's best move is g4 but that's a hard move to play. f4  e4 is their second best option with a very interesting equal game ahead of us. Any other move than those hard to play moves is an edge for Black with those two powerful center pawns staring at White. So practically, if White plays a hard to find move, they will be equal. Good for us.} *

