1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. d5 {Black has two great options here: 1. c6 , transposing to the Battering Ram Plan where White can't hold it together and 2. Be7 going for a kingside pawn storm. Objectively speaking, c6 is better in this specific position (and indeed it wins 53% of the time) but the kingside plan wins even more at 55%, probably because even though it's not as high on the evaluation, it's easy to find the moves (and fun!). I give both: you choose! For the sake of reducing your study, c6 will be the mainline.} Be7 6. Bd3 {A popular move and I have no idea why. I guess the bishop really had no great squares anyway.  Bd3 is great against f5 but does nothing against c6 and in fact, blocks the White queen's gaze and defense of the pawn. Of course, the f5 plan is STILL good. So I will give the f5 plan as an alternative to the alternative to drive in the point that you can play almost anything against these random moves and as long as things makes sense, you will be fine. So...} c6 ({Bc4} 6... Nb6 {Bb3 cxd5 exd5 will lead us to eventually play f5 and get two connected monster pawns in the center for us to steamroll White with. Bc4 Nb6 Bb3 cxd5 Nxd5 Nfxd5 Bxd5 Nxd5 Qxd5 is a way of preserving a hole on d5 . But at what cost? White has lost the bishop pair and pretty much every piece that could occupy d5 . Black will play Be6 later and have total control over d5 , playing d5 themselves at their leisure.}) 7. dxc6 {Because of the threat of cxd5 and making White recapture with the pawn, White really only had two choices: take on c6 or play Bc4 . The note to my last move shows why White couldn't play Bc4 .} bxc6 8. O-O O-O {The diagram shows some piece options. Eventually we will play d5 but remember to protect e5 as after we move our d6 pawn, it won't be protecting e5 anymore and I've seen some players drop the e-pawn while only calculating whether they were losing the d-pawn! We can protect e5 by playing Re8 and Bf8 or just Qc7 . We can also protect it with our knight providing White doesn't have a rook on e1 waiting to discover attack it. But sometimes we want the knight on d7 to go to c5 and dream big.} 9. h3 {The most common Club Player move in this position. The idea is to not fall into back-rank checkmates. I would also say it's to stop Ng4 so White can play Be3 but for some reason White players in this rating range put the bishop on g5 anyway. Black is already slightly better with more center pawns, active pieces and an open b-file.} Qc7 {Guarding e5 through an x-ray so we can later play d5 and also vacating the d8 square in case a rook wants it later.} 10. Bg5 {This seems like a mistake but it's also the leading move played in this position. Since this section is all about what you are most likely to face, I'm pleased to say you will most likely face a mistake. Why is it a mistake? A few reasons.   First, it doesn't threaten anything.  Be3 would have at least kept Qb6 at bay, but Bxf6 would just be an error as Black would take the bishop pair in a position about to be wide open. If you've never won using a bishop pair advantage and you are insecure about your ability to do so, let me reassure you. You don't need to do anything but keep it around. The bishop pair advantage is nice because if you're losing, you can trade a bishop for a knight and enter an opposite color bishop ending, which are known to be drawish. And it's unlikely you will be losing because the bishops scythe across the board and immobilize the opponent. It's not what you do with them, it is what your opponent cannot do because you have them blocking all these key squares. For example, say Black played a move I'm not recommending but is still fine and played...} {h6 Bxf6 Bxf6 . Taking back with the knight may even be better but I want to illustrate a point: Where could White's knights move in this position? Practically nowhere? That's because of the bishop pair. Look how they totally immobilize the enemy army and make your pieces feel alive. Eventually Black plays d5 in the Philidor so it's only a matter of time before these positions open up for those bishops.} Rb8 {Lots of moves were good but attacking the b2 pawn that the bishop left behind when departing to g5 immediately reveals the advantage of the b-file and how hard it is to develop with White. According to the computer, Black is already up a pawn.} 11. b3 {Rb1 was probably better but according to my database b3 is the preferred move of players. Why is Rb1 better? Because pawn moves always carry a cost in a way that rook moves often don't. Unlike a rook, a pawn cannot move back. So the pawn to b3 weakens c3 and a3 because those will never be defendable by a pawn ever again. EVER AGAIN. Therefore, Black can act like a frog and hop on in, up close and personal. Of course, it might be handy to have a bishop on the dark squares to invade those places, and we should let it come and play!} d5 12. exd5 cxd5 {Black's center is very strong. Here, according to my database, a non-professional player decided to randomly part with the bishop pair and played...} 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 {That c3 weakness is already feeling a bit drafty: just ask the c3 knight being eyed by the queen.  e4 is also threatened and Black has the two bishops and a monster center. White has misplayed the opening.} ({Play might continue Nb5} 13... Qc5 14. Nxe5 Rb5 {with a big advantage for Black.}) *

