1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. dxe5 {This is a pawn trade that White probably shouldn't make as this is the queenless middlegame structure with the queens still on. Although Black was doing really well in the queen trade line, in this one Black has virtually nothing that would warrant having an advantage.} dxe5 {Black has really easy play just putting their pieces where the arrows point. In practice, White is losing the vast majority of their games as a result.} 6. Bc4 {Again, Black has many options but probably most convincing is...} Bb4 {We could always choose to not punish the early pawn trade. After all, c6 would be a great way to transpose to other lines and simplify our prep. However, we can't count on them not playing a4 and we can really test them here. With the king still on e1 , the knight can be pinned. The threat is Bxc3 and Nxe4 . This wasn't possible before the pawn trade because d6 blocked our bishop. White should have castled before doing this. Now technically, the position is around equal according to an engine, but in practice Black has a huge plus score here as it's very hard for White to navigate this chaos.} 7. O-O {White is hoping to get a counterattack with Re1 after Bxc3 and Nxe4 , taking advantage of the fact that our king is still in the center. But we don't allow it and just castle.} O-O 8. Bg5 {This isn't the best move but the most common way at Club level. Other moves can just be handled with trying to double White's pawns and play c6  Qc7  a5 etc.} Bxc3 9. bxc3 h6 10. Bh4 Qe7 {Now that the White dark-squared bishop is occupying the queenside diagonals, it's time to relocate the queen to attack. Normally Nc5 is great in the Philidor and it's still good here, but occupying the square in front of doubled pawns is a positional way to exploit them. As such, we should consider ideas of Nb6 - c4 later. Black has a great game and already has a nice edge.} 11. Re1 Nb6 {With the doubled pawns, Black wants to try to control c4 and the squares ahead of the pawns. This move attacks the bishop and works towards c4 control.} 12. Bb3 a5 {This move is free as the threat of a4 demands White waste their turn moving a pawn to stop us.} 13. a4 Bg4 {And White just looks worse to me with those hideous pawns. They do have the bishop pair so the computer hovers around -0.2 and -0.5. Black has won 66% of games in this position. Next they will consider moves like Rfd8 and Nbd7 to guard f6 and free up the queen to attack c3 . We can try Nbd7 to free our queen without having doubled pawns on f6 (most sound) or play to go into c4 later while accepting the pawns weakness depending on circumstances.} *

