1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 {White keeps the tension as mentioned in the Pawns are the Soul of Chess.} Nbd7 {Guarding e5 .} 5. Bc4 {The best diagonal for the bishop and a sign of a good player. Because Ng5 is threatened when White plays this move, we always respond the same way.} Be7 {So we can castle if f7 comes under assault.} 6. O-O {Both sides are playing well so far.} O-O 7. h3 {A useful move where White prevents back rank checkmates later and stops knights from going to g4 . The idea usually is to put a bishop on e3 : that's why you're worried about a knight going to g4 .} c6 8. Bg5 {Bg5 is not great and it doesn't improve in anyway by avoiding a4 .} b5 9. Bb3 a5 {We pretty much play the same thing. There are other strategies for Black against this, but let's keep everything consistent.} 10. a3 Ba6 {Qb6 is also excellent but it's hard to remember when we play Ba6 in so many other lines. So, might as well be consistent and do our usual threat.} 11. Re1 h6 {An important move! Black's last move is a subtle way to block a knight maneuver because if Bh4 then the knight can't go to h4 itself and get to f5 : After all, the one downside to Ba6 is that the idea Nh4 - f5 can't be countered by the bishop swapping it off.} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 {Again, stopping Nh4 . Black is better with the two bishops and more space on the queenside.} *

