1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 {White keeps the tension as mentioned in the Pawns are the Soul of Chess.} Nbd7 {Guarding e5 .} 5. Bc4 {The best diagonal for the bishop and a sign of a good player. Because Ng5 is threatened when White plays this move, we always respond the same way.} Be7 {So we can castle if f7 comes under assault.} 6. O-O O-O {Both sides are playing well so far.} 7. h3 {A useful move where White prevents backrank checkmates later and stops knights from going to g4 . The idea usually is to put a bishop on e3 : that's why you're worried about a knight going to g4 .} c6 8. Bg5 b5 9. Bb3 a5 10. a3 Ba6 11. Re1 h6 12. Bh4 Qc7 {Now that White has blocked Nh4 with Bh4 , we continue just gradually improving our position and holding our queenside space gains. White has more center space and we have more queenside space. The position is technically equal and like many positions of this nature, Black wins more than White in actual games. The issue is that Black's play is straightforward with queenside pressure and lots of interesting pawn breaks to decide between while White has to be careful in the shuffling of pieces. For example, here, White's only move to not be slightly worse is Ba2 , which isn't an intuitive move at all.} *

