1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 {White keeps the tension as mentioned in the Pawns are the Soul of Chess.} Nbd7 {Guarding e5 .} 5. Bc4 {The best diagonal for the bishop and a sign of a good player. Because Ng5 is threatened when White plays this move, we always respond the same way.} Be7 {So we can castle if f7 comes under assault.} 6. O-O O-O {Both sides are playing well so far.} 7. h3 {A useful move where White prevents back rank checkmates later and stops knights from going to g4 . The idea usually is to put a bishop on e3 : that's why you're worried about a knight going to g4 .} c6 8. dxe5 {White can exchange pawns now, later or earlier. It amounts to very little for White most of the time and we should rarely fear it. Maybe they're thinking that in an open position, no pawn storms are coming on the queenside? Well, grab an umbrella, because a storm is still coming.} dxe5 9. Be3 {a4 should still be played.} b5 10. Bd3 {Bd3 is probably the better move to guard the e4 pawn should the knight be kicked. But many players just play Bb3 as a reflex. Somehow they don't believe until b4 comes. Let's look at Bd3 . It's better in that e4 isn't just hanging in half these lines. But White is still very cramped.} a5 {The move a5 has two purposes here. First, it gives a bit more support to b4 either by protecting it or by playing a4 next to take away a knight retreat square. Second, Ba6 will need support from the a8 rook after b4 (otherwise, White will just play Bxa6 ).} 11. a3 {White stops b4 . For now.} Qc7 {As Black here, don't rush. You have more space, so it's just time to make sure you can hold onto all the pawn advancements without allowing a counterstrike. When you have more space, you usually have an advantage in maneuvering battles so if White wants to shuffle pieces in their one-room apartment building, by all means we will oblige. Why Qc7 specifically? We want to overguard e5 so that our knight can go to c5 without it hanging. From c5 , it will attack e4 and threaten White's bishop pair. Also, the d8 square is now clear for Black's rook--most likely the f-rook.} 12. Qe2 {White anticipates the rook staring at their queen across the board from d8 and gets off the file, also clearing the way for their rook to come to d1 .} Nc5 {White will now say goodbye to the bishop pair. Just which bishop is the question for White. Most players here have opted for...} 13. Bxc5 Bxc5 14. Rad1 a4 {The idea of a4 is to block any Na4 moves hitting out bishop after b4 . Also, somewhat trickily it clears the a5 square for our bishop, preparing Bb6  Ba5 and without White's dark-squared bishop, it's awkward to move or defend the c3 knight. But that's just one of many things Black can do to improve their position. Again, we are more than happy to incrementally improve our position and to quote the Disney parrot Iago, 'Squeeze 'em, Jafar! Squuuueeze 'em!'} 15. Rd2 {It's difficult to suggest moves for White but a natural move is to try to double rooks on the d file. In all likelihood, they will instead reach some kind of breaking point and play b3 and just drop the a pawn. But let's pretend they are keeping their cool for now and trying to play risk-free chess.} Nh5 {And White is losing by 1.7. There's just too much queenside space and all of Black's pieces are rocking it. Black can continue slow playing and improving their position, consolidating e5 with f6 after the knight goes to f4 and takes advantage of the missing dark-squared White bishop. Safe play without understanding the core concepts is a recipe for disaster for White in the Philidor.} *

