1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 {White keeps the tension as mentioned in the Pawns are the Soul of Chess.} Nbd7 {Guarding e5 .} 5. Bc4 {The best diagonal for the bishop and a sign of a good player. Because Ng5 is threatened when White plays this move, we always respond the same way.} Be7 {So we can castle if f7 comes under assault.} 6. O-O O-O {Both sides are playing well so far.} 7. h3 {A useful move where White prevents back rank checkmates later and stops knights from going to g4 . The idea usually is to put a bishop on e3 : that's why you're worried about a knight going to g4 .} c6 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Be3 b5 10. Bb3 {And we refute Bb3 as per usual with a boopity boo to the knight c3 and goobledeegoo to the pawn on e4 . I will demonstrate the most precise way to go ahead now.} a5 (10... b4 {is solid and does win the pawn. The issue is that White is better developed here and if they play actively, they probably have just enough, but not more, compensation for the dropped pawn. However, there's no rush as Black can make several threats in a row that need immediate attention and so don't allow White a chance to defend e4 . For example, a5 is completely free because the threat is a4 winning the bishop and as a result, White doesn't have time to defend e4 .}) 11. a4 {This is one of two ways of blocking Black from trapping the bishop. But now...} b4 {And White has to not only retreat the knight but retreat it to a passive square because they have put a pawn on a4 .} 12. Nb1 Nxe4 {Ba6 first is also excellent, but now perhaps it's time to just opt for something simple and eat the pawn. With the knight on b1 , White can't claim a development edge for the pawn and so is simply losing. We will consolidate the usual way we do after taking on e4 , by retreating the knight to d6 , over-guarding e5 because it's now on an open file and putting our pieces on good squares.} *

