1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 {White keeps the tension as mentioned in the Pawns are the Soul of Chess.} Nbd7 {Guarding e5 .} 5. Bc4 {The best diagonal for the bishop and a sign of a good player. Because Ng5 is threatened when White plays this move, we always respond the same way.} Be7 {So we can castle if f7 comes under assault.} 6. O-O O-O {Both sides are playing well so far.} 7. h3 {A useful move where White prevents backrank checkmates later and stops knights from going to g4 . The idea usually is to put a bishop on e3 : that's why you're worried about a knight going to g4 .} c6 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Be3 {a4 should still be played.} b5 10. Bb3 {Bd3 is probably the better move to guard the e4 pawn should the knight be kicked. But many players just play Bb3 as a reflex. Somehow they don't believe until b4 comes. Let's look at Bd3 . It's better in that e4 isn't just hanging in half these lines. But White is still very cramped.} a5 {The move a5 has two purposes here. First, it gives a bit more support to b4 either by protecting it or by playing a4 next to take away a knight retreat square. Second, Ba6 will need support from the a8 rook after b4 (otherwise, White will just play Bxa6 ).} 11. a3 {Unlike a4 , a3 actually does stop b4 --well, temporarily--and saves the e4 pawn with best play.} {Now b4 axb4 axb4 Rxa8 would be a sad way to lose. Luckily, White still won't have time to guard e4 in this position.} Ba6 {Black threatens b4 , attacking knight and rook at the same time. Now b4 works because our rook isn't hanging after we trade pawns on b4 .} 12. Re1 b4 13. axb4 axb4 14. Na4 {Na4 is a very active move and is ready for the counterattack after Nxe4 . Unfortunately for us, White has played well. We have to be a bit careful whenever White chooses the most accurate square for the knight against b4 . 14. Nb1 would have allowed a simpler 14... Nxe4 in response.} ({But now taking the pawn will set up some tricks for White: Nxe4 Nb6 Nxb6} 14. Bb6 Qxb6 {Rxe4 and Black can't defend the double attack on e5 -- f6 is illegal because of the bishop on b3 . Yes, you can risk these pawn grabs with Black and sometimes do okay, but hope chess doesn't really deserve being a main recommendation on Chessable, especially since against normal Club Player play, we should still achieve a very nice edge.}) 14... c5 {Rather than being greedy, Black decides to not give up their space and initiative gains for the sake of a pawn. They block off b6 control and threaten c4 , imprisoning the light squared bishop and making the knight on a4 very shaky and fragile. White's best move here will be hard for your opponent to play and they may even let you play c4 instead which is totally crushing.} 15. Bd5 {Giving Black a beautiful bishop so that c4 doesn't wreck them. We should not decline the gift.} Nxd5 16. exd5 Bd6 {Blockading the white pawn.} 17. Qd2 {A sensible move for White who doesn't know what to do and decides to clear files for rooks.} h6 ({Here, the computer recommends White sacrifice the bishop and predicts the best play for both sides will go as follows: Bxh6} 17... Bb5 18. Bg5 f6 19. b3 fxg5 20. Nxg5 Bxa4 21. bxa4 Rf5 {giving a -2 assessment--Black is essentially just up a piece for a pawn. You know it's bad when the computer thinks an unsound sacrifice that just drops a bishop for a pawn without enough compensation is better than the alternatives. If White doesn't like that, f5  c4 and other pawn pushes will allow Black to dominate both sides of the board.}) *

