1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 {Now we can castle on Ng5 so we will be quite safe.} 6. O-O O-O 7. h3 c6 8. Be3 {Club players tend to not always understand the subtleties of c6 and will often allow the b5 harassment. And if it's an open invitation...} b5 9. Bb3 {Bd3 is probably better but Bb3 is more often played. It's hard to optically believe the e4 pawn is dropping. Until it does.} b4 10. dxe5 ({'That which doesn't kill me... delays the inevitable.' Or} 10. Ne2 Nxe4 {right away.}) 10... dxe5 11. Ne2 Nxe4 {It's not over yet as White has some mild compensation (maybe half a pawn worth?) with better developed pieces and open files... but Black is clearly winning according to the computer and just a human look at the position. Black will consolidate by retreating the knight and deploying the bishop on the long diagonal.} *

