1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. h3 c6 8. a4 {Sometimes White knows enough to block b5 .} a5 9. Bg5 {Bg5 after a4  a5 is its own thing as we don't just do our usual b5  a5  Ba6 strategy. The problem with this move positionally is that the bishop does a lot on its original diagonal in terms of being able to attack c5 and b6 , useful squares for Black to have.} h6 {We invite White to retire from the strong diagonal.} 10. Bh4 {Now the bishop is confined to a two-square option and c5 and b6 can no longer be guarded. Let's take advantage of that, shall we?} Qb6 {The idea of this move is to punish the bishop for not being on the diagonal to stop us. So it reminds me a lot of the d6 Assault Plan except there's no d6 assault. So it's just the ________ Plan.} 11. Bb3 {b3 is recommended by my Stockfish engine instead but it looks so suspect without a dark-squared bishop over there. Now we just make a bunch of natural moves. Bg5 isn't such a mistake that we will be better, but it does throw away the edge and makes our play easy.} Re8 12. Re1 {Now we can take on d4 .} exd4 13. Nxd4 Nc5 ({There is a temptation sometimes to play} 13... Ne5 {and go for the Bxh3 trick but} 14. f4 {is strong and was always played there. Believe it or not} Bxh3 15. fxe5 Bg4 16. exf6 Bxd1 {is a playable queen sacrifice but I'd rather be the one without the queen there. 13... Nc5 is simple and attacks the b3 bishop.}) 14. Ba2 {Now many moves are possible: Qb4 attacking a4 , Qxb2 for the greedy strategy and just Bd8 to clear the rook (Not Bf8 ? Bxf6 ruining our pawns). This Ba2 move is hard to play as it looks like Qxb2 is good for Black but the open b-file actually presents some headaches for Black. Nevertheless, it's good to plan against the best plan by White. White has stopped the b5 plan and not done anything horrible besides develop their bishop a little poorly. As such, they gain equality. Good for them.} Bd8 (14... Bf8 {is our usual move but we need to keep an eye on f6 while unleashing the rook on e4 . The position is about even and we will continue by trying to neutralize White's strongest piece: the a2 bishop. To do this, we need to plop our knight on e6 . But we could also reroute it to e5 . Black should be fine here with many options moving forward.}) *

