1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 {A club player (rated between 1000 and 2000 on Lichess is way more likely to take than play anything else here. Here's the stats according to the Lichess database when sorted to match most opponents in the pre-Master range: 592,500 play} ({dxe5 186,223 play Nf3 184, 109 play} 3... d5 {33,000 play} 4. Bg5 {. In my dxe5 chapters, I include the most popular Club Player lines which are even more likely than the lines you see in this chapter. Still, if your opponent reflects the Lichess average, you are likely to see the Philidor mainline in approximately 31% of your Philidor games. If I take out blitz variants (so only Rapid, Slow, and Correspondence), dxe5 is still more popular than Nf3 by a rate of 79,000 to 24,000 with d5 hitting 42,000 as the second most popular. Therefore, let's consider d5 the mainline for club players (even though it is a bad move). This ranking holds even if I make the rating range 1400 to 2000.}) 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. h3 c6 8. a4 a5 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 Nh5 {I like this best, but it does have a downside in two senses that make me not recommend it: 1. that the win record for Black is pretty poor 2. it involves some concrete stuff making it a bit harder to play than Qb6 3. Similar positions don't work as well as this specific position does, so there's a change you'll play the same idea in another line. That said, it's a pretty cool move to play for a win and not too complicated--in fact, it would be the move I would play personally. So I give another move against the early bishop pin in Qb6 which is a much faster learn and transposes to a sort of good-for-Black mainline-like position. It also fits our concept-based positional repertoire better. So given the downsides, why do I list it? Because it's not horribly complicated and because unlike Qb6 , if White plays the most common moves, they are actually losing, giving it a practical chance for an opening KO. And if White plays right, it's equal.} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 {The threat is Nf4 and a solid position. Without the dark-squared bishop, we won't be taking on d4 because the d6 pawn will be weak on the open file. But this also delivers a terrific trap that most White players won't resist. Now I don't advocate so called trap or 'hope chess' but we didn't play a trap, there just happens to be one!} 12. Nxe5 {This is how most games have gone.} dxe5 {Seven games reached this position in expert level blitz and rapid games and shockingly Black lost all of them. But I can only blame the poor Black play who probably accidentally stumbled into this position instead of came prepared. This is actually not just equal but CLEARLY better for Black with a few accurate moves.} 13. Qxh5 exd4 14. Ne2 Qxe4 15. Bd3 {This guards the pawn with tempo but relocates the bishop to a worse diagonal.} Qe5 16. Qf3 Nc5 {Black has a clear edge and White is without clear compensation for the pawn. Next up will be trying to gobble up that bishop or, if they move it, to think about Bf5 ideas.} *

