xe7 {The threat is Nf4 and a solid position. Without the dark-squared bishop, we won't be taking on d4 because the d6 pawn will be weak on the open file. But this also delivers a terrific trap that most White players won't resist. Now I don't advocate so called trap or 'hope chess' but we didn't play a trap, there just happens to be one!} 12. Nxe5 {This is how most games have gone.} dxe5 {Seven games reached this position in expert level blitz and rapid games and shockingly Black lost all of them. But I can only blame the poor Black play who probably accidentally stumbled into this position instead of came prepared. This is actually not just equal but CLEARLY better for Black with a few accurate moves.} 13. Qxh5 exd4 14. Ne2 Qxe4 15. Bd3 {This guards the pawn with tempo but relocates the bishop to a worse diagonal.} Qe5 16. Qxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxd4 Nxd3 18. cxd3 Rd8 19. Nf3 Rxd3 20. Rad1 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Be6 {And not only is White down a pawn but Black has the better pawn structure and the a4 pawn is weak to the superior Black minor piece.} *

