xe7 {The threat is Nf4 and a solid position. Without the dark-squared bishop, we won't be taking on d4 because the d6 pawn will be weak on the open file. But this also delivers a terrific trap that most White players won't resist. Now I don't advocate so called trap or 'hope chess' but we didn't play a trap, there just happens to be one!} 12. Nxe5 {This is how most games have gone.} dxe5 {Seven games reached this position in expert level blitz and rapid games and shockingly Black lost all of them. But I can only blame the poor Black play who probably accidentally stumbled into this position instead of came prepared. This is actually not just equal but CLEARLY better for Black with a few accurate moves.} 13. Qxh5 exd4 14. Ne2 Qxe4 15. Ng3 {This was the most popular move, but in all games Black played Qe5 . That still gives Black an edge, but the c2 pawn is hanging and it comes with tempo on the bishop.} Qxc2 {Black at first looks a bit precarious but Nf6 will come with tempo and White has a horrible pawn structure on the queenside so the two pawn Black advantage may even grow. White doesn't have enough to justify everything.} 16. Rac1 Qd2 {Black's queen won't be trapped, it has too many exits.  Qxb2 would be asking for it a bit as that Ng3 is just waiting to jump into the attack. Black need only consolidate to be winning and after Black's queen arrives on f4 , we will be able to guard Nf5 ideas.} 17. Rfd1 Qf4 {Black holds on to the pawn, not trading queens so fast.} *

