1. e4 d6 2. d4 ({Okay, we've all been there. You've put in hours of your time preparing the Philidor and your opponent rolls out something ridiculous like} 2. a3 {or slightly less ridiculous but not optimal like Bc4 here. I get the frustration. In fact, when creating this course, I played the Philidor almost exclusively online and in classical and I entered an abnormal amount of sidelines. You have two choices against all these second-rate moves: 1. Memorize them all    2. Understand the themes and play intuitively against them unless they are dangerous or require different moves than our normal ones.   I strongly believe you should do the second.  Why? Well, usually against sub-optimal moves, you have many paths so you're not in great danger if you just develop your pieces. Second, it's not practical to prepare against everything in a non-forcing position. For example, instead of 2. d4 , White had a number of reasonable but not super great moves. And even if you memorized the engine reply to every single second move deviation, they would have more options on their third move and it would eventually approach gargantuan lines. No master memorizes their way to every deviation; they usually prepare against the scariest and most common and then make it up against the weird stuff based on chess principles. So let's explore this further: [The Three Types of White Deviations and Their Counters] I. The Weird Deviations that We Can Play Principled Against Instead of the queen pawn move, I'd count b3 , g3 , a3 , d3 as fitting within this category. These moves give lots of options for Black based on your preferences. For example, playing the normal Philidor moves on autopilot: Nf6 , Be7 , O-O , Nbd7 , c6 , Re8 , should move you through the opening without a hiccup and almost all White's big tries like pushing the d-pawn up two will merely transpose to our repertoire in terms of pawn structure. Often you'll also have additional options like developing your knight to c6 or playing d5 super fast. When we face weird deviations like these, we should counter by following some basic principles: 1. Develop our knights and dark-squared bishop.  For your own comfort, you may want to develop them according to the Philidor scheme so that if White plays d4 , you reach a position you feel good in, but this is based on your own experience with other schemes. World Champion Rueben Fine's principles of chess are also good general guidance here.   2. Castle.   3. Look for either a central break with d5 or a queenside pawn storm with c6  b5 etc.   If the White player deviates after playing 2. d4 , we should usually follow the 'Pawns are the Soul of Chess Chapter in finding our 'normal' path.    II. The Transposition Deviations These would be moves like Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 , guarding the pawn, e5 d4 will probably move us back into the normal positions of the Philidor. These usually indicate your opponent is either trying to trick you into playing a move you didn't understand or, more likely, that your opponent doesn't know what they're doing. There's usually no way to punish the development of knights and classical play this early but nonetheless, we should view these normal moves as if they will transpose at any minute. Unlike the first type of deviations, these demand that we play something like our Philidor setup so transpositions won't catch us off guard. To reduce study, you can play Philidor moves against Deviations 1 and 2. So, our counter against highly transpositional non-committal moves will be to first, develop according to the normal Philidor scheme and second, look out for any forcing tactics related to your opponent's weird move order, especially a hanging e4 pawn.  Our Philidor scheme will be moves like Nf6  e5  Nbd7  Be7  O-O  c6  Re8 and even a5 . III. The Dangerous or Unique Deviations These lines can expose cruise-control Philidor players and are a bit dangerous. Let me give you an example: Bc4 Nf6 Nf3 e5 Ng5 . Here, on Black's third move, they should have just eaten the completely free e-pawn. But instead, they just rattled out moves without thinking and now f7 is going to be a nightmare to defend. Against most of these cheapos, you can just be careful around the deviation and take adequate pauses along the way. Better White players will play something like Bc4 Nf6 Nc3 e5 Nf3 and on Nbd7 cruise control instead of the correct Be7 play Ng5 . These dangerous lines require a little memorization of the common traps or pawn structures. So, in this chapter, we aren't exploring all deviations but largely this third category of poisonous deviations that we can't play normal moves against or are a bit weird in terms of our plans. Let me divide these setups into these general categories: 1. The biggest trap variation is the one I just mentioned: early Bc4 and Ng5 combos, covered in this chapter under the 'Caveman Attacks.'  You have to know all the blocks there, but the good news is they are easy to block if you have seen it before.   2. The Bc4  d3  f4 structure. This I call the 'King's Gambit Plan,' but it will also appeal to Vienna players. Basically, White just does a Philidor pawn structure themselves and plays with the bishop outside of the chain and the move f4 . Certain players do this against everything: Vienna against e5 , Grand Prix against the Sicilian, etc. The move order may vary here: sometimes they start with Bc4 or Nc3 , sometimes directly with f4 . In this chapter, I give it with f4 first but know that transpositions to it are possible.      3. Less legitimately, White can play a number of bad moves that don't allow us to play our normal setup. Specifically, they can, for example, play the Roscher Gambit which I call less romantically 'Dropping the e4 pawn for little to no compensation.' And they can also play the seemingly aggressive but actually just kind of bad Nf3 early e5 plan.  These you could just make up moves against at the high levels but I provide you a basic optimal plan in case you want to actually claim an edge right out of the opening.   4. The f4 plan combined with d4 . The idea of pawns on d4 , f4 , and e4 is common against the Pirc and so I call this the 'Austrian Attack plan.' It makes some sense. After all, let's face it, we looked like we were playing the Pirc when we played d6 . So this is sometimes entered into by confused White players, but it's not so intuitive to play against. In fact, we kind of find ourselves in a new structure, which is why I dedicate three variations to it and an alternative path that would maximize the counterplay for the ambitious. It is rare in most games, 1-3% depending on rating, but if you capture the wrong pawn, you can end up worse quickly.   5. Bd3 c3 plans.  This idea is actually pretty good though not very forcing. Our moves will be the same largely but our plans slightly different. There are few traps and we can play fairly normal against it, but I cover some of its weirdness here and in the Master Deviations chapter--as Masters play this.  6. g3 fianchetto and d4 space gaining plans.  Again, not super forcing and below 2200, I would say just normal Philidor stuff works. But if you're 2200 Plus, I explore some nuances there in the Master Deviation chapter.    Other: Three deviations I am not covering here include the Shirov Gambit, the f3 stuff and early d5 . The first two get their own chapters as they are played at high level and require a bit of precision against high-level play. Most Club Players can just play intuitively against f3 and according to the Quickstarters against the Shirov Gambit. But thorough players can work through them in the relevant chapters. The big one for Club Players is very early d5 pushes by White, although I hope to show that it will usually just be the f3 variation or the Tension Player Club Player Line in the end anyway. There, you can find more information in the relevant chapter you are transposing to for guidance, and in this chapter, I'll just explain how we get there.}) *

