1. e4 d6 2. f4 ({A weird move. Black is fine playing almost anything here.} 2. e5 {is a King's Gambit (White can't play fxe5 because of Qh4+ so Nf3 exf4 is the mainline Fisher 'refutation' of the King's Gambit. It's ridiculously good for Black--at the end of the line in Ian Nepomniatchi's Long Live the King's Gambit Chessable course he declares White has almost no winning chances and against the only alternative line for White, he declares Black to be better. Still, it seems a bit intense to learn King's Gambit theory all for the sake of this obscure try by White, but if you play the e5 Philidor or know someone plays this who plays the King's Gambit, feel free to go that route.} c5 {is the Grand Prix attack. d5 is a Center Counter where White has played the bad move f4 and you can always play} 3. e6 {to play d5 if you used to be a French player. If you've played any one of those, then you can transpose and move on with your life. I'll keep things tricky and unique.}) 2... Nf6 {Now White should play Nc3 as e5 isn't very good for them.} 3. Nc3 e5 {If Nf3 Black could consider grabbing the pawn with exf4 here for more winning, and more losing, chances. I've recommended a simpler, stabler course though. White taking Black on e5 here is slightly advantageous for Black as they will be able to develop their bishop to d6 or c5 and get very good play with their pieces. So there's no rush. You could also aim for a g6 setup. Against sidelines, usually Black is spoiled for choice.} 4. Nf3 Be7 {Let's stick to the script as much as possible. Black has a tactic to guard the pawn. In the meantime, not blocking the d-file with Nbd7 is preventative as White can't easily play Bc4 without another tactic for Black coming up based on the open d-file.} 5. fxe5 {It looks like Black just dropped a pawn by playing Be7 . But that's not the case.} dxe5 6. Nxe5 Nxe4 {Tactically regaining the material.} 7. Nxe4 Qd4 {With equality as the knight must be returned to Black. With an imbalance in pawns--kingside majority versus queenside majority--there's still a lot to play for! Aggressive players can even aim for O-O-O and a kingside attack!} *

