1. e4 d6 2. f4 ({A weird move. Black is fine playing almost anything here.} 2. e5 {is a King's Gambit (White can't play fxe5 because of Qh4+ so Nf3 exf4 is the mainline Fisher 'refutation' of the King's Gambit. It's ridiculously good for Black--at the end of the line in Ian Nepomniatchi's Long Live the King's Gambit Chessable course he declares White has almost no winning chances and against the only alternative line for White, he declares Black to be better. Still, it seems a bit intense to learn King's Gambit theory all for the sake of this obscure try by White, but if you play the e5 Philidor or know someone plays this who plays the King's Gambit, feel free to go that route.} c5 {is the Grand Prix attack. d5 is a Center Counter where White has played the bad move f4 and you can always play} 3. e6 {to play d5 if you used to be a French player. If you've played any one of those, then you can transpose and move on with your life. I'll keep things tricky and unique.}) 2... Nf6 {Now White should play 3. Nc3 as 3. e5 isn't very good for them.} 3. Nc3 e5 {If Nf3 Black could consider grabbing the pawn with exf4 here for more winning, and more losing, chances. I've recommended a simpler, stabler course though. White taking Black on e5 here is slightly advantageous for Black as they will be able to develop their bishop to d6 or c5 and get very good play with their pieces. So there's no rush. You could also aim for a g6 setup. Against sidelines, usually Black is spoiled for choice.} 4. Nf3 Be7 ({Let's stick to the script as much as possible. Black has a tactic to guard the pawn. In the meantime, not blocking the d-file with} 4... Nbd7 {is preventative as White can't easily play} 5. Bc4 {without another tactic for Black coming up based on the open d-file.}) 5. Bc4 {White is developing well. Luckily, Black can act fast here and take advantage of a downside to Bc4 .} exf4 {We aren't trying to win this pawn but rather setting up a tactic involving d5 . We don't want e5 to hang at the end of our tactic against the 5. Bc4 move.} 6. d4 ({White is so close to recapturing the f-pawn and having a gigantic center. Unfortunately, it's not fast enough. In all of these lines where White doesn't take the center, pushing our d-pawn should be the plan. White could have played the slow and less ambitious} 6. d3 {on this move, or even earlier, trying for some kind of Vienna game reminiscent of Jessie Kraai's recommendations in Chess Dojo's 1. e4 Repertoire for White , but then we'd just play} O-O 7. Bxf4 c6 8. O-O d5 {and we get the same center break in the end... if White doesn't have many pawns in the center, they have trouble clamping down on possibilities like these which equalize and, in fact, hold a tiny edge for Black.}) 6... Nxe4 {And a fork is coming to regain the material. The position is level.} 7. Nxe4 d5 {With equality. White will probably win the d5 pawn and take on f4 , evening out the material. That's why we played 4... Be7 and not 4... Nbd7 , to guard the pawn with our queen here.} *

