{And White's center is breaking apart with all Black's pieces able to develop easily. This line is very obscure so no need to full on analyze this but Black is fine (-0.3 according to the computer and that's if they find the move d5 (all others, it's even worse). Black's moves are intuitive (for example, if they find the best move you play exd5 --no advanced degree required).} 1. e4 d6 2. f4 ({A weird move. Black is fine playing almost anything here.} 2. e5 {is a King's Gambit (White can't play fxe5 because of Qh4+ so Nf3 exf4 is the mainline Fisher 'refutation' of the King's Gambit. It's ridiculously good for Black--at the end of the line in Ian Nepomniatchi's Long Live the King's Gambit Chessable course he declares White has almost no winning chances and against the only alternative line for White, he declares Black to be better. Still, it seems a bit intense to learn King's Gambit theory all for the sake of this obscure try by White, but if you play the e5 Philidor or know someone plays this who plays the King's Gambit, feel free to go that route.} c5 {is the Grand Prix attack. d5 is a Center Counter where White has played the bad move f4 and you can always play} 3. e6 {to play d5 if you used to be a French player. If you've played any one of those, then you can transpose and move on with your life. I'll keep things tricky and unique.}) 2... Nf6 {Now White should play Nc3 as e5 isn't very good for them.} 3. e5 {I mean how could White not consider attacking the knight?} dxe5 4. fxe5 Nd5 {And it looks a little like the Alekhine's except Black has traded a d-pawn for an f-pawn. This makes a big difference. For example, let's pretend White thinks they can play it like the normal Alekhine's and goes....} 5. Nf3 Bg4 {We aren't in Philidor territory anymore and should just develop normally and think about castling queenside.} 6. d4 e6 7. Be2 c5 {Now if c3 we exchange cxd4 cxd4 , and our knight will live on d5 for a long time. So White should kick us now.} 8. c4 Nb6 *

