1. e4 d6 2. f4 ({A weird move. Black is fine playing almost anything here.} 2. e5 {is a King's Gambit (White can't play fxe5 because of Qh4+ so Nf3 exf4 is the mainline Fisher 'refutation' of the King's Gambit. It's ridiculously good for Black--at the end of the line in Ian Nepomniatchi's Long Live the King's Gambit Chessable course he declares White has almost no winning chances and against the only alternative line for White, he declares Black to be better. Still, it seems a bit intense to learn King's Gambit theory all for the sake of this obscure try by White, but if you play the e5 Philidor or know someone plays this who plays the King's Gambit, feel free to go that route.} c5 {is the Grand Prix attack. d5 is a Center Counter where White has played the bad move f4 and you can always play} 3. e6 {to play d5 if you used to be a French player. If you've played any one of those, then you can transpose and move on with your life. I'll keep things tricky and unique.}) 2... Nf6 {Now White should play Nc3 as e5 isn't very good for them.} 3. e5 dxe5 4. fxe5 Nd5 {And it looks a little like the Alehkine's except Black has traded a d-pawn for an f-pawn. This makes a big difference. For example, let's pretend White thinks they can play it like the normal Alehkines and goes....} 5. c4 Nb4 {Threatening Nd3 winning the bishop pair and a great position. So...} 6. d4 {This is sensible at first glance, gaining the center and stopping Nd3 . This is what White would do in a normal Alekhine's. White was worse anyway but this clinches it.} Qxd4 ({if} 6... Qxd4 {Nc2+ Kf2 Nxd4 And oh, that open d-file for Black does matter after all. This isn't a regular Alekhine's--as White learns too late in this variation.}) *

