1. e4 d6 2. f4 ({A weird move. Black is fine playing almost anything here.} 2. e5 {is a King's Gambit (White can't play fxe5 because of Qh4+ so Nf3 exf4 is the mainline Fisher 'refutation' of the King's Gambit. It's ridiculously good for Black--at the end of the line in Ian Nepomniatchi's Long Live the King's Gambit Chessable course he declares White has almost no winning chances and against the only alternative line for White, he declares Black to be better. Still, it seems a bit intense to learn King's Gambit theory all for the sake of this obscure try by White, but if you play the e5 Philidor or know someone plays this who plays the King's Gambit, feel free to go that route.} c5 {is the Grand Prix attack. d5 is a Center Counter where White has played the bad move f4 and you can always play} 3. e6 {to play d5 if you used to be a French player. If you've played any one of those, then you can transpose and move on with your life. I'll keep things tricky and unique.}) 2... d5 ({This is a sensible alternative and scores extremely well: no Black losses in 9 games. Now on} 2... e5 {, we can play Bf5 and a French defense-- e6  c5 next--without a bad bishop. The only issue is that if they play 2. Nc3 first, d5 will be trickier so this alternative involved learning another line against that. In the position on the board, White should play...}) 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qd8 {This is another sensible option. It's a Center Counter--which is already playable... Magnus played a Qd8 Scandinavian against Caruana--but here White has played the move f4 , which is just awful.  f4 blocks their bishop from going there, sets up checks on the diagonal after White castles and doesn't add much. White will still have a better center like most Scandinavian Defenses but Black has a solid position.} *

