{Taking back with the queen would also be fine, but we follow the principle knights and bishops first in the opening. Here is a good place to stop as White has many plans like d4 , Bc4 , Nc3 and Be2 all played with a similar frequency at Club Level play. The position favors Black by about half a pawn according to the engine. But why? Well, because Black has two developed pieces and White has absolutely no developed minor pieces five moves into the game. We can play e6  c5  Bc6 in whichever order we deem most anxiety-provoking for our opponent next. White will be missing the f3 knight so attacks against the enemy king should go well with our lead in development and active pieces.} 1. e4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 dxe5 {If we have to move our knight, we are committing the same 'not developing' issue as White was. Because White doesn't want to lose a pawn, they must violate an opening principle and move a piece twice in the opening.} 4. Nxe5 Nbd7 ({Offering White a trade.} 4... Nc6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 {would have been possible but let's not take on doubled pawns needlessly. White's only good piece--scratch that: only developed piece at all --is their knight on e5 . It's not sustainable to keep it in that nice location.}) 5. Nxd7 (5. d4 Nxe5 6. dxe5 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Ng4 {forking f2 and e5 is winning and of course} 8. f4 {doesn't work in guarding both pawns as} Nf2+ {would win a whole rook.}) 5... Bxd7 *

