1. e4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 ({Instead} 3. c3 {is a tricky trap as 3…} Nxe4 $4 4. Qa4+ {forks the knight and king and so wins a piece. Instead, 3… e5 –or even c6 –would be the better path and leave Black with a typical Philidor game plan.}) 3... Nxe4 {This line is very rare and even rarer if done on purpose. It's called the Roscher Gambit, which I believe is Spanish for 'loses a pawn.' Okay, okay, it's not Spanish for that, and not even Spanish, but it does lose a pawn for almost no compensation. This has only been played four times in Master level chess--I'm convinced by mistake--with a dismal record for White: two draws and two Black wins. I'm giving it here to quickly summarize how to consolidate this pawn edge whenever you snag this e-pawn.} 4. Bd3 {d5 is tempting but because White leads in development, it's best not to allow an opening up of the position. So we play the very boring looking...} Nf6 {Now we are fine as long as we settle on some general rules and plans. What we don't want to do is rush e5 . White's rook now has an open e-file. So we can either play e6 and keep it calm for now with e6  Be7  O-O and only much later think about e5 . Or, if you're a Queen's Gambit Declined player, play e6  d5 and play the queen pawn openings a pawn up. Simplest is to play g6  Bg7 and go for e5 later. Why is this good? Because there is no f-pawn threat nor is there a center expansion threat anymore. So just building a fortress and castling should give us a clean pawn lead. We can then play a6  b5  Bb7  Nbd7 and one day c5 or e5 . This is what I would recommend for most Philidor players as we can keep our pawns on the right colored squares.} *

