[PlyCount "28"]

1. e4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Bc4 ({A key position. Do not play Nbd7 and think White will transposes to the mainline.} 4. Ng5 {and you will be feeling some heat. Instead, whenever you see Nf3 and Bc4 , play Be7 to O-O .}) 4... Be7 5. d4 {And now Black has a pleasant choice. They can accept White's apologies for playing the trap and play 5... Nbd7 , heading to the mainline, or not allow White the luxury and play 5... exd4 .} Nbd7 {This is the mainline offer, which for simplicity sake, is my main recommendation. However, one deviation strategy for White I like to call the 'Caveman Attack.' I call it that because it's simple and aggressive. It has a certain, 'I have club and I thwak your friend with it' logic to it. White sees that f7 , your friend, isn't defended. White realizes that they are not that much better developed than Black but White believes that despite that fact, it is time to thwak their opponent with a club. Online, they might not even move their knight to g5 to do it, but may sacrifice the bishop right away! This, of course, isn't justified, but it is tricky.} ({For example: Bxf7 Kxf7 Ng5+ Kg8 Ne6 Qe8 Nxc7 and there's just one concept to remember here before you mourn your rook and resign... Qg6 Nxa8 Qxg2 Rf1} 5... exd4 6. Qxd4 {Ne5 and the threat is Nf3 and on f4} Ng4 {threatening Bh4 will be fairly easy to calculate over the board once you've seen the general concept. With most of these lines, if the knight eats the a8 rook, just counterattack! That's why White will often play} 7. Ng5 {here, which is more legitimate. The idea is to play the clickable version above but make sure that a Black rook, instead of the king, recaptures on f7 , which will block this queen counterattack maneuver that is so devastating for White.}) 6. Ng5 {So White Caveman's us. Okay, okay.} O-O 7. Bxf7+ {This is a trappy opening and we have to be careful. The Caveman style works sometimes which is why people still play it.} Rxf7 8. Ne6 ({This is the best way to Caveman.} 8. Nxf7 Kxf7 9. dxe5 Nxe5 {is what we were hoping for which is much better for Black with White so underdeveloped and the White rooks having no great files. Luckily, even the good version of the Caveman attack isn't so bad for Black as long as you know the next few moves.}) 8... Qe8 9. Nxc7 Qd8 10. Nxa8 b5 {b6 is also fine but I like b5 better. The point is to play Bb7 . You will lose a pawn for the knight no matter what so it's just whether you want White playing Nxb5 or Nxb6 .} 11. O-O Bb7 {We aren't greedy about taking the knight and saving b5 . Just win the knight and don't let White do tricks.} 12. Nxb5 Bxa8 {White has traded the two minor pieces for the rook and three pawns in a way as to have almost equality ( almost, White is slightly worse). Now best is Nxa7 and trying to play with the queenside pawns. This is rare though and White will really need to have studied... and still, even if your opponent is booked up on cheapo f7 attacks, this results in a Black advantage. In fact, in all computer lines, White has to give back one of the pawns as there are just too many threats and misplaced white pieces.   Why is Black better despite the material? Because of their activity. Black's pieces all are functionally strong or have a pathway towards being strong. For example, Black has the bishop pair, an open file for the rooks, possibilities of attack with White's f3 knight gone, possibilities of queenside pressure with the a and b files clear and lots of options for their pieces. White's rooks lack open files, and they are also behind in development. The only way to save the e4 pawn is to make another non-developing move in f3 . How do you exploit the lead in development? By opening up the center and luckily that's not so hard to do as d5 by White hangs the e4 pawn. The pawns might matter in an endgame one day but there's no easy path to getting there for White and in the meantime two minor pieces in an open position against one stunted a1 rook that can't do anything will be a nightmare for White.} 13. Nxa7 Qb8 14. Be3 {The tactical point of White's play: if you take it, they'll take on e5 and threaten your knight on f6 . Clever! I recommend not taking the knight but just playing simply with...} Bxe4 ({The position is almost even but easier to play with Black due to their bishop pair and active pieces. The computer agrees and gives Black a small edge. The top computer line here runs as follows c4 Bxg2 Kxg2} 14... Qxa7 15. d5 {because 17. dxe5  Qb7 +, the point of the bishop sacrifice} Qb8 {When Black has already won back one of the pawns and still has a ton of compensation for the other one with active knights, nice files, an opponent's stunted rooks and a weak opposing king.}) *

