1. e4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Bc4 ({A key position. Do not play Nbd7 and think White will transpose to the mainline.} 4. Ng5 {and you will be feeling some heat. Instead, whenever you see Nf3 and Bc4 , play Be7 to O-O .}) 4... Be7 {Preparing to meet Ng5 with castles. Now Black wins more than they lose by a wide margin. White should probably attempt the mainline with...} 5. d4 {And now Black has a pleasant choice. They can accept White's apologies for playing the trap and play Nbd7 , heading to the mainline, or not allow White the luxury and play exd4 .} exd4 {This line has a major appeal: it's simpler. No scary attacks. The disadvantage and the reason I list it as my alternative is that 1. you don't get a totally clean transposition as now White has Bf4 as an option and Black has Nc6 options, and 2. the other line is quite good for Black. But for those not encountering the Caveman Attack option, the memorization could be a chore or you could just dislike the chaos of the resulting positions. I leave it up to you!} 6. Nxd4 O-O {This transposes to just the open variation but the addition of Bc4 means that if White castles queenside, you'll get a boop on the bishop when you play b5 . To stop b5 will require a4 , which is also not ideal for castling queenside. Additionally, since Black was never forced to play Nbd7 , suddenly Nc6 becomes a tempting option. Food for thought if you hated the Ng5 position or are looking for alternatives to the mainline. I'd recommend you look over the Austrian Attack lines which involves a similar structure. Without the black knight on d7 , the Caveman Attack isn't so good as the e6 square is not a possibility for the white knight. It's also possible to also play O-O and Nd7 later, retaining a feel more similar to the rest of the course.} *

