1. e4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Bc4 ({A key position. Do not play Nbd7 and think White will transposes to the mainline.} 4. Ng5 {and you will be feeling some heat. Instead, whenever you see Nf3 and Bc4 , play Be7 to O-O .}) 4... Be7 5. Ng5 {This is similar to the right way to play the Caveman Attack and so similar some readers may think it's the same. But White has not played d4 and Black hasn't played Nbd7 . This favors Black as without the knight on d7 , Black's bishop gives extra cushion to e6 , a key square.} O-O 6. Bxf7+ Rxf7 {Now there's no Ne6 so this is a very sad Caveman.} 7. Nxf7 Kxf7 {The position could have arisen by knight takes f7 first as well. Many Club Players think this is an even trade but actually White is down almost a piece according to the engine. White just doesn't have enough minor pieces to survive the middle game and their extra rook will only be good in the endgame. Just attack them and play actively and you should see yourself start to win things. Black is winning.} *

