1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. f4 {White weeps that they didn't get the Austrian Attack against the Pirc and tries to play it against the Philidor. White is trying to bully us into losing our center. They will have their way but to misquote the Princess Bride: You keep urging us to take on d4 , I do not think it means, what you think it means.' I don't have any super GM's playing this move, a telling sign given that super GM battles take place in the Philidor all the time. The highest rated player to play it is Julian Hodgson at 2640 (which is admittedly close to, if not already a, super GM). But the one game in it involved him losing to someone 240 points lower than him, so even that isn't the biggest sell from the White point of view. On the other hand, if Black takes the wrong pawn, White is suddenly winning a lot--65% to Black's 25% in Master play--so this is a dangerous position you can't merely intuit, and unlike our normal ones--hence the three chapters. Once you know the early moves though, you should smile every time White plays this way.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {This is a perfect example of a good reason to take on d4 : the move f4 doesn't develop a piece so White will lag behind in development and doubly so because Nc6 will hit their queen. The move f4 also means they can't play f3 to defend e4 when the going gets tough. Finally, the extra tempos mean we can develop the bishop to the long diagonal right away without worrying about Bc4  Nf3 - g5 stuff (it will be way too slow for White).} Nc6 6. Bb5 {I'm not a big believer in pinning as it just means they are delaying the tension. Nonetheless it is the most popular move.} Bd7 7. Bxc6 {This is the most popular Club Player move and not a good one. White gives up the bishop pair and feels even MORE heat on e4 .} Bxc6 8. Nf3 Nxe4 ({This works because the Black queen will pin and win anything lost on the e-file. And White won't be able to defend pieces on that file because they have already pushed their d and f-pawns up the board. On O-O Black will just play Nf6 , stopping the queen gaze on g7 so they can respond to Re1 with} 8... Be7 {blocking the check and beginning to consolidate the pawn advantage.}) 9. Nxe4 Qe7 10. Kf2 Bxe4 11. Re1 d5 {The dust has settled and with White playing incredibly well, they have gained a microscopic disadvantage, close to equal. Temporarily, Black's king is in the center, so we will aim to play Qc5 , trading queens and stopping Qxd5 --what White wants if you played Qf6 .  Then we will play Bb4  O-O . We can guard our bishop with f5 and d5 with c6 in the meantime. White has to be very careful to not just end up a pawn down.} *

