1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. f4 {White weeps that they didn't get the Austrian Attack against the Pirc and tries to play it against the Philidor. White is trying to bully us into losing our center. They will have their way but to misquote the Princess Bride: You keep urging us to take on d4 , I do not think it means, what you think it means.' I don't have any super GM's playing this move, a telling sign given that super GM battles take place in the Philidor all the time. The highest rated player to play it is Julian Hodgson at 2640 (which is admittedly close to, if not already a, super GM). But the one game in it involved him losing to someone 240 points lower than him, so even that isn't the biggest sell from the White point of view. On the other hand, if Black takes the wrong pawn, White is suddenly winning a lot--65% to Black's 25% in Master play--so this is a dangerous position you can't merely intuit, and unlike our normal ones--hence the three chapters. Once you know the early moves though, you should smile every time White plays this way.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {This is a perfect example of a good reason to take on d4 : the move f4 doesn't develop a piece so White will lag behind in development and doubly so because Nc6 will hit their queen. The move f4 also means they can't play f3 to defend e4 when the going gets tough. Finally, the extra tempos mean we can develop the bishop to the long diagonal right away without worrying about Bc4  Nf3 - g5 stuff (it will be way too slow for White).} Nc6 6. Bb5 {I'm not a big believer in pinning as it just means they are delaying the tension. Nonetheless it is the most popular move.} Bd7 7. Qf2 {This is the mainline.} a6 8. Bd3 {Keeping the bishop is a logical idea.} Nb4 ({This was played in a game by a strong grandmaster. Other moves are also playable but I find this simplest: we just want the bishop pair in return for the center space. The bishop cannot move because Bc4} 8... Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Qe7 10. Qe2 d5 {and you will regain the material easily--even if the bishop wasn't hanging, moving the knight would result in Nxc2 because the queen would be pinned.}) ({After Bc4 ,} 8... Qe7 {is also a clear edge for Black if you want less fireworks.}) 9. Nf3 Nxd3+ ({This is the simplest path to a playable game. It's not as tricky for White as a d-pawn push on move 8 but our memorization is way down. After cxd3 Black can play} 9... d5 {, c5 , b5 or even Be7 here and get a good game with the bishop pair in exchange for a bit more cramped space. So moves can vary after this point but Black is doing well and has easy play as the nature of their pluses does not hinge on a single sequence.}) *

