1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. f4 {White weeps that they didn't get the Austrian Attack against the Pirc and tries to play it against the Philidor. White is trying to bully us into losing our center. They will have their way but to misquote the Princess Bride: You keep urging us to take on d4 , I do not think it means, what you think it means.' I don't have any super GM's playing this move, a telling sign given that super GM battles take place in the Philidor all the time. The highest rated player to play it is Julian Hodgson at 2640 (which is admittedly close to, if not already a, super GM). But the one game in it involved him losing to someone 240 points lower than him, so even that isn't the biggest sell from the White point of view. On the other hand, if Black takes the wrong pawn, White is suddenly winning a lot--65% to Black's 25% in Master play--so this is a dangerous position you can't merely intuit, and unlike our normal ones--hence the three chapters. Once you know the early moves though, you should smile every time White plays this way.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {This is a perfect example of a good reason to take on d4 : the move f4 doesn't develop a piece so White will lag behind in development and doubly so because Nc6 will hit their queen. The move f4 also means they can't play f3 to defend e4 when the going gets tough. Finally, the extra tempos mean we can develop the bishop to the long diagonal right away without worrying about Bc4  Nf3 - g5 stuff (it will be way too slow for White).} Nc6 6. Bb5 {I'm not a big believer in pinning as it just means they are delaying the tension. Nonetheless it is the most popular move.} Bd7 7. Qf2 {This is the mainline.} a6 8. Bd3 d5 {This is a novelty. The previous games went Nb4 and Be7 . Black scored well but this is the most aggressive at pursuing equality. I give it as an alternative as it's complicated and this variation is obscure anyway. It's logic is as follows: we have three minor pieces out to White's two and so it's time to open things up.} 9. exd5 Nb4 {Qe7+ is also good for Black but trickier to play (it involves a positional pawn sacrifice which will make a lot of readers uncomfortable as explaining the compensation is complex--for a sideline, let's keep things simpler). Black threatens taking the bishop pair and doubling White's pawns for a pawn or just retaking on d4 . White should probably just play Nf3 and allow Black to either retake the pawn or take the bishop and play positionally. But greed is a thing so I imagine that Bc4 and Qd4 will be popular.} 10. Qd4 Qe7+ {White's greed is very understandable. But now the White king has to allow 11... Bg4 or move. Black can castle queenside and attack the weak d-pawn or take the bishop pair and play for initiative. I would play around on a computer here with Black to understand how Black is just ahead. I don't think it's worth memorizing long lines against it, but instead would invite you to assess this position yourself: do you think you have compensation for the pawn? If not, just play my main recommendation. If so, go for it. The position is very natural for Black to play and although White has many options in the coming moves, you don't need to memorize every contingency to enjoy Black's prospects here: just play sensibly and aggressively.} *

