1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. f4 {White weeps that they didn't get the Austrian Attack against the Pirc and tries to play it against the Philidor. White is trying to bully us into losing our center. They will have their way but to misquote the Princess Bride: You keep urging us to take on d4 , I do not think it means, what you think it means.' I don't have any super GM's playing this move, a telling sign given that super GM battles take place in the Philidor all the time. The highest rated player to play it is Julian Hodgson at 2640 (which is admittedly close to, if not already a, super GM). But the one game in it involved him losing to someone 240 points lower than him, so even that isn't the biggest sell from the White point of view. On the other hand, if Black takes the wrong pawn, White is suddenly winning a lot--65% to Black's 25% in Master play--so this is a dangerous position you can't merely intuit, and unlike our normal ones--hence the three chapters. Once you know the early moves though, you should smile every time White plays this way.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {This is a perfect example of a good reason to take on d4 : the move f4 doesn't develop a piece so White will lag behind in development and doubly so because Nc6 will hit their queen. The move f4 also means they can't play f3 to defend e4 when the going gets tough. Finally, the extra tempos mean we can develop the bishop to the long diagonal right away without worrying about Bc4  Nf3 - g5 stuff (it will be way too slow for White).} Nc6 6. Bb5 {I'm not a big believer in pinning as it just means they are delaying the tension. Nonetheless it is the most popular move.} Bd7 7. Qf2 {This is the mainline.} a6 8. Bd3 d5 {This is a novelty. The previous games went Nb4 and Be7 . Black scored well but it's time to take advantage of the fact that we have three minor pieces out to White's two and open things up.} 9. exd5 Nb4 {Qe7+ is also good for Black but trickier to play (it involves a positional pawn sacrifice which will make a lot of readers uncomfortable as explaining the compensation is complex--for a sideline, let's keep things simpler). Black threatens taking the bishop pair and doubling White's pawns for a pawn or just retaking on d4 . White should probably just play Nf3 and allow Black to either retake the pawn or take the bishop and play positionally. But greed is a thing so I imagine that Bc4 and Qd4 will be popular.} 10. Bc4 {This move is really bad for White actually.} Qe7+ {If White blocks the check by moving a piece to e2 , then Black plays Nxc2 + so sadly for White, they have to move their king.} 11. Kd1 Ng4 ({And now more threats are coming. It's not so easy as even the last ditch effort to trade queens doesn't work because on} 11... Qe2+ 12. Qxe2+ {you want to recapture with the king to stop Nf2 but then Nxc2 and you're not even up a pawn for your troubles.}) 12. Qf3 O-O-O {Black is temporarily down a pawn but the compensation is pretty easy to see: it's sitting right there on d1 . Black will be able to retake on d4 soon (after Nf6 ) as there are too many tactics on the file for White to protect it.} 13. Nge2 Nf6 14. Bd2 {White blocks the d-file to stop Nxd5 tactics.} Qc5 {Attacking d5 again. Bg4 is next gaining a tempo attacking the queen and pinning the knight on e2 . The queen will have to move off defending g4 . The c4 bishop is also attacked. This is just depressing for White.} 15. Bb3 {The tactics work out on Nbxd4 already but there's an even better move...} Bg4 {And White is not able to protect d4 and will be much worse as we will have compensation without even being a pawn down!} *

