1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. f4 {White weeps that they didn't get the Austrian Attack against the Pirc and tries to play it against the Philidor. White is trying to bully us into losing our center. They will have their way but to misquote the Princess Bride: You keep urging us to take on d4 , I do not think it means, what you think it means.' I don't have any super GM's playing this move, a telling sign given that super GM battles take place in the Philidor all the time. The highest rated player to play it is Julian Hodgson at 2640 (which is admittedly close to, if not already a, super GM). But the one game in it involved him losing to someone 240 points lower than him, so even that isn't the biggest sell from the White point of view. On the other hand, if Black takes the wrong pawn, White is suddenly winning a lot--65% to Black's 25% in Master play--so this is a dangerous position you can't merely intuit, and unlike our normal ones--hence the three chapters. Once you know the early moves though, you should smile every time White plays this way.} exd4 5. Qxd4 {This is a perfect example of a good reason to take on d4 : the move f4 doesn't develop a piece so White will lag behind in development and doubly so because Nc6 will hit their queen. The move f4 also means they can't play f3 to defend e4 when the going gets tough. Finally, the extra tempos mean we can develop the bishop to the long diagonal right away without worrying about Bc4  Nf3 - g5 stuff (it will be way too slow for White).} Nc6 6. Bb5 {I'm not a big believer in pinning as it just means they are delaying the tension. Nonetheless it is the most popular move.} Bd7 7. Qf2 {This is the mainline.} a6 8. Bd3 d5 {This is a novelty. The previous games went Nb4 and Be7 . Black scored well but it's time to take advantage of the fact that we have three minor pieces out to White's two and open things up.} 9. Nxd5 {White could try to trade the knights to give them a c4 option.} Nxd5 10. exd5 Nb4 {Again let's look at the greedy because allowing Nxd5 will be more evidently equal if not slightly better for Black.  c4 isn't immediately available as the white bishop will hang.} 11. Qd4 {Guarding the bishop to play c4 and guarding the d4 pawn. Black has an edge already and can exploit a pin to keep attacking d5 .} Be6 {And White really should let it go, but we have to look at...} 12. c4 {It looks like White is keeping the pawn with a nice center but Black has a pretty shot here with...} Bc5 ({Now Qxc5} 12... Nxd3+ {wins the queen. It looks at first like White can play Qe4 , pinning the bishop and seemingly winning but Black can just reply c6 because if White plays dxe6 Black has Nxd3 and all their pieces come into play. If White doesn't take on e6 , then c6xd5 will end the pawn on d5 once and for all. So White should probably try the most aggressive option...}) 13. Qxg7 {White is losing, to be sure, but this creates the most chaos so is a good move.} Nxd3+ {This doesn't win a bishop as after the king attacks our knight we will be under a double attack. But trading the knight for the bishop is a good deal for us, especially if White has to come out into the center of the board with their king!} 14. Kd2 Rf8 15. Kxd3 {The king's placement gives Black a huge edge and in fact it is entirely justified here to sacrifice the bishop for two pawns for the sake of hunting down the king.} Bxd5 16. cxd5 Qxd5+ 17. Kc3 O-O-O {And the computer gives Black as up 8 which sounds about right. White's pieces, with the exception of the vulnerable king and queen are all on their starting squares.  Qd3 checkmate is threatened along with Bd4 winning the queen. It's bleak for White.} *

