1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. d5 {Instead, White could exchange pawns, a common and not so good try, but we can proceed with the strategy of that specific pawn structure mentioned in 'Pawns are the Souls of Chess' .   White's third move was a reasonable sideline played by high rated players and you will find its coverage more fully in the Master Deviations section. But the masters usually combine it with 4. c3 . Instead, the move d5 is a more Club Player try, though not exclusively, and is arguing that without the white knight on c3 , White can play c4 against our usual retort c6 . But that's easy enough: we just won't play c6 unless we see Nc3 . If their goal is to transpose to a King's Indian of sorts, we will welcome it. The bishop is not very ideal on d3 in the King's Indian and pairs poorly with d5 .   If you do accidentally reflex move c6 , don't worry: that's equal too just a bit too much what White wants. If you accidentally play it, I advise you to not take on d5 and just keep the pawn on c6 or play c5  Nbd7 as without a5 , c5 is not so horrible for Black.} Be7 5. c4 {Why else play Bd3 if not for the sake of c4 ?} ({Now one way of playing is to play our normal anti-d5 move anyway and that would look like this: c6} 5. Nf3 Na6 6. Nc3 Nc5 {Bc2 Qb6 . This position is dynamically equal and quite interesting. I worry a little that it's not the usual Philidor setup though, so would prefer something a bit more in line with our usual plans.}) 5... Nbd7 6. Nc3 Nc5 7. Bc2 a5 {Guarding b4 to secure our knight on c5 . Now we will continue with moves like Nfd7  Bg5 --to trade bishops now that our pawns are stuck on dark squares-- O-O and later f5 , possibly prepped with g6 . The position reminds me of a sort of weird King's Indian. We will go for the plan outlined in Pawns are the Soul of Chess section and should be around equal here.} 8. Nge2 Nfd7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 Bg5 {The position is equal and easy to play for Black.  Plan:  Pawnstorm the kingside.} *

