1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 ({In addition to the Shirov Gambit and Yugoslav-like setups, which are both concrete and get their own individual chapters, we also have two common and strategically complex Master deviations that are of a non-forcing nature. They both require less memorization than they do understanding and are covered here in a compact way. The first arises after Bd3} 2... e5 3. c3 {. Here, White has a worse than normal bishop but a slightly more robust control of their central pawn mass. A quick d5 is mentioned in GM Cuenca's course against this and it probably equalizes to the point of reminding us why this is, indeed, merely a sideline. Still the play is concrete, the position is open, and complete and utter liquidation possible. None of those appeal to the spirit of this course which should allow strategic, positional play and opportunities to outplay opponents in structures we know and understand well and are unforcing in nature.   So I recommend playing very normal Philidor moves against this setup for simplicity sake and arriving at a rich and solid position. Because play is strategic and not forcing, I don't intend to have a million lines trying to cover it all but aim to have just a couple that explore the ideas and prepare you for the scariest version of this type of play.  So I have decreased the variation count to only the most poisonous here, but given depth in terms of move count, which will not only help you have a memorized reply to the scariest way to play it as White but also help you form some pattern recognition for the middle games.   Against White's very best way to play this sideline, I propose a pawn sacrifice with intuitive and good compensation. For those who must see the pawn sacrifices to the very end, I give two 'alternative' long lines that help you memorize a bit further to calm worried minds. They're 'alternatives' as in 'alternatives to playing intuitively.' For most players, no further memorization is recommended. It's also worth noting that this line is difficult to play as White. Black can respond to it with d5 , Nc6 and our move, Be7 . Each one is very different and White must know them all and be ready to play tactical and fast concrete games as well as slow maneuvering games.}) ({The other common sideline path White has is to play Nc3} 2... e5 3. Ne2 Be7 4. g3 Nd7 5. Bg2 {with a plan to eventually squeeze us to death on the kingside. Play is slow and non-forcing. Here again, most readers below 2000 can just skip this chapter and play normal Philidor moves with good practical chances, but the highest rated here may want to go over the two recommended variations which explore some subtle changes to the usual development scheme and may move the compass slightly closer to equality at the expense of having a bit more to review and understand. Again, this line is not easy to play for White as Black has many different types of setups and plans while White's piece placement and pawn pushes are predictable.}) *

