[Black "g3 System: White prevents b5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "24"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nge2 {This is like the last variation except instead of having two connecting knights going one direction, it's going the other! What's the idea? White wants to fianchetto the bishop so doesn't mind blocking it in and wants the option to move the f-pawn later. Technically, Nc6 may equalize the easiest but that is very un-Philidor so let's stick to our system.} Be7 {There's no knight attacking our e5 pawn so although Nbd7 is fine, there's no reason for it before Be7 . Personal preference. I chose Be7 to remind you of the missing knight.} 5. g3 Nbd7 {Again, Bg4 is another line, as is Na6 later (played by Caruana once against Carlsen). But let's not confuse our systems by having different setups against each one for fractions of centipawns.} 6. Bg2 O-O 7. h3 c6 {We ask White about whether they will stop our queenside expansion. It's less powerful for us without a bishop to attack or with their e2 knight blocking a Ba6 gaze, but it's still not bad.} 8. a4 a5 9. O-O Re8 10. Be3 Bf8 11. g4 {This is White's basic idea. It's not so much an attack with the king over there as it is a slow squeeze. Luckily, we can follow classic chess rules by counterattacking in the center whenever they expand on the wing.} exd4 {As the old saying goes, an attack on the wing is best met by a strike in the center. We want to open up a place for our f6 knight so are headed somewhere with our other knight.} 12. Bxd4 {And the rules here are not so different from the mainline. Open up the center and attack e4 with Ne6 ideas.  Ne5 isn't so great as White wants to play f4 anyway.} Nc5 {Normally, I'd be a bit hesitant to allow Bxc5 but with h3  g4 played, there will be so many dark squares to attack. The position is a tiny bit better for White but very easy to play for Black. For those wanting equality or bust, you can consider b6 instead of a5 on move 8. It leads to different positions than our normal setup: the idea is a6  Bb7  b5 . Personally, I'd just take the 0.29 the computer is evaluating the position to simplify the repertoire as that's not even enough to be a 'slight edge' but rather just labelled 'equal.' The issue for White in this position is they want to play f4 to increase the squeeze, but there's enough pressure on the e-pawn to make that hard to do: after all, the f-pawn can't move back to f3 .   The computer recommends giving up the dark-squared bishop here for White with Bxc5 and playing a position where White has a better pawn structure against the bishop pair.} *

