1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nge2 {This is like the last variation except instead of having two connecting knights going one direction, it's going the other! What's the idea? White wants to fianchetto the bishop so doesn't mind blocking it in and wants the option to move the f-pawn later. Technically, Nc6 may equalize the easiest but that is very un-Philidor so let's stick to our system.} Be7 {There's no knight attacking our e5 pawn so although Nbd7 is fine, there's no reason for it before Be7 . Personal preference. I chose Be7 to remind you of the missing knight.} 5. g3 Nbd7 {Again, Bg4 is another line, as is Na6 later (played by Caruana once against Carlsen). But let's not confuse our systems by having different setups against each one for fractions of centipawns.} 6. Bg2 O-O 7. h3 c6 {We ask White about whether they will stop our queenside expansion. It's less powerful for us without a bishop to attack or with their e2 knight blocking a Ba6 gaze, but it's still not bad.} 8. O-O b5 {This is more or less the end of the opening. White has played solidly and Black will continue Qc7  a5  Bb7 with possible f5 or d5 pawn breaks. g3 is a solid positional try with the idea of not making it a forcing opening battle but rather a game of chess. I will continue with aggressive White tries just to show you what to do if you face a player who tries to put a little wildness in this quiet line.} 9. a3 {White stops b4 as the knight really is low on retreat squares with a knight on e2 .} a5 10. f4 {Not a great move but again, let's see what happens when White pawn storms quickly as it looks scary visually.} Bb7 {We don't need to react to the f4 move as if they keep taking on e5 , they'll just have an isolated pawn to show for it. Instead, we prepare a counter attack on e4 .} 11. g4 {White continues this scary looking assault. The issue is that the king is on g1 so it's not like White is opening up files with this type of play. They're just trying to stymie our pieces.} b4 12. Na4 Ba6 {Pinning the knight. Both sides are immobilizing the other with space gains! Yet that sounds very equal when in fact, Black is better here.} 13. g5 {Not a good move but scary enough to talk about. Generally, we can go to h5 when this occurs as e8 is hard for the knight to relocate.} Nh5 {Because Black hasn't moved their kingside pawns, White isn't opening any files here. The queen eyes our knight but their knight has literally no moves that don't result in capture because we haven't taken on f4 or d4 !} 14. Rf2 {Many moves are possible here, but let's just invade f4 . First, to take out a useful defender.} Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Nxf4 16. Bxf4 exf4 {And now g5 is hanging. White can try to take the f4 pawn leisurely but Black can counterattack and White can't fine the time. Too aggressive play by White has backfired. I'll end the Movetrainer here but give a natural line for those curious on the follow up.} 17. h4 Nb6 {Stockfish 16 much prefers h6 , though Hiarcs, Deep Fritz and Shredder disagree. It's probably objectively best but very technical and chaotic. So if Deep Fritz is having trouble following the logistics of h6 , let's just play a more solid hypothetical.} 18. Nxb6 Qxb6 19. Qc4 h6 {Or bxa3 right away. Black has an edge with White's king weak and the dark-squares falling into Black's clutches.} *

