1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 {This line was a bit irritating for me to plan around. On the one hand, it's a line that a lot of Club Players play when they're just making stuff up. On the other hand, it has been played by some very strong grandmasters and is no minor system.   The reason it's not the mainline for White is because the bishop blocks the queen's center access so d5 here should equalize. Unfortunately, that's a pain because it's not incredibly common and the lines where Black just plays d5 to explode everything open are unlike other lines in the Philidor: crazy, technical, very concrete, not at all idea based but move based. So the equalizing line won't be super easy to learn nor perhaps are fun to play if you like more closed structures where you can outmaneuver a lower-rated opponent.   Therefore, I decided to just recommend we play our normal setup for the sake of simplicity. We should be aware of two big differences between this and the mainline. First, a con: If we ever take on d4 , White will recapture with a pawn. So the idea of taking on d4 to clear up c5 for a knight is totally out the window.   Now luckily, there's also a pro:  The bishop on d3 means most of White's plans: attack on f7 (bishop on wrong diagonal), battering ram (bishop and knight aren't guarding d5 for piece recaptures), d6 assault (d5 is weak and the knight will have to go to d2 further closing down White's d-file play) are all weak now.   Therefore, it's like White will be playing mainly for Nf5 . Because they don't have Bc4 , we have g6 ideas to stop it along with our usual bishop takes knight stuff. Of course, White could have played d5 last move with the idea that without Nc3 they have c4 plans. I covered this in the Club Player Deviations section as it's more of a forte in the lower rated sections, though still sometimes employed by a master or above. Let's see how our normal moves play out against c3 .} Nbd7 5. Nf3 Be7 {d5 is a top engine move but is tricky to play. Black sacrifices a pawn in some lines for complicated compensation. It would maybe be a nice GM prep or idea if we were facing c3  Bd3 all the time but for people who only face this line rarely (99% of us) it's not worth all that effort. The main Philidor moves should give us a position we are comfortable playing.} 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 {Black develops in the normal fashion.} 8. Nbd2 Qc7 {b5 is less good here because of d5 when b5 is hanging if we take on d5 . A useful tactic to watch out for before queenside expanding.  Re8 is the main move and we do want to play it at some point but there's no rush. Taking on e4 is not a priority when White can retake with the pawn and we mainly play Re8 for maneuvering. Let's see what White's allowing on the queenside before deciding on maneuvering battles. b5 is now threatened as we have something defending c6 if White replies d5 .} 9. a4 {White opts to prevent queenside expansion. This is a good concession to induce as now if we trade in the center, the b4 square will be weak.} a5 10. Nf1 {White's knight is a bit awkward in this variation (a big downside to c3 along with the worse bishop) so it heads to f5 via g3 .} Re8 {We're less moving this rook in order to open things up (because we typically won't unless we have to) and more making space for f8 relocating--very important because we don't have Nc5 in this variation.} 11. Ng3 Nf8 {Eyeing f5 with our bishop and preparing to play Ne6 later.} 12. Be3 {White has completed their development. Because they are limited in plans, we can anticipate either a Nf5 plan or a very delayed attack on f7 plan. Of those, Nf5 looks scarier because they are doing it with two knights instead of one after Nh4 . So, let's take away that plan.} g6 {This move is fine because White isn't controlling the key diagonal and if they try, we can block it up with our knight on f8 ready to support.} 13. h3 {White plays an improving move and stops Ng4 . Very reasonable.} Ne6 {The black knight can go to f4 in some variations and we allow Bf8 should we need to shift things around on the backline.} 14. Qb3 {White is out of all the normal plans with g6 blocking the knight relocation. So they go back to trying to control the a2  g8 diagonal with the idea of punishing g6 in the long run... maybe a very very distant f4 .} Nf4 {We are happy to do our own Nf5 equivalent. The white dark-squared bishop is very good, and so we don't mind trading it for our knight and, in fact, White shouldn't trade.} 15. Bxf4 exf4 16. Ne2 Nh5 {The knight on h5 is surprisingly sturdy and stops White's kingside play. Against g4 we will en passant. I'm not sure what White will do on the queenside, so let's look at an attempt by White to take on f4 eventually. I'm ending the variation here officially but will list the rest of the variation for the interested.} 17. Qc2 Bf8 18. Qc1 Qd8 {The pawn can't be easily taken here. So, it's not clear how White is supposed to make progress and Black's two bishops will eventually start to matter, especially when d5 is played in the long run. Black redeploys the queen in case Qf6 is needed and simultaneously supports g5 if we really need to up the ante. Black will proceed on the queenside themselves eventually, looking for a b5 push. White has a tiny edge here technically but I would be frustrated playing them. After all, the knights can hardly move, the bishop is blocked in, the rooks lack files and the queen is passive. Playing improving moves with White is no easy task here. If White goes for the pawn to force matters, it's bad...} 19. Nxf4 Bh6 20. g3 {What else?} Bxh3 {Black has a clear edge. They have regained the pawn and White is still pinned and without the bishop pair. The computer recommends White play Ne6 here and allow a trade of queens, evaluating the position as worse for White by about a pawn.} *

