1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 {This line was a bit irritating for me to plan around. On the one hand, it's a line that a lot of Club Players play when they're just making stuff up. On the other hand, it has been played by some very strong grandmasters and is no minor system.   The reason it's not the mainline for White is because the bishop blocks the queen's center access so d5 here should equalize. Unfortunately, that's a pain because it's not incredibly common and the lines where Black just plays d5 to explode everything open are unlike other lines in the Philidor: crazy, technical, very concrete, not at all idea based but move based. So the equalizing line won't be super easy to learn nor perhaps are fun to play if you like more closed structures where you can outmaneuver a lower-rated opponent.   Therefore, I decided to just recommend we play our normal setup for the sake of simplicity. We should be aware of two big differences between this and the mainline. First, a con: If we ever take on d4 , White will recapture with a pawn. So the idea of taking on d4 to clear up c5 for a knight is totally out the window.   Now luckily, there's also a pro:  The bishop on d3 means most of White's plans: attack on f7 (bishop on wrong diagonal), battering ram (bishop and knight aren't guarding d5 for piece recaptures), d6 assault (d5 is weak and the knight will have to go to d2 further closing down White's d-file play) are all weak now.   Therefore, it's like White will be playing mainly for Nf5 . Because they don't have Bc4 , we have g6 ideas to stop it along with our usual bishop takes knight stuff. Of course, White could have played d5 last move with the idea that without Nc3 they have c4 plans. I covered this in the Club Player Deviations section as it's more of a forte in the lower rated sections, though still sometimes employed by a master or above. Let's see how our normal moves play out against c3 .} Nbd7 5. Nf3 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 {Black develops in the normal fashion.} 8. Nbd2 Qc7 {b5 is less good here because of d5 when b5 is hanging if we take on d5 . A useful tactic to watch out for before queenside expanding.} 9. a4 {White decides to stop b5 .} a5 10. Nf1 {White's knight is a bit awkward in this variation so it heads to f5 via g3 . Black wins a majority of games here on Lichess as White's position is trickier than ours even if they are technically fine.} Re8 {We're less moving this rook in order to open things up (because we typically won't unless we have to) and more making space for f8 relocating--very important because we don't have Nc5 in this variation.} 11. Ng3 Nf8 {Eyeing f5 with our bishop and preparing to play Ne6 later.} 12. Be3 {White has completed their development. Because they are limited in plans, we can anticipate either a Nf5 plan or a very delayed attack on f7 plan. Of those, Nf5 looks scarier because they are doing it with two knights instead of one after Nh4 . So, let's take away that plan.} g6 {This move is fine because White isn't controlling the key diagonal and if they try, we can block it up with our knight on f8 ready to support.} 13. h3 {White plays an improving move and stops Ng4 . Very reasonable.} Ne6 {The black knight can go to f4 in some variations and we allow Bf8 should we need to shift things around on the backline.} 14. Qb3 {White is out of all the normal plans with g6 blocking the knight relocation. So they go back to trying to control the a2  g8 diagonal with the idea of punishing g6 in the long run... maybe a very very distant f4 .} Nf4 {We are happy to do our own Nf5 equivalent. The white dark-squared bishop is very good, and so we don't mind trading it for our knight and, in fact, White shouldn't trade.} 15. Bc4 {This line is more beloved by the computer than taking the f4 knight. White allows the f4 knight to stay and keeps their bishop pair, reasoning Black can't exactly attack with just one knight.} Be6 {But without trading, the knight is useful at helping parry attacks on f7 .} 16. Bxe6 Nxe6 {The diagonal has been neutralized. Now White doesn't have an easy plan--to be fair, neither does Black and probably a long maneuvering game, waiting for the others to jump at phantoms is ahead of us. White has an opportunity to do something useful here by putting a bishop on b6 , but they must act now or Nd7 comes in, blocking b6 and toying with either f5 ideas in the very long run--or more standard b5 after Rab8 .} 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Bb6 {This is the computer's favorite continuation, trying to put the queen on an unfortunate square but there's a tactic to remember in these positions.} Nc5 ({This amounts to a very fun pawn sacrifice. The Chessable Stockfish engine is terrified of Qxf7 Kxf7 Bxc7} 18... Nd7 19. Red1 {. Here, taking on e5 will allow a fork on d3 whenever the bishop takes. So, Ke6 . Stockfish initially wants instead} Bd8 {which is more complicated. But why not just defend the pawn with the king? and I ran this position after 21... Ke6 by Stockfish 14 and on Deep Fritz 13 and both said it was very equal 0.0. Black looks fine there and a double edged game is ahead of you. If you're not a fan of any pawn sacrifices or risk, 18... Qb8 in the original position is quite fine as well.}) 19. Bxc7 {Forced as moving the queen to a safe square would result in the bishop being en-prise.} Nxb3 {We have reached a level endgame. White will take on e5 but can't hold onto the pawn because e4 will fall soon after. I'll stop the MoveTrainer here but show a few more moves for the curious and to give you a feel for the plans.} 20. Rad1 ({White can instead play} 20. Ra2 {and hold onto the pawn for a little bit with an atrocious out-of-play rook. But Black can just play actively and has full compensation for the pawn--you don't need a ton of understanding to play the position, just attack things and stay active and you'll find it's quite natural. I give the Ra2 line here as well. Since it's so lengthy, unlikely, and intuitive, I list working through the move trainer as an 'alternative' when really that means 'alternative to playing intuitively against it.'}) 20... Nc5 21. Bxe5 Nxa4 {Black will probably continue Nc5 and maybe Ne6 and expand their queenside majority with b5 . In return for   that queenside pawn majority, White has more center space but without a queen, there's no scary attacks coming. Our plan is to try to promote a pawn on the queenside.  Computer says equal but it feels more fun for Black in my opinion.} *

