1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 {This line was a bit irritating for me to plan around. On the one hand, it's a line that a lot of Club Players play when they're just making stuff up. On the other hand, it has been played by some very strong grandmasters and is no minor system.   The reason it's not the mainline for White is because the bishop blocks the queen's center access so d5 here should equalize. Unfortunately, that's a pain because it's not incredibly common and the lines where Black just plays d5 to explode everything open are unlike other lines in the Philidor: crazy, technical, very concrete, not at all idea based but move based. So the equalizing line won't be super easy to learn nor perhaps are fun to play if you like more closed structures where you can outmaneuver a lower-rated opponent.   Therefore, I decided to just recommend we play our normal setup for the sake of simplicity. We should be aware of two big differences between this and the mainline. First, a con: If we ever take on d4 , White will recapture with a pawn. So the idea of taking on d4 to clear up c5 for a knight is totally out the window.   Now luckily, there's also a pro:  The bishop on d3 means most of White's plans: attack on f7 (bishop on wrong diagonal), battering ram (bishop and knight aren't guarding d5 for piece recaptures), d6 assault (d5 is weak and the knight will have to go to d2 further closing down White's d-file play) are all weak now.   Therefore, it's like White will be playing mainly for Nf5 . Because they don't have Bc4 , we have g6 ideas to stop it along with our usual bishop takes knight stuff. Of course, White could have played d5 last move with the idea that without Nc3 they have c4 plans. I covered this in the Club Player Deviations section as it's more of a forte in the lower rated sections, though still sometimes employed by a master or above. Let's see how our normal moves play out against c3 .} Nbd7 5. Nf3 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 {Black develops in the normal fashion.} 8. Nbd2 Qc7 {b5 is less good here because of d5 when b5 is hanging if we take on d5 . A useful tactic to watch out for before queenside expanding.} 9. a4 a5 10. Nf1 {White's knight is a bit awkward in this variation so it heads to f5 via g3 .} Re8 {We're less moving this rook in order to open things up (because we typically won't unless we have to) and more making space for f8 relocating--very important because we don't have Nc5 in this variation.} 11. Ng3 Nf8 {Eyeing f5 with our bishop and preparing to play Ne6 later.} 12. Be3 {White has completed their development. Because they are limited in plans, we can anticipate either a Nf5 plan or a very delayed attack on f7 plan. Of those, Nf5 looks scarier because they are doing it with two knights instead of one after Nh4 . So, let's take away that plan.} g6 {This move is fine because White isn't controlling the key diagonal and if they try, we can block it up with our knight on f8 ready to support.} 13. h3 {White plays an improving move and stops Ng4 . Very reasonable.} Ne6 {The black knight can go to f4 in some variations and we allow Bf8 should we need to shift things around on the backline.} 14. Qb3 {White is out of all the normal plans with g6 blocking the knight relocation. So they go back to trying to control the a2  g8 diagonal with the idea of punishing g6 in the long run... maybe a very very distant f4 .} Nf4 {We are happy to do our own Nf5 equivalent. The white dark-squared bishop is very good, and so we don't mind trading it for our knight and, in fact, White shouldn't trade.} 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Bxe6 Nxe6 {The diagonal has been neutralized.} 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Bb6 {This is the computer's favorite continuation, trying to put the queen on an unfortunate square but there's a tactic to remember in these positions.} Nc5 {This amounts to a very fun pawn sacrifice.} 19. Bxc7 {Forced as moving the queen to a safe square would result in the bishop being en-prise.} Nxb3 {We have reached a level endgame. White will take on e5 but can't hold onto the pawn because e4 will fall soon after.} 20. Ra2 {White's best according to the computer but it's hard to imagine a human playing this ugly move where their rook has no safe squares. The idea is to guard a4 on Nc5 . The greedy will do anything for their pawns. I'm listing this variation as an alternative one to memorize not because it's different from our normal line but because in human-level play we could stop here and see the compensation in the ugly rook on a2 and hole on d3 . Additionally, the low probability of your opponent playing this move and arriving here means this is an optional trainable variation. I'll keep it here for the gung ho workhorses though.} Nc5 {Black prepares Nd3 if White ends up on e5 with a bishop. The White bishop is horribly misplaced and we should enjoy attacking it.} 21. Nxe5 {The principled move but that opens up the e-file for a counter attack. White's rook on a2 is bad so if we trade pawns, White will be worse--they really need to be up a pawn to be equal.} h5 {Threatening h4 and Nxe4 .} 22. h4 {Stopping Black's threats but allowing the g4 square to be used by a knight in the future.} Ne6 {Winning tempos on the bishop.} 23. Bb6 Nc5 {This is also sensible just dominating the dark squares by taking out White's bishop. The downside is that Bc7 repeats moves. The computer recommends...} 24. Bxc5 Bxc5 25. Nc4 {Nd3 was also possible, which guards a lot of threats but allows Rad8 later with important tempos. Black could just double on the d-file and play actively there.} Ng4 26. Re2 Rad8 {The position is around equal with Black's active pieces giving them compensation for the pawn (computer evaluation is 0.15). We will just control the d file, threaten things and not let White out of their weird position. The knight on g3 cannot move and White struggles to play with their pieces.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Deviations (Masters)"]
[Black "Bd3 c3: Memorize Option II"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "50"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3 e5 4. c3 {This line was a bit irritating for me to plan around. On the one hand, it's a line that a lot of Club Players play when they're just making stuff up. On the other hand, it has been played by some very strong grandmasters and is no minor system.   The reason it's not the mainline for White is because the bishop blocks the queen's center access so d5 here should equalize. Unfortunately, that's a pain because it's not incredibly common and the lines where Black just plays d5 to explode everything open are unlike other lines in the Philidor: crazy, technical, very concrete, not at all idea based but move based. So the equalizing line won't be super easy to learn nor perhaps are fun to play if you like more closed structures where you can outmaneuver a lower-rated opponent.   Therefore, I decided to just recommend we play our normal setup for the sake of simplicity. We should be aware of two big differences between this and the mainline. First, a con: If we ever take on d4 , White will recapture with a pawn. So the idea of taking on d4 to clear up c5 for a knight is totally out the window.   Now luckily, there's also a pro:  The bishop on d3 means most of White's plans: attack on f7 (bishop on wrong diagonal), battering ram (bishop and knight aren't guarding d5 for piece recaptures), d6 assault (d5 is weak and the knight will have to go to d2 further closing down White's d-file play) are all weak now.   Therefore, it's like White will be playing mainly for Nf5 . Because they don't have Bc4 , we have g6 ideas to stop it along with our usual bishop takes knight stuff. Of course, White could have played d5 last move with the idea that without Nc3 they have c4 plans. I covered this in the Club Player Deviations section as it's more of a forte in the lower rated sections, though still sometimes employed by a master or above. Let's see how our normal moves play out against c3 .} Nbd7 5. Nf3 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 {Black develops in the normal fashion.} 8. Nbd2 Qc7 {b5 is less good here because of d5 when b5 is hanging if we take on d5 . A useful tactic to watch out for before queenside expanding.} 9. a4 a5 10. Nf1 {White's knight is a bit awkward in this variation so it heads to f5 via g3 .} Re8 {We're less moving this rook in order to open things up (because we typically won't unless we have to) and more making space for f8 relocating--very important because we don't have Nc5 in this variation.} 11. Ng3 Nf8 {Eyeing f5 with our bishop and preparing to play Ne6 later.} 12. Be3 {White has completed their development. Because they are limited in plans, we can anticipate either a Nf5 plan or a very delayed attack on f7 plan. Of those, Nf5 looks scarier because they are doing it with two knights instead of one after Nh4 . So, let's take away that plan.} g6 {This move is fine because White isn't controlling the key diagonal and if they try, we can block it up with our knight on f8 ready to support.} 13. h3 {White plays an improving move and stops Ng4 . Very reasonable.} Ne6 {The black knight can go to f4 in some variations and we allow Bf8 should we need to shift things around on the backline.} 14. Qb3 {White is out of all the normal plans with g6 blocking the knight relocation. So they go back to trying to control the a2  g8 diagonal with the idea of punishing g6 in the long run... maybe a very very distant f4 .} Nf4 {We are happy to do our own Nf5 equivalent. The white dark-squared bishop is very good, and so we don't mind trading it for our knight and, in fact, White shouldn't trade.} 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Bxe6 Nxe6 {The diagonal has been neutralized.} 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Bb6 {This is the computer's favorite continuation, trying to put the queen on an unfortunate square but there's a tactic to remember in these positions.} Nc5 {This amounts to a very fun pawn sacrifice.} 19. Bxc7 {Forced as moving the queen to a safe square would result in the bishop being en-prise.} Nxb3 {We have reached a level endgame. White will take on e5 but can't hold onto the pawn because e4 will fall soon after.} 20. Ra2 {White's best according to the computer but it's hard to imagine a human playing this ugly move where their rook has no safe squares. The idea is to guard a4 on Nc5 . The greedy will do anything for their pawns. I'm listing this variation as an alternative one to memorize not because it's different from our normal line but because in human-level play we could stop here and see the compensation in the ugly rook on a2 and hole on d3 . Additionally, the low probability of your opponent playing this move and arriving here means this is an optional trainable variation. I'll keep it here for the gung ho workhorses though.} Nc5 21. Nxe5 h5 {Threatening h4 and Nxe4 .} 22. h4 {Stopping Black's threats but allowing the g4 square to be used by a knight in the future.} Ne6 23. Bb6 Ra6 {This is already very difficult for White as Black's petty attacks continually drive White back who is playing without a rook (thanks for nothing a2 rook!). For example, Be3  Bd6 is already a slight edge for Black and so White must find...} 24. Nc4 Ng4 {On f3 there's Bxh4 and on Ra2 - a1 there's Rxb6 followed by Bc5 . The dark squares are in trouble everywhere. The computer gives this near equality but it's monstrously hard to play for White.} 25. Rf1 Nf4 {The position is level. White still has their pawns but the precarious bishop, amazing knights and weak h4 pawn amount to a teeny bit of an edge for Black (-0.09, basically equality). I feel Black is having all the fun though in this 'equal' position.} *

