[White "10) The Shirov Gambit (g4!? M"]
[Black "Shirov Gambit Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "10"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 ({We can also reach our main position after h3} 4... c6 5. g4 g6 {. It's important to note that we avoid Be7 against h3 so we have the fianchetto option. Sometimes, White will just play Bc4 and transpose to the mainlines but until they do, we shouldn't rush Be7 and sometimes will be able to fianchetto it because of White's lack of pressure on f7 .}) ({After finishing the draft of this course, I was delighted to see the Philidor Defense used in the Women's Candidate Championships in 2024 where IM Nurgyul Salimova played it in a high-stakes game against GM Lei Tingjie. In that game, GM Tingjie played Rg1 here, but was held to a draw. Though an interesting game, the contribution to the course is minimal as after Rg1} 4... c6 5. g4 g6 {we're back to our regular lines and IM Salimova went a different course and played h6 instead of g6 on move six. It worked out fine practically though GM Tingjie could have gotten a noteworthy advantage with some hard-to-find moves at one point and so I ultimately decided to not include a different line against it: we just play the moves in this chapter.}) ({White could try Bc4} 4... Be7 {and only now} 5. g4 {Nb6 hitting the bishop and attacking g4 with our bishop so that Rg1 in response to taking won’t threaten anything. White often plays Bb5} c6 {and the computer recommends White try to trade queens and go for equality, with} 6. dxe5 {. Here, taking back the pawn equalizes and probably is an edge for Black practically. Black can take on g4 with the knight for an objectively better but more complicated position as well, so two good options to choose from.}) 5. g4 {[The Shirov Gambit] g4 here marks the start of the Shirov Gambit, named after its first top-rated pioneer: Latvian Super GM Alexei Shirov, whose book Fire on the Board in its title alone reveals a lot about his style. If you are rated between 1200 and 2000, you have about an 8% chance of facing this after Nbd7 , which means it's really remote. After all, Nf3 is already a sideline in Club level play as most players trade queens, so this is a sideline of a sideline. This chapter, therefore, is not a critical one for the masses. I advise most readers to play g6 , look at the basic layout of the pieces, and then make it up as you go along because your opponent will probably be out of book, too.   This chapter is written, therefore, for the people teetering on expert or above, or those who know they will face it for sure. It is incredibly dangerous and there have been Chess.com videos advising White to play in this way along with a Chessable on this for the very, very prepared 1. e4 player. So I would be remiss to not give you a weapon against it, even if it is very rare. In fact, here I have more variations than usual because my readers at this point will be limited to the perfectionists and we have to be careful. I will give you two lines against the mainline and have made this chapter longer than usual to account for the danger of this variation. If you are rated 1600 or below, this chapter is a low priority. It just doesn't come up much and if you just memorize the following moves to make: g6  Bg7  c6  O-O and Nh5 on g5 , you should play it adequately enough.   Since it is so rare for many of you, memorizing a forcing line will often result in memory loss anyway by the time you face it, hundreds of games later. Therefore, I propose an offbeat system to not allow White to play their type of game. I can't get 0.0 if White plays like a computer for the next several upon several moves, but I can promise you that even if you play against Stockfish, the best they will have is a small edge with this weapon and its practicality against humans cannot be understated.} g6 {[Why do I recommend g6 ?]This move is fully trying to counter via the 'g4 wasn't a developing move' idea by fianchettoing our bishop and optimizing its scope over what we had in the Bc4 lines.   Before we move on, I should admit, begrudgingly, that the best way to equalize is to play the 5. ... Nxg4 move, and counter via the 'it loses a pawn' idea. Indeed, that is what is recommended in many books including Sergey Kasparov's older book and Cuenca's Lifetime Repertoire: Philidor Defense here on Chessable. It does equalize for Black after some precise play, but I don't recommend we take it for two reasons:   The first reason I like 5... g6 more than the mainline is that it has a much better win rate for Black. It's a more rare response, and Shirov Gambit players will know those mainlines much better. Even after we end the 5... Nxg4 line with equality, we are in for a big fight of a tactical nature. 5... Nxg4 has a 47%-32% win-loss rate for White in Master level games. 5... g6 in the meantime has a 23%-37% win-loss rate for White. You read that right: White usually loses in Master level games. This alone is evidence of how White players fall apart a bit against it. Even if we look at results 12 moves into the mainline with Black playing perfectly, to rule out Black just getting after pawn grabbing, White still has a winning record against 5... Nxg4 , and in some databases, I don't see a single Black win.   In sub Master Level we see a similar trend when comparing the moves: With 5. ... g6 , Black wins more than White right out the gate and 12 moves in of optimal White play against the sideline, Black is at 47%-47%. With Nxg4 , Black's record is 30%-49% right out the gate, with the higher number there being White's win rate. With perfect play 12 moves in, it gets arguably better and goes to 39%-57%, with draws dropping and Black increasing their chances more than White did by a little but not changing the general divide much. These are the practical facts: Black is losing almost 20% more in the mainline after 12 moves of perfect play than with the move 5. ... g6 !} ({I don't think it's because of the objective evaluation of the resulting position, but rather because they've tricked a Philidor player into playing tactical, quasi-irrational chess. Just look at the most common Master level moves there:} 5... Nxg4 6. Rg1 Ngf6 7. Bc4 {the 7. Be3 sideline also has a high White win rate} h6 8. Be3 c6 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qd3 b5 11. Bb3 {, 11. Bxf7 is another line where Black must sacrifice a queen and then play accurately in a weird follow up position... it's objectively fine yet Black usually loses in human chess,} Qa5 12. O-O-O Ba6 13. Nd2 {we are in the end Mainline position that the Lifetime Repertoires: Philidor Defense and Sergey Kasparov and a ton of others recommend for Black. That involves 12 moves of memorizing concrete moves where one mistake is instant disaster and two deadly sidelines with their own poison.}) ({What would we get for all that sweat over memorizing moves? In the end, the computer gives the evaluation as equal. Good news, right? But according to the Lichess Master level database, in 14 games reached from this position, White won 64% and the rest were draws with not a single Black win. Club Players have fared better with a 40% win record for Black, 50% win record for White, but note they're still losing more than they're winning, implying it's not exactly equal. I think part of the difficulty is the Black plan in the resulting position is tricky, the strategic ideas complicated, and the position concrete and not in the style of the Philidor. White is in heaven in the meantime. They played g4 for an open attacking battle and there's lots of open lines and opportunities to play for checkmate, so psychologically they have obtained what they wanted even when they end up with equality. With some work, I think this variation is okay for Black and maybe even best. But Black players must go beyond memorization and have deep understanding of three types of resulting positions that are all complex. That's a lot of work for a Gambit that will appear in 0.01 percent of Club Player Games and 0.04 percent of Master ones--its rarity making it easier to forget the lines.   The second reason I like g6 over the main reply is because even though it doesn't fully equalize against best play (we will take a very slight disadvantage for the practical edge) it's easier to learn than the alternatives and psychologically difficult for White. Less of your moves hinge on a single tactical shot and it's more philosophical and idea based, very much in the spirit of the course and the opening and agony for players with a Shirov Gambit personality.   [What's the idea behind g6 ?]White's idea was to sacrifice a pawn to open the g file and we say no to the open g-file. g6 guards our knight if it needs to hang out on h5 , prepares to fianchetto the bishop in a way that likely will point to the White king, and plans to close everything down on the kingside.  Additionally, with g6 , g7 isn't hanging anymore in case one day we do want to take the g4 pawn. We will dine on it as soon as we complete development. White can defend it by pushing it and make us play Nh5 , but then h4 - h5 will be harder to accomplish because the g-pawn won't be able to move back to kick away our h5 knight. White could defend it with Rg1 , but then the rook is on the wrong file, as g6 shuts down g-file attacks on our castled king. This presents White with some practical issues in running their attack. This is our piece setup strategy:   The Black bishop will go to g7 and the knight will often go to b6 - c4 possibly -- Nc5 and Nf8 are also possible but harder to pull off against best play.  Nb6 is an especially good rejoinder against Bh3 , which White will be tempted to play because Bc4 will give us tempos on the kingside as we attack it. The reason Nb6 is good against Bh3 is because the c4 square won't be defended, so we'll have a natural advancement plan. Against} 5... g5 {, now or later, we will always play Nh5 and try to play Nf4 . Sometimes playing Nf4 is good even if it loses a pawn because if we get the enemy dark-squared bishop and can open up ours by retaking with the e-pawn, a mating attack is more likely to decide the game than an endgame.  We shouldn't fear castling as White's attack up the center is stronger than it is against our kingside.    Our queen will go to c7 or a5 , situationally-- a5 is more aggressive immediately but gets in the way of our a-pawn pushing later. Pawn wise, we should play c6 to block knights. Although an immediate queenside pawn storms like b5 work practically in lower level play, be a bit careful because they're not engine approved. If you have a talented opponent, White will castle queenside and wait for you to push b5 too soon. Then they will switch gears off attack: trade queens by playing Qd6 , then go after the weak c6 pawn in the endgame, and your king will have trouble activating because of your space disadvantage on the kingside. Generally, if you haven't played b5 , your endgame prospects are fine as you have no easy weaknesses and can take some time to centralize your king and pieces.  So, pawn storm only after completing some development moves as given above or attack with your pieces, not pawns in the beginning.}) *

