1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. h3 {See the alternative way of getting here via 5. h3 in this part.} Bg7 7. Be3 c6 {This setup is very clever for White as a lot of times their whole goal is to get the g4 variation without allowing Black the change to take. And those who take must memorize the idea of h3 as a separate dangerous setup. Luckily, since we play g6 against g4 , against h3 , we just play c6 and then g4  g6  Be3  Bg7 is a clean transposition.} 8. dxe5 {One idea for White is to clarify the center. This is theoretically good for White but in practice, Black is currently 5-0 in Club level play.} dxe5 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Qc7 11. Bh6 {The most popular move where White has many choices.} Re8 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Be2 {This isn't the top played move but the top played move-- g5 --has a horrible record for White while this one has a good one. A general rule of thumb is to be careful with b5 in these positions. Practically, it wins a lot but it's a risky move as after Qd6 by White, the c pawn can be a little weak. So try to attack with pieces for now.} Nf8 {Black has terrific practical results and an equal computer evaluation. The goal is to play h6 for a solid defensive setup--to meet h4  h5 with g5 --and to play Be6 with an attack on a2 or Ne6 - f4 depending on the scenario and what is looking good at the moment.} *

