1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. h3 {See the alternative way of getting here via 5. h3 in this part.} Bg7 7. Be3 c6 {This setup is very clever for White as a lot of times their whole goal is to get the g4 variation without allowing Black the change to take. And those who take must memorize the idea of h3 as a separate dangerous setup. Luckily, since we play g6 against g4 , against h3 , we just play c6 and then g4  g6  Be3  Bg7 is a clean transposition.} 8. g5 Nh5 {Our usual hiding place. This knight is largely just on defense for now until it decides to jump to f4 later and have some fun.} 9. Qd2 {White plays a standard queenside-castling attack formation.} O-O {Don't fear castling here. The center is scarier.} 10. O-O-O Qa5 {With lots of ideas for attacking White's king. Because White was a bit slow with h3 , they're more susceptible to more aggressive queen play than in the mainline. After all, not only did h3 cost a tempo but it stopped White from developing their bishop on that diagonal and hounding the d7 knight so the center play doesn't require us to keep our queen as far back.} 11. Kb1 Nb6 {With the idea of Be6 and Bc4 and queenside expansion. The computer recommends b3 here for White which is a sign of how difficult it is to play White's position despite them having an objectively slight edge. I would take Black every time.} *

