[Black "Shirov Gambit: English Attack"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "20"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. g5 Nh5 7. Be3 {The most common move.} c6 8. Qd2 Bg7 9. O-O-O Qc7 {This is less tactical than Qe7 in my opinion and the usual square for the Black queen in the Philidor.} 10. Be2 O-O {We reach a position that has never occurred in master play but has occurred four times on Lichess, all with White players in the 1900-2150 Lichess range, all White losses. White has, unfortunately, tried four different moves so at this point, it really comes down to playing the position instead of memorizing a variation. Now that the position is move consolidated and liquidation harder for White, we can consider pawn storming. Our plan is to play c5 if White ever plays d5 , to play b5  Nb6 and attack the kingside. The knight can go to f4 as long as we get the dark-squared bishop... in fact, often it's okay to lose a pawn doing it. This position is very cutting edge for both sides and the computer slightly favors White but in practice, Black has always come out on top, at least at the time of writing. This is probably because Black's plan of pawn storming is easier to execute than White's plan, which is very subtle and hard to accomplish.} *

