1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. g5 Nh5 7. Be3 {The most common move.} c6 8. Qd2 Bg7 9. O-O-O Qc7 {This is less tactical than Qe7 in my opinion and the usual square for the Black queen in the Philidor.} 10. d5 c5 {We refuse to allow White an open d-file because our bishop is on g7 so not defending d6 as well as in the Philidor mainline.} 11. Nb5 Qb8 {Guarding d6 and out of the way of our pawns so that we can pawn storm on the queenside. Note: Pawn storming again okay here because White has no way of trading pieces and playing an endgame with an open d-file.} 12. c4 a6 13. Nc3 O-O {This position can arise with lots of different d5 pushes. Unlike the mainline Philidor, we didn't played a5 so didn't mind playing c5 in response to d5 . Black will play b5 next and sacrifice the pawn for open files towards White's king in the style of the Benko gambit: only White never castles into the Benko Gambit's queenside assault! Let's play a few more moves to just get a flavor of the position, though I'll end the MoveTrainer here.} 14. h4 b5 15. cxb5 {Nf4 here is another good move, trying to open up the dark-squared bishop for another pawn... bxa6 is rarely a threat since we want to play Bxa6 in response and open up both a and b files anyway.} Nb6 {Black has a lot of move, but I will go down this line further with this one because it's a common idea against a lot of White plans besides h4 here.} 16. Be2 Nf4 {Again, losing a pawn to open up our dark-squared bishop unopposed is often more than acceptable.} 17. Bxf4 exf4 18. Qxf4 {A bad mistake but it's hard to blame White for wanting to win pawns.} axb5 {White is in trouble with all Black's pieces flowing towards the enemy king. b4  Rxa2 is threatened. Let's see if White just keeps taking Black pawns!} 19. Nxb5 Rxa2 {It's worth seeing the following checkmating line just to give you a sense of how to play the attack with Black against the Shirov Gambit.} 20. Nc3 {I'm just guessing what Club players will do to stop the attack on b2 . There is no way to defend for White.} Bxc3 21. bxc3 Qa7 22. Rd2 Qa3+ {White should be weaping right now. Any king move loses so let's just go over a sample end.} 23. Kb1 Qb3+ 24. Kc1 Ra1# {And that's checkmate.} *

