1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. g5 Nh5 7. Be3 {The most common move.} c6 8. Qd2 Bg7 {Preparing castling and lighting up the long diagonal.} 9. O-O-O Qe7 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Bh3 O-O 12. Na4 f5 {exf5 gxf5 is very double edged and fun. More critical is the computer line of en passant.} 13. gxf6 Qxf6 {This position is difficult for White to play well. Bxd7 can be met by Qxf3 with a trading down to equality so White must go for it with...} 14. Ng5 {Now Black has to be careful. Only one move works! White is threatening to take the Black knight on d7 and if pinned, play Be6 + with a discovered attack on the rook. If Nb6 , they can just trade pieces and play a good bishop versus a bad bishop and Black's attack will be hard to launch.} Nf4 {This move leaves everything hanging! The idea is to meet Bxd7 with Qxg5 .} 15. Bxd7 {The only move for White that doesn't result in a slight edge for Black.} Qxg5 {After finding perfect move after perfect move, White has a slight edge in a position that could be won by either side. An interesting chess game lies ahead!} *

