1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. g5 Nh5 7. Be3 {The most common move.} c6 8. Qd2 Bg7 9. O-O-O Qe7 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Bh3 O-O 12. Na4 f5 13. gxf6 Qxf6 {This position is difficult for White to play well. Bxd7 can be met by Qxf3 with a trading down to equality so White must go for it with...} 14. Ng5 {Now Black has to be careful. Only one move works! White is threatening to take the Black knight on d7 and if pinned, play Be6 + with a discovered attack on the rook. If Nb6 , they can just trade pieces and play a good bishop versus a bad bishop and Black's attack will be hard to launch.} Nf4 {This move leaves everything hanging! The idea is to meet Bxd7 with Qxg5 .} 15. Bxf4 exf4 16. Ne6 Ne5 17. Nxf8 Bxh3 {And Black is winning because the knight isn't coming home.} *

