1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. g5 {The second most popular move.} Nh5 {Why does our knight always retreat here in this variation? Well there's two ideas. First, we want to jam up any h4  h5 ideas. Second, we consider Nf4 and making White consider giving us the bishop pair. Even if we lose a pawn in the process, often our un-contested dark-squared bishop will be a beast.} 7. Be3 {Throughout, the move Rg1 will usually transpose to Rg1 at the beginning. So, we will look at White just castling queenside as fast as possible.} c6 {Black is in no rush to castle into that attack. Activating the queen and neutralizing the d-file pressure is priority number one. For example, after Qd2 and 0-0-0 dxe5  dxe5  Nxe5 will be a looming threat.} 8. Qd2 Bg7 {Bg7 isn't just a reflex move. Be7 is a real contender with the idea of relocating the knight later with Ng7 . That said, it is simple and makes sense. We have to be careful before taking on d4 now as we don't have a bishop to guard d6 .} 9. O-O-O Qe7 {Qc7 is also playable. Here we want to eye g5 though in case White stops defending it, eye the e4 pawn, and think about control of the e7 - a3 diagonal.} 10. dxe5 {White has a queen and a rook on the open diagonal so correctly opens the file.} dxe5 11. Bh3 {Again, great White play. Bc4 as usual would have led to b5  a5 stuff, even better with the opposite wings castling.} O-O {This doesn't hang a knight because Bxd7  Rd8 pins the bishop and takes it back leisurely, securing the bishop pair.} 12. Na4 {White plays on the dark squares. Luckily, we played Qe7 to make occupying c5 trickier. It's not an easy position for White as the g5 pawn jams the usual Bh6 stuff and the h-file is closed. Na5 is a brilliant and not easy to find move though, so we won't usually face it. It is very direct though as the idea is to take on d7 with the white bishop and on Rd8 play Nc5 and Qd6 ideas. The tactics in that crazy position favor White. So we have to cut off the bishop or guard the knight. Moving the knight isn't an option because of Bc5 and Rd8 allows Nc5 anyway because it will be pinned.} f5 {Surprisingly, Black can counterattack on the kingside effectively. The g-pawns travels have weakened the f3 knight. The tactics on this are a bit tricky though, so play close attention just in case you make it this far. That said, other reasonable moves without as much tactical flair could have been used.} 13. Qc3 Qf7 {Eyeing a2 and being careful about tactics on c5 .} 14. Bf1 {White defends cleverly and sets a trap. Qxa2 loses to Bc4 +!} Kh8 {Renewing the threat on a2 . Bc4 isn't a move we're concerned about because it means b5 will carry even more venom later.} 15. a3 fxe4 16. Nd2 Nf4 {Our knight is finally active.} 17. Nxe4 ({This position is very equal. Black has an isolated pawn and a bit less space on the kingside, but active pieces and backward pawns to attack. Black can play} 17. Nb6 {here for a tiny edge according to Stockfish 14. Still, I prefer an even simpler line with no pawn sacrifices. White's attack never quite took off so we have our nice maneuvering battle without any horrible attacks.}) 17... Nd5 {Next we will play N7b6 and enjoy epic knights and queenside pressure. If they take the b6 knight, we will happily open the a-file for our rook. Black has more pressure on White than the other way around and so the engine and most humans would give Black the slight pull.} *

