1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. g5 {The second most popular move.} Nh5 {Why does our knight always retreat here in this variation? Well there's two ideas. First, we want to jam up any h4  h5 ideas. Second, we consider Nf4 and making White consider giving us the bishop pair. Even if we lose a pawn in the process, often our un-contested dark-squared bishop will be a beast.} 7. Be3 {Throughout, the move Rg1 will usually transpose to Rg1 at the beginning. So, we will look at White just castling queenside as fast as possible.} c6 {Black is in no rush to castle into that attack. Activating the queen and neutralizing the d-file pressure is priority number one. For example, after Qd2 and 0-0-0 dxe5  dxe5  Nxe5 will be a looming threat.} 8. Qd2 {White prepares to castle queenside.} Bg7 {Bg7 isn't just a reflex move. Be7 is a real contender with the idea of relocating the knight later with Ng7 . That said, it is simple and makes sense. We have to be careful before taking on d4 now as we don't have a bishop to guard d6 .} 9. O-O-O {White is playing for an opposite wings attack and this fits with g4 --where else was the king going to go.} Qe7 10. dxe5 {White has a queen and a rook on the open diagonal so correctly opens the file. Plus, we haven't castled.} dxe5 11. Bh3 {Again, great White play. Bc4 as usual would have led to b5  a5 stuff, even better with the opposite wings castling. Bh3 puts pressure on the d7 knight and so we have to calculate exchanges carefully. That said, it has its downsides: it's undefended, opening up discovered attack tactics later, and it blocks in the h pawn.} O-O {This doesn't hang a knight because Bxd7  Rd8 pins the bishop and takes it back leisurely, securing the bishop pair.} 12. Bg4 {This looks good for White... aiming to double black's h pawns and clear the f5 square. But it's not actually terribly effective because the light-squared bishop is a very good piece, the h5 pawn takes a long time to take in a position that is essentially a race to checkmate, and because of tactical reasons.} Nb6 {Bxg4 is threatened after any move except Bxh5 . So this variation is very forcing. This is the downside of Bh3 from White's perspective: the discovered attack that ruins the bishops fun. Why not Nc5 ? Well, we want to take advantage of another downside to Bh3 : no control of c4 ! The knight will be great on that square which is even better than c5 !} ({Here, White should play Bxc8 Raxc8} 12... Qd6 {and beg for an endgame that Black can happily accept or even decline with Qe8 when the computer says it's about equal.}) {That said, it's hardly the style of the Shirov Gambit to seek out endgames and there is a little 'about face' in trying to attack the h5 knight only to chicken out at the last moment. So let's go with the move that White will probably play here.} 13. Bxh5 {A useful move to cover because it shows how Black's attack can materialize seemingly out of thin air.} Nc4 14. Qe2 {Just taking out White's bishops would be enough for the structural issues, but here it's even worse than that for White.} Qb4 ({When the computer recommends White play Qxc4 and play down a queen, you know things haven't worked out as planned for them. Qxb2 is threatened and b3} 14... Qa3 15. Kb1 Qxb2# {is game over. The computer gives Black a decisive advantage. The attack-the-knight-plan with Bg4 was just too slow. Black will never even have to recapture the bishop.}) *

