1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. g5 Nh5 7. Be3 {The most common move.} c6 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Bc4 {White has played reasonable moves and is losing. The dangers of playing the Shirov Gambit at the sub master level for you. That said, this mistake is understandable: Bc4 is what White plays in the mainline Shirov Gambit!} Be7 {Black can play slowly here for a clear advantage according to the computer. Even Be7 wasn't forced. The white bishop is misplaced and fodder for accelerating Black's pieces; after all, the f7 pawn will never be under siege and now the knight on h5 is an effective blockader.  Bg7 last move probably would have been fine too but here I like supporting the knight in going to c5 . From here on out, Black will do the usual plan: attack with their pieces and queen and castle kingside. If the bishop on c4 ever slinks back to b3 , Bg4 at some point will be rough for White! This is often the issue with Bc4 : they need that bishop to stop that pressure down the diagonal.} *

