1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. g5 Nh5 7. Bc4 {A favorite at non-professional levels, this move isn't so scary and allows us to equalize. The issue is that it doesn't help White caste queenside or make many direct threats. The f-file is difficult for White to open and Ng5 can't be played against f7 . So the bishop might be fodder for c6  b5 or Qa5 - Qb4 or even Nb6 without contributing much.} Bg7 8. Be3 c6 9. Qd2 {Here, Black has lots of moves: O-O , b5 , Qe7 , Qc7 are all pretty equal. I'd like to propose a new move.} Nb6 {I like this move because it makes our repertoire consistent: against the Shirov Gambit, we are often playing with our pieces against White's queenside. Be2 is best here and about equal but Bb3 will be the auto retreat for most players who chose not to put the bishop on e2 in the first place.} 10. Bb3 Bg4 {With the White light-squared bishop off the long diagonal, Bg4 stings. There's just no Be2 and if the knight moves, castling will be a difficult feat.} 11. Nh4 {Ng1 is better but somehow I think people will prefer this move rather than to put their pieces back on their starting squares.} exd4 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 O-O {Now that we've moved the queen off d2 , Qxg5 is threatened.} 14. Qe3 {An easy mistake to make: it looks natural. But the king has been hanging out in the center for too long.} d5 ({Black threatens to push the d-pawn and fork White and on exd5} 14... Re8 {is crushing. Black has a winning position.}) *

