1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. Rg1 {This is the most played move here. It is logical: defend the pawn. That said, with g6 , our main weakness will be on the h-file, so we are relieved to not have a rook protecting h4 - h5 ideas.} c6 {Many other moves are possible as well, but c6 will be our thematic move, waiting to decide on where everything goes on the kingside.} 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Qd2 exd4 {If White doesn't commit to g5 , taking in the center is a great way to create counterplay. White should take with the queen here, but most players will retake with the knight, which is what we want.} 9. Nxd4 Ne5 {And now we will take on g4 with the g file not going very many places for White. We also have a big threat in c5 , kicking the only piece stopping Nf3 + with a royal fork.} 10. g5 {Or we take it.} Nfg4 {And we see the problem of White delaying g5 : we have more options than Nh5 . Now we should be closing in on equalizing here as White's precious dark-squared bishop is leaving the board and so our g7 bishop will be amazing. Trying to save the bishop ends in doom.} 11. Bf4 (11. O-O-O {was better with an interesting, double-edged and about equal game. This will illustrate how careful White must be.}) 11... c5 {Black is dominating and almost a piece up according to the engine. If the knight moves anywhere then Black will move into f3 with their knight forking the royalty. So it's over.} *

