1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 {Please see this informational, if you haven't already checked it out, for what this move is all about and why I think we should respond as follows.} g6 6. Rg1 {This is the most played move here. It is logical: defend the pawn. That said, with g6 , our main weakness will be on the h-file, so we are relieved to not have a rook protecting h4 - h5 ideas.} c6 {Many other moves are possible as well, but c6 will be our thematic move, waiting to decide on where everything goes on the kingside.} 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Qd2 exd4 {If White doesn't commit to g5 , taking in the center is a great way to create counterplay. White should take with the queen here, but most players will retake with the knight, which is what we want.} 9. Qxd4 {Attacking d4 .} Qe7 {Defending d6 . 10. ... Qc7 was also valid but I like keeping the e-pawn in check here. It looks like the d pawn is falling after White castles but we will hold everything.} 10. O-O-O Ne5 {We're about equal again. We're threatening their knight and the g4 pawn, so White should probably trade knights and allow us to un-backwards and save our d6 pawn.} *

