1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 e5 {[f3 by White Introduction]When we played Nf6 , White's most natural defense of the e-pawn was with the knight, following the rules of developing minor pieces and knights before bishops. Therefore, on the whole, f3 breaks too many opening rules to be considered the main line in any regard. It's played 4% of the time by Club Players and 5% of the time by Masters. Nonetheless, f3 is an interesting way to defend the e4 pawn, totally sound, leading to many non-standard Philidor positions. For Club Players, skimming over this chapter will probably be fine as objectively, it's hard to play for White anyway and you are unlikely to encounter tough opposition with it, but higher rated players should be prepared. One challenge that makes it in need of its own chapter is that f3 is so diverse in how it can be played and the structures you may get out of it. In fact, White may have three completely different intentions in mind! Let's discuss what White may have in store for us:   1. White may want to enter the Queen Trade Line in an attempt to confuse us a bit. Masters play it this way about 38% of the time according to my Lichess database and Club Players around 34% after f3  e5 , so it's something we need to be prepared for. The big difference from the queen trade chapter is that combatting Bc4 is done with Ke8 instead of Be6 . But luckily for us, play is intuitive otherwise in many ways if we are well versed in the queen trade lines.    2. White may want to attack us as if we were playing the Sicilian Dragon--or as if they were playing the English attack against the Najdorf. I call this the f3 Line: Yugoslav Attack . It's not as popular as the next plan I'll cover in Club Level play and almost completely absent in Master Level Play but GM Jesse Kraai, in his Chessable course on 1.e4 recommends playing in this way against the Pirc or the Modern, which is totally viable and even dangerous for Black, and we may also encounter some confused players, thinking it's the same position because of our first two moves. Unfortunately for them, it doesn't work well against the Philidor. In fact, White has to be extremely careful in their move order and placement and even if they are, we have strong counters. For example, not pushing d5 , or playing Nc3 before f3 , fall into move order problems. I consider this method of play the least difficult for a prepared Black player to face, and I handle it along with the move order debacles in this chapter.    2. A more sophisticated approach is to try to build a gigantic and crushing pawn center, suffocating our pieces under its tyrannical grip. It views 3. f3 as the start of this magnificent pawn chain and I call it f3 Line: The Squeeze . White plays d5 later and takes advantage of not having played Nc3 by playing c4 to put even more pawns in the center. Once achieved, they have a giant pawn center and plan on squeezing us to death to the point where we can't move. It's not very nice and the main way this is played. Luckily for us, there's some issues. One problem for White is that they must break so many opening rules in playing this way and are, as a result, severely underdeveloped. I give two ways of playing, one strategic, idea-based and fully in the spirit with the course as my main recommendation, and the other a guilty pleasure of sorts in a rare, enterprising pawn sacrifice aimed at immediately obliterating White's strategy.} *

