[Black "f3 Line: White Refuses to Pus"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "24"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 {White defends the pawn with a pawn instead of developing a knight. At first, this seems to violate chess principles. After all, the pawn on f3 gets in the way of the knight and weakens the dark diagonals to the king. But the point is that White wants to play Be3  Qd2 and castle queenside, launching a pawn storm at you. Sounds scary, right? Well, they call this the Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw, so yes, it's scary. Additionally, in Master games, White wins 43% to Black's 18% after e5 . So this isn't a wing it opening.   Some good news:   1. I don't think it's the hardest opening to play against for Philidor players as long as you do a little homework. Most openings that violate opening principles are more smoke than fire against correct play.   2. It's incredibly fun to play against. You will feel alive!   3. In Club Level play, the win rates are much more balanced at 48% win rate for White and 47% for Black, the rest draws. Here, Black has many effective deviations. For example, 4. ... d5  e5 is a French Defense where we lost a tempo on d6  d5 but White played f3 instead of f4 .   4. ... c5 transposes to a Benoni, Benko, Sicilian or even French-like position where f3 is often not ideal. If you play those, you have another out. 4... c5 was the favorite of Kramnik, Jobava, Dominguez Perez, and Caruana--essentially a bunch of Super GM's!   I really wanted to recommend c5 but it's hard to recommend you learn how to play the Benko Gambit, French Defense and Sicilian as a backup for when your opponent plays f3 . That certainly would be doable on the Super GM level where we live and breathe chess but for the rest of us, we need to sometimes be practical. Therefore, I recommend stepping right into the lion's jaw.} e5 4. Be3 Be7 {exd4 is also good, but to simplify our prep, let's offer to transpose to d5 .} 5. Nc3 {This is the most popular move at Club Level.} O-O 6. Qd2 {White's plan is very aggressive. They will castle queenside and throw their pawns up at us.} Nbd7 {For now, Black doesn't need to react and should just complete their development in the usual fashion.} 7. O-O-O c6 {And now White shouldn't play a4 because then Black could still play b5 later and open up files heading right towards the White king. This means we are going to get a queenside pawn storm versus a kingside pawn storm! We're in for some rain! A quick word of caution though, holding the a-pawn back is often a good idea. The queen often wants to go to a5 to eat the a2 pawn after we kick the knight and putting a pawn there would delay our attack. Unless White plays a3 , therefore, we will just play b5 for now.  a5 is not a bad move but committal. Black has a 31% win, 15% loss rate in this position even though objectively it is even. This is probably because mindless White play backfires badly.} 8. Kb1 {A sensible move. White usually plays g4 right away but this is a careful move you may encounter.} b5 9. g4 {White must attack the kingside or we will just play b4  Qa5 and Be6 ideas against the White king.} b4 10. Nce2 d5 {Qa5 was logical but this move is very good and White has to be careful here. 11. g5 is the only move as any pawn capture activates one of the Black knights and gives Black an edge. If White does nothing, we want to play pxe4 and take the g4 pawn.} 11. g5 {The best and only move that preserves White's position.} Ne8 12. h4 Nd6 {The position is roughly balanced but slightly more intuitive for Black because their pieces have normal squares to go to. We will target a2 or think about sacrifices on b2 . Another possible plan is a5 and c5 with a pawn storm.} *

