1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 {White defends the pawn with a pawn instead of developing a knight. At first, this seems to violate chess principles. After all, the pawn on f3 gets in the way of the knight and weakens the dark diagonals to the king. But the point is that White wants to play Be3  Qd2 and castle queenside, launching a pawn storm at you. Sounds scary, right? Well, they call this the Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw, so yes, it's scary. Additionally, in Master games, White wins 43% to Black's 18% after e5 . So this isn't a wing it opening. Some good news: 1. I don't think it's the hardest opening to play against for Philidor players as long as you do a little homework. Most openings that violate opening principles are more smoke than fire against correct play. 2. It's incredibly fun to play against. You will feel alive! 3. In Club Level play, the win rates are much more balanced at 48% win rate for White and 47% for Black, the rest draws. Here, Black has many effective deviations. For example, 4. ... d5  e5 is a French Defense where we lost a tempo on d6  d5 but White played f3 instead of f4 . 4. ... c5 transposes to a Benoni, Benko, Sicilian or even French-like position where f3 is often not ideal. That move was the favorite of Kramnik, Jobava, Dominguez Perez, and Caruana--essentially a bunch of Super GM's! I really wanted to recommend c5 but it's hard to recommend you learn how to play the Benko Gambit, French Defense and Sicilian as a backup for when your opponent plays f3 . That certainly would be doable on the Super GM level where we live and breathe chess but for the rest of us, we need to sometimes be practical. Therefore, I recommend stepping right into the lion's jaw.} e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 {An unsual variation of the queen trade line arises here.} 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Let's assess. On the one hand, White has not committed the knight to c3 . This allows Nd2 - c4 possibilities and is a pro for White. On the other hand, they are less well developed here, with the f3 pawn making f4 a whole tempo down on the other line and blocking the knight's best square. If we're allowed to play Be6 next, we will have a sedate Bg5 variation. So, White should play...} 6. Bc4 {Here, this endgame is like many of the others. Only unfortunately, the doubled pawns work less well without the knight commited to c3 (as they have Nd2 - c4 ideas which will hit a bishop on d6 and the e5 pawn.).} Ke8 {This move is playable against Bc4 as well but here it's even better because the wasted development downside of it in the mainline Bc4 isn't as relevant because White isn't so well developed themselves.} 7. Be3 Bb4+ {We are ready for Nc3 , looking like a normal Bc4 line where we can ruin their structure and play against the c4 square later after Be6 . But we don't want to play Bd6 and find ourselves facing Nd2 so we ask White to commit the knight one way or another.} 8. c3 {After Black checks to see if a knight is going to c3 in dramatic fashion. White has answered 'no' as c3 will block that knight move} Ba5 {And we will do our normal queenside pawn storm. The trade of bishops will favor Black a little and then we can even try an f6 fortress for our king later.} *

