1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 {White defends the pawn with a pawn instead of developing a knight. At first, this seems to violate chess principles. After all, the pawn on f3 gets in the way of the knight and weakens the dark diagonals to the king. But the point is that White wants to play Be3  Qd2 and castle queenside, launching a pawn storm at you. Sounds scary, right? Well, they call this the Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw, so yes, it's scary. Additionally, in Master games, White wins 43% to Black's 18% after e5 . So this isn't a wing it opening. Some good news: 1. I don't think it's the hardest opening to play against for Philidor players as long as you do a little homework. Most openings that violate opening principles are more smoke than fire against correct play. 2. It's incredibly fun to play against. You will feel alive! 3. In Club Level play, the win rates are much more balanced at 48% win rate for White and 47% for Black, the rest draws. Here, Black has many effective deviations. For example, 4. ... d5  e5 is a French Defense where we lost a tempo on d6  d5 but White played f3 instead of f4 . 4. ... c5 transposes to a Benoni, Benko, Sicilian or even French-like position where f3 is often not ideal. That move was the favorite of Kramnik, Jobava, Dominguez Perez, and Caruana--essentially a bunch of Super GM's! I really wanted to recommend c5 but it's hard to recommend you learn how to play the Benko Gambit, French Defense and Sicilian as a backup for when your opponent plays f3 . That certainly would be doable on the Super GM level where we live and breathe chess but for the rest of us, we need to sometimes be practical. Therefore, I recommend stepping right into the lion's jaw.} e5 4. d5 {This is the main move in both Master and Club Level play with a close second being dxe5 . For some reason, in my personal experience, I see Nge2 the most and I have no idea why. d5 is probably the biggest try for an advantage. White is just trying to control everything and creating a long pawn chain.} Be7 {c6 is another popular move but it allows c4 and I'd prefer to keep things flexible for now.} 5. Be3 {Be3 is the main move and the most played. And here we have a major turning point in terms of how Black should proceed. Grandmasters have been divided and the following moves have been tried: c6 , Nfd7 !?, Nh5 , 0-0. Personally, I think c6 is the most intensely fighting line because Black should really sacrifice a pawn to blow things open before White can consolidate their center. It's not to everyone's taste, so I'll list it as an alternative line.} O-O {0-0 is a waiting move. We are looking to see whether White plays c4 .} 6. Bd3 {Now the c6 plan is even better as they have wasted a tempo. So c6 is definitely good, but to make things consistent...} Nh5 7. Qd2 {Without c4 , things are a bit different. f5 could lose a piece because we can't swap the bishop for the b1 knight in an emergency. Still, the bishop on d3 allows us to try to make our knight even better.} Nf4 {For those who want a safer course, h6  Bg5 is also a good plan.} 8. Bxf4 {This is a mistake but it's sometimes hard to resist what looks like a free pawn.} exf4 9. Ne2 Bg5 10. Nxf4 {It may seem like the knight can be protected but actually this is going to be an avalanche against White. The computer says Black is up 4 points!} Qf6 {This is what White players typically miscalculate: it's not just about the knight but also about b2 and the a1 rook.} 11. g3 Qxb2 12. Qc3 {This doesn't stop us from winning a rook.} Qc1+ {And Black is winning a lot of material.} *

