{And now White should play Qe3 Bg6 and accept a worse position without much of an attack but of course, there's always the ability to make things worse with 12. g4 ? Bxg4 . Black is up about 1.29 according to Stockfish 14. Not bad for the opening.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 {White defends the pawn with a pawn instead of developing a knight. At first, this seems to violate chess principles. After all, the pawn on f3 gets in the way of the knight and weakens the dark diagonals to the king. But the point is that White wants to play Be3  Qd2 and castle queenside, launching a pawn storm at you. Sounds scary, right? Well, they call this the Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw, so yes, it's scary. Additionally, in Master games, White wins 43% to Black's 18% after e5 . So this isn't a wing it opening. Some good news: 1. I don't think it's the hardest opening to play against for Philidor players as long as you do a little homework. Most openings that violate opening principles are more smoke than fire against correct play. 2. It's incredibly fun to play against. You will feel alive! 3. In Club Level play, the win rates are much more balanced at 48% win rate for White and 47% for Black, the rest draws. Here, Black has many effective deviations. For example, 4. ... d5  e5 is a French Defense where we lost a tempo on d6  d5 but White played f3 instead of f4 . 4. ... c5 transposes to a Benoni, Benko, Sicilian or even French-like position where f3 is often not ideal. That move was the favorite of Kramnik, Jobava, Dominguez Perez, and Caruana--essentially a bunch of Super GM's! I really wanted to recommend c5 but it's hard to recommend you learn how to play the Benko Gambit, French Defense and Sicilian as a backup for when your opponent plays f3 . That certainly would be doable on the Super GM level where we live and breathe chess but for the rest of us, we need to sometimes be practical. Therefore, I recommend stepping right into the lion's jaw.} e5 4. d5 {This is the main move in both Master and Club Level play with a close second being dxe5 . For some reason, in my personal experience, I see Nge2 the most and I have no idea why. d5 is probably the biggest try for an advantage. White is just trying to control everything and creating a long pawn chain.} Be7 {c6 is another popular move but it allows c4 and I'd prefer to keep things flexible for now.} 5. Be3 {Be3 is the main move and the most played. And here we have a major turning point in terms of how Black should proceed. Grandmasters have been divided and the following moves have been tried: c6 , Nfd7 !?, Nh5 , 0-0. Personally, I think c6 is the most intensely fighting line because Black should really sacrifice a pawn to blow things open before White can consolidate their center. It's not to everyone's taste, so I'll list it as an alternative line.} O-O {0-0 is a waiting move. We are looking to see whether White plays c4 .} 6. c4 Nh5 {A system where Black tries to jam up the queenside with Nfd7  a5  Na6 worked out in precise detail was the path of the Lifetime Philidor class here on Chessable. It's a good plan but for the sake of adding something new, let's follow Eljanov in his game against a titan of chess, Boris Gelfand.} 7. Qd2 {Gelfand's choice and consistent.} f5 ({At first it seems like exf5} 7... Bf5 8. g4 {wins a piece but then Bxb1 and all is fine for Black with g4 weakening White's kingside. f5 is relatively new with 7. ... h6 followed by Black playing Bg5 to trade the bishops being the usual path here. But f5 has been previously unexplored and is quite underrated, giving it surprise value, soundness and venom! White has only one move to not be a little worse: 8. exf5 . Otherwise, we will play Bh4 + and then f4 . So not only is this idea new, but it's tricky. In fact, in Lichess games, White has played Nc3 in 4 out of 6 Club Player games, which gives Black a small edge!}) 8. Nc3 Bh4+ {This check has never been played before but is the engine's top choice and gives Black a tiny edge if White finds some hard to play moves. How hard to play? Well, as White, what is the right move here? Believe it or not, it's not g3 (that's much worse for White) or Bf2 (again, worse for White) but Kd1 is the only move that retains close to equality for White.} 9. Bf2 {This move isn't great because the White dark-squared bishop is so much better than the Black one (just look at the pawns!).} Bxf2+ 10. Qxf2 a5 {And Black says 'all your dark-squares belong to me.' The knight on the queenside will go to c5 or b4 , the other to f4 or f6 . Black has a clear edge in all lines according to the engine.} 11. exf5 Bxf5 *

