1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 {White defends the pawn with a pawn instead of developing a knight. At first, this seems to violate chess principles. After all, the pawn on f3 gets in the way of the knight and weakens the dark diagonals to the king. But the point is that White wants to play Be3  Qd2 and castle queenside, launching a pawn storm at you. Sounds scary, right? Well, they call this the Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw, so yes, it's scary. Additionally, in Master games, White wins 43% to Black's 18% after e5 . So this isn't a wing it opening. Some good news: 1. I don't think it's the hardest opening to play against for Philidor players as long as you do a little homework. Most openings that violate opening principles are more smoke than fire against correct play. 2. It's incredibly fun to play against. You will feel alive! 3. In Club Level play, the win rates are much more balanced at 48% win rate for White and 47% for Black, the rest draws. Here, Black has many effective deviations. For example, 4. ... d5  e5 is a French Defense where we lost a tempo on d6  d5 but White played f3 instead of f4 . 4. ... c5 transposes to a Benoni, Benko, Sicilian or even French-like position where f3 is often not ideal. That move was the favorite of Kramnik, Jobava, Dominguez Perez, and Caruana--essentially a bunch of Super GM's! I really wanted to recommend c5 but it's hard to recommend you learn how to play the Benko Gambit, French Defense and Sicilian as a backup for when your opponent plays f3 . That certainly would be doable on the Super GM level where we live and breathe chess but for the rest of us, we need to sometimes be practical. Therefore, I recommend stepping right into the lion's jaw.} e5 4. d5 {This is the main move in both Master and Club Level play with a close second being dxe5 . For some reason, in my personal experience, I see Nge2 the most and I have no idea why. d5 is probably the biggest try for an advantage. White is just trying to control everything and creating a