1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 {White defends the pawn with a pawn instead of developing a knight. At first, this seems to violate chess principles. After all, the pawn on f3 gets in the way of the knight and weakens the dark diagonals to the king. But the point is that White wants to play Be3  Qd2 and castle queenside, launching a pawn storm at you. Sounds scary, right? Well, they call this the Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw, so yes, it's scary. Additionally, in Master games, White wins 43% to Black's 18% after e5 . So this isn't a wing it opening. Some good news: 1. I don't think it's the hardest opening to play against for Philidor players as long as you do a little homework. Most openings that violate opening principles are more smoke than fire against correct play. 2. It's incredibly fun to play against. You will feel alive! 3. In Club Level play, the win rates are much more balanced at 48% win rate for White and 47% for Black, the rest draws. Here, Black has many effective deviations. For example, 4. ... d5  e5 is a French Defense where we lost a tempo on d6  d5 but White played f3 instead of f4 . 4. ... c5 transposes to a Benoni, Benko, Sicilian or even French-like position where f3 is often not ideal. That move was the favorite of Kramnik, Jobava, Dominguez Perez, and Caruana--essentially a bunch of Super GM's! I really wanted to recommend c5 but it's hard to recommend you learn how to play the Benko Gambit, French Defense and Sicilian as a backup for when your opponent plays f3 . That certainly would be doable on the Super GM level where we live and breathe chess but for the rest of us, we need to sometimes be practical. Therefore, I recommend stepping right into the lion's jaw.} e5 4. d5 {This is the main move in both Master and Club Level play with a close second being dxe5 . For some reason, in my personal experience, I see Nge2 the most and I have no idea why. d5 is probably the biggest try for an advantage. White is just trying to control everything and creating a long pawn chain.} Be7 {c6 is another popular move but it allows c4 and I'd prefer to keep things flexible for now.} 5. Be3 {Be3 is the main move and the most played. And here we have a major turning point in terms of how Black should proceed. Grandmasters have been divided and the following moves have been tried: c6 , Nfd7 !?, Nh5 , 0-0. Personally, I think c6 is the most intensely fighting line because Black should really sacrifice a pawn to blow things open before White can consolidate their center. It's not to everyone's taste, so I'll list it as an alternative line.} O-O {0-0 is a waiting move. We are looking to see whether White plays c4 .} 6. c4 {I think c4 is much better than Nc3 because c6 has a little less bite (though it's still playable!) .} a5 {I recommend this move guarding c5 as an alternative to Nh5 , the main move. The idea is twofold: we prevent b4 by White in the event White castles kingside (the main point) and if White castles queenside, it helps activate our rook and attack the queenside. You'll need a bit of self study as I won't go over all lines here, but if you don't like the other knight move, this is a good option.} 7. Nc3 {A natural move to help in castling queenside.} Na6 8. Qd2 c6 {Nd7 was also possible with the idea of installing a perpetual knight on the queenside. The idea of c6 is to open files on the queenside as Qd2 indicates the opponent's king will find their home on c1 .} 9. Bd3 cxd5 {We open as many files as possible.} 10. cxd5 Nd7 {I'm not sure recapturing the knight on c5 with a pawn is always good, so let's bring reinforcements, shall we?} 11. Nh3 Ndc5 {We use the a6 knight to hold this point. The reason we use the d7 knight instead of the a6 is for two reasons. First, we want our bishop on c8 to have life. Second, if the d7 knight was staying there, it could only go to b6 while the a6 knight can go to b4 , which is great for tactical shots later as we will double up on attacking d3 . We would love to take the h3 knight here and weaken the White structure.} 12. Nf2 {It's equal and tense! I recommend taking the bishop pair here...} Nxd3+ 13. Nxd3 b6 {This move helps us install a knight on c5 without worrying about giving White a protected passed pawn. Black can follow up with f5  Nc5 and Ba6 . It's equal but White's plan is tricky and if they castle queenside, they will be worse because of the open c-file.} *

