1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 {White defends the pawn with a pawn instead of developing a knight. At first, this seems to violate chess principles. After all, the pawn on f3 gets in the way of the knight and weakens the dark diagonals to the king. But the point is that White wants to play Be3  Qd2 and castle queenside, launching a pawn storm at you. Sounds scary, right? Well, they call this the Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw, so yes, it's scary. Additionally, in Master games, White wins 43% to Black's 18% after e5 . So this isn't a wing it opening. Some good news: 1. I don't think it's the hardest opening to play against for Philidor players as long as you do a little homework. Most openings that violate opening principles are more smoke than fire against correct play. 2. It's incredibly fun to play against. You will feel alive! 3. In Club Level play, the win rates are much more balanced at 48% win rate for White and 47% for Black, the rest draws. Here, Black has many effective deviations. For example, 4. ... d5  e5 is a French Defense where we lost a tempo on d6  d5 but White played f3 instead of f4 . 4. ... c5 transposes to a Benoni, Benko, Sicilian or even French-like position where f3 is often not ideal. That move was the favorite of Kramnik, Jobava, Dominguez Perez, and Caruana--essentially a bunch of Super GM's! I really wanted to recommend c5 but it's hard to recommend you learn how to play the Benko Gambit, French Defense and Sicilian as a backup for when your opponent plays f3 . That certainly would be doable on the Super GM level where we live and breathe chess but for the rest of us, we need to sometimes be practical. Therefore, I recommend stepping right into the lion's jaw.} e5 4. d5 {This is the main move in both Master and Club Level play with a close second being dxe5 . For some reason, in my personal experience, I see Nge2 the most and I have no idea why. d5 is probably the biggest try for an advantage. White is just trying to control everything and creating a long pawn chain.} Be7 {c6 is another popular move but it allows c4 and I'd prefer to keep things flexible for now.} 5. Be3 {Be3 is the main move and the most played. And here we have a major turning point in terms of how Black should proceed. Grandmasters have been divided and the following moves have been tried: c6 , Nfd7 !?, Nh5 , 0-0. Personally, I think c6 is the most intensely fighting line because Black should really sacrifice a pawn to blow things open before White can consolidate their center. It's not to everyone's taste, so I'll list it as an alternative line.} c6 {We are threatening to take on d5 and make White take back with their strong e-pawn, breaking their chain and allowing f5 later, creating mobile center pawns and attacking chances. White should stop this.} 6. c4 {White will still have to take back with a pawn if Black takes but is importantly preserving the very long pawn chain. The c4 pawn is quite annoying and we should remove it from the equation even at the cost of a pawn.} b5 {What is the idea of this move? Well, first, it is a gambit. We can't technically regain the pawn after cxb5 , but we will have a lot of very active play and full compensation. Our idea if White allows it is to take on c4 and enjoy active play for our pieces, including our rook--which will have the b-file--and our bishop--which will be able to develop to a6 . Many of these players on the White side who play these structures like closed maneuvering games so psychologically, this can be difficult. The move b5 has been played only three times in master games--though boasting very high rated players on the Black side of 2600, 2599, and 2319. White has a few options in reply and the positions are a bit different from our normal ones, so I would recommend this for my higher rated readers or those who don't mind a little bit of extra work in learning the dynamics of this position.} 7. cxb5 {This is how White can accept the pawn sacrifice.} cxd5 8. exd5 {The Black pieces will all find easy squares to go to and in order to keep the pawn, White will have to give us their beautiful dark-squared bishop once we play Nb6 and Bb7 . Then there will be lots of dark squared issues in their camp.} Nbd7 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. Bc4 Nb6 {Our play is easy to remember: just focus everything on d5 .} 11. Bb3 {White is trying to keep the two bishops and the pawn on d5 . But this can't be: they must make a concession.} a6 {What's the idea? To play Rxa6 and then Qa8 hitting the d5 pawn more times than White can defend it. Or if White doesn't take, to take White and distract a defender from d5 --like the knight--with axb5 .} 12. bxa6 Rxa6 {The rook guards the b6 knight and clears the a8 square for the queen to continue the attack on d5 !} 13. Nge2 Qa8 {And White must give us the bishop pair and pressure down the open queenside files or return the pawn. We are happy either way. Let's look at if they keep the pawn as I have a feeling that is what will scare most of my readers.} 14. Bxb6 Rxb6 {The dark squares in White's camp are weak, their bishop is bad and the queenside pressure is also good.  d5 needs constant babysitting which stymies White's ability to play moves they want.} 15. O-O O-O 16. Qd2 Ba6 {The computer says completely equal but I'll leave it to you to determine whether you like this alternative line or the main one. Black is very active with lots of pressure and in the worst case scenario can trade light-squared bishop for knight to achieve an opposite colored bishop ending for assistance in holding. But for now, it would be a pity to lose such a dragon on a6 . Black's play is fun and easy. They will one day play g6  f5 and dominate both sides of the board in return for the pawn. Black has a slight edge and more than enough compensation.} *

