1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 {White defends the pawn with a pawn instead of developing a knight. At first, this seems to violate chess principles. After all, the pawn on f3 gets in the way of the knight and weakens the dark diagonals to the king. But the point is that White wants to play Be3  Qd2 and castle queenside, launching a pawn storm at you. Sounds scary, right? Well, they call this the Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw, so yes, it's scary. Additionally, in Master games, White wins 43% to Black's 18% after e5 . So this isn't a wing it opening. Some good news: 1. I don't think it's the hardest opening to play against for Philidor players as long as you do a little homework. Most openings that violate opening principles are more smoke than fire against correct play. 2. It's incredibly fun to play against. You will feel alive! 3. In Club Level play, the win rates are much more balanced at 48% win rate for White and 47% for Black, the rest draws. Here, Black has many effective deviations. For example, 4. ... d5  e5 is a French Defense where we lost a tempo on d6  d5 but White played f3 instead of f4 . 4. ... c5 transposes to a Benoni, Benko, Sicilian or even French-like position where f3 is often not ideal. That move was the favorite of Kramnik, Jobava, Dominguez Perez, and Caruana--essentially a bunch of Super GM's! I really wanted to recommend c5 but it's hard to recommend you learn how to play the Benko Gambit, French Defense and Sicilian as a backup for when your opponent plays f3 . That certainly would be doable on the Super GM level where we live and breathe chess but for the rest of us, we need to sometimes be practical. Therefore, I recommend stepping right into the lion's jaw.} e5 4. d5 {This is the main move in both Master and Club Level play with a close second being dxe5 . For some reason, in my personal experience, I see Nge2 the most and I have no idea why. d5 is probably the biggest try for an advantage. White is just trying to control everything and creating a long pawn chain.} Be7 {c6 is another popular move but it allows c4 and I'd prefer to keep things flexible for now.} 5. Be3 {Be3 is the main move and the most played. And here we have a major turning point in terms of how Black should proceed. Grandmasters have been divided and the following moves have been tried: c6 , Nfd7 !?, Nh5 , 0-0. Personally, I think c6 is the most intensely fighting line because Black should really sacrifice a pawn to blow things open before White can consolidate their center. It's not to everyone's taste, so I'll list it as an alternative line.} c6 6. c4 b5 {What is the idea of this move? Well, first, it is a gambit. We can't technically regain the pawn after cxb5 , but we will have a lot of very active play and full compensation. Our idea if White allows it is to take on c4 and enjoy active play for our pieces, including our rook--which will have the b-file--and our bishop--which will be able to develop to a6 . Many of these players on the White side who play these structures like closed maneuvering games so psychologically, this can be difficult. The move b5 has been played only three times in master games--though boasting very high rated players on the Black side of 2600, 2599, and 2319. White has a few options in reply and the positions are a bit different from our normal ones, so I would recommend this for my higher rated readers or those who don't mind a little bit of extra work in learning the dynamics of this position.} 7. b3 {This is probably what a lot of scared players will do who don't want to go into a prepped gambit. But it allows Black equality. Like with most moves, we react slowly not quickly, just happy to keep the awkward tension on the queenside.} O-O ({Believe it or not, this is a new move even though it's natural. We are ready for cxb5} 7... cxd5 {. We are also ready for dxc6 bxc4 lines where we prioritize very active pieces over being greedy, confident it will result in us winning pawns back in the end.}) 8. Nc3 {White tries to keep the tension, not wanting to activate our pieces. They also defend d5 and really do think about taking on b5 .} b4 {We don't want them to be able to control d5 so easily. The knight must move and there's no great squares for it.} 9. Na4 {This is probably best so as not to block in the other knight. Now here, c5 would be a bit of a mistake as we don't want to close the queenside just yet. After all, we have great play and if it gets all locked up, we'll be left only able to play on the kingside, where we'll be confronted with g4  h4 and a horror fest.} Na6 {Again, typically, Black has a bit more space on the queenside in these lines and so we don't want to hurry to play c5 and lock everything down. We are considering taking on d5 but there's no rush, it's okay for White to take us as they have no c3 square to bounce off of unto the position and Nc5 will always be strong in the resulting structure.} 10. dxc6 {White could take instead of waiting for us to take them. Fine by us!} Qc7 {This outwardly looks scary... here we have this backward d-pawn on an open file and no hope to ever push it to d5 . But the more you look at this very weird position, the more you realize there's nothing to be afraid of. White's knights cannot easily get to d5 and if they do, they can be taken by Black's minor pieces. A Black knight will sit on c5 , and if it ever is taken, the Black d-pawn will no longer be backwards. This position has never been reached, but I'll continue making computer moves (providing they are logical and human-like) to show you how play may unfold.} 11. a3 {This makes sense as White wants to do something with the a4 knight.} bxa3 {The a3 pawn is untakeable because of d5 , so White will have to recapture it later.} 12. Bd3 Nb4 13. Ne2 Nxc6 {Taking with the knight renews the bishops awkward defense of a3 .} 14. Nac3 {White aims to control d5 . Our play continues to be on the queenside.} Bd7 15. Nb5 Qa5+ {We aren't trying to be up a pawn, just trying to be active, connect our rooks and take advantage of the b4 wholes for White. Generally, White has the d pawn to attack but the knight b5 isn't there to stay (a6 is coming) and their backwards b-pawn is annoying to defend.} 16. Kf2 {The best move as the bishop is effective on e3 and Bd2  Qb6 would have made activating the h1 rook hard.} a6 {I will end the move trainer here for the exhausted but will continue with analysis for the excited!} 17. Nxa3 Rfb8 18. Bc2 Qd8 19. Nb1 Be6 20. Nbc3 Nd7 {And both sides have their backward pawns. Maneuvering is in order and not surprisingly, best moves by both sides have led to an equal-ish position, though the computer still gives Black a pull and practically Black's position is a bit easier to play. The plan is to play on the queenside and let your knights frolic on that side of the board.} *

