1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 {White defends the pawn with a pawn instead of developing a knight. At first, this seems to violate chess principles. After all, the pawn on f3 gets in the way of the knight and weakens the dark diagonals to the king. But the point is that White wants to play Be3  Qd2 and castle queenside, launching a pawn storm at you. Sounds scary, right? Well, they call this the Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw, so yes, it's scary. Additionally, in Master games, White wins 43% to Black's 18% after e5 . So this isn't a wing it opening. Some good news: 1. I don't think it's the hardest opening to play against for Philidor players as long as you do a little homework. Most openings that violate opening principles are more smoke than fire against correct play. 2. It's incredibly fun to play against. You will feel alive! 3. In Club Level play, the win rates are much more balanced at 48% win rate for White and 47% for Black, the rest draws. Here, Black has many effective deviations. For example, 4. ... d5  e5 is a French Defense where we lost a tempo on d6  d5 but White played f3 instead of f4 . 4. ... c5 transposes to a Benoni, Benko, Sicilian or even French-like position where f3 is often not ideal. That move was the favorite of Kramnik, Jobava, Dominguez Perez, and Caruana--essentially a bunch of Super GM's! I really wanted to recommend c5 but it's hard to recommend you learn how to play the Benko Gambit, French Defense and Sicilian as a backup for when your opponent plays f3 . That certainly would be doable on the Super GM level where we live and breathe chess but for the rest of us, we need to sometimes be practical. Therefore, I recommend stepping right into the lion's jaw.} e5 4. d5 {This is the main move in both Master and Club Level play with a close second being dxe5 . For some reason, in my personal experience, I see Nge2 the most and I have no idea why. d5 is probably the biggest try for an advantage. White is just trying to control everything and creating a long pawn chain.} Be7 {c6 is another popular move but it allows c4 and I'd prefer to keep things flexible for now.} 5. Be3 {Be3 is the main move and the most played. And here we have a major turning point in terms of how Black should proceed. Grandmasters have been divided and the following moves have been tried: c6 , Nfd7 !?, Nh5 , 0-0. Personally, I think c6 is the most intensely fighting line because Black should really sacrifice a pawn to blow things open before White can consolidate their center. It's not to everyone's taste, so I'll list it as an alternative line.} c6 6. c4 b5 {What is the idea of this move? Well, first, it is a gambit. We can't technically regain the pawn after cxb5 , but we will have a lot of very active play and full compensation. Our idea if White allows it is to take on c4 and enjoy active play for our pieces, including our rook--which will have the b-file--and our bishop--which will be able to develop to a6 . Many of these players on the White side who play these structures like closed maneuvering games so psychologically, this can be difficult. The move b5 has been played only three times in master games--though boasting very high rated players on the Black side of 2600, 2599, and 2319. White has a few options in reply and the positions are a bit different from our normal ones, so I would recommend this for my higher rated readers or those who don't mind a little bit of extra work in learning the dynamics of this position.} 7. dxc6 {White can take this pawn, now or later.} bxc4 ({Now Bxc4} 7... Nxc6 {seems like the natural sequence but in Gallagher vs. Pelletier 2012, the player of the White pieces chose to activate their queen, which has concrete threats and I list it as the main one. If White instead recaptures the pawn simply with the bishop, we would arrive at a position that looks a little like a Sicilian where the black b pawn has been traded for the White c-pawn. That's a good deal for us because we don't have Marozy Bind ideas for White.}) 8. Qa4 {I'm not sure if Qa4 is objectively the best move but it is practically a challenging one. White threatens c7 + and aims to play on the diagonals. It was also the try of a 2500 in this position.} Qc7 9. Bxc4 Nxc6 ({Not} 9... Qxc6 10. Bb5 {.}) 10. Nc3 {10. Ne2 was better but Nc3 is incredibly natural given all the places for the White knight to advance on the Black army. After 10. Ne2 , we would continue in a similar fashion.} Bd7 11. Rc1 {And now Rb8 might be slightly stronger than our move--we will continue following Pelletier--but Rb8 results in yet another pawn sacrifice after the natural Bb5  a6 ! and the position is obscure enough that I don't know about memorizing some tiny 0.1 advantage when we could play simpler and still get a good position.} Nd4 {Here, Gallagher played Nb5 which looks reasonable but Pelletier could have replied (12… Qb8 ) when the threat of a6 and queenside play give Black a strong edge. So, we should probably go with White's objectively best move and live by the adage, prepare for the worst, hope for the best.} 12. Qa6 {Defending the bishop.} Rc8 {The computer prefers Rb8 but Rc8 is simpler without a lot lost. It also discourages the pawn structure after Bxd4 . White should play Nb5 rather than accepting a pin on the c-file.} 13. Bxd4 {This seems sensible ruining Black's structure but it heightens the c-file attack.} exd4 14. Nb5 Qb8 {This calm move is troubling to deal with. The threat is d5 . Since the bishop can't capture, Black will be able to play Qe5 + and attack the enemy king in a decisive maneuver. For example...} 15. Qxa7 {This sets a trap that backfires. White is hoping for 15… Bxb5 Bxb5+ when the rook on c8 is hanging. It's also White's best move as Black's response is practically unavoidable.} d5 {And Black is going to win some serious material because trading queens results in a double attack and taking on d5 allows Qe5 with a decisive initiative. For example...} 16. exd5 Qe5+ {A critical move and the idea of d5 ! The position is incredibly concrete.} 17. Kf1 {If the knight blocks, d3 takes advantage of the pin on the c-file.} Nxd5 {Ne3 is threatened and White can't take the knight because of Rxc1 .} 18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. Nxd4 Ne3+ {And Black is winning.} *

