1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 {White defends the pawn with a pawn instead of developing a knight. At first, this seems to violate chess principles. After all, the pawn on f3 gets in the way of the knight and weakens the dark diagonals to the king. But the point is that White wants to play Be3  Qd2 and castle queenside, launching a pawn storm at you. Sounds scary, right? Well, they call this the Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw, so yes, it's scary. Additionally, in Master games, White wins 43% to Black's 18% after e5 . So this isn't a wing it opening. Some good news: 1. I don't think it's the hardest opening to play against for Philidor players as long as you do a little homework. Most openings that violate opening principles are more smoke than fire against correct play. 2. It's incredibly fun to play against. You will feel alive! 3. In Club Level play, the win rates are much more balanced at 48% win rate for White and 47% for Black, the rest draws. Here, Black has many effective deviations. For example, 4. ... d5  e5 is a French Defense where we lost a tempo on d6  d5 but White played f3 instead of f4 . 4. ... c5 transposes to a Benoni, Benko, Sicilian or even French-like position where f3 is often not ideal. That move was the favorite of Kramnik, Jobava, Dominguez Perez, and Caruana--essentially a bunch of Super GM's! I really wanted to recommend c5 but it's hard to recommend you learn how to play the Benko Gambit, French Defense and Sicilian as a backup for when your opponent plays f3 . That certainly would be doable on the Super GM level where we live and breathe chess but for the rest of us, we need to sometimes be practical. Therefore, I recommend stepping right into the lion's jaw.} e5 4. d5 {This is the main move in both Master and Club Level play with a close second being dxe5 . For some reason, in my personal experience, I see Nge2 the most and I have no idea why. d5 is probably the biggest try for an advantage. White is just trying to control everything and creating a long pawn chain.} Be7 {c6 is another popular move but it allows c4 and I'd prefer to keep things flexible for now.} 5. Be3 {Be3 is the main move and the most played. And here we have a major turning point in terms of how Black should proceed. Grandmasters have been divided and the following moves have been tried: c6 , Nfd7 !?, Nh5 , 0-0. Personally, I think c6 is the most intensely fighting line because Black should really sacrifice a pawn to blow things open before White can consolidate their center. It's not to everyone's taste, so I'll list it as an alternative line.} c6 6. c4 b5 {What is the idea of this move? Well, first, it is a gambit. We can't technically regain the pawn after cxb5 , but we will have a lot of very active play and full compensation. Our idea if White allows it is to take on c4 and enjoy active play for our pieces, including our rook--which will have the b-file--and our bishop--which will be able to develop to a6 . Many of these players on the White side who play these structures like closed maneuvering games so psychologically, this can be difficult. The move b5 has been played only three times in master games--though boasting very high rated players on the Black side of 2600, 2599, and 2319. White has a few options in reply and the positions are a bit different from our normal ones, so I would recommend this for my higher rated readers or those who don't mind a little bit of extra work in learning the dynamics of this position.} 7. dxc6 {White can take this pawn, now or later.} bxc4 {Now Bxc4 seems like the natural move but in Gallagher vs. Pelletier 2012, the player of the White pieces chose Qa4 . That has concrete threats and so let's pursue that line has the main one. After Bxc4  Nxc6 we would arrive at a position that looks a little like a Sicilian where the black b pawn has been traded for the White c-pawn. That's a good deal for us because we don't have Marozy Bind ideas for White.} 8. Bxc4 {This is the most natural move.} Nxc6 {Our compensation for the backward pawn will be found in the b2 attack.} 9. Nc3 {A natural move, aiming to control the d5 outpost.} Rb8 10. b3 Qa5 {Hitting c3 and stopping the knight from jumping into d5 for now.  Bd2 is possible but then after Qb6 or later Nd4 , White has some castling issues.} 11. Nge2 Be6 {We will fight for d5 . If they take, our doubled pawns will stop the knight from infiltrating and we will have an open f-file for Nh4 - f4 later.} 12. O-O {Best. Let's keep examining best play by White.} Bxc4 13. bxc4 {White has finally won the d5 square, but at a cost. They now have a weak c4 pawn.  Nd5 can just be taken so they still don't have complete control of the square here.} O-O {White has a small edge but Black is doing fine with counterplay against the c-pawn and good places for all their pieces.} *

