1. e4 d6 {[How to Study Model Games]Welcome to a critical part of the course: the Model Games section! I have divided these up into the almost superhuman, colossal battles between GM's and the error-ridden encounters you'll find in Club Level play, either by using people rated lower or by using blitz games from higher-rated players, who due to the time pressure will be calculating at a lower depth on par with most non-GM players in classical. Let's get into what to do with this session...   What's the purpose of studying the model games over memorizing and practicing opening moves?   Opening moves will give you the start of a game, but the middle game and endgame positions of the Philidor require pattern recognition. Each opening has their stereotypical middle game and endgame dynamic which take some modelling to fully understand. We cannot memorize an entire game, but we can watch a few to see how we go from the end of the opening battle to the end of the game. This is critical or else you will get solid or even great opening positions and squander them again and again. So, we have two next steps after you have a basic sense of the opening:   1. Play games and review them intensely with a coach or engine.   2. Look over games in the Philidor to learn the thematic follow ups that may occur late, late into the game, beyond what many would classify as the opening.  For item 1, unfortunately, you are on your own. But for 2, this section should eliminate all the database searches you would need to do. I have chosen not only good games, but thematic ones, that often end up in positions similar to ones I get in playing this opening. In fact, I was biased towards the thematic over the beautiful because I wanted to give you a sense of the typical plans and tactics that would arise later. I hope it will be helpful.   The Five Steps for Maximizing Your Learning Here   Let's get into how to maximize the utility of a Model Game. After doing at least the Quickstarter, I'd follow these five steps:   Step 1: Turn off the engine. You need to be thinking on your own, and I've already engine checked all the lines anyway.    Step 2: Look only at the position and try not to look at the notation. Use your swipe, if using a phone, or keyboard, if using a computer, to go through the moves without seeing what's about to happen next.    Step 3: Before each move, guess Black's response. For optimal results, create a tally system for each correct guess and incorrect guess, trying to approach at least 80% accuracy. If you guess wrong, read my notes to see if your guess is mentioned and if not, ask why the move played was played instead of yours. Make a mental note on what rule might be being followed by the Philidor player, and write down the move you had preferred instead for later. Repeat until the game is done. For practice in classical, deliberate as if in classical time controls; for practice in blitz, deliberate as if in a blitz game.    Step 4: After the game is over, turn on the engine and go through your options to see if they were at least equally valid to the game's suggestion and if not, whether your reasoning for why they were inferior was correct.    Step 5: Create a list of 'takeaways' from the game, points to remember going forward.   Following these five steps will maximize your enjoyment and learning while going over these games. Feel free to come back to them later after you've played a little and they're a little fuzzier in the memory and see if you obtain higher accuracy.} *

