[Black "Queen trade Bg5: Lichess Game"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B07"]
[PlyCount "92"]

{This was a 5 0 Lichess blitz game that is instructive. White was rated 1765 and Black 1850. Despite the fact that it was blitz, Black played incredibly well and illustrated how to play against unprepared opponents. Black clenches an opening advantage and holds on to the lead the entire game.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 {This is the most accurate way of getting into the Philidor. Black is committing White to Nc3 before setting up their pawn chain. Why? Because we plan on playing c6 later and so a knight on c3 will be completely blocked out of play.} 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 {The overwhelmingly favorite move among Club Players. White aims to deprive Black of castling rights.} dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 {The most popular move yet again is chosen by the 1765 rated player. It is logical: White develops a minor piece and prepares to castle queenside, checking the Black king. Whenever we see this plan, it's very important that we can hide on c8 , so Black plays the right move.} Be6 {We do not care about Bxf6 gxf6 because in those cases, the open g-file will be a headache for White and later Black can play Bh6 ideas if they want. The f6 pawn will also protect the e6 bishop from knight attacks and bolster the e5 pawn.} 7. O-O-O+ Kc8 {Black steps away from the d-file. Black clearly knows their opening theory as this is not a natural move compared to Nbd7 .} 8. Nf3 {Okay, okay, perhaps the dubious mark is a bit much but this seems to be a positional mistake by White and is the first step in a downward spiral. One of the tricky things about playing against the Philidor is that 'going with your gut' isn't a good path unless you have an AMAZING gut. Developing knights and then bishops is typically met with a nearly lost position for White. Why? Well, because Black will play c6  Kc7 and then a5  b5  Bb4  Rb8 and launch this incredibly powerful attack. White's best course is to play a move like f4 with the idea of putting a bishop on f4 and stopping the enemy king from finding a hiding spot on c7 . This has downsides as well but White must play carefully here or they will be worse as this game will illustrate well.} Nbd7 {Black does NOT play this move to guard f6 --we will usually respond to Bxf6 with pxf6 as we want a pawn to defend e5 so that our knight can do bigger and better things. We only play this move to guard e5 here and think about Nc5 later.} 9. Bb5 ({White has a dream. Let's see the dream in action by playing a bad move by Black... a6 Bxd7+ Nxd7 guarding e5} 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Rd8+ {. This tragedy is the quality of Shakespeare. Unfortunately for White, Bb5 is just a trap that will backfire badly for them. Why is it a mistake? Well, because it inspires Black to play c6 when c6 is a move Black would have played even if there wasn't a bishop on b5 !}) 9... c6 {This move is always useful whenever we don't have doubled-e-pawns in this variation. Why? It helps us in many ways! For one, it gives a square for our king, c7 , that is very safe from knight and bishop attacks and allows us to move our other rook to the queenside to join the party. It also stops the c3 knight from moving forward and prepares b5 . We will activate our rooks in an unusual way: by pushing the a and b pawns. So, for all these reasons, c6 is a great move in these types of positions. And here it comes with tempo on the bishop!} 10. Ba4 Bb4 ({The 1850's player finds a great move! It's tempting in these positions to play} 10... b5 11. Bb3 Bxb3 12. axb3 b4 {followed by Nxe4 . But these types of lightning attacks to win a pawn can backfire quickly. After all, White is better developed than Black in this position and if we are only moving pawns and capturing pawns with already-developed pieces, we might face a reckoning. So Black instead develops their bishop and makes concrete threats against the white pawns.}) 11. Rhe1 {It's tough to label this a mistake as almost any White move is better for Black. But Bxf6 followed by Bb3 is probably the best of the bad choices, allowing a wrecked structure. Maybe White thinks they are still holding here, stopping Nxe4 after the trade on c3 . This is an important psychological point: White often forgets a2 is hanging in these endgames. Why? Well, because the Black bishop develops early and then inspires people to forget about it. It doesn't look like a2 is takeable because the knight is guarding it and even if it wasn't, it looks like b3 will trap it. You'd be surprised though, how often Black can, in fact, nab this pawn.} Bxc3 12. bxc3 Bxa2 {And White doesn't have the b pawn to try to trap it! Black is a clean pawn up and now it's time to convert.} 13. Bb3 {White forces Black to undouble the pawns or lose the bishop.} Bxb3 14. cxb3 h6 {h6 can often be played against the white bishop, though there was no rush and a5 opening up the rook was also good. The point of 14... h6 is to force a trade on f6 --which we are usually okay with because it opens up the g-file and the f-pawn protecting e5 frees up our knight--or move the bishop to a less desirable location.} ({For example, Be3} 14... Ng4 {is a common reaction and makes things tricky for White.}) 15. Bh4 {This move is a reflex move for many players. But the bishop now has only g3 and h4 to go to and so their diagonals have been shortened.} Re8 {Black plays a move protecting e5 so that they can move their knight.} 16. Rd6 {White tries to double on the d-file. Reasonable.} Kc7 {Attacking d6 and connecting the rooks. Black has decided to change plans from the usual one and just try to trade the pieces and win the pawn-up position.} 17. Red1 Rad8 {Not the only move but a nice and simple one.} 18. Bxf6 {Perhaps hoping for gxf6 but Black isn't dogmatic. Even though we usually recapture with the pawn, chess is a concrete game and Black calculates a sequence that will make the game simpler: often a goal of the player who is up in material.} Nxf6 {Again, not typical but all the more important because it is atypical. In all of chess, you need to be able to go your own way if the position seems to call for it. Memorizing the general rules is good for your chess but never thinking to break them is bad for your chess. Here, e4 is weak and Black correctly calculates they will have very good play and that the trade of rooks will favor them because they are up a pawn.} 19. Rxd8 {Forced because Rxd6 was threatened.} Rxd8 20. Rxd8 Kxd8 21. Nxe5 Nxe4 22. Nxf7+ {White regains the pawn for a few seconds, but Black is going to get it back.} Ke7 {Too many White pieces are threatened and so Black will regain the pawn.} 23. Ne5 Nxc3 {A good move reflecting a good understanding of endgames. Black's idea is that they will be able to make a queenside passer even faster now and have two connected passed pawns on that side of the board.} 24. Kc2 Ne4 25. f3 Nc5 26. Kc3 Nd7 {Black correctly offers a trade of minor pieces.} 27. Nxd7 {White was in trouble no matter what but the losing side should always work to keep the heavy pieces on the board to maximize their comeback potential. This maybe was outside of their calculation abilities but the simplest way to understand this endgame is conceptual. White will never be able to take Black's pawns on the queenside because the white king will always be drawn to the farthest-behind pawn--after all, any pawn not farthest behind can be defended by a pawn behind it--providing Black is reasonably careful. But if White captures a pawn at the very back, then Black will rush forward with the remaining two and create a passed pawn that is uncatchable.   In the meantime, if White tries the same thing on the other side, when Black captures White's farthest-behind pawn, White will only have a 2 vs. 2 situation with the remaining pawns. This won't be enough to create a passer. So White is lost.} Kxd7 28. f4 {White plays a good move and pushes pawns on the side where they have a majority. Unfortunately for them, nothing can save them at this point.} Ke6 {Black is coming to have some comfort food on the kingside.} 29. g4 {White stops Black from invading... for now.} Kd5 {The black king keeps marching forward in great endgame technique by Black.} 30. Kd3 {White blocks the black king. But now we have a classic 'Fox in the Chicken Coop' situation. Black will make a decoy on the queenside and when the white king goes to eat it, the Chicken Coop door on the kingside will open and the foxy black king will invade.} b5 {A tiny inaccuracy that doesn't amount to much. Generally, in these endgames, you want to push the pawn that has no enemy pawn on its file, so the a-pawn going first is simplest. Why? To stop moves like b4 that try to hold us back. Not that it would in this case because of c5 , but on principle, it's useful to just instinctively move the a-pawn.} 31. h4 {White plays actively on the side with the majority. They are doing a great job defending but will need an error on Black's part to prevail. And Black does not let up.} a5 {Excellent! Black creates a decoy. White's king is already being tempted over there and away from the black king.} 32. f5 {White moves the uncontested pawn. A good idea.} a4 33. bxa4 bxa4 34. g5 {White aims to trade pawns as quickly as possible on the kingside, realizing that the fox is coming into the coop soon.} hxg5 35. hxg5 a3 {If the white king runs to the pawn, the black king will run in the opposite direction and eat the white pawns. So White tries to trade even more pawns and minimize the damage.} 36. f6 gxf6 37. gxf6 Ke6 38. f7 {Tempting the black king away from the action.} Kxf7 39. Kc3 Ke6 {Black now needs to get their king in front of their remaining passed pawn to win the game. They quickly focus their sights on a good king placement.} 40. Kb3 Kd5 41. Kxa3 Kc5 {Personally, I would have played Kd4 or Kc4 so I could move my pawn and STILL be in front of it in case of an emergency. But this move is good enough. With the king in front of the pawn, it can escort the princess to her coronation.} 42. Kb3 Kb5 {Kd4 is easier just guiding the way but Black figures it out soon.} 43. Kc3 Kc5 44. Kd3 Kb4 {A good move, and now Black is almost ready to guide the pawn.} 45. Kd2 Kb3 46. Kd3 c5 {White resigned. The black king will guide the pawn and then go to b2 to finish the guiding. A beautiful game exploiting an opening mistake by White and then consolidating the advantage into a winning endgame.} *

