{This was played by two extremely strong players. It is in the Club Player games though because it is our most popular Club Player line.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ Kc8 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. Bxf6 {In this game, White--a 2400--opts to give up the bishop pair for the doubled pawns. Generally, we are delighted to see this. Why? Because opening up the g-file solves the problem of our kingside rook (generally, rooks are Black's problem in this variation because the one open file--the d-file--can be dominated by White who has connected rooks. We eventually can contest, but it takes us a lot of time. The doubled pawns also free up the d7 knight for adventuring--because they guard e5 --the h6 square for the bishop, and they can be fixed with f5 later--let's not be overeager with f5 though as we don't want to open the e-file for White to attack e5 ... this is a later plan not a now plan.)} gxf6 10. Nh4 {White, being a good player, tries to control f5 . Generally, we are not in a position to stop them.} Bc5 ({I prefer} 10... Bb4 {in these types of positions but Black probably feared} 11. Nd5 {, attacking the bishop. That said, Nd5 isn't terribly good for White as it allows c6 later with tempo on a move we want to play anyway. So,} Bc5 {is a tiny advantage for Black out of the opening. Either way, our bishop ends up on c5 so these decisions won't change the strategy too much.}) 11. f3 {A natural move and a good one. But Black now has stopped White from doubling on the d-file for a little bit as Rd2 will be met with Be3 and a pin.} c6 {Black's c6 move continues to be a trademark of the Queen trade Bg5 system.} 12. Kb1 b5 {Black starts activating their rooks in the typical way, playing against the c3 knight.} 13. Bd3 Nb6 {Nb6-c4 is a great maneuver. Now that e5 is guarded by the doubled pawn, our knight can venture into the enemy position.} 14. Ne2 {White tries to fix their worst piece, the c3 knight.} Kc7 {Again, Black calmly connects the rook and doesn't rush the queenside play.} 15. Ng3 h5 {Stopping Nh5 which would have been an annoying move against f6 . Also, preventing g4 ideas securing the knight on f5 .} 16. Ngf5 Rhg8 {The rook does a nice defensive job. Black doesn't so much aim to attack the kingside as they do slow White down on that side of the board. Another advantage of the doubled pawns is the g file.} 17. g3 {Freeing up the knight to not guard g2 .} a5 {Now that the kingside shuffling is at a stall point, Black returns to the queenside pawn storm.} 18. Be2 Nc4 {The knight on c4 is a terror. So White decides to trade it for their bad bishop.} 19. Bxc4 Bxc4 {Black has the bishop pair and more queenside space, but this is far from easy to make that matter. The white knights look ferocious but they actually have very little to attack and very little spaces to move.} 20. Rd2 Bb4 (20... Rgd8 {was also very sensible, but Black tries to keep the rooks on for awhile to fight for a win. The goal is to stop White from doubling unless they induce a weakness with c3 .}) 21. c3 Bc5 22. Rhd1 Be6 {Guarding the 7th. Black's bishop has no interest in trading for the knight as both white knights want to be on f5 so there's knight over-supply in White's camp.} 23. Nd6 {This tries to force the knight in but the issue is that the knight doesn't really attack much on d6 and is vulnerable to tactics. It's understandable at the same time as it's hard to know what to do as White.} Rad8 {Slightly better was b4 continuing the attack but moving rooks to open files is rarely bad.} 24. Ndf5 Rxd2 {Usually when you have rooks staring at each other on an open file, whoever flinches first and trades gives the other side the control of the file--because when they recapture, they will have the only rook. This is true here as well but Black reasons that it's best to trade so that White cannot trade both rooks. Again, Black is dedicated to winning.} 25. Rxd2 b4 {I find it kind of funny that even with so few pieces on the board, Black is still able to put pressure on the queenside.} 26. cxb4 Bxb4 {The bishops enjoy the trade of pawns and now become even more active.} 27. Rd1 Bc5 ({Personally, I would have played} 27... Rb8 {and taken advantage of the open file. Black plays preventatively though. The idea is that the knight on f5 cannot move with the black bishop on c5 . So Black plays slowly and makes it hard for White to undo their knight moves.}) 28. Rd3 {Guarding e3 so that the knight has an escape chute.} Bc8 {Black reroutes the bishop to a6 to pressure the rook. Many moves were possible and Black is playing for incremental better pieces here and there, waiting for later to try to force anything and seeing what White does.} 29. Rc3 Bb4 {Black aims to eventually attack every available square on the d-file before securing it for their own rook... ensuring White can't trade their way to a draw. The bishop on b4 covers d2 and Ba6 - Be2 can even be thought about guarding the other two places the White rook could go.} 30. Rc1 ({White was not eager to give Black} 30. Rd3 Ba6 31. Rd1 Be2 {when White must leave the file and Black's bishops look very impressive.}) 30... Rd8 {Taking the open file and dreaming of Rd2 .} 31. a3 {A good move taking advantage of the lack of squares available to the bishop.} Bf8 32. Kc2 {Guarding d2 and preparing to fight back for the lost d-file. Black, in the meantime, has gained a weakness from White in a3 . Every pawn move weakens the square next to it and so the b3 square is now weak and open for invasion , the b2 pawn is backwards.} Be6 ({Eyeing the new weakness in White's camp. How bad is it? I mean, the square seems perfectly guarded by the king. But just watch how it can lead to White's demise with this variation:} 32... Rd1 {Bb3+} 33. Kb3 {Rxd1 winning.}) 33. Ng2 {The knight finally wants to come home. It is very lonely sitting on h4 for half a game.} a4 {Securing the b3 square. Black continues to have a slight edge with their murderous bishops threatening things.} 34. Nge3 Bb3+ {Playing for a bind, but Rb8 was better objectively.} ({That said, the move played is a good one practically because the right move for White here, Kb1} 34... Rd2+ {, is just so hard to play as it looks horribly passive. Only a supercomputer engine would recommend such passivity and deem it equal.}) 35. Kc3 Bc5 {Now Black has come into their element as Bb6  Ba5 is a very annoying threat.} 36. Nc4 {Stopping Black's threat.} Bd1 {The harassment continues.} 37. Ncd6 {A mistake but White was just exhausted from having to defend this till kingdom come and was looking for a way to force matters. Nd2 was much better, allowing the torture to continue but still surviving.} Bxf3 38. Nxf7 Rd7 {And this is the problem... the knight is almost trapped and forced to go to an abysmal square.} 39. N7h6 Bxe4 {Black is up a lot of pawns now and the white knights have no good places to go.} 40. Re1 Bd5 41. g4 Bb6 {The threat of Ba5 , converting the extra pawn and squeezing the knights to death was too much for White here. They resigned and the engine agrees, arguing all those factors give Black about a rook advantage in this position.} *

