[PlyCount "114"]

{Now for a game between me and a 2330 chess.com player. It is blitz, but I think a 2330 on chess.com blitz is basically the equivalent of something like a 1700-1800 or so in classical and so it gives you a good idea of what to expect. I wanted to show a flawed game to be more practical with the positions we will reach: not perfection on both sides but a back and forth struggle. Hopefully, you enjoy the humility of my own moves here to show you we don't need perfection.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ Kc8 {Nothing new so far. See the other games for remarks about this position.} 8. Nf3 {You might be wondering why 2300's are playing this variation. And it's because the Philidor is still a surprise even at the higher levels. In playing, I was seeing the 'Club Player Variation' played by National Masters and even International Masters. I don't know if this would be repeated as much in classical chess but this is a big advantage in not playing the Sicilian or even French Defense.} Nbd7 9. Bxf6 {It's almost always dubious to take, but the temptation is real for high-rated and low-rated players alike!} gxf6 10. Bb5 {Again, a mistake. The bishop is out of play.} c6 11. Ba4 Bb4 {I'm not threatening e4 directly here as my knight has gone to a better place, but I am threatening it indirectly through forking on c5 after taking on c3 . Plus, the a2 pawn can make a nice snack. Remember, if they double their c-pawns, they can't trap your bishop.} 12. Bb3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Nc5 {Eyeing e4 .} 14. Nd2 Rg8 {This is always useful because usually White can't respond by developing. After all, g2 is threatened. I don't know if the rook will live here forever, but it's a great hangout place.} 15. g3 a5 16. a4 Nxb3+ ({A mistake. I simply missed} 16... Bxb3 17. cxb3 Nd3+ {forking the king and f2 , winning the exchange. For that reason, after Bxb3 White would have to recapture with the knight and lose the a-pawn.}) 17. cxb3 b5 {This was my idea: the knight is just a worse piece than my bishop and I will be able to open the b-file for my rooks.} 18. Kc2 Kc7 {Connecting the rooks.} 19. c4 {White attempts to reduce the pressure on the b3 square but it's yet another pawn on a white square.} bxa4 {I didn't want to take on c4 and allow their knight to be good.} 20. bxa4 Kb6 ({And I give up the advantage just like that! The dream was some kind of active king but I block my own file. I'm hoping here you can learn from my mistakes! Better was} 20... Rgb8 {and just controlling the b-file with Rb4 ... where White will have to connect my pawns or let me harass a4 and c4 .}) 21. Rb1+ {My opponent plays simple and good chess. I gave them the b-file so they take the b-file! I'm not losing here but Black had about a -1.48 evaluation--an advantage of about a pawn and a half--according to the computer and now White has a 0.29 advantage.} Kc5 22. Kc3 {Guarding c4 . Nb3 is threatened and White now has an advantage. You will find this happens to you too. You miss something small, you have a hallucination, you think about what you will do to them only to miss what they can do to you. When this happens, it's important not to panic. Play classical chess and aim for counterplay. Here, I take a deep breath and decide my king will have to run to d6 and not b6 , and that I need to fight for the b-file.} Rgb8 {Here, White should have played Rxb8 Rxb8 Nb3+ and then my king would need to go to b6 , blocking my file and White would be able to play Rd1 with an edge. Just so you know, if they do this, you're not dead... Black should play h5 and go for counterplay and the opening of some other file. Generally, when losing, counterattack is better than passive defense. So, I would say if White finds this concept: attacking a5 with the knight to lure the king there, it's uncomfortable for Black but the outcome isn't clear, even among high rated players.} 23. Rhd1 {White plays Rhd1 , threatening Nb3 + where my king must say hello to a rook on either the d or b file. But even this natural move is a mistake that swings the pendulum back to equal, and an equality where Black can play for a win at that.} Rb4 {This is the tricky part for White. Black can put the rook ahead of the king. If White takes the rook, Black will create a protected passed pawn with a later c5 . These types of protected passed pawns leave Black with a huge endgame advantage because if the pieces trade off, the white king will always have to look at the pawn, and never be able to take it. So then, the black king can just run around the board eating things while White's king is in passed pawn jail and stuck watching the un-takeable pawn.} 24. Nb3+ Kb6 25. Nd2 {It's hard to criticize this move even though now Black has a clear edge. The right plan was to kick the b4 rook by playing Na1 - c2 and achieving an equal game. But Na1 is so unnatural that it's hard to fault a human on not finding it, especially in a faster-time control game.} c5 {Now the rook will live on b4 forever, harassing c4 and a4 to tie down the white pieces or White will allow Black a protected passed pawn.} 26. Rxb4+ {Passed pawn it is. This is losing but I get the headache of holding everything passively all game.} cxb4+ {A mistake on my part.  axb4 would be simpler as the old adage 'capture towards the center' is in effect and the a-file would be open for pressure on a4 . I had this vision of an active king going through c5 , which is why I made this mistake. Both are still good for Black, but the other would have been easier to play.} 27. Kb3 {In light of the idea of Kc5 , White should have kept this square available for the knight. In Reuben Fine's rules of chess, he mentions that in endgames, blockade with the king, but in this case, blocking the passed pawn with the knight makes more sense as it would obligate Black to keep a defender on a5 and stop c5 invasions. To be fair, the scary thing about defending with a knight here is that c4 and a4 would both be undefended. So tactically, Kb3 is the safer move even though White cannot afford to play safe chess at this point. As I mentioned earlier, counterattack is critical for defenders of worse positions over passive defense.} Rd8 {And the d-file continues to obstruct White from being able to make useful moves.} 28. Kc2 {Unpinning the knight and a good move.} Rd4 {Threatening c4 --possibly e4 if the knight moves--and asking the white king whether it wants to return to the pin.} ({Unfortunately, for White Kb3} 28... Kc5 {means the pawn will drop no matter what.}) 29. f3 Bxc4 30. Nxc4+ Rxc4+ 31. Kb2 Rd4 ({Up a pawn, my goal is to prevent counterplay. White would love} 31... Rc3 32. Rd6+ Rc6 33. Rd7 {with active counterattacking. Once winning, the goal is to neutralize any White plans and we need to start thinking about what White wants to do while attacking to lure them into passivity.}) 32. Rc1 Rd2+ {White must trade rooks to stop the loss of another pawn. The computer recommends moving the rook to block here for White but no high-rated White player would do this as the king and pawn endgame is over. Why? Well, look at Rc2 Rxc2 Kxc2 Kc5 . In that position, the White king must always be afraid of b3 - b2 - b1=Q so must hang out near the Black b4 pawn. If Black moved their king away, the White king would still be stuck, because if it ever ran towards a5 , the b-pawn would run and queen. So Black could just run over to the other side of the board and eat all White's pawns without the enemy king being able to follow. After White moves the king instead of trades rooks, my king guards the 6th and 7th ranks so I'm okay making my rook active and allowing the counterattack.} 33. Kb1 Rxh2 34. Rc8 Rf2 {In rook endgames, which happen a lot in the Philidor defense because of our commitment to create a different file instead of contesting White for the d-one, we often want to counterattack rather than defend. So I see White is threatening to attack f7 and h7 and maybe f6 one day and rather than panic, I just try to attack equivalent pawns in the White camp.} 35. Rf8 Rxf3 36. Rxf7 {White is doing a good job here trying to recover. The losing side often wants to trade pawns. There are, after all, many positions where a pawn and a rook draws a rook. The extra pawns favor the winning side. By this logic, maybe I should have chosen to play h5 here to inflict the maximum pain on my opponent and minimize the trading. But I had calculated that the course I took in the game would result in a winning advantage.} Rxg3 37. Rxf6+ Kc5 38. Ra6 {White goes after a5 over all other pawns because it is the root of the protected passer on b4 . But notice that when they check me, I go towards the center with the king. King position often decides whether White can hold or not in these types of games.} Ra3 {I counterattack rather than defend. I could have also attacked e4 but I wanted to attack e4 with my king.} 39. Rxa5+ Kd4 40. Ra7 Kxe4 41. Rxh7 Rxa4 {Here's the rule: if you are winning by only one pawn, it's a win if your king is in front of it. These rook and pawn endgames are critical to know and so look up the Lucena Position and Philidor--woohoo--Position if you don't already know why the king decides.} 42. Kb2 Kd4 {Moving the king out of the way to push the passed pawn. If White's king tries to get in front of the e-pawn, I'll use the b-pawn and vice versa.} 43. Kb3 Ra1 {I don't care about the b-pawn as long as my king is in front of the passer. So here, I set some bait. White should probably decline to take it for the best practical chance but it's just so tempting to only be down by a single pawn.} 44. Kxb4 Rb1+ {And the enemy king is pushed away from the passer resulting in a known win for Black.} 45. Ka3 {The rest of the game I won't have too many comments except to say the idea is to use the pawn as a shield against rook checks. The rooks can check horizontally or vertically. But either way, I should be able to get my pawn all the way to e7 and king to e8 . The unwinding there is a well-known maneuver.} e4 46. Ka2 Rb8 {No, White, you will not be playing with a king. The rook just works as a laser to prevent White from playing with their monarch.} 47. Rd7+ Ke3 48. Rh7 Kd2 {The king moves diagonally. Vertical check and I will go to e2 . Horizontal checks and I will go to d3 and then push the pawn.} 49. Rd7+ Ke2 {Not too far from the pawn as to not defend it, not so close as to prevent it from advancing.} 50. Rh7 e3 51. Rh2+ Kd1 52. Rh1+ Kd2 53. Rh7 e2 54. Rd7+ Ke1 {This position was inevitable more or less. To convert this, you just need to bring in your rook as a shield.} 55. Re7 Rb5 {The rook prepares to be a shield. It may look too far away but the king can zigzag from the checks to the right place.} 56. Ka3 Kd2 ({Rd7+ Ke3 Re7+ Kd3 Rd7+ Ke4 Re7+} 56... Re5 {would have been a more normal end of the game when the pawn will promote to a queen.}) 57. Ka4 Rd5 {Stopping the checks of the rook and promoting next move. A back-and-forth game that will be perhaps more characteristic of most people's than the 'Model Games' of Grandmasters, which are also included.} *

