{This game was played between two strong players. White was rated 2235 and Black 2400 (not a GM versus GM game, but perhaps what to expect against a White player that is really good but still somehow more human) .} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 {The move Bc4 can be tricky to face as f7 truly is vulnerable. But we will see here how White can easily go wrong in this endgame even when they have a lot of talent.} Be6 {Black takes on the doubled pawns in order to neutralize the bishop.} 7. Bxe6 fxe6 8. Be3 {Let's examine this position for a moment. Black looks like something has gone horribly wrong at first glance: doubled, isolated pawns? Has the 2400 just sunk into a lost position? But look deeper. The e-pawn is not easy to attack. White's bishop will never attack it because it's on the wrong color and the knights can only attack it via g5 or c5 , two squares Black can fight for.   Finally, the black king can go to e7 to support it, requiring TWO White pieces to attack it. But it's not just less vulnerable than usual, it also guards d5 and f5 . Usually we have to waste a whole move on guarding d5 with c6 but now we have accelerated our setup by guarding it without having to go c6 . Finally, White's main counterplay against the enemy king involved f4 . But this will undouble our pawns so it's sometimes tricky for White to create a plan in this position.} Bd6 {Black wants to play Ke7 to guard e6 and connect the rooks--specifically we want both our rooks to follow the white king to wherever it castles. It's important to not lock in the bishop though, so Black develops it quickly to setup their ideal position.} 9. O-O-O Ke7 ({It's worth noting that Nb5?} 9... Nxe4 {is a mistake I've seen more than one player fall into. For now, the knight on c3 cannot move because e4 will fall. Black steps off the e-file with the king to avoid annoying pins, quietly guarding e6 and preparing the rooks to go to the same side of the board as the enemy king.}) 10. Nf3 a6 {I award this an exclam for the idea. Black is going to storm the queenside to activate the rooks--every pawn move over there will make the rooks better. Black could have started c6 but this would mean the d-file is a bit more open and d6 a bit weaker. Usually this is a necessary concession but with our beautiful doubled pawn, we have d5 under control without having to play c6 . So let the pawn attack begin! Black also stop Nb5 ideas for later--this wasn't an issue previously as e4 was hanging.} 11. Nd2 {The white knight wasn't doing much on f3 , so it begins rerouting to c4 where it can eye the enemy bishop and still retain a glance at the e5 pawn.} b5 {'No Nc4 for you,' says Black.   Next, Black will move the knight out and the rook to the queenside to put pressure on White where Black will try to open files. The king on e7 sits happily in the center.} 12. f3 {This stops Ng4 by Black and helps overguard e4 so that White can move their knights at ease. Perhaps one day there is the dream of g4 but it will weaken the f3 pawn so that will be a very dangerous dream.} Nc6 {I recommend ideas like c5 in my chapter, but these are small details compared to the general point: Black is developing pieces towards the queenside quickly and trying to open a file.} 13. Ne2 {Afraid of d4 , White attempts to run away from the pawn attacks. This is technically still not a bad position for White from an objective standpoint, but Black's plan is easy and fluid: open files, attack, attack, squeeze, squeeze. White's setup is trickier and so the moves are just hard to figure out.} Rhb8 {Black sets up the rooks and is patient to complete development before attacking. This should be stated clearly: we need to use all of our pieces in this queenside play in order to secure any kind of advantage. The pawns themselves pose very little threats to White. It is only the space they create for our minor pieces and eventually rooks that make the pawn moves threatening, so we must ensure we have the pieces with them to make it effectively.   The one thing to watch for in this position is White playing a move like Nc4 after b4 . So, Black proceeds cautiously. Now is the time to get concrete in executing the pawn storm.} 14. Kb1 {Great defense by White! The king clears a space for a knight on f1 for extra protection and even thinks about Ka1  Rb1 in an emergency.} Na5 ({Black doesn't play} 14... b4 15. Nc4 {and instead guards the spaces the enemy knights can go into. Remember, the goal is to open files here and one way to do that is to trade knights and recapture with a pawn! If you had developed the b8 knight to d7 , you could have achieved this by going to b6 first as I've shown with the arrows. The knight technique is great because White has to either trade and give us a great rook or let the knight just gloom over everything on c4 !}) 15. Rhf1 Nc4 ({The computer recommends} 15... Kf7 {instead but Black is making the practical choice and thematic one. Black wants to open files on the queenside for their rooks and so asks White what they want to do about the knight on c4 .}) 16. Bg1 a5 {Both black rooks are staring down hallways that keep getting longer and longer. And the twins staring down that long hotel hallway at the king have all the Red Rum feels of a horror movie. Who needs queens to attack? Not Black!} 17. c3 {A mistake but a common misconception. White is trying to stop these enemy pawns from advancing without confrontation and trying to stake out some queenside space. But the misconception is that it's the pawns that are attacking White. It's not the pawns. The pawns are actually in the way. It's the rooks. And any white pawn advancements will make it easier for Black to trade a pair of pawns and clear files for those rooks.} Nd7 {Black's knight wasn't contributing and again, we want to use all of our pieces. Since the knight wasn't pinned, it is welcome to come over and help, giving Black a critical force advantage in pressuring the enemy king.} 18. f4 {White cracks.  f4 undoubles the black pawns without solving the situation on the queenside. The computer said it was just a tiny bit better for Black before this moment, but that seems overly harsh on White. This position is just incredibly difficult for White to play from a practical perspective. Black's purpose is clear: bring things over to the queenside, control the counterplay on the kingside, and play aggressively. White's is a little more concrete and situational, definitely harder to understand.} Nxd2+ {Black removes one of the defenders and un-coordinates the white rooks in preparation of the open f-file.} 19. Rxd2 exf4 20. Nxf4 Rf8 {Black senses an opportunity to punish White for their panicked f4 and leaps into action. This is a good time to talk about playing the Philidor more broadly. In teaching this, I have seen students dogmatically stick to the prescribed plan through thick and thin. But chess is a game of relationships: what are you doing in relation to your opponent's moves. We must be willing to deviate when a rare opportunity presents itself. Always think concretely, even if you know the usual plans. Muscle memory works in bullet but in slower chess, never throw away minutes on your clock examining what makes a position unique. Here, Black sees that White's knight is pinned because the rooks aren't guarding each other.} 21. Rdf2 {Otherwise the knight was going to be attacked with a pawn. White unpins the knight.} Bc5 22. Rf3 Bxg1 {Great concrete calculation by Black! Black un-coordinates the rooks once more to weaken their defense of the knight.} 23. Rxg1 Ne5 {And the knight is G-L-O-R-I-O-U-S! White's problem is that the rook can't go to f2 because then the knight will be pinned and vulnerable to g5 . But Rff1 blocks the other rook from fighting for the d-file.} 24. Rff1 {The f1 rook now blocks out the other rook and moving it will cause the death of the knight. So Black takes advantage of an opportunity.} Rad8 ({The threat of the rook to the seventh is not easy to meet. For example, Rd1 drops the knight on f4 . And Kc1} 24... Rxf4 25. Rxf4 Nd3 26. Kc2 Nxf4 {is a pretty tactical refutation of Kc1 . Finally, Kc2 Nc4 and the threat of rook to the seventh or Ne3 + loom large.}) 25. Ne2 {White aims to regroup and makes things worse. The best move was 25. h4 , preventing g5 threats but the position is bleak regardless.} Rxf1+ {Black trades rooks in preparation for invading the seventh rank. They didn't want to allow White to take on f8 and distract the king from guarding e6 .} 26. Rxf1 Rd2 ({White is losing material. Guarding the knight with the rook with} 26... Rd1+ {allows Nd3 .}) 27. Nd4 Rxg2 ({White taking the pawn would be met with a counterattack like Nxb5} 27... Nc4 {threatening b2 and a fork.}) 28. b3 {Stopping Nc4 .} c6 {Black is not only up a pawn but has the better pieces. The game is over and Black sees it through to the end.} 29. h4 g6 {In endgames, we push pawns where there is a pawn advantage. For Black this is the kingside. They want to play h6 without allowing h5 . Generally, Black pushes the uncontested pawn first--the g-pawn lacks an opposing white g-pawn and so wants to lead the way.} 30. Nf3 {White is bothered by the amazing knight so offers a trade despite being behind in material. I don't blame them: that black knight was a beautiful, beautiful steed.} Nxf3 31. Rxf3 Rg4 {And the active rook translates to even more material gain. If you're rated high enough to know how to convert this, you can move quickly through the remaining moves as we are at a position that the grandmasters typically annotate with 'the rest is just technique.' My remaining comments will be for those wanting to better understand the techniques of the conversion.} 32. Re3 Rxh4 {Black now has two passed pawns on the kingside. When winning in pawns, we only push the pawns where we have the advantage, so you might notice Black is no longer interested in pushing the queenside pawns: there is no pawn advantage there and there are no longer any rooks behind them so opening files is not important.} 33. a4 {White wants to play actively with the rook but finds it obligated to complete its guard duty of e4 . They could push the pawn to e5 but then Black would just play Ra5 and the guard duty would continue. So White tries to have the king do the guarding so the rook can go try to gobble things. This means White wants Kc2  Kd3 .} ({Unfortunately,} 33. Kc2 Rh2+ {leaves the king worried about the a2 pawn and unable to come out of hiding. So White plays this move not to win on the queenside but to free their king from the obligation of defending the rook pawn.}) 33... bxa4 34. bxa4 Rh2 {Black decides that if it has to jail the king or the rook, it's the king that poses more difficulty for White in liberating. So Black guards the seventh to cut the king off for the action while their king can emerge and guide the pawns down the board. The only way out of this king jail for White is to block it with their rook, but trading rooks will be an easy win for Black as the pawns on the queenside will distract the white king and the black king will be able to eat everything on the kingside.} 35. Rg3 Kd6 {Here comes the black king! It's 2v1, a black king and rook against a white rook. The white king is going to be very late to this party thanks to king jail.} 36. Rg5 {White tries to block off the black king.} Rh5 {Again, usually when you are winning, king and pawn endgames are very good for you. So Black has the advantage of 'threatening' a trade.} 37. Rg2 Ke5 {The black king is released from the blockade and comes forward to attack more white pawns. White's king is finally free but there's just no time anymore.} 38. Re2 Rh4 {White is losing another pawn and resigns. Three pawns down is pretty bleak, especially since Black also has a dominant king. A beautifully played game by Black.} *

