{This game was between a 2280 and a 1980 FIDE. It shows a non-mainline-but-sensible approach by White. In this game, White starts with 1. d4 . Technically, you can't play the Philidor against this unless White obliges. That said, the idea of d6  e5 against d4 isn't a bad one. It's called the Rat Defense and even World Champion Magnus Carlsen has employed it.} 1. d4 d6 {Now e4 is back to the Philidor while Nf3 and c4 move the game towards something different. That said, King's Indian players may like the Philidor in their arsenal so that after Nf3 they can claim they've avoided the Saemisch and four pawn attack by White. This is especially true if you like the Gawain Jones's pet line of Nbd7 as you get one more waiting move in before playing g6 and committing to another line of development. Finally, the Old Indian Defense involves an almost identical setup as the Philidor and Black players may find it very natural to play.} 2. e4 {Of course, White played e4 or else we'd be in territory outside of this course.} Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 {This line is playable for Black and the idea is to avoid the queen trade lines. Simon Williams covers it in his Black Lion course, a way of playing the Philidor that is incredibly aggressive and recommended by Alekhine in one of his annotations to his own games. That said, it's a bit apositional to kingside pawn storm instead of developing and White has moves like f4 and g4 that presented me with a headache while analyzing it. Surely, the queen trade line isn't to everyone's taste, but if you really hate it that much, play 1. ... e5 and take on d4 instead for much more palatable lines. Nonetheless, this game should serve to show that there's many ways of getting into our mainline.} 4. Nf3 {White doesn't play f4 or g4 and just develops normally, allowing for a transposition to our lines.} e5 {This is our standard Tension Variation. Now Bc4 and Re1 lines are the norm at the highest levels but White plays a very normal looking move.} 5. Bg5 {The reason why this isn't positionally optimal is that the dark-squared bishop is White's good bishop and the pin on f6 can't amount to much with a bishop on e7 . Unlike the queen-trade line, we will respond to Bxf6 by taking back with a minor piece, preferably one that guards e5 sufficiently.} Be7 6. Bc4 {The best square for the white bishop and a good move.} O-O {Black completes development. That may seem small but I've seen a lot of premature h6 and c6  b5 's. Following the principles of healthy development is a hallmark of a good player.} 7. O-O c6 {c6 is a good move in the tension variation as it threatens b5  b4 in some positions, makes a path for the queen to live so as to connect the rooks and guard e5 and prevents Nd5 ideas by White.} 8. dxe5 {White takes the pawn and gives up on d5 ideas. This is very common in games below Master level.} dxe5 {Taking back with the knight might give us a backward d-pawn on an open file, so Black does what I recommend you do in most situations: take back with the pawn.} 9. Qe2 {White guards the e-pawn and clears the files for the rooks. A sensible move but Black already has an edge.} Qc7 ({Black plays a very sensible move. That said, when your opponent doesn't stop it, then} 9... b5 10. Bb3 a5 {is almost always a great setup as the light-squared bishop can go to a6 with terror on the diagonal and White ends up very squished.}) 10. a4 {White stops b5 wisely. Now the position is about equal. I don't want you to think that equal means a draw though. In fact, the Chessable database lists four games here with three Black wins and only one draw. So how does Black win positions like this? For one, you play off the imbalance. White's knight on c3 is blocked out by the c6 pawn and Black's knight can come to c5 and become quite active. Later in the game, Black can play for a kingside attack by putting a knight on f4 or for queenside play by playing a5  b5 . These ideas are always very situation specific and this game will show the kingside plan.} Nc5 11. h3 {White starts to worry about a piece landing on g4 --either a knight if the bishop returns to e3 or a bishop to pin the f3 knight.} Ne6 {Black asks White to give up the bishop pair or face a knight invasion. It's hard to make these decisions as White but probably Bxe6 is best with the idea of gaining back the bishops by installing a knight on f5 .} 12. Be3 {White has a nightmare of their bishop being completely out of play if it tries to stay attacking f6 . After all, Black can play h6 and then Nf4 and the bishop is just locking in a small area of the board.} Bb4 {I'm not sure about this sudden switch in plan.  h6 to stop Ng5 ideas--maybe even toy with the idea of g5 later--would have been consistent with the kingside plan.  Bb4 isn't bad though and even though trading the bishop for the knight isn't a real threat--the dark squares in Black's camp need defending and that knight on c3 is really bad--the optical look of doubled c-pawns is enough to scare White.} 13. Na2 {White tries to relocate the knight and avoid the doubled pawns. Sensible even if not required.} Ba5 {One of the perks of Black avoiding the normal a5 move that I recommend is that they can play their bishop here. It's not a good move, but it is a move. The issue is we don't want to be squeezed on the queenside. That said, there will be games where White pulls it off despite our best efforts and this game shows not everything going according to plan and is an excellent example of practical Philidor games for both sides.} 14. b4 Bb6 {Black wants the bad bishop to be traded for White's good one. If White obliges, then Black will party on f4 with their knight. Of course, White shouldn't allow this and should play Bxe6 and then Bxb6 with a tiny edge due to their queenside expansion--the kind we typically get to do! But again, it's hard to give up the c4 bishop for White players, psychologically speaking, as many have been trained to value bishops over knights.} 15. Bg5 {White tries to argue that the black bishop is in danger of being trapped. But then the black bishop is uncontested, it's very hard for White as we will see. This is why Bg5 itself is such a questionable plan: it threatens trades that White doesn't want.} Nxg5 16. Nxg5 {Now Black's bishop is uncontested. This can come up in your games when White takes on f6 early.} a5 {Better late than never!  a5 is an instinct move in many of these Philidor positions, queen traded or not, it's almost always useful for squeeze prevention.} 17. c3 h6 {Black drives back the enemy knight. They are not eager to take on b4 and give White scary pawns over there.} 18. Nf3 Nh5 {Eyeing f4 , even g3 if White allows it. White misses the dark-squared bishop. Whenever you play Nh5 , you have to lookout for discovered attacks on the knight with moves like Nxe5 .} {Fortunately here though Nxe5 Qxe5 guards the knight.} 19. Kh2 {White is scared of Ng3 with the f2 pawn pinned. The king move is probably meant to overguard h3 so that g3 is one day a move.} Nf4 20. Qc2 {Black's knight cannot be kicked as it will just take on h3 . Black begins moving over their big pieces to the kingside to have an advantage in 'force count' as World Champion Gary Kasparov used to call it.} Qe7 {Black wants more pieces point at the enemy king. Notice how the Black queen, bishop and knight all are very happy on these dark squares without the white bishop defender.} 21. bxa5 {White tries to get queenside play going, frustrated by the blocking power of a5 and giving themselves isolated pawns to stop it.} Bxa5 22. Nb4 {White tries to activate their worst piece. Noble, but they are still down pieces on the other side of the board.} Qf6 ({The queen pairs incredibly well with the knight. White misses the Black threat though to be fair, Black had a few. For example on Be2 Qg6 Rg1} 22... c5 23. Na2 Qe6 {the Black attack would just go on and on and on. Black has a -2.21 evaluation in their favor here even with best White play. And Black's plan is simple, attack g2 and h3 continually, threatening sacrifices at the right moment.}) 23. Nd3 {A mistake but a human one. White is just terrified of that Black nightmare on f4 and offers a trade, missing a tactic that comes up in this position. It's also worth noting that this is an inverse of White's dream position in the mainline tension variation. Look at Tension Variation Nh5 attack for more information on White trying to do this to us! Our antidote is to always take the knight with our bishop once it lands on the f-file. But White has traded off the antidote!} Nxh3 {Taking the white knight will result in the f3 knight falling to the queen and the attack continuing! The bishop ensures the king can't take.} 24. Ndxe5 {White tries to regain the pawn somewhere else. But this opens up more diagonals.} Bc7 {Bxe4 is threatened. White tries to win a knight and make it just a trade.} 25. gxh3 {Here, White hoped for Bxe5 Nxe5 Qxe5 . But unfortunately for them, Black has a game winner.} Qxf3 {The e5 knight is falling soon, pinned to the king and h3 is also attacked. So White will have to try to trade queens and enter an endgame down a piece and with a horrible pawn structure. Instead of opting for this doom, White resigned.} *

