{My last game for pragmatic play comes from a Titled Tuesday game I won against an International Master. Trademark of this section, it was far from perfect and played at fast time controls. It shows a very basic response to mainline tries by White in case you encounter them.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 {The mainline tension variation, as I dub it in this course, is popular with higher-rated players and well-researched Club Players. It takes a level of comfort with holding tension that is a skill that takes awhile to cultivate.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 {Black threatens b5 .} 8. a4 {Again, a trademark of higher level games is this move preventing the b5  a5 advance.} a5 {Stopping White from playing a5 and seizing some queenside space for later. If you play a high-rated player and haven't gone over the mainlines, here's the basics: Put a pawn on c6 and a5 . Prepare to play h6 , Re8 and Qc7 and the moment it looks like your opponent wants to do something, take on d4 . What do I mean do something? I mean they move the queen, f3 knight, or their bishop. It's more complicated than that with precision play and you can milk the position for more before taking on d4 with practice, but even that simple rule is good enough to get you through most games.} 9. b3 {This looks like White is planning something like Ba3 (why else play b3 ?) . So following my rule: whenever White tries to do something here, take on d4 ....} exd4 10. Nxd4 Ne5 {The knight doesn't always land on e5 . In fact, if you don't know what to do, Nc5 is often the safest move, because from there you hit e4 and can go back to e6 , neutralizing White's strong knight. But it just so happens that the knight hits the bishop and sets up very nice tactics against the b3 move's flaws.} 11. Bf1 Qb6 {The queen asks the bishop if it wants to go to e3 , making the move b3 silly. If White did that, I'd quickly retreat to c7 and be happy playing the trench warfare that followed.} 12. Ba3 Bg4 ({This you will see later is a magic bishop. Why? Because attacking it doesn't result in it moving. It just hovers there. For example, attacking it looks natural enough but then f3 Bxf3 gxf3} 12... Qxd4 13. Qxd4 Nf3+ {Kg2 Nxd4 . This idea only works when a bishop is not guarding d4 as it all revolves around this Qb6 and Qxd4 plan. So it's a b3 exclusive idea.}) 13. Qd2 {My opponent, a strong IM, sees the point and plays a good move consistent with the attack d6 plan.} Rad8 {It was hard to decide on a rook move to the d-file or e-file. Both looked fine.} 14. Kh1 ({This looks funny but the magic bishop creates a lot of stress. For example,} 14. h3 Bxh3 15. gxh3 Qxd4 16. Qxd4 Nf3+ {and f3 Bxf3 gxf3 Qxd4 Qxd4 Nxf3 is a similar theme: sacrifice the bishop to create a knight check on f3 that allows for temporary queen sacrifices.}) 14... Rfe8 {I continue principally by developing all my pieces.} 15. f4 {An interesting try, attempting to one day eat the magic bishop on g4 by trapping it on White's kingside.} Ng6 16. f5 {Trapping the black bishop and threatening a knight. Oddly though, the magic bishop is still very much magical and trying to take it will result in unpleasantness for White. If I hadn't computer checked the basic soundness of Bg4 for this Chessable before this Titled Tuesday game, I would have been pretty terrified at this point. As it was, I just continued to play actively.} Ne5 17. h3 Bh5 ({Better was} 17... Nh5 {with some very interesting complications. Alas, this was a speed chess game and both of us weren't playing on full accuracy levels. What can I say except I, for a moment, lost faith in the magical bishop just staying on g4 forever? I issue it my apologies.}) 18. g4 {A reasonable looking move that makes the position incredibly difficult for White. Generally, these kingside pawn attacks are risky in open positions as White's king is out in the middle of everything and Black's pieces are active.} Nfxg4 19. hxg4 Nxg4 {And this position, believe it or not, is clearly better for Black despite the fact that I've lost a knight. Why? Well, b3 has weakened dark squares and all of Black's pieces have nice squares now. For example, Bf6 is coming, opening up diagonals and files and d5 will open up a rook. White is up a pawn technically, but their king safety and bad pieces give Black more than compensation. For example, one of their bishops is still on its starting square, the other one has no useful moves forward. Neither knight has any move forward that don't result in being taken.} 20. Be2 {My opponent makes an error. The best move was Nf3 but this is one of the main reasons White is in trouble: it's just very hard to play White here. The bishop on e2 cuts off the queen's defense of f2 , creating tactical opportunities.} Bf6 {The bishop going off the big diagonal is already starting to show cracks.} 21. Bxg4 Bxg4 22. Rad1 ({White offers some material back in order to mitigate the power of the bishop pair. d5} 22. e5 Rxe5 23. Rxe5 Bxe5 24. Nce2 Bxd4 25. Nxd4 Bd1 26. Qxd1 Qc7 {represents accurate play by both sides had this been a position where we were both at classical time controls and playing incredibly well. There, Black has a winning edge. However, even the simpler-minded play proves sufficient.}) 22... Bxd1 23. Rxd1 d5 {When you have an extra rook, it seems logical to open up the position so you can play on the freshly created files. Even after gaining the magic bishop for a rook and trading for the powerful knight, White's position is still hard to defend.} 24. exd5 cxd5 {The file is now clear for rook lifts.} 25. Ncb5 {Over defending d4 , trying to remove the knight from the bishop's eventual gaze and even playing aggressively into d6 in some instances. White's move seems logical. It does have a downside though in that the knight no longer covers e4 .} Re4 {The rook on e4 is very annoying for White, eyeing the knight, preparing to double, and preparing to swing to the kingside.} 26. c3 {Protecting d4 to allow Nd6 .} Rg4 {Rh4 was also probably good. Sometimes though, the threat of check is better than the execution, to paraphrase GM Nimzovitch.} 27. Re1 {Trying to take an open file. This misses the threat but then again, White was already in trouble even if they saw it coming.} Bg5 {The queen comes to the kingside attack and the threat continues. This kind of counterattack to early White aggression will happen in your games. Often, the Philidor position is like a spring and the more White presses, the more they risk a sudden turn.} 28. Qh2 {Stopping Qh6 but allowing the follow up.} Rh4 29. Qxh4 Bxh4 {The rest of the game is not really worthy of much comment as Black is up a bunch of material. Nonetheless, both of us were in severe time pressure and within a few moves were playing completely off the 2 second increment. So, you can stop here with lesson learned or watch on to watch how sloppy even titled players like me can be when given only two seconds a move.} 30. Re2 Qh6 31. Kg2 Qg5+ 32. Kf3 {Here, Qg3 is checkmate. But I'm pretty much playing the first move I see to not lose on time, and alas, it wasn't the first move I saw.} Qh5+ 33. Kg2 Qg4+ 34. Kf1 Qg3 35. Bc5 h6 36. Bb6 Rc8 37. Ba7 Kh7 38. Bb6 Re8 {And it's over...} 39. Rxe8 Qf2# {A good example of the tension variation in that the dynamics are constantly living with tension and waiting for White to just get a tad too eager only to play a counterattack.} *

