[PlyCount "98"]

{This game was played by Ukrainian Grandmaster Olexander Bortnyk, who turned out this gem at the age of nineteen! His opponent was a strong player with a Grandmaster title as well: Alexey Kislinsky. Kislinsky was rated FIDE 2482 at the time to Bortnyk's rating of FIDE 2568. This was a rapid game played in Kyiv in 2016, but the quality of the play doesn't disappoint and it illustrates the tension in the mainline Philidor.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. Nf3 e5 5. Bc4 {The choice of top players overwhelmingly but not exclusively.} Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 a5 8. h3 c6 9. Re1 h6 {This move order is also fine.  Re8 is my preference as sometimes we can get away with the free move but it usually ends up in the same place.} 10. Ba2 {This introduces the idea of the slingshot variation but it could also be just a simple waiting move, removing the bishop from d5 - b5 break tempos.} Re8 11. Nh4 Nf8 {exd4 is also fine for Black as soon as they see the knight move. I have recommended this course though waiting for one more piece of information and trying to see if we can lure the queen out first. But the downside it is allows White's next, harmless retort, which could have been forced anyway before dxe5 .  Ng6 wouldn't be horrible to allow but Nf8 takes it off the table anyway--remember that the a2 bishop pins the f7 pawn!} 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Qf3 {White doesn't want to trade queens sensing an attack.  Qg3 and Nf5 are on the agenda. Remember, the bishop on a2 still makes Ng6 an immediate dropping of a piece as White can simply take. So we must stop this diagonal from being used against us.} Be6 {Black plays principally.} 14. Nf5 {14. Bxe6 was also possible but then without that diagonal control, Black would have h5  g6 ideas later in the game. The issue with g6 is often that the f-file can open and the f7 pawn comes under attack if White's light-squared bishop is still staring icily at it.} Bxf5 {If there is a knight on f5 and you can take it, you almost always do in the Philidor. That said, taking out the bishop on a2 would probably be even better. The knight on f5 is not as terrifying when White doesn't have the diagonal.} 15. Qxf5 (15. exf5 Bb4 {was also interesting and a better course for White. It's a hard move to play though--why else did they play Qf3? But usually you don't want to take back with the pawn as White because of the move d5 , forcing out the enemy bishop from being useful. But with the pawn trade in the center, obviously there's no d6 pawn anymore to play d5 , so this pawn capture is now more enterprising. White would still have some kingside pressure in return for less of a center. Still, it wouldn't have been a bad result for Black from the opening even if they could have improved by taking on a2 instead earlier.}) 15... Bb4 {Whenever White trades in the center, the dark-squared black bishop finds new life as there's no d6 pawn to hedge it in. So look to develop it to b4 usually and c5 occasionally.} 16. Be3 Qd7 {The engine prefers Qe7 but I can see that Black wanted to just stop White from attacking them and wanted to trade queens or push the White queen back to its side of the board.} (16... Bxc3 17. bxc3 {may look tempting but remember that the c3 knight is really awful and pinned. Also, our c6  a5 pawns create a backward pawn on b7 that will only be under pressure if we open the b-file. So we should trade on c3 for concrete reasons--like we can put pressure on the doubled pawns or e-pawns--not because of boredom.}) 17. Qf3 N8h7 {Again, the computer wants the queen on e7 to support Ne6 - c5 . The main idea here is for Black to double White's pawns after being able to quickly being able to attack e4 --which is defended by the c3 knight.   But the GM sees a different plan--installing a knight on g5 . The plus side of this is that it will come with tempo on the white queen and tempt White to give up the ultra strong dark-squared bishop on e3 . It will also attack e4 , which combines well with Bb4 . The downside of it compared to the computer way is that if Black wins the bishop this way, they will have somewhat weak kingside pawns, while if the knight goes to c5 and is eaten, the queen can retake, pressuring the c-file--the same file where we plan to double, isolate their pawns.   Both plans work in different circumstances and so this game helps show ways to develop these knights and make progress against an opponent with a similar pawn structure.} 18. Red1 Qe7 {One idea to watch out for when the white queen is on f3 is this Bxh6 idea when the f6 knight can fall sometimes--say, if the knight on h7 had moved back to f8 . So Qe7 guards the f6 knight to stop this tactic in the future. But more importantly, if you're thinking about doubling White's pawns, you want your queen looking down the c-file to pressure those pawns and help support pieces coming into c4 , the square in front of the future isolated pawns.} 19. Ne2 {White starts to get scared about doubled pawns and also tries to make their worst piece better by relocating it.} Ng5 {Forcing White to give up the bishop as e4 is under fire.} 20. Bxg5 hxg5 {Sometimes Black gets these doubled pawns and generally they are not much of an issue. They are slightly weak but not easily taken and g6  Kg7  Rh8 sometimes allows for attacks on the h-file. Definitely an imbalance and exactly what you want to create when playing against a lower-rated but highly skilled opponent. They also support knights landing on f4 .} 21. Ng3 {White has relocated the knight and prepares to install it on f5 . Black doesn't have another light-squared bishop to take it so has to stop it in another way.} g6 {Again, this move is usually good for us when White doesn't have the c4 bishop anymore. We don't have to worry about g6 falling because of the pinned f7 pawn or the f-file opening up. It's also better to be preventative with it than reactive as once the knight lands on f6 , it can respond to g6 with Nh6 ideas. Those don't always work out for White but why give them that option?} 22. Rd3 {White tries to double on the d-file.} Rad8 {Black activates their final piece and has fully equalized.} 23. Rad1 Rxd3 {Black lessens the d-file pressure by removing a rook.} 24. Qxd3 {White tries to stop Black from playing Rd8 so keeps the doubled-up pressure to control the file. The file, of course, is not enough on its own to give White much, but if Black somehow makes a concession, it may come in handy.} Bc5 {Black makes slow moves that incrementally improve their position. The bishop on b4 was just asking for c3 at a moment of White's pleasure and without a second rook, there's no need for White to play Rd2 --so it wasn't preventing the easy way to double anymore. So Black puts it on c5 to put pressure on the long diagonal and pin the f2 pawn.} 25. Qc4 Kg7 {Black ends the pin on f7 and more importantly paves the way for the rook to redeploy on the open h-file. Black is careful to attack with all their pieces and doesn't rush the improvement of the knight or the pawn push to g4 .} 26. Rd3 {I don't really know why White would do this except maybe some dream of pressuring b7 ? To be fair, these types of positions are hard to play as it's not clear how White is supposed to improve their position. That said, White must do something as Black has a clear and logical progression on the kingside. After this move, Black has a clear edge.} b6 {I'm not sure this is necessary but Black just calmly locks down the queenside so it's safe and secure before continuing the kingside buildup.} 27. c3 Rh8 {The h-file can be opened at any time with g4 so Black starts to make that a more terrifying idea for White and also supports the knight that want to move to the h-file in order to relocate to f4 . Finally, rook lifts against e4 are now possible.} 28. Rf3 Rh4 {Black pressures e4 while keeping the threat of g4 alive. Note that g4 right away is tricky because with the rook on f3 , the knight is pinned to stopping Rxf7 .} 29. b4 {White knows Black has committed to the kingside so tries to make things happen on the kingside.} axb4 30. cxb4 Bxb4 31. Qxc6 (31. Rf4 {would have been best for Black here but they make a small error.}) 31... Bc5 {Black misses White's retort.} 32. a5 ({And on bxa5 Black has to address} 32. Rxf6 {distracting the queen from guarding the bishop and obtaining an edge.}) 32... Rf4 33. a6 {axb6 is stronger, and now the game evens out again. It's a passed pawn versus kingside pressure imbalance. With both players under faster time controls, the game is exciting!} g4 {Technically, 33... Qa7 going after the a-pawn is best and threatening b5 at some point with more pressure on f2 , but it's hard to assess these positions in quick chess and Black's play seems outwardly very logical.} 34. hxg4 {It's hard to fault White for such a natural move but after Black's next move, White is just lost.  Qb7 was absolutely critical to try to escort the pawn and not waste a single tempo on the kingside. That one move will matter.} Nxg4 35. Qb7 {Threatening a7  a8 .} Bxf2+ {The attack here is brutal. On Kh1 we have Qh4 . And Qc5 is threatened should White take the bishop with the rook.  So...} 36. Kf1 Qb4 {Threatening mate and activating the queen. The passed pawn now seems like an afterthought.} 37. Ke2 Qb2+ 38. Kd3 Qa3+ 39. Kc4 Qxa2+ 40. Kb5 {White is down material and struggles to find a way to not be mated.} Qa5+ 41. Kc6 Qc5+ 42. Kd7 Nf6+ 43. Kd8 Qd6+ 44. Kc8 {White can resign. They are down a piece with horrible king safety. But they limp on with the hope of an a-pawn queen.} Rh4 45. Nf5+ {Desperation.} gxf5 46. Rh3 Rxe4 {Black is still up and the threats keep coming.} 47. Qc7 Qxc7+ 48. Kxc7 Ra4 49. Kb7 b5 {The white pawn can't promote and so White finally resigns.} *

