{This was a game between Wesley So and Philidor expert Meliket Khachiyan. Despite Black being rated almost 300 ELO points lower than White, they not only held their own against one of the top players in the world, but even were pressing with the Black pieces for most of the game. An incredibly high accuracy rate by White of 94% managed to just barely hold against Black's pressure.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 {The queen exchange is a powerful line at the GM level when combined with f4 . But Black has equalizing lines against this that are a bit easier to understand than against the tension variation.} dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 Be6 7. O-O-O+ Kc8 8. f4 {Why is f4 so much stronger than Nf3 ? Well, the black king needs to connect the rooks at some point and the clearest way to do this while stopping an enemy rook from going to the seventh is via c6 - Kc7 . A white bishop on f4 just ends this idea and makes it very hard for Black to unwind.  f4 aims to accomplish this in a straightforward manner. If Black declines to take, either f5 or fxe5 are both very powerful threats.} exf4 {Black must not allow White to kick away the beautiful bishop or take an e5 pawn.} 9. Nf3 {Wesley So tries to surprise his opponent with a different move than the mainlines. White isn't taking back on f4 but can at any moment.} Bc5 {In these lines, sometimes Bxf4 and Nb5 can wreak havoc on us so developing the bishop to c5 allows Bb6 in case of an emergency. Also, Black anticipates Bxf4 transposing to the mainline in the course where Black can force a trade of bishops or at least kick the enemy bishop off the long diagonal.} 10. Nd4 {So surprises his opponent no doubt with a novel approach. The knight threatens to take on e6 and so White tempts Black to give up the bishop pair.} Bg4 {In open positions, the bishop pair matters a lot and Black displays awareness in moving the bishop and counterattacking.} 11. Rd3 Rd8 (11... Nh5 {protecting the pawn would have been annoying for White. But Black plays naturally and with all their pieces so it's hard to fault them here.}) 12. Nb3 ({This gives Black an edge as it's not altogether clear if White will ever retake the f-pawn. This happens a lot. White gets a bit cute in not taking back right away only to have Black play keepsies. Against a natural move like} 12. Nd5 Nxd5 {or just the simple Nbd7 which only equalizes but has less firework craziness} 13. Bxd8 Nb4 14. Rd2 N8c6 15. Nxc6 Nxc6 {and the White bishop is attacked and Be3 is threatened.}) ({Best was probably} 12. Bxf6 gxf6 {when the computer gives White a tiny edge, although Black can be happy there in the imbalanced endgame with the bishop pair versus pawns.}) 12... Be3+ 13. Kb1 Nbd7 (13... Rxd3 {would have been slightly better, just trying to start the trading process even if it is scary to give up the d-file in the future. Development moves may not be the engine recommendation but they are seldom 'bad' as Black needs to develop quickly in the Philidor as in all openings.}) 14. h3 Bh5 15. Nd5 {This is a common idea but here, Black just keeps trading to an edge and White's attack whithers.} Nxd5 {Taking advantage of the idea that after Bxd8 Nb4 saves Black and gives an edge.} 16. Rxd5 c6 17. Ra5 f6 {Black kicks back the bishops and hopes for Bh4  g5 but the discovered attack on the other bishop will make things more complicated.} 18. Bxf4 {A clever tactic winning a pawn.} Bxf4 19. Rxh5 {The opening is over. Black has the d-file, an isolated pawn to play against and very good pieces. The engine gives this a -1.46 edge for Black, though with the opposite-colored bishops, the position is still very tricky for both sides.} g6 {Taking advantage of the fact that on Rxh7  Nf8 attacking the rook also threatens a back rank. White must put the rook on a passive square.} 20. Ra5 Nc5 {Threatening back rank checkmate. White must play very carefully right now to just be clearly worse.} 21. Be2 Nxe4 {Black is up a pawn now and clearly better. Again though, White has drawing chances with the opposite colored bishops and the world-class So is up for the challenge--though your opponents will probably not be.} 22. Bf3 Nd2+ {Trading pieces and moving towards a pleasant endgame that promises one of two results: draw or win.} 23. Nxd2 Rxd2 24. Ra4 {White needs to get the rook back and so tempos off the bishop.} Be5 25. Rh4 h5 {Black keeps the pawn and pushes the majority.} 26. Rd1 {It's unpleasant to offer a trade but allowing the rook to live on the seventh rank was even more unpleasant so White offers a trade.} Rxd1+ 27. Bxd1 Kc7 {Activating the rook... finally.} 28. Re4 Rd8 29. Bf3 Rd2 {This seems like a rerun.} 30. c3 a5 {I'm not so sure about this move. It has Philidor all over it to be sure, but usually we push these pawns to activate rooks and there's no rooks over there. Plus, Black doesn't have a majority. Slightly better was Rf2 with an attempt to pressure the kingside a bit.} 31. a4 Kd6 {Again, it's tough to criticize this as it's often EXACTLY what you want to do as Black: activate the king. But Black should aim to control the last rank here with Rf2 - Rf1 and h4  f5 etc.} 32. Kc1 Rf2 33. Re2 {A great move indicating excellent endgame knowledge. The bishop endgame will probably be drawn and so White aims to simplify. Why? Because Black's passed pawn must pass over a light square and White's bishop will be able to just block f3 and stop its progress.} Rf1+ 34. Kc2 Ra1 35. Rd2+ Kc7 36. Kb3 Rf1 {The position is one where White must play very accurately to hold with Black's active rook and extra pawn. The opposite-colored bishops offer chances to hold in an unpleasant position that will demand precision at every turn.} 37. Re2 h4 {Black locks in the pawn and starts the majority rolling.} 38. Be4 g5 {The majority keeps coming.} 39. Bf3 b5 {Another inaccuracy. The space is great on the queenside if we had more pieces. Then again, perhaps inaccuracy is too harsh as it's hard for Black to win on the queenside alone. In endgames, GM's talk of the principle of two weaknesses: if White has two things wrong here, they can't hold them both. The kingside issues are one thing but they are Fort Knox-ing well there. So Black aims to try to create a weakness on the other side. But this also gives Black weaknesses and without a majority, it's going to be very hard to make progress on that side.} 40. axb5 cxb5 41. Rd2 {The open file gives White an active rook and now Black is only down to being up a pawn which just isn't enough. Black can press but this is drawn.} Kb6 42. Kc2 a4 {Trying to make something happen on the queenside again.} 43. Be2 Rf2 44. Bd1 Rf4 {Again, the rook trade makes the result clear and Black is still playing for the win against his higher rated opponent as he should be!} 45. Kb1 a3 46. bxa3 Bxc3 47. Rd3 Be5 48. Rf3 Rd4 49. Kc2 Rc4+ 50. Kb1 Kc5 51. Rb3 Rc3 52. Rxc3+ Bxc3 53. Kc2 Be5 54. Be2 Bd6 55. Kb3 Bf4 56. Bd3 Bd6 {1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.} *

