{It's not every day that World Champion Contender Fabiano Caruana goes down with the white pieces but Black was up to the task in this amazing game. Vorobiov, playing Black, has incredible precision in this game.} 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 a5 8. Re1 c6 {This is the mainline among grandmasters. I call it the tension variation as White holds the tension for awhile.} 9. h3 h6 {I recommend Re8 first trying to steal a tempo but this is fine too and usually transposes.} 10. Ba2 {Indicating the slingshot variation, as I call it in this Chessable. But Ba2 is also very non-committal as White has many setups still available.} Re8 11. Be3 {This sensible move just aims to develop and decide on a plan later. Fabiano might be considering Qd2 as well as Qe2 - c4 .} Qc7 {The queen guards e5 so that the Black knight can reroute.} 12. Qe2 {This move commits to the Sling Shot Variation. On Qd2 , Black should play Bf8 to stop the h6 sacrifice. Now Black has two options I give in the theory section. One is to take on d4 and the other is to try to retain the tension. In this game, Black opts for the former.} Nf8 {Black keeps the tension and guards e6 which will be an important square later when White is going down the long diagonal.} 13. Qc4 Bd8 {Black's idea of Nf8 --clearing the rank for the queen to guard and playing for a win. This is listed as an alternative in the theory section.} 14. Rad1 Ng6 {Black keeps the tension and plays the maneuvering game.} 15. d5 {Caruana plays very well. The idea here is that Black can't play Be6 and dxc6 is threatened attacking f7 and b7 . For example, with that pin on c6 , Nb5 can be played in some variations.} Ra6 (15... Rf8 {was probably better but this is a thematic idea, going to b6 in some variations and just supporting c6 . Plus, it means a rook isn't hanging at the end of the dxc6 line.}) 16. Qd3 Be7 {Protecting d6 .} 17. Nd2 Nh5 {Black aims to gain space on the kingside while holding the queenside together.} 18. Ne2 Rf8 ({As I said in the chapter on the alternative line,} 18... Nhf4 {would have been consistent and objectively better. Black instead goes for an f5 break possibly and keeps the pawn on e5 , which I like for its practical chances. The opening was about equal after Nhf4 but after Rf8 White has a pull. Still, this is a position rich in strategy and tactics and the type we want with the Philidor.}) 19. dxc6 {A mistake. Even Super GM's find it tricky to navigate when to break the tension. Now Black can develop pieces through e6 harmoniously.} bxc6 20. Nf1 Nhf4 {Black's pieces become very active.} 21. Qd2 Be6 {Black is slightly better with pieces that easily find squares and some central and queenside pressure coming.} 22. Bxf4 Nxf4 23. Bxe6 fxe6 {This leads to a more equal game than Nxe6 , preserving Black's pristine pawn structure.} 24. Nxf4 Rxf4 (24... exf4 {was also interesting.}) 25. c4 Ra8 {The rook prepares to relocate.} 26. Re2 Rb8 {After a little back and forth, the two GM's reached an equal endgame. Vorobiov played this position brilliantly to secure the win.} 27. Qd3 Qb6 {Despite the equal engine diagnostic, the d6 pawn is easily defended but the b-pawn is not. This gives Black a bit of an easier to play position.} 28. Nd2 ({Hoping for Qxb2} 28. Rb1 {winning material.}) 28... Qd4 {Offering a queen trade and to continue playing the b-file pressure plan into the endgame.} 29. Nf3 Qxd3 30. Rxd3 c5 31. Ne1 Rb6 {Black prepares to double while keeping an eye on e4 with the other rook for now.} 32. b3 Rf8 33. Rb2 Rfb8 {Again, the position is technically equal but the b-file play of Black is better than White's d-file pressure as the bishop holds the pawn on d6 easily.} 34. Nc2 d5 {A beautiful tactical calculation makes this possible. If the white c-pawn takes then c4 hits and the b3 pawn is pinned.} 35. exd5 e4 36. Rd1 exd5 37. Rxd5 Rxb3 {The trades have favored Black a little whose bishop is better at both defending and attacking than the white knight.} 38. Rxb3 Rxb3 39. g3 Rb2 {Black has obtained a rook on the seventh rank and is clearly better now.} 40. Ne3 Ra2 41. Re5 Kf7 42. Nd5 {White gains a tempo on the bishop and makes the knight a bit better. Still, it's only a matter of time before the outside passed pawn becomes more of a problem then White's kingside majority which will run into the black king as it advances.} Bd6 43. Rxe4 Rxa4 44. Kg2 Ra3 45. h4 Rb3 {Black has removed the rook from the a-file to charge the pawn.} 46. h5 a4 47. Re2 a3 48. f4 Rb2 {The pawn keeps marching. Black has a winning advantage and White can resign at this point. The rest of the game shows Black's fine technique.} 49. Rxb2 axb2 50. Nc3 g6 51. hxg6+ Kxg6 52. Kf3 h5 53. Ke4 Bc7 54. Nb1 Ba5 55. Na3 Bb4 56. Nb1 Be1 57. Kf3 {White's knight can hardly move and so Black will win the king fight with so many tempos to waste and the better minor piece.} Kf5 58. Na3 Bc3 59. Nb1 Bb4 60. Ke3 Kg4 61. Kf2 Ba5 62. Na3 Bc3 63. Nb1 Bb4 64. Ke2 Kxg3 65. f5 Ba5 66. f6 Bd8 67. f7 Be7 68. Kf1 Kf4 69. Nc3 Ke5 70. Ke2 Kf6 71. Kd3 Kxf7 72. Kc2 Bf6 73. Ne4 Bd4 {And White understandably resigned in this lost position. A brilliant game by Black.} *

