[Black "Tension Variation Ba3 Attack:"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "106"]

1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 4. Nf3 e5 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4 a5 9. b3 {White tries to place a bishop on a3 and later pressure the d6 pawn. The bishop will be out of the way with the rooks creating more central pressure down the files.} exd4 {Now that the bishop has decided not to go to e3 , exd4 works well as we can put a queen on b6 without worrying about harassment.} 10. Nxd4 Ne5 {Another advantage of White playing b3 from Black's perspective is the c4 bishop's inability to retreat.} 11. Bf1 Re8 {Black calmly develops and leaves the f8 square vacant for the bishop. Qb6 was probably also fine but Black waits for the white bishop to commit to a3 just to be extra safe.} 12. Ba3 Qb6 13. Qd2 Bd7 ({I recommend} 13... Bg4 {here but later we retreat back to d7 with a similar position. The black bishop thinks about supporting b5 one day and importantly connects the rooks.}) 14. Rad1 Rad8 {These positions are a tiny bit better for White but very solid for Black. The d6 pawn isn't easily taken and on Nf5 we will eat the knight with our bishop and play d5 .} 15. f3 {Guarding e4 but creating some issues on the long diagonal. Without the bishop on that side, f4 also becomes a potential square for a black piece.} h6 {A general useful move slowly improving the position, though Ng6 with the idea of Nh5 - f4 would have been a more active try.  h6 stops back ranks and dreams of Bg5 one day.} 16. Qf2 {Unpinning the knight.} Bf8 {This move looks a bit slow. Again, Black should control f4 . Then again, I say this with a supercharged engine guiding my assessment, in practice it's hard to determine the best course and all Black's moves are classic Philidor moves that you should play when feeling uncertain as they improve the Black position.} 17. Nde2 {The endgame will result in d6 annoyance so Black decides to decline this offer. That said, the endgame isn't lost or anything, just annoying.} Qc7 18. h3 {This move weakens the dark squares as now if Black puts a knight on f4 , g3 will be harder to achieve. Additionally, it allows a thematic expansion on the queenside.} b5 {With a concrete threat.} 19. axb5 cxb5 {Now Black will be able to create a passed pawn on the outside via a4 or box out the white bishop with b4 .} 20. Nd5 {Ensuring that Black's b4 doesn't fork the pieces. But piece trades ease Black's game as Black has less space.} Nxd5 21. Rxd5 b4 22. Bb2 {Black has played skillfully and now has an edge. The c-pawn is falling.} Qxc2 23. Nd4 {White reasons that the endgame offers some chances to hold the draw as Black has some weak pawns, but this is a miscalculation: Black has an excellent endgame.} Qxf2+ 24. Kxf2 a4 {Fixing the backwards a5 pawn and creating a passed pawn on the queenside.} 25. bxa4 Bxa4 26. Ra5 Ra8 27. Rxa8 Rxa8 28. Ra1 {Black must be careful as White's position has drawing chances with rooks and many minor pieces still on the board. It won't be easy to queen and White even has the more active king and less pawn islands.} Nd7 {Relocating the knight to unpin the rook.} 29. Bb5 Nb6 30. Ke2 d5 {Solving another pawn island problem by offering to trade or turn the d-pawn into a passed pawn if White declines.} 31. Bxa4 Rxa4 {White can't easily trade rooks here as Nxa4 would be very powerful, hitting the bishop and threatening Nc3 in some lines. But moving the rook away would allow Black to place a rook on the seventh. So White tries to blockade the passed pawn and keep the rook tension.} 32. Nb3 dxe4 33. fxe4 {Now Black has a clearer path with the pawn islands being equal. That said, White STILL has the active king and pawn trades, generally, help the side that's losing. So this position is unclear, though Black is definitely better.} g5 {Trying to activate the black king. f6 might have been a bit more natural. Black must have wanted to restrict White and control f4 .} 34. Kd3 Bg7 {Continuing to trade.} 35. Rxa4 Nxa4 36. Bc1 Bc3 37. h4 f6 38. hxg5 fxg5 {Black takes away from the center to go all in for a win. This allows White a passed pawn but ensures Black will have a passer on the queenside, splitting White's army. Objectively speaking, White should be able to hold this but in practice, it's a difficult task.} 39. Kc4 Nb6+ 40. Kc5 Nd7+ {The black knight heads to the other side of the board. Black's king will soon join the fight.} 41. Kd6 Ne5 42. Ke6 Kg7 43. Be3 Kg6 44. Bb6 {The bishop on e3 should probably stay put as it might want to sacrifice itself on g5 if Black goes for the g2 pawn.} h5 45. Bc7 Nd3 46. Kd5 {Black's king is now active and Black is looking great here: completely winning actually as the h-pawn is hard to stop. Again, very difficult for White to hold that.} h4 47. e5 Nf4+ 48. Ke4 Nxg2 49. e6 h3 50. Bg3 Nf4 51. e7 Kf7 52. Kf5 Ne2 53. Bd6 Nd4+ {And the trade of knights means the white bishop will be overloaded trying to stop both pawns. A beautiful game by Black.} *

