[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "54"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4 ({The Shirov Gambit, named after famous super GM Alexei Shirov, is common in high level play. The idea is that on Nxg4} 5. Rg1 {Ngf6 Bc4 Black can't stop Ng5 with Be7 as g7 is hanging. The downside? Well, without Bc4 being played and threatening Ng6 immediately, Black can develop their bishop to an even better square than usual.}) 5... g6 6. g5 Nh5 {This can be our reflex move against g5 .} 7. Be3 Bg7 {White tries to quickly castle queenside.} 8. Qd2 O-O {Black should continue as planned. For now the kingside is blocked up and tricky for White to attack. The g5 pawn stops the usual attacking plan of Bh6 in positions like these. That said, I prefer to briefly refrain from castling so that if White plays a quick Qd6 , our king is in the center. This is likely to transpose anyway.} 9. O-O-O {Black would love to pawn storm the queenside but the fact that the d-file can open suddenly means we have to be careful.} c6 10. dxe5 {White chooses to make this move to block the g7 bishop from contributing to the queenside attack and exploit the extra rook on the d-file.} dxe5 11. Bh3 {This pin is critical. Luckily, Black is okay.} Qa5 {Threatening a counter pin on Bxd7 with Rd8 ! Note how Black attacks with their pieces in this position. Qc7 would be more in line with the main recommendation in this course, but this game nicely illustrates what happens when White goes hunting for the knight on h5 , which is a clear plan even if it's not a great one.} 12. Bg4 {Not the best move but one that seems natural from a human point of view. White reasons that the doubled h-pawns will spell doom for Black but the plan is slow and this is a fast-paced position.} Nb6 {The downside of the bishop on the a3 diagonal is that Nb6 will always be powerful. The attack on the queen, bishop and b2 pawn is a trifecta threat!  b3 would be nice but the bishop on g4 is now hanging.} ({To show the threat just look at Bxc8 Nc4 Qd7 Nxb2 Kxb2} 12... Qb4 {Kc1 Qxc3 with a small practical edge for Black after best play by White.}) 13. Bxb6 {Taking out the Nc4 threat but unleashing the rook.} axb6 {Now Black can queenside pawn storm without creating a problem spot on c6 in case of an endgame and here it is trickier for White to play Qd6 and try to endgame us anyways.} 14. Bxh5 gxh5 {White accomplishes their plan. And Black is clearly better. The issue is that it takes White a long time to come down the h-file and without their light squared bishop, the light square h7 is harder to attack. They may win a pawn one day but it's time consuming and the game is filled with urgent matters.} 15. Nh4 b5 16. Nf5 b4 {Some people do whatever they can to save their g7 bishop but it's important to note that it's actually usually a bad piece after the pawn trades on e5 . And White has no easy way in if we don't play Bxf5 . This isn't the mainline Philidor so Bxf5 shouldn't be automatic anymore. That said, Bxf5 may be possible to open up the g7 bishop. It's a close call. Zarkua allows the knight for a bit.} 17. Nb1 {White allows Black to take on a2 , arguing that b2 will be hard to invade. Black must act fast.} Bxf5 18. exf5 Rfd8 {Taking out the king attack and developing a rook to help with the attack.} 19. Qe3 Qxa2 {The game remains intense. Neither side have an easy time making progress.} 20. f6 Bf8 {Importantly, Bh8 would be tragic as the bishop would never come out again.} 21. Qxe5 Ra5 {An excellent move! Black lifts the rook tactically.} 22. Qc7 Rda8 {Qxb1 and then Ra1 checkmate is threatened so the position becomes concrete.} 23. Kd2 {An ugly move that had to be played to stop the mate. But now White finds their king in the center of the board and they are completely lost.} Qxb2 24. Ke3 Re8+ 25. Kf3 Qxc2 {The game is over. Black has many different ways to finish. The endgame is good for Black as is the attack.} 26. Rd4 Rf5+ 27. Rf4 Qe4+ {The white rook is pinned and the end is near. White resigned.} *

