[White "User Requested Lines"]
[Black "User Request 1: Plan Against "]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C41"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. a4 {This was recommended in Gustafsson's 'Aggressive e4 ! Part 1.' I have to admit it's a clever try and quite creative. The downside to playing it for White is that a lot of memorization is required. White has to be willing to play a Shirov Gambit accepted, Shirov Gambit declined, or a more positional grind game. And so a lot of memorization and precision in different types of positions is required on their part against a defense (the Philidor) that is uncommon so particularly hard on the memory of our opponents. The move is, right now, very uncommon--so uncommon it doesn't even get ranked on the screen in Lichess games. It has appeared in Master games though (67 times out of the 8,445 times this position was reached, so very very rare, but with a healthy win record for White and possibly on the trend after the Chessable recommendation). The point is that on our very intuitive move a5 , White transposes to the Shirov Gambit with g4 and as you may recall there, I said Black should try to avoid moving their queenside pawns for a bit in the g6 line: so they have tricked us.} Be7 {Again, a5 has some issues. The Shirov Gambit declined line still scores well for Black in the few lines it's been played, living up to its practical durability, but objectively, Black is worse and there will inevitably be some White player that memorizes it all into the endgame against us and so I can't allow White that much. I should say also that a5 and then accepting the gambit is still equalizing for Black so this is one of the few cases where the gambit accepters have an edge over us in being able to play more normal. That said, Be7 is very normal. We just want to see Bc4 on the board before playing a5 as Bc4 is often not a great move against our Shirov Gambit lines.} 6. a5 O-O {The best way to take advantage of lots of pawn moves is to develop quickly and get one's king to safety.} 7. Be2 {7. Bc4 is also possible but then many moves like c6 - b5 or dxe4  Ne5 will gain a tempo on it later. So this is the point and the recommendation of the aforementioned Chessable course.} c6 {We prepare Qc7 and later d5 ideas and eye the a5 pawn.} 8. O-O Qc7 ({Gustafsson in his own course gives this equalizing line for Black:} 8... Re8 9. d5 cxd5 10. exd5 Nf8 11. Nd2 Ng6 12. Nc4 Bd7 13. Ra3 h6 14. Rb3 Qc7 15. Be3 {. He then details plans for White in that line. I considered moving down that track as a result but both my Chessbase Live Book and some engines were making that line complicated if White deviates from the Gustafsson recommendation. We can't make our opponents promise to play that, and the other downside is that our opponents will be prepared. So I wanted to go a different way but the line above is there and also works. In many cases, it will just transpose anyway as both moves are natural enough.}) 9. h3 {Preventing Ng4 ideas on Be3 and waiting to see if we capture in the center before choosing where the bishop goes.} Re8 {We clear up f8 and plan an attack on e4 to punish the early pawn movements. One advantage of the bishop being on e2 is that it's harder to harass, but a disadvantage is it blocks the rook's defense of e4 .} 10. d5 {White fears the e4 pawn attack so pushes. Here, Gustafsson in his Chessable gives a line featuring 10... cxd5 which probably does equalize for Black with precise play, but given that's what his users are expecting and he outlines the plans for that, why not throw them off by deviating in a way that also equalizes? It is typically the case that when White doesn't develop their pieces and plays a bunch of pawn moves, there's more than one way forward.} ({That said, cxd5} 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 a6 12. b4 b5 {(improving on his course's response of b6 , which allows c4 ) is also a very playable line.}) 10... Nc5 {The computer's instinct and first choice and not listed in the course. It seems to equalize. The attack on e4 is annoying. White doesn't want to play Bd3 and weaken control of d5 --if they play that move, you can just capture on d5 and play Bd7 with a great position--so their next move is predictable...} 11. Nd2 {The computer move here is Na6 but very, very close is the move I'm going to recommend, which is simpler. And if in doubt: lets play the easier one conceptually. Now that said, Na6 illustrates an important point: we want to reroute the knight off the c-file in these positions so we can attack the White queenside pawns. Doubling our pawns with Bxa6 often backfires as giving Black the two bishops and an open b-file to continue the queenside pawn assault is definitely enough compensation.} cxd5 {Clearing the c-file and creating a pawn advantage in the center: 2 to 1.} 12. Nxd5 {White can also recapture with the pawn immediately but their idea here is to go for c4 with some kind of bind. I think it's the better White move as a result and the only one where White can try to push.} Nxd5 {Taking out the scary pony.} 13. exd5 Bf5 {Deep Fritz states equality and Stockfish gives White a tiny, miniscule edge with tricky play required. The idea of Bf5 is to stop the c4 bind by responding Nd3 and winning the two bishops if they do it. Black can follow up with Rf8 and f5 plans as well as playing on the queenside with Nd7 or even Na6 ideas and pressure down the file. White will have a hard time attacking our king as Bg6 later will block the g-file and so their 'aggressive' repertoire will end up being a very positional maneuvering game instead. Fun and exactly what we want psychologically!} *

