1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Bxf7+ {The so called 'Improved Caveman.' The point is that in the normal caveman attack, Black trades pawns in the center at the end to play Ne5 . By exchanging on e5 first, White aims to end this idea. However, there are downsides. Namely, one of the reasons Black often needed to trade in the center was to activate their d7 knight. However, here, without a d4 pawn, the Black knight can develop to c5 , so White has solved a Black challenge. The other problem from White's perspective is that Black has two very good lines to choose from: one very safe and easy on the memory and another where Black just stands better. Let's have a look...} Kxf7 8. Ng5+ {The point of White's bishop sacrifice is to put a knight on e6 . Now Black can play aggressively with some risk and be better (Kg6) or safely to just not play White's games (Ke8). I'll give both lines so you can choose based on your temperament.} Kg6 {This move is harder to memorize than Kg8 but it's objectively better. The idea is to give a square for the queen on g8 .} 9. Ne6 Qg8 {This is the point of Kg6 : Black is not obliged to put a queen on e8 and allow a fork.} 10. Nxc7 Rb8 {Black saves the rook and braces for the storm.} 11. O-O {The most popular move on Lichess.} Bd8 {A rarely played move but a computer favorite with an 80% win record for Black on Lichess. The idea is to attack the knight and gain a tempo, put the bishop on a square where it won't be attacked by a d5 knight and will cover key infiltration squares, and plan a later rerouting to b6 .} 12. N7d5 {White usually takes the outpost in reply.} h6 {Black has a material edge as the two bishops are going to be superior to the pawns. So all Black needs to do is unwind and stop White's current intiative. With h6 , Black plans to retreat the king back to h7 where it's particularly safe because it's on a light square and White has given up their light-squared bishop.} 13. f4 Kh7 {Qe8 was also better for Black, trying to take care of the light-diagonal. The point of Kh7 is to just safely get out of dodge and prepare to unwind. White's attack is starting to lessen and their missing bishop is starting to show. Black can follow up with moves like Nc5 , b6 , Bb7 , and Qe8 to make way for the rook and reroute to c6 or even the kingside. Black is better. Deep Fritz shows -0.6 with a long term edge and Stockfish is even more excited at -1.8.} *

