1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Bxf7+ {The so called 'Improved Caveman.' The point is that in the normal caveman attack, Black trades pawns in the center at the end to play Ne5 . By exchanging on e5 first, White aims to end this idea. However, there are downsides. Namely, one of the reasons Black often needed to trade in the center was to activate their d7 knight. However, here, without a d4 pawn, the Black knight can develop to c5 , so White has solved a Black challenge. The other problem from White's perspective is that Black has two very good lines to choose from: one very safe and easy on the memory and another where Black just stands better. Let's have a look...} Kxf7 8. Ng5+ {The point of White's bishop sacrifice is to put a knight on e6 . Now Black can play aggressively with some risk and be better ( Kg6 ) or safely to just not play White's games ( Ke8 ). I'll give both lines so you can choose based on your temperament.} Kg8 {The easier to remember variation. Our moves resemble the course's main path when the pawns hadn't been exchanged.} 9. Ne6 {Attacking the black queen and c7 .} Qe8 10. Nxc7 Qg6 {Usually if you can play Qg6 , you do in these variations. If they guard g2 , we move our rook to b8 , so White's next move is forced...} 11. Nxa8 Qxg2 {The rook is threatened and Black's pieces are coming into action.} 12. Rf1 Nc5 {Black's knight is a little less strong here than it was on e5 (the point of White's play). However, White doesn't have a centralized queen and so they are even further away from castling and have no checks on the a2 - g8 diagonal. Black's threats are all around: Ng4 , Bg4 , Bh3 .} 13. Qe2 {The computer's favorite move here, preparing to castle and eyeing checks on c4 .} Bh3 {This is simplest, just going for a tiny edge.} 14. Be3 ({Many White moves were possible but they have nothing better than just aiming to castle and accepting the queen trade.} 14. Qc4+ {could have been met with Be6 and if Qe2 trying to repeat, Black can accept a draw or play for more by taking on e4 with Nfxe4 . The position is objectively better for Black so I recommend continuing the attack.}) 14... Qxf1+ {Simplest and best.} 15. Qxf1 Bxf1 16. Kxf1 Kf7 {Black is ready to move the king towards the center and activate their rook. White has to lose time moving their knight. Black will capture the e4 pawn and put a rook on c8 for pressure against White's queenside and stands a tiny bit better due to having the initiative and less isolated pawns after e4 falls.} *

