1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 (5. Rg1 {This move just transposes.} c6 6. g4 g6 {This transposes to the Shirov Gambit line. You can find that variation by clicking here.}) 5... Be7 6. g4 {Some may wonder whether you can play the Shirov Gambit after Bc4 and the short answer is... no you cannot.} Nb6 {This is the issue. Black will just take the g-pawn with the bishop and White lacks compensation. Their best bet is to try to make things crazy with...} 7. Bb5+ {Otherwise, we'd just take on g4 with our bishop.} c6 {And again, the pawn on g4 is threatened. White has had okay results making it chaotic with...} 8. g5 {But if you find some tactics you'll be okay here. Actually, the tricky part is that Black has many good moves but the best knight moves are the most unintuitive ones!} Nxe4 {This is very strong along with exd4 , Nfd5 and cxb5 . We happily trade the knight for the bishop is the point.} 9. Nxe4 cxb5 {White's light squares are very weak so Black can count on an edge.} *

